{"title_page": "Cunard Building (New York City)", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Cunard Building{{!}}Cunard Building, Liverpool}}\n{{short description|Office skyscraper in Manhattan, New York}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name = Cunard Building\n| image = File:Bowling Green-Battery Pk 01 - Cunard.jpg\n| image_size =\n| image_caption =\n| former_names =\n| alternate_names = Standard & Poors Building\n| status = Complete\n| building_type = Office\n| architectural_style = [[Renaissance Revival architecture|Neo-Renaissance]]\n| classification =\n| location = 25 [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]]<br />[[Financial District, Manhattan]], New York\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|42|21|N|74|00|51|W|display=inline,title}}\n| groundbreaking_date =\n| start_date = 1920\n| stop_date =\n| topped_out_date =\n| completion_date = 1921\n| opened_date = May 2, 1921\n| inauguration_date =\n| client = [[Cunard Line]]\n| owner =\n| height = {{convert|254.74|ft|m}}\n| material =\n| size =\n| floor_count = 22 (+1 basement)\n| floor_area =\n| elevator_count =\n| architect = [[Benjamin Wistar Morris (architect)|Benjamin Wistar Morris III]]\n| architecture_firm = [[Carr\u00e8re & Hastings]]\n| embedded = {{Designation list\n| embed = yes\n| designation1 = NYC\n| designation1_date = September 19, 1995\n| designation1_number = 1928 (exterior), 1929 (interior)\n}}\n| references = <ref name=\"emporis\" />\n}}\nThe '''Cunard Building''', also known as the '''Standard & Poors Building''', is a 22-story office building located at 25 [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]], adjacent to [[Bowling Green (New York City)|Bowling Green Park]] in the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]] of [[Lower Manhattan]] in [[New York City]]. The Cunard Building was designed in the [[Renaissance architecture|Italian Renaissance]] style by [[Benjamin Wistar Morris (architect)|Benjamin Wistar Morris]], in conjunction with consultants [[Carr\u00e8re & Hastings]].\n\nThe Cunard Building's main facade, on Broadway, is made of limestone and consists of three horizontal sections. The design employs [[Setback (architecture)|setbacks]] and open \"light courts\" as mandated by the [[1916 Zoning Resolution]]. The structure was designed around an irregular street grid and is located directly above a [[New York City Subway|subway]] line that crosses the building site diagonally. The first floor interior contains an elaborately decorated lobby, as well as a similarly opulent Great Hall, which extends {{Convert|185|ft||abbr=}} with a {{Convert|65|ft|m|abbr=|-tall|adj=mid}} dome. The remaining floors contain various offices and school spaces.\n\nThe Cunard Building was erected for the New York City office of the [[Cunard Line]], a British-American steamship line; construction started in 1920 and the building was completed the next year. Upon completion, the Cunard Building was almost fully leased to tenants of various industries. The Twenty-five Broadway Corporation, a Cunard Line affiliate, owned the building until the 1960s. The Great Hall was vacated after the Cunard Line moved out in 1968; the [[United States Postal Service]] occupied the Great Hall from 1974 until 2000, and [[Cipriani S.A.]] started using the space in 2014. The upper floors continued to host offices and various educational facilities.\n\nUpon completion, the Cunard Building's exterior and interior designs received critical acclaim. The Cunard Building's facade and principal first-floor interior spaces were designated as [[List of New York City Landmarks|landmarks]] by the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] in 1995.\n\n== Description ==\nThe Cunard Building is a 22-story building,<ref name=\"emporis\" /> bounded by the [[Bowling Green Offices Building]] (11 Broadway) to the south, Broadway to the east, [[Greenwich Street]] to the west, and Morris Street to the north.<ref name=\"NYT-Cunard-1919\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1918/02/20/archives/cunard-to-have-big-building-here-10000000-structure-of-26-stories.html|title=Cunard To Have Big Building Here; $10,000,000 Structure of 26 Stories Going Up on Site of Old Stevens House.|last=|first=|date=February 20, 1918|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"Tribune-Cunard-1919\" /> It is located across from [[Bowling Green (New York City)|Bowling Green Park]] to the southeast, and [[26 Broadway]] and the ''[[Charging Bull]]'' sculpture to the east.<ref name=\"lpc95\" /> While 25 Broadway is considered to be its primary address, it is also known as 13\u201327 Broadway, 13\u201339 Greenwich Street, and 1\u20139 Morris Street.<ref name=\"emporis\">{{cite web |url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/115358/standard-poors-building-new-york-city-ny-usa |title=Standard & Poors Building |website=Emporis |accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"lpc95\" /> The Cunard Building has a [[frontage]] of {{Convert|203|ft||abbr=}} along Broadway, {{Convert|231|ft||abbr=}} along Greenwich Street, and {{Convert|248|ft||abbr=}} along Morris Street.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\">{{harvnb|''Architecture and Building''|1921|ps=.|p=61}}</ref> Due to the irregular street grid of the area, none of its corners are at right angles.<ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\">{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=October 1919|title=The Cunard Building, New York|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.c2640733&view=1up&seq=260|journal=Architectural Review|volume=26|pages=113\u2013114|via=}}</ref><ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43286591/|title=$20,000,000 Office Building Projects of Cunard and Munson Lines Completed|date=May 1, 1921|work=New-York Tribune|access-date=January 30, 2020|page=37|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref>\n\nThe Cunard Building was largely designed by [[Benjamin Wistar Morris (architect)|Benjamin Wistar Morris]].<ref name=\"NYT-Cunard-1919\" /> The [[massing]] and [[facade]] were devised by [[Carr\u00e8re and Hastings]], while exterior detail was created by Rochette & Parzini.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|p=5}}</ref> The structure was laid out so that ancillary structures such as smoke stacks, penthouses, and storage tanks could not be seen from the side. Its location near ferry slips, the [[New York City Subway]], elevated [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company|Interborough Rapid Transit]] lines, and the [[Hudson & Manhattan Railroad]]'s [[Hudson Terminal]] made the Cunard Building desirable to tenants.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> In the 1970s, the Cunard Building became known as the Standard & Poors Building, after its tenant [[Standard & Poor's]],<ref name=\"Oser 1977\" /> though the name also came to refer to nearby structures.{{efn|The Standard & Poor's Building may refer to [[65 Broadway]]<ref>{{cite aia5|page=22}}</ref> or [[55 Water Street]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Standard & Poor's, Given Subsidies, Is to Stay in New York | website=The New York Times | date=April 25, 1997 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/04/25/nyregion/standard-poor-s-given-subsidies-is-to-stay-in-new-york.html | access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>}}\n\n=== Form ===\n[[File:Bowling Green NYC Feb 2020 78 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Eastern facade seen from across Broadway]]\nAt the time of the Cunard Building's construction, large buildings in New York City were being erected in a \"C\" or \"H\" shape to maximize illumination of the interior space.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> Additionally, the [[1916 Zoning Resolution]] necessitated the inclusion of [[Setback (architecture)|setbacks]] on buildings in New York City that were above a certain height.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/26/nyregion/new-yorks-first-zoning-resolution-which-brought-order-to-a-chaotic-building-boom-turns-100.html|title=Zoning Arrived 100 Years Ago. It Changed New York City Forever.|last=Dunlap|first=David W.|date=July 25, 2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Cunard Building was the first large structure built in the city after the end of [[World War I]], and set an example for compliance to the 1916 law.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" />\n\nThe building is H-shaped, with \"light courts\" facing north toward Morris Street and south toward the Bowling Green Building.<ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> The \"light courts\" are located above the base. The placement of these courts allowed light to enter the Great Hall, located on the first floor.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /> Because of the presence of large intersections on either side of the building (Bowling Green to the east and the intersection of Greenwich Street and [[Trinity Place]] to the west), the required setback under the 1916 zoning law was minimal.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|p=3}}</ref> According to Morris, the irregular street grid of the neighborhood made it difficult to determine the orientation of the building; he finally decided on its current alignment since, at the time, it would have been possible to see the [[North River (Hudson River)]] to the south.<ref name=\"Morris p. 1\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Morris|1920|p=1}}</ref>\n\n=== Foundation ===\nThe New York City Subway's [[BMT Broadway Line]] (now the {{NYCS trains|Broadway south day}}) crosses diagonally underneath the Cunard Building from northwest to southeast. Two additional subway lines, the [[IRT Lexington Avenue Line]] ({{NYCS trains|Lexington south}}) and the [[IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line]] ({{NYCS trains|Broadway-Seventh South Ferry}}), run adjacent to the western and eastern boundaries of the building, respectively.<ref name=\"AR pp. 21\">{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|p=21}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://new.mta.info/document/2461|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Bowling Green (4)(5)|date=2018|website=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|mta.info]]|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=September 13, 2018}}</ref> The Lexington Avenue Line's [[Bowling Green station]] is located directly under the building's boundary, while the Broadway Line's [[Whitehall Street station]] is located one block south.<ref name=\":0\" /> Because of the confluence of subway tunnels in the area, the Cunard Building's foundation was built around the subway.<ref name=\"Morris pp. 2-3\" /><ref name=\"AR p. 22\">{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|p=22}}</ref>\n\nDuring construction, the engineers considered and rejected an idea for placing the Cunard Building's [[girder]]s on the roof of the Broadway Line tunnel, since that would have resulted in vibrations every time a subway train passed by.<ref name=\"AR pp. 21\" /> Furthermore, the subway tunnel was designed to support the weight of several small buildings and might not have been able to support one large building.<ref name=\"Morris pp. 2-3\" /><ref>{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|pp=17\u201318}}</ref> Instead, engineers decided to place the building's foundation columns on either side of the subway tunnel, and then erect girders for the building above the tunnel's roof. The foundation columns were placed as close to the subway tunnel as possible, in order to reduce the length of the trusses, which would have had to carry heavy loads. All of the foundation columns were sunk to the depth of the rock underneath.<ref name=\"AR pp. 21\" />\n\nA [[cofferdam]] was then built on the eastern border of the site, and on part of the northern border. The rock surface underneath the building site was closer to the ground on the western side of the lot, requiring extensive excavation. On the eastern side of the lot, the rock surface sloped below the elevation of the subway tunnel. A {{Convert|6|ft|m|-thick|abbr=|adj=mid}} wall was built on the southern boundary of the Cunard lot, of which a {{Convert|2|ft||adj=on}} width was located under the Bowling Green Offices Building. The wall served several purposes: it closed the cofferdam, underpinned the subway, and provided support for the columns on the southern side of the Cunard Building.<ref name=\"AR p. 22\" />\n\n=== Facade ===\n\n==== Broadway elevation ====\n[[File:Bowling Green-Battery Pk 03 - Cunard.jpg|thumb|left|Center arches at the base|alt=]]\nThe facade at the Broadway [[Elevation (architecture)|elevation]] is made of [[Indiana Limestone]], making Cunard Building part of a masonry \"canyon\" on lower Broadway.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /> It is divided into three horizontal sections on the western and eastern facades. The outermost portions of these facades consist of pavilions that project outward, while the central pavilion is set back {{Convert|5|ft||abbr=}}.<ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\" /><ref name=\"Morris p. 4\">{{harvnb|Morris|1920|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> The projecting \"side pavilions\" rise to the maximum height allowed under the 1916 law.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Morris p. 4\" /> On the Broadway facade, the side pavilions are {{Convert|50|ft||abbr=}} wide, while the central pavilion is about {{Convert|103|ft||abbr=}} wide.<ref name=\"Morris p. 4\" />\n\nThe Broadway facade contains decorative elements that signify the area's historic connections with the maritime industry, including \"nautically-inspired sculpted elements\", decorative [[Keystone (architecture)|keystones]] above the first-floor arches, decorative ship-themed [[roundel]]s above the third-floor loggia, and carvings of seahorses with their riders above the pavilions' setbacks.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"AB p. 62\" />\n\nWithin the four-story base, the central section is recessed slightly. The first floor contains five double-height arches, set within [[Rustication (architecture)|rusticated]] masonry, facing east toward Broadway.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|p=6}}</ref> The center three arches, within the recessed central pavilion, lead to the Great Hall; the southernmost arch leads to the elevator lobby for the office space above; and the northernmost arch led to a banking area on the north side of the building.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /> All the arches contain doors and windows with bronze frames.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=6}}</ref> The third and fourth floors contain an Ionic-style [[loggia]] structure supported by [[Italianate architecture|Tuscan-style]] column pairs. Above the base, the facade is mostly composed of smooth limestone, except for rustication around the fifth story windows. The columns of windows around the central pavilion, which is recessed further, are also set within a rusticated facade. The outer pavilions are set back beyond the 18th story to comply with the 1916 Zoning Resolution. The central pavilion contains a loggia between the 19th and 21st stories, also supported by Tuscan-style column pairs, and includes a [[mansard roof]] above the 22nd story. The roofs of the outer pavilions, above the 22nd story, are flat.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" />\n\n==== Other elevations ====\n{{multiple image\n|total_width=450\n|image1=Cunard Building side Feb 2020 02.jpg\n|caption1=Morris Street facade, looking up at the light court, which is faced mostly in brick. The section at far left, closest to Broadway, is faced with limestone\n|image2=Cunard Building rear Feb 2020 2.jpg\n|caption2=Greenwich Street facade, with the triple-height window recessed at an angle. Below is the full-height basement, faced with granite\n}}\nOn Morris Street, the first and second stories are faced with limestone, while the basement is faced with a [[Water table (architecture)|water table]] made of granite. Above the second story is a light court. The facade of the eastern wing (facing Broadway) is limestone, while the rest of the Morris Street facade is made of tan brick. There are also numerous glazed doors with bronze frames, as well as glazed paneled windows with metal frames. The remaining windows on Morris Street are [[sash window]]s.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" />\n\nOn Greenwich Street, the basement is faced with granite and the remaining stories are faced with tan brick. The basement contains service doors, a garage door, and metal window openings. Above the garage door is a large triple-height arched window on the first through third floors, with balconies on the second and third floors; the window is recessed at an angle. The remaining windows on Greenwich Street are sash windows. There is a [[cornice]] of stone above the 22nd floor. The southernmost section of the Greenwich Street facade only goes to the third floor<!-- four stories high, including basement --> to allow light to enter the light court within the southern side of the building.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /> The gray brick at both Morris and Greenwich Streets was designed to \"harmoniz[e] closely with the limestone\".<ref name=\"AB p. 62\" />\n\nThe south elevation consists of a brick facade with sash windows. The light court faces south toward the Bowling Green Offices Building.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" />\n\n=== Interior ===\nAt opening, the Cunard Building featured over {{convert|700,000|ft2||abbr=}} of space, of which {{Convert|500,000|ft2||abbr=}} was made available for tenants when it opened. A basement in the building contained a safe-deposit vault.<ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\" /> The structure also included a fireproof internal structure.<ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\">{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=August 2, 1919|title=Unusual Features Mark Plans of New Cunard Building|url=https://rerecord.library.columbia.edu/pdf_files/ldpd_7031148_064_32.pdf|journal=The Real Estate Record: Real Estate Record and Builders' Guide|volume=104|pages=141|via=[[Columbia University|columbia.edu]]|number=5}}</ref> According to data collected by ''[[The Real Deal (magazine)|The Real Deal]]'' magazine, the precise floor area of the Cunard Building is {{convert|809,401|ft2}}.<ref>{{cite web | title=25 Broadway \u2013 TRD Research | website=The Real Deal | date=March 13, 2019 | url=https://therealdeal.com/new-research/topics/property/25-broadway/ | access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe building also contained 36 elevators: 33 for passengers and 3 for freight.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Morris p. 3\">{{harvnb|Morris|1920|ps=.|p=3}}</ref> Of the passenger elevators, 28 were \"high-speed\" elevators for general use and the remaining 5 were private cabs.<ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\" /><ref name=\"Morris p. 3\" /><ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\"/> Twenty of the \"high-speed\" elevators were local and express elevators, accessible from the elevator lobby at the southern end of the Broadway facade. The other eight were located at the building's northwest corner, near Greenwich and Morris Streets.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" />\n\n==== Lobby and Great Hall ====\n{{Multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| total_width = 250\n| image1 = Cunard Building 02.JPG\n| caption1 = Lobby\n| image2 = Cunard 6.jpg\n| caption2 = Great Hall\n}}\n\nThe main entrance is from Broadway, through the three center arches, each of which contains a small entrance vestibule inside. The vestibules and the two outer arches all lead to the building's main lobby.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 12\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=12}}</ref> The lobby contains a ceiling of five [[groin vault]]s, each of which correspond to one of the arches on the Broadway facade. The floors are made of [[travertine]] with [[marble]] trim and contain maritime-themed bronze medallions.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> The walls are also made of travertine; there is a fireplace on the southern wall and a roll-down gate and doors on the northern wall.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> A passageway runs along the western wall of the lobby, connecting the northern four bays to the Great Hall to the west.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 12\" /> The building's original owners had decided against putting \"miscellaneous minor business adventures\" in the lobby, such as newsstands, shoe-shine stands, and cigar shops.<ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\"/>\n\nThe Great Hall, extending {{Convert|185|ft||abbr=}} from east to west,<ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\" /><ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\" /> was described as \"the largest of its kind\" within the United States when completed, and was compared to the waiting rooms of railroad terminals.<ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\" /><ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 4\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> It includes three separate vaults. The central vault is {{Convert|65|ft||abbr=}} tall with a diameter of {{Convert|70|ft||abbr=}}.<ref name=\"Morris p. 1\" /><ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\" /><ref name=\"nytm51\" /> There are large arched windows or \"luminary squares\" at the ends of its diagonal axes, under which are Ionic columns.<ref name=\"Morris p. 1\" /><ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /><ref name=\"AB p. 63\">{{harvnb|''Architecture and Building''|1921|ps=.|p=63}}</ref> Flanking the main dome are two spaces with rectangular [[rib vault]]s, which extend the hall to the west and east.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /><ref name=\"AB p. 63\" /> There are additional arched openings through the west and east walls of the Great Hall: the former leads to a window facing Greenwich Street, while the latter leads to the lobby.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> As built, the hall was overlooked by wrought-iron balconies on the east wall, designed by [[Samuel Yellin]].<ref name=\"AB p. 63\" /> The features are reminiscent of [[Thermae|Roman bathhouses]] and the treatment of the artwork resembles that at the [[Villa Madama]]'s loggia in Italy.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 4\" />\n\nThe north side of the Cunard Building's first floor contained a banking area, which had a private elevator to the fourth floor and a basement-level bank vault.<ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\"/> This was initially occupied by a branch of the [[Mechanics and Metals National Bank]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes-MM-1921\"/>\n\nThe first floor contains numerous elaborate works of art.<ref name=\"nycland\">{{cite nycland|page=10}}</ref> The lobby ceiling was painted by [[Ezra Winter]] and sculpted by [[C. Paul Jennewein|Carl Jennewein]], and contains decorations of marine animals and children.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /><ref name=\"nycland\" /> The lobby's end bays also contain [[bas-relief]]s carved by Jennewein.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> Wrought-iron screens topped by [[lunette]] grilles, designed by [[Samuel Yellin]], separate the passageway from both the lobby to the east and the Great Hall to the west.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> The ceiling of the Great Hall contains maritime-themed frescoes, which Winter painted using the [[fresco-secco]] method,<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 4\" /><ref>{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|p=13}}</ref> which depicted maritime activity.<ref>{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|p=16}}</ref> [[Barry Faulkner]] painted murals of maps into the walls of the Great Hall's niches.<ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\" /><ref name=\"nycland\" /> The [[pendentive]]s of the Great Hall's dome include depictions of oceanic explorers [[Leif Erikson]], [[Christopher Columbus]], [[Sebastian Cabot (explorer)|Sebastian Cabot]], and [[Francis Drake]].<ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Morris|1920|ps=.|p=6}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> On the Great Hall's floor is a marble compass surrounded by a bronze frieze, designed by [[John Gregory (sculptor)|John Gregory]] as an \"allegory of the sea\".<ref>{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=7}}</ref>\n\n==== Upper stories ====\nEach of the office floors consisted of about {{Convert|48,000|ft2||abbr=}} of space,<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /> though the actual rentable space on each floor ranged from {{convert|20,000|to|30,000|ft2}}.<ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\"/> Because of the \"H\" shaped design, all offices had access to windows.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\" />\n\nThe upper four floors were later converted for use by the [[L\u00e9man Manhattan Preparatory School]], which utilizes a side entrance at 1 Morris Street. The school space contains a cafeteria; 30 classrooms; a library; a 400-seat auditorium; and a {{convert|40,000|ft2|adj=on}} athletic complex with a gym, swimming pool, and rock climbing wall.<ref name=\"Shapiro 2010\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20100920/downtown/claremont-prep-opens-new-40-million-school-downtown|title=Claremont Prep Opens New $40 Million School Downtown|last=Shapiro|first=Julie|date=September 20, 2010|website=DNAinfo New York|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Context ===\nThe site of the Cunard Building was occupied by Dutch houses after the colony of [[New Amsterdam]] was founded in the 17th century.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/iconographyofma_02stok#page/220/mode/2up|title=The iconography of Manhattan Island, 1498\u20131909|last=Phelps Stokes|first=I.N.|date=1916|volume=2|pages=220\u2013222|access-date=January 28, 2020|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> In 1846, the future site of the Cunard Building became a hotel and restaurant operated by Joseph and Lorenzo Delmonico. This later became a hotel called the Stevens House which was popular among shipping and mercantile industry figures.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|p=2}}</ref> By the 1900s and 1910s, the Stevens House name applied to two 5-story buildings at the corner of Broadway and Morris Street.<ref name=\"NYT-Cunard-1919\" /> According to a 1910 photograph, the buildings on 13-27 Broadway were largely commercial and included a restaurant, art publishers, the [[Anchor Line (steamship company)|Anchor Line]] steamship company, hatters, and Stevens House.<ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\"/><ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/bothsidesofbroad00dele|title=Both sides of Broadway, from Bowling Green to Central Park, New York City.|last=De Leeuw|first=Rudolph M.|date=1910|publisher=De Leeuw Riehl publishing company|others=Columbia University Libraries|isbn=|location=|pages=42|oclc=7536624}}</ref> Meanwhile, the lots facing Greenwich and Morris Streets contained [[Manhattan Railway Company]]'s lost-property building and former vice president [[Aaron Burr]]'s old house.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\">{{cite book | title=Architecture and Building | publisher=W.T. Comstock Company | issue=v. 52 | year=1920 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nCznAAAAMAAJ&pg=RA4-PR54 | access-date=February 5, 2020 | pages=4\u20135}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Cunard Line]], for whom the Cunard Building was constructed, was one of the preeminent British transatlantic [[steamship]] companies of the 19th century. Its New York City office, which opened in 1846, had always been situated in or around Bowling Green.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /> After moving several times, the Cunard Line sought \"an adequate and permanent American headquarters\" by the 1910s.<ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\" /> Benjamin Wistar Morris started planning for a new office building for the Cunard Line by August 1917, before the site had even been purchased. His preliminary plans called for a grandiose ticket lobby for Cunard's ticket offices and a smaller elevator lobby for tenants of the upper floors. Despite subsequent modifications to the draft, the two separate lobbies remained in the final plan.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> The individual lots comprising the future Cunard Building were then purchased by the Irons & Todd real-estate firm, which then formed the Todd, Irons & Robertson, Inc. construction company. Irons & Todd eventually hoped to turn over the land to the Twenty-Five Broadway Corporation, a subsidiary headed by an official for the Cunard Line.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" />\n\n=== Construction ===\n[[File:Pilot lore; from sail to steam (1922) (14779091221).jpg|thumb|1922 view from [[Whitehall Street]] to the south]]\nPlans for the Cunard Building were announced in February 1918. At the time, the building was supposed to be 26 stories and cost $10\u201315 million.<ref name=\"NYT-Cunard-1919\" /><ref name=\"Tribune-Cunard-1919\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43161159/|title=Cunard Line Will Build Skyscraper At Bowling Green: Home of Aaron Burr, Stevens House and Other Landmarks Bought|last=|first=|date=February 20, 1918|work=New York Tribune|access-date=January 28, 2020|url-status=live|page=13|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> One ''New York Times'' writer lamented that the plans would involve the destruction of the Stevens House, described as \"the last quaint landmark standing as an interesting connecting link between\" historic and modern New York City.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1918/03/03/archives/passing-of-the-stevens-house.html|title=Passing of the Stevens House|date=March 3, 1918|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Due to World War I, further planning was delayed until June 1919 when Morris was authorized to create \"working drawings, specifications and contracts\".<ref name=\"Morris p. 1\" /> The demolition of the Stevens House began in July 1919, at which point the Cunard Building's final plans were publicized, showing that it was to comprise only 21 stories.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1919/07/20/archives/monumental-broadway-building-for-cunard-steamship-company-a.html|title=Monumental Broadway Building For Cunard Steamship Company; A Structure of Twenty Stories, Representing an Investment of $10,000,000, to be Elected on Site of Old Stevens House on Lower Broadway, Facing Bowling Green|date=July 20, 1919|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Several details were revised in the final plans; for instance, a colonnade on the Broadway facade was replaced with arches.<ref name=\"Morris p. 4\" /> The [[New York City Department of Buildings]] received the blueprints for the Cunard Building in August 1919 and approved the project the next January, allowing construction to begin right afterward.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" />\n\nConstruction was hindered by the presence of [[New York City Subway|subway]] lines directly underneath the building site, as well as the irregular plot shape and \"unknowable\" costs.<ref name=\"Morris p. 1\" /> During construction, the underground BMT Broadway Line was carried on a concrete bed held by [[quicksand]] above the bottom of the Cunard Building's excavation site, in order to dampen the noise. The presence of the subways, combined with the fact that the Cunard site had been assembled from numerous separate plots, made construction more difficult.<ref name=\"Morris pp. 2-3\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Morris|1920|pp=2\u20133}}</ref><ref name=\"AR p. 22\" /> In one construction incident in February 1920, rock blasts from the building's excavation resulted in several subway passengers being injured.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1920/02/19/archives/six-hurt-in-subway-as-blast-hits-train-rocks-from-cunard-building.html|title=Six Hurt In Subway As Blast Hits Train; Rocks from Cunard Building Excavation Bombard B.R.T. Passengers Near Whitehall.|date=February 19, 1920|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The designs of the interior artworks were devised off-site and then transferred to a studio within the Cunard Building.<ref>{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|pp=9\u201310}}</ref> The paintings were then installed within the building in four months; the artists used scaffolds to paint the ceilings while the foundations were still being built beneath them.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 4\" />\n\nThe Cunard Building opened in May 1921<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\" /><ref name=\"nytm51\" /> at a total cost of $15 million.<ref name=\"The Nautical Gazette 1921 p. 434\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mqk5AQAAIAAJ&pg=PA434|title=The Nautical Gazette|year=1921|page=434|access-date=January 29, 2020|issue=v. 100}}</ref> Despite increasing material costs at the end of World War I, the project had been completed on time, within 3% of its original budget.<ref name=\"AB p. 62\">{{harvnb|''Architecture and Building''|1921|ps=.|p=62}}</ref> The Cunard Building was one of several structures built on the lower section of Broadway in the early 20th century that would be affiliated with the maritime trade.<ref>{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|pp=4, 8}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1920/10/03/archives/lower-new-yorks-building-activity-recent-broadway-purchase-by.html|title=Lower New York's Building Activity; Recent Broadway Purchase by Harriman Interests, Near the New Cunard Structure an Object Lesson of Recent Trade Expansion|date=October 3, 1920|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n=== Usage ===\nAt opening, the Great Hall was the home of Cunard and Anchor Lines, which occupied the Great Hall, first three stories, basement, and top floors.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"nytm51\" /> The remaining floors housed numerous other tenants,<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"nytm51\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1921/05/01/archives/new-cunard-building-imposing-office-structure-at-25-broadway-opens.html|title=New Cunard Building; Imposing Office Structure at 25 Broadway Opens Its Doors Tomorrow--Striking Architectural Features|date=May 1, 1921|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> including [[Atlas Portland Cement Company]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1921/02/10/archives/5000000-involved-in-two-big-leases-times-square-corner-leased-by.html|title=$5,000,000 Involved in Two Big Leases|date=February 10, 1921|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[Anaconda Copper]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43288262/|title=Pay $4,200,000 For Space in Steamship Row|date=November 4, 1920|work=New-York Tribune|access-date=January 30, 2020|page=20|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> [[Merchant Shipbuilding Corporation]], [[Consolidated Steel Corporation]], [[International Motor Truck Company]], and Atlantic, Gulf & West Indies Steamship Lines.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> A branch of the [[Mechanics and Metals National Bank]] was located at the first floor, within the retail space on the northeast corner.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes-MM-1921\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1921/05/16/archives/bank-branch-moved-mechanics-and-metals-opens-an-office-in-the.html|title=Bank Branch Moved; Mechanics and Metals Opens an Office in the Cunard Building.|date=May 16, 1921|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Even before the Cunard Building's official opening, it was almost fully leased, with only {{Convert|24,000|ft2|m2|abbr=}} remaining unused by April 1921.<ref name=\"The Nautical Gazette 1921 p. 434\" /> Factors in the Cunard Building's near-complete occupancy included relatively low rents, the inclusion of 21-year leases, the timely completion of the project, and a shortage of available office space in the Financial District.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> In later years, other industries moved into the Cunard Building as well, such as attorneys, railroad and steamship companies, shipbuilding companies, brokers, engineers, and raw materials companies.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /> These included the [[New York Central Railroad]], which moved into the building in 1946.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1946/04/10/archives/ny-central-in-lease-takes-floor-in-25-broadway-for-foreign-freight.html|title=N.Y. Central in Lease; Takes Floor in 25 Broadway for Foreign Freight and Marine|date=April 10, 1946|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThe building's owners were given a loan of $8 million in 1930,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1931/10/10/archives/lends-8000000-at-4-on-the-cunard-building.html|title=Lends $8,000,000 at 4 % On the Cunard Building|date=October 10, 1931|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and another $2.82 million in 1944.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/1282862777/D445EE0D35DD4530PQ|title=Loan of $2,820,000 For Cunard Building|date=April 18, 1944|work=New York Tribune|access-date=January 28, 2020|page=28|via=ProQuest|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1944/04/11/archives/2820000-loan-placed-on-the-cunard-building.html|title=$2,820,000 Loan Placed On the Cunard Building|date=April 11, 1944|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In subsequent years, the assessed taxes for the Cunard Building was reduced multiple times. The New York Supreme Court gave the building's owners tax reprieves in 1946,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1946/01/01/archives/cunard-building-gets-assessment-reduction.html|title=Cunard Building Gets Assessment Reduction|date=January 1, 1946|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> 1948,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1948/03/31/archives/cunard-building-valuations-cut.html|title=Cunard Building Valuations Cut|date=March 31, 1948|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and 1950.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1950/04/22/archives/court-cuts-valuations-lowers-assessments-on-hotel-lincoln-and.html|title=Court Cuts Valuation; Lowers Assessments on Hotel Lincoln and Cunard Building|date=April 22, 1950|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In 1955, the owners completed a $3 million project to add air conditioning to the Cunard Building, one of the largest such retrofits in an existing structure.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/1323294095/D445EE0D35DD4530PQ|title=Space in Cunard Building Cooled at $3,000,000 Cost|date=August 14, 1955|work=New York Tribune|access-date=January 28, 2020|page=3C|via=ProQuest|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/08/21/archives/cunard-building-aircooled.html|title=Cunard Building Air-Cooled|date=August 21, 1955|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nAshforth, Todd & Company purchased the building in 1962.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1962/11/09/archives/25-broadway-building-is-sold-by-cunard-line.html|title=25 Broadway Building Is Sold by Cunard Line|date=November 9, 1962|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Cunard Line continued to operate the ticket hall until 1968, when it moved to [[555 Fifth Avenue]];<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /> the vacant space was then leased by brokerage company Francis I. duPont Co.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1968/12/19/archives/news-of-realty-cunard-tenancy-francis-i-dupont-leases-space-at-25.html|title=News of Realty: Cunard Tenancy; Francis I. duPont Leases Space at 25 Broadway|date=December 19, 1968|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The building was sold again in 1971, this time to the Cementation Company of America, a subsidiary of [[Trafalgar House (company)|Trafalgar House Investment Group]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/07/01/archives/trafalgar-house-reveals-576million-cunard-bid.html|title=Trafalgar House Reveals $57.6\u2010Million Cunard Bid|date=July 1, 1971|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Initially, the owners had difficulty finding tenants for the Great Hall due to its vast size.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/119455656/F536749CA6244088PQ|title=Tenant Hunted for Cunard Building's 'Great Hall'|date=October 1, 1972|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|via=ProQuest|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The [[United States Postal Service]] leased the Great Hall in 1974, intending to relocate its post office from the nearby [[Alexander Hamilton U.S. Custom House]] two years later.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1974/09/16/archives/cunard-will-lease-its-great-hall-to-postal-service-move-planned-in.html|title=Cunard Will Lease Its Great Hall to Postal Service|last=Horsley|first=Carter B.|date=September 16, 1974|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> By 1977, the USPS had moved into the Great Hall, and [[Standard & Poor's]] had signed a 20-year lease for space at the Cunard Building.<ref name=\"Oser 1977\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/12/07/archives/about-real-estate-gradual-changes-for-the-old-cunard-building.html|title=About Real Estate|last=Oser|first=Alan S.|date=December 7, 1977|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The building was sold to Zev W. Wolfson for $15 million by 1979.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/10/10/archives/real-estate-a-foreign-interest-in-manhattan.html|title=Real Estate|date=1979-10-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The [[City College of New York]]'s Center For Worker Education was established on the seventh floor of the Cunard Building in 1981.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ccny.cuny.edu/news/%E2%80%9C-realm%E2%80%9D-opens-ccnys-sixth-annual-taffny-film-festival|title='The Realm' opens CCNY's sixth annual TAFFNY film festival|last=|first=|date=June 11, 2019|website=www.ccny.cuny.edu|publisher=The City College of New York|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Elizabeth Berger Plaza 78 - L\u00e9man Manhattan.jpg|alt=L\u00e9man Manhattan Preparatory School sign|thumb|[[L\u00e9man Manhattan Preparatory School]] sign outside the Morris Street entrance]]\n\nIn 1995, the exterior and the first floor interior of the Cunard Building, along with several other buildings on Bowling Green,{{efn|Namely [[26 Broadway]]; the [[Bowling Green Offices Building]]; and the [[International Mercantile Marine Company Building]]<ref name=\"Dunlap 1995\" />}} were formally designated as New York City landmarks.<ref name=\"Dunlap 1995\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/10/15/realestate/bringing-downtown-back-up.html|title=Bringing Downtown Back Up|last=Dunlap|first=David W.|date=1995-10-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>{{efn|The interior designation included the entrance vestibules and lobby, the passage to the Great Hall, and the Hall up to the height of its rotunda.<ref name=\"lpc95\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=1}}</ref>}} Two years later, S&P vacated its spaces at the Cunard Building, as well as at [[26 Broadway]] directly to the east, when the company started leasing space at nearby [[55 Water Street]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Oser|first=Alan S.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/08/03/realestate/downtown-is-looking-up.html|title=Downtown Is Looking Up|date=August 3, 1997|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>  The post office closed in 2000.<ref>{{cite web | last=Geier | first=Stephanie | title=A Look Inside the Opulent Cunard Building in NYC | website=Untapped New York | date=December 4, 2015 | url=https://untappedcities.com/2015/12/04/a-look-inside-the-opulent-cunard-building-in-nyc/ | access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> Afterward, the Great Hall went unused again for over a decade. ''The New York Times'' cited the hall's landmark status as a factor in the difficulty of leasing the space.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/23/realestate/commercial/the-tricky-task-of-renovating-a-buildings-landmark-interior.html|title=The Tricky Task of Renovating a Building Without Altering Its Landmark Insides|last=Hughes|first=C. J.|date=November 22, 2011|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The doors were locked, barring visitors from entering the Great Hall.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/20/nyregion/so-you-think-you-can-see-a-landmark.html|title=So, You Think You Can See a Landmark?|last=Dunlap|first=David W.|date=2006-01-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-30|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> During the mid-2000s, the [[Sports Museum of America]] considered opening within the Great Hall,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2004/11/02/sports-hall-switches-sides-founder-crosses-bway-to-keep-national-museum-in-play/|title=Sports Hall Switches Sides \u2013 Founder Crosses B'way To Keep National Museum In Play|last=Cuozzo|first=Steve|date=2004-11-02|website=New York Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Pennington|first=Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/13/sports/ncaafootball/sports-museum-and-heisman-find-place-in-lower-manhattan.html|title=Sports Museum and Heisman Find Place in Lower Manhattan|date=2005-04-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> but the museum ultimately opened in 2008 at 26 Broadway.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/12/arts/artsspecial/12sport.html|title=Luring Sports Fans of All Seasons to Lower Manhattan|date=2008-03-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In 2014, the Great Hall was leased to [[Cipriani S.A.]] for the operation of an event venue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribecacitizen.com/2014/01/09/cipriani-is-adding-another-grand-space-to-its-empire/|title=Cipriani Is Adding Another Grand Space to Its Empire|date=January 9, 2014|website=Tribeca Citizen|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2015/02/16/lower-broadway-finally-blossoming-after-years-of-neglect/|title=Lower Broadway finally blossoming after years of neglect|last=Cuozzo|first=Steve|date=February 17, 2015|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe upper floors remained in use by multiple tenants, including school and college campuses. In 2002, [[Deloitte]] leased three floors of the Cunard Building after its previous offices at the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] were destroyed in the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/03/27/business/commercial-real-estate-deloitte-picks-light-flexibility-and-link-to-history.html|title=Commercial Real Estate; Deloitte Picks Light, Flexibility and Link to History|last=McDowell|first=Edwin|date=2002-03-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-30|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[L\u00e9man Manhattan Preparatory School]] moved to the Cunard Building in 2010,<ref name=\"Shapiro 2010\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/05/nyregion/05claremont.html|title=Claremont Prep Is Sold to For-Profit Firm|last=Anderson|first=Jenny|date=April 4, 2011|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 30, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>{{efn|At the time of the purchase, it was known as the Claremont Preparatory School;<ref name=\"Shapiro 2010\" /> the name was changed to L\u00e9man in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/08/31/in-private-school-world-a-rush-to-be-international/|title=In Private School World, a Rush to Be 'International'|last=Anderson|first=Jenny|date=2011-08-31|website=City Room|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>}} occupying the top four floors for its middle and high school campuses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2014/10/07/take-a-look-inside-manhattans-first-and-only-boarding-school/|title=Inside Manhattan's first & only boarding school|last=Ridley|first=Jane|date=October 7, 2014|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> [[Relay Graduate School of Education]], a private graduate school for teachers, moved into the building in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/06/25/education-nonprofit-moves-into-historical-cunard-building/|title=Education nonprofit moves into historical Cunard Building|last=Weiss|first=Lois|date=June 26, 2019|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\nUpon its opening, writers praised the Cunard Building's design. ''[[Architectural Forum]]'' magazine published six pieces about the Cunard Building in its July 1921 volume alone.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" />{{efn|For a list of these pieces, see {{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.}}}} In one such piece, art historian [[Royal Cortissoz]] described the external plan as \"indeed organic architecture\", writing that the \"genuine architectural inspiration [sprang] straight from the personality of the designer\".<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref>{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|pp=4, 5, 8}}</ref> ''Architecture and Building'' called the site \"exceedingly well chosen\",<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /> and the ''New-York Tribune'' called the Cunard Building \"one of the fine structures of the city\".<ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\" /> Other critics praised the building's manner of construction, and how it had been built above the Broadway subway line.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" />\n\nThe interior was similarly regarded. In a piece for ''American Architect and Architecture'' in 1928, C.H. Blackall described the building as having \"a magnificent counting room\", and that the domed ceiling had \"individuality and a most charmingly successful decorative effect.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nKkwAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA11|title=American Architect and Architecture|publisher=J. R. Osgood & Company|year=1928|page=11|access-date=January 30, 2020|issue=v. 133}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=3}}</ref> David Dunlap of ''The New York Times'' said in 1991 that the Great Hall was \"one of New York's most magnificent\u2014and least appreciated\u2014public spaces\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/09/15/travel/hidden-corners-of-lower-manhattan.html|title=Hidden Corners of Lower Manhattan|last=Dunlap|first=David W.|date=1991-09-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-30|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Landmarks Preservation Commission, in its 1995 landmark-designation report, called the hall \"among New York's most impressive interiors\".<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 4\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|New York City|Architecture}}\n* [[List of buildings and structures on Broadway in Manhattan]]\n* [[List of New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan below 14th Street]]\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{notelist}}\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{commons category|25 Broadway Cunard Building}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |title=Cunard Building |url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1928.pdf |date=September 19, 1995 |publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] |ref={{harvid|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995}}}}\n* {{cite web |title=Cunard Building, First Floor Interior |url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1929.pdf |date=September 19, 1995 |publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] |ref={{harvid|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995}}}}\n* {{cite journal|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|title=Cunard Building|ref={{harvid|''Architectural Forum''|1921}}|pages=1\u201324|postscript=:}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=11|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=Royal|last=Cortissoz|title=The Cunard Building|pages=1\u20138}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=29|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=Ezra|last=Winter|title=Mural Decorations of the Cunard Building|pages=9\u201316}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=49|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=S.O|last=Miller|title=Structural Features of the Cunard Building, New York|pages=17\u201320}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=53|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=Carlton S.|last=Proctor|title=Special Problems in Foundations of the Cunard Building|pages=21\u201322|via=}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=54|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=Henry C., Jr.|last=Meyer|title=Electrical, Heating and Ventilating Equipment of the Cunard Building|pages=22\u201323|via=}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=56|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=Clyde R.|last=Place|title=Plumbing in the Cunard Building|pages=24|via=}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Morris|first=Benjamin Wistar|date=July 1920|title=The Cunard Building, New York|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015082471254&view=1up&seq=15|journal=Architectural Forum|volume=33|pages=1\u20136|ref={{harvid|Morris|1920}}}}\n* {{cite journal|year=1921|title=The Cunard Building, New York|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Hy_nAAAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PR19|journal=Architecture and Building|publisher=W.T. Comstock Company|volume=53|pages=61\u201364|ref={{sfnref |''Architecture and Building''| 1921}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Broadway (Manhattan)}}\n{{Financial District, Manhattan}}\n\n[[Category:Carr\u00e8re and Hastings buildings]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City interior landmarks]]\n[[Category:Financial District, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Broadway (Manhattan)]]\n[[Category:1921 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 1921]]\n[[Category:Bowling Green (New York City)]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Cunard Building{{!}}Cunard Building, Liverpool}}\n{{short description|Office skyscraper in Manhattan, New York}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name = Cunard Building\n| image = File:Bowling Green-Battery Pk 01 - Cunard.jpg\n| image_size =\n| image_caption =\n| former_names =\n| alternate_names = Standard & Poors Building\n| status = Complete\n| building_type = Office\n| architectural_style = [[Renaissance Revival architecture|Neo-Renaissance]]\n| classification =\n| location = 25 [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]]<br />[[Financial District, Manhattan]], New York\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|42|21|N|74|00|51|W|display=inline,title}}\n| groundbreaking_date =\n| start_date = 1920\n| stop_date =\n| topped_out_date =\n| completion_date = 1921\n| opened_date = May 2, 1921\n| inauguration_date =\n| client = [[Cunard Line]]\n| owner =\n| height = {{convert|254.74|ft|m}}\n| material =\n| size =\n| floor_count = 22 (+1 basement)\n| floor_area =\n| elevator_count =\n| architect = [[Benjamin Wistar Morris (architect)|Benjamin Wistar Morris III]]\n| architecture_firm = [[Carr\u00e8re & Hastings]]\n| embedded = {{Designation list\n| embed = yes\n| designation1 = NYC\n| designation1_date = September 19, 1995\n| designation1_number = 1928 (exterior), 1929 (interior)\n}}\n| references = <ref name=\"emporis\" />\n}}\nThe '''Cunard Building''', also known as the '''Standard & Poors Building''', is a 22-story office building located at 25 [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]], adjacent to [[Bowling Green (New York City)|Bowling Green Park]] in the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]] of [[Lower Manhattan]] in [[New York City]]. The Cunard Building was designed in the [[Renaissance architecture|Italian Renaissance]] style by [[Benjamin Wistar Morris (architect)|Benjamin Wistar Morris]], in conjunction with consultants [[Carr\u00e8re & Hastings]].\n\nThe Cunard Building's main facade, on Broadway, is made of limestone and consists of three horizontal sections. The design employs [[Setback (architecture)|setbacks]] and open \"light courts\" as mandated by the [[1916 Zoning Resolution]]. The structure was designed around an irregular street grid and is located directly above a [[New York City Subway|subway]] line that crosses the building site diagonally. The first floor interior contains an elaborately decorated lobby, as well as a similarly opulent Great Hall, which extends {{Convert|185|ft||abbr=}} with a {{Convert|65|ft|m|abbr=|-tall|adj=mid}} dome. The remaining floors contain various offices and school spaces.\n\nThe Cunard Building was erected for the New York City office of the [[Cunard Line]], a British-American steamship line; construction started in 1920 and the building was completed the next year. Upon completion, the Cunard Building was almost fully leased to tenants of various industries. The Twenty-five Broadway Corporation, a Cunard Line affiliate, owned the building until the 1960s. The Great Hall was vacated after the Cunard Line moved out in 1968; the [[United States Postal Service]] occupied the Great Hall from 1974 until 2000, and [[Cipriani S.A.]] started using the space in 2014. The upper floors continued to host offices and various educational facilities.\n\nUpon completion, the Cunard Building's exterior and interior designs received critical acclaim. The Cunard Building's facade and principal first-floor interior spaces were designated as [[List of New York City Landmarks|landmarks]] by the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] in 1995.\n\n== Description ==\nThe Cunard Building is a 22-story building,<ref name=\"emporis\" /> bounded by the [[Bowling Green Offices Building]] (11 Broadway) to the south, Broadway to the east, [[Greenwich Street]] to the west, and Morris Street to the north.<ref name=\"NYT-Cunard-1919\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1918/02/20/archives/cunard-to-have-big-building-here-10000000-structure-of-26-stories.html|title=Cunard To Have Big Building Here; $10,000,000 Structure of 26 Stories Going Up on Site of Old Stevens House.|last=|first=|date=February 20, 1918|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"Tribune-Cunard-1919\" /> It is located across from [[Bowling Green (New York City)|Bowling Green Park]] to the southeast, and [[26 Broadway]] and the ''[[Charging Bull]]'' sculpture to the east.<ref name=\"lpc95\" /> While 25 Broadway is considered to be its primary address, it is also known as 13\u201327 Broadway, 13\u201339 Greenwich Street, and 1\u20139 Morris Street.<ref name=\"emporis\">{{cite web |url=https://www.emporis.com/buildings/115358/standard-poors-building-new-york-city-ny-usa |title=Standard & Poors Building |website=Emporis |accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"lpc95\" /> The Cunard Building has a [[frontage]] of {{Convert|203|ft||abbr=}} along Broadway, {{Convert|231|ft||abbr=}} along Greenwich Street, and {{Convert|248|ft||abbr=}} along Morris Street.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\">{{harvnb|''Architecture and Building''|1921|ps=.|p=61}}</ref> Due to the irregular street grid of the area, none of its corners are at right angles.<ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\">{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=October 1919|title=The Cunard Building, New York|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.c2640733&view=1up&seq=260|journal=Architectural Review|volume=26|pages=113\u2013114|via=}}</ref><ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43286591/|title=$20,000,000 Office Building Projects of Cunard and Munson Lines Completed|date=May 1, 1921|work=New-York Tribune|access-date=January 30, 2020|page=37|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref>\n\nThe Cunard Building was largely designed by [[Benjamin Wistar Morris (architect)|Benjamin Wistar Morris]].<ref name=\"NYT-Cunard-1919\" /> The [[massing]] and [[facade]] were devised by [[Carr\u00e8re and Hastings]], while exterior detail was created by Rochette & Parzini.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|p=5}}</ref> The structure was laid out so that ancillary structures such as smoke stacks, penthouses, and storage tanks could not be seen from the side. Its location near ferry slips, the [[New York City Subway]], elevated [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company|Interborough Rapid Transit]] lines, and the [[Hudson & Manhattan Railroad]]'s [[Hudson Terminal]] made the Cunard Building desirable to tenants.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> In the 1970s, the Cunard Building became known as the Standard & Poors Building, after its tenant [[Standard & Poor's]],<ref name=\"Oser 1977\" /> though the name also came to refer to nearby structures.{{efn|The Standard & Poor's Building may refer to [[65 Broadway]]<ref>{{cite aia5|page=22}}</ref> or [[55 Water Street]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Standard & Poor's, Given Subsidies, Is to Stay in New York | website=The New York Times | date=April 25, 1997 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/04/25/nyregion/standard-poor-s-given-subsidies-is-to-stay-in-new-york.html | access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>}}\n\n=== Form ===\n[[File:Bowling Green NYC Feb 2020 78 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Eastern facade seen from across Broadway]]\nAt the time of the Cunard Building's construction, large buildings in New York City were being erected in a \"C\" or \"H\" shape to maximize illumination of the interior space.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> Additionally, the [[1916 Zoning Resolution]] necessitated the inclusion of [[Setback (architecture)|setbacks]] on buildings in New York City that were above a certain height.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/26/nyregion/new-yorks-first-zoning-resolution-which-brought-order-to-a-chaotic-building-boom-turns-100.html|title=Zoning Arrived 100 Years Ago. It Changed New York City Forever.|last=Dunlap|first=David W.|date=July 25, 2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Cunard Building was the first large structure built in the city after the end of [[World War I]], and set an example for compliance to the 1916 law.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" />\n\nThe building is H-shaped, with \"light courts\" facing north toward Morris Street and south toward the Bowling Green Building.<ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> The \"light courts\" are located above the base. The placement of these courts allowed light to enter the Great Hall, located on the first floor.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /> Because of the presence of large intersections on either side of the building (Bowling Green to the east and the intersection of Greenwich Street and [[Trinity Place]] to the west), the required setback under the 1916 zoning law was minimal.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|p=3}}</ref> According to Morris, the irregular street grid of the neighborhood made it difficult to determine the orientation of the building; he finally decided on its current alignment since, at the time, it would have been possible to see the [[North River (Hudson River)]] to the south.<ref name=\"Morris p. 1\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Morris|1920|p=1}}</ref>\n\n=== Foundation ===\nThe New York City Subway's [[BMT Broadway Line]] (now the {{NYCS trains|Broadway south day}}) crosses diagonally underneath the Cunard Building from northwest to southeast. Two additional subway lines, the [[IRT Lexington Avenue Line]] ({{NYCS trains|Lexington south}}) and the [[IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line]] ({{NYCS trains|Broadway-Seventh South Ferry}}), run adjacent to the western and eastern boundaries of the building, respectively.<ref name=\"AR pp. 21\">{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|p=21}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://new.mta.info/document/2461|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Bowling Green (4)(5)|date=2018|website=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|mta.info]]|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=September 13, 2018}}</ref> The Lexington Avenue Line's [[Bowling Green station]] is located directly under the building's boundary, while the Broadway Line's [[Whitehall Street station]] is located one block south.<ref name=\":0\" /> Because of the confluence of subway tunnels in the area, the Cunard Building's foundation was built around the subway.<ref name=\"Morris pp. 2-3\" /><ref name=\"AR p. 22\">{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|p=22}}</ref>\n\nDuring construction, the engineers considered and rejected an idea for placing the Cunard Building's [[girder]]s on the roof of the Broadway Line tunnel, since that would have resulted in vibrations every time a subway train passed by.<ref name=\"AR pp. 21\" /> Furthermore, the subway tunnel was designed to support the weight of several small buildings and might not have been able to support one large building.<ref name=\"Morris pp. 2-3\" /><ref>{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|pp=17\u201318}}</ref> Instead, engineers decided to place the building's foundation columns on either side of the subway tunnel, and then erect girders for the building above the tunnel's roof. The foundation columns were placed as close to the subway tunnel as possible, in order to reduce the length of the trusses, which would have had to carry heavy loads. All of the foundation columns were sunk to the depth of the rock underneath.<ref name=\"AR pp. 21\" />\n\nA [[cofferdam]] was then built on the eastern border of the site, and on part of the northern border. The rock surface underneath the building site was closer to the ground on the western side of the lot, requiring extensive excavation. On the eastern side of the lot, the rock surface sloped below the elevation of the subway tunnel. A {{Convert|6|ft|m|-thick|abbr=|adj=mid}} wall was built on the southern boundary of the Cunard lot, of which a {{Convert|2|ft||adj=on}} width was located under the Bowling Green Offices Building. The wall served several purposes: it closed the cofferdam, underpinned the subway, and provided support for the columns on the southern side of the Cunard Building.<ref name=\"AR p. 22\" />\n\n=== Facade ===\n\n==== Broadway elevation ====\n[[File:Bowling Green-Battery Pk 03 - Cunard.jpg|thumb|left|Center arches at the base|alt=]]\nThe facade at the Broadway [[Elevation (architecture)|elevation]] is made of [[Indiana Limestone]], making Cunard Building part of a masonry \"canyon\" on lower Broadway.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /> It is divided into three horizontal sections on the western and eastern facades. The outermost portions of these facades consist of pavilions that project outward, while the central pavilion is set back {{Convert|5|ft||abbr=}}.<ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\" /><ref name=\"Morris p. 4\">{{harvnb|Morris|1920|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> The projecting \"side pavilions\" rise to the maximum height allowed under the 1916 law.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Morris p. 4\" /> On the Broadway facade, the side pavilions are {{Convert|50|ft||abbr=}} wide, while the central pavilion is about {{Convert|103|ft||abbr=}} wide.<ref name=\"Morris p. 4\" />\n\nThe Broadway facade contains decorative elements that signify the area's historic connections with the maritime industry, including \"nautically-inspired sculpted elements\", decorative [[Keystone (architecture)|keystones]] above the first-floor arches, decorative ship-themed [[roundel]]s above the third-floor loggia, and carvings of seahorses with their riders above the pavilions' setbacks.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"AB p. 62\" />\n\nWithin the four-story base, the central section is recessed slightly. The first floor contains five double-height arches, set within [[Rustication (architecture)|rusticated]] masonry, facing east toward Broadway.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|p=6}}</ref> The center three arches, within the recessed central pavilion, lead to the Great Hall; the southernmost arch leads to the elevator lobby for the office space above; and the northernmost arch led to a banking area on the north side of the building.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /> All the arches contain doors and windows with bronze frames.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=6}}</ref> The third and fourth floors contain an Ionic-style [[loggia]] structure supported by [[Italianate architecture|Tuscan-style]] column pairs. Above the base, the facade is mostly composed of smooth limestone, except for rustication around the fifth story windows. The columns of windows around the central pavilion, which is recessed further, are also set within a rusticated facade. The outer pavilions are set back beyond the 18th story to comply with the 1916 Zoning Resolution. The central pavilion contains a loggia between the 19th and 21st stories, also supported by Tuscan-style column pairs, and includes a [[mansard roof]] above the 22nd story. The roofs of the outer pavilions, above the 22nd story, are flat.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" />\n\n==== Other elevations ====\n{{multiple image\n|total_width=450\n|image1=Cunard Building side Feb 2020 02.jpg\n|caption1=Morris Street facade, looking up at the light court, which is faced mostly in brick. The section at far left, closest to Broadway, is faced with limestone\n|image2=Cunard Building rear Feb 2020 2.jpg\n|caption2=Greenwich Street facade, with the triple-height window recessed at an angle. Below is the full-height basement, faced with granite\n}}\nOn Morris Street, the first and second stories are faced with limestone, while the basement is faced with a [[Water table (architecture)|water table]] made of granite. Above the second story is a light court. The facade of the eastern wing (facing Broadway) is limestone, while the rest of the Morris Street facade is made of tan brick. There are also numerous glazed doors with bronze frames, as well as glazed paneled windows with metal frames. The remaining windows on Morris Street are [[sash window]]s.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" />\n\nOn Greenwich Street, the basement is faced with granite and the remaining stories are faced with tan brick. The basement contains service doors, a garage door, and metal window openings. Above the garage door is a large triple-height arched window on the first through third floors, with balconies on the second and third floors; the window is recessed at an angle. The remaining windows on Greenwich Street are sash windows. There is a [[cornice]] of stone above the 22nd floor. The southernmost section of the Greenwich Street facade only goes to the third floor<!-- four stories high, including basement --> to allow light to enter the light court within the southern side of the building.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /> The gray brick at both Morris and Greenwich Streets was designed to \"harmoniz[e] closely with the limestone\".<ref name=\"AB p. 62\" />\n\nThe south elevation consists of a brick facade with sash windows. The light court faces south toward the Bowling Green Offices Building.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" />\n\n=== Interior ===\nAt opening, the Cunard Building featured over {{convert|700,000|ft2||abbr=}} of space, of which {{Convert|500,000|ft2||abbr=}} was made available for tenants when it opened. A basement in the building contained a safe-deposit vault.<ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\" /> The structure also included a fireproof internal structure.<ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\">{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=August 2, 1919|title=Unusual Features Mark Plans of New Cunard Building|url=https://rerecord.library.columbia.edu/pdf_files/ldpd_7031148_064_32.pdf|journal=The Real Estate Record: Real Estate Record and Builders' Guide|volume=104|pages=141|via=[[Columbia University|columbia.edu]]|number=5}}</ref> According to data collected by ''[[The Real Deal (magazine)|The Real Deal]]'' magazine, the precise floor area of the Cunard Building is {{convert|809,401|ft2}}.<ref>{{cite web | title=25 Broadway \u2013 TRD Research | website=The Real Deal | date=March 13, 2019 | url=https://therealdeal.com/new-research/topics/property/25-broadway/ | access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe building also contained 36 elevators: 33 for passengers and 3 for freight.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Morris p. 3\">{{harvnb|Morris|1920|ps=.|p=3}}</ref> Of the passenger elevators, 28 were \"high-speed\" elevators for general use and the remaining 5 were private cabs.<ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\" /><ref name=\"Morris p. 3\" /><ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\"/> Twenty of the \"high-speed\" elevators were local and express elevators, accessible from the elevator lobby at the southern end of the Broadway facade. The other eight were located at the building's northwest corner, near Greenwich and Morris Streets.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" />\n\n==== Lobby and Great Hall ====\n{{Multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| total_width = 250\n| image1 = Cunard Building 02.JPG\n| caption1 = Lobby\n| image2 = Cunard 6.jpg\n| caption2 = Great Hall\n}}\n\nThe main entrance is from Broadway, through the three center arches, each of which contains a small entrance vestibule inside. The vestibules and the two outer arches all lead to the building's main lobby.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 12\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=12}}</ref> The lobby contains a ceiling of five [[groin vault]]s, each of which correspond to one of the arches on the Broadway facade. The floors are made of [[travertine]] with [[marble]] trim and contain maritime-themed bronze medallions.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> The walls are also made of travertine; there is a fireplace on the southern wall and a roll-down gate and doors on the northern wall.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> A passageway runs along the western wall of the lobby, connecting the northern four bays to the Great Hall to the west.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 12\" /> The building's original owners had decided against putting \"miscellaneous minor business adventures\" in the lobby, such as newsstands, shoe-shine stands, and cigar shops.<ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\"/>\n\nThe Great Hall, extending {{Convert|185|ft||abbr=}} from east to west,<ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\" /><ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\" /> was described as \"the largest of its kind\" within the United States when completed, and was compared to the waiting rooms of railroad terminals.<ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\" /><ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 4\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> It includes three separate vaults. The central vault is {{Convert|65|ft||abbr=}} tall with a diameter of {{Convert|70|ft||abbr=}}.<ref name=\"Morris p. 1\" /><ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\" /><ref name=\"nytm51\" /> There are large arched windows or \"luminary squares\" at the ends of its diagonal axes, under which are Ionic columns.<ref name=\"Morris p. 1\" /><ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /><ref name=\"AB p. 63\">{{harvnb|''Architecture and Building''|1921|ps=.|p=63}}</ref> Flanking the main dome are two spaces with rectangular [[rib vault]]s, which extend the hall to the west and east.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /><ref name=\"AB p. 63\" /> There are additional arched openings through the west and east walls of the Great Hall: the former leads to a window facing Greenwich Street, while the latter leads to the lobby.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> As built, the hall was overlooked by wrought-iron balconies on the east wall, designed by [[Samuel Yellin]].<ref name=\"AB p. 63\" /> The features are reminiscent of [[Thermae|Roman bathhouses]] and the treatment of the artwork resembles that at the [[Villa Madama]]'s loggia in Italy.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 4\" />\n\nThe north side of the Cunard Building's first floor contained a banking area, which had a private elevator to the fourth floor and a basement-level bank vault.<ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\"/> This was initially occupied by a branch of the [[Mechanics and Metals National Bank]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes-MM-1921\"/>\n\nThe first floor contains numerous elaborate works of art.<ref name=\"nycland\">{{cite nycland|page=10}}</ref> The lobby ceiling was painted by [[Ezra Winter]] and sculpted by [[C. Paul Jennewein|Carl Jennewein]], and contains decorations of marine animals and children.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /><ref name=\"nycland\" /> The lobby's end bays also contain [[bas-relief]]s carved by Jennewein.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> Wrought-iron screens topped by [[lunette]] grilles, designed by [[Samuel Yellin]], separate the passageway from both the lobby to the east and the Great Hall to the west.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> The ceiling of the Great Hall contains maritime-themed frescoes, which Winter painted using the [[fresco-secco]] method,<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 4\" /><ref>{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|p=13}}</ref> which depicted maritime activity.<ref>{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|p=16}}</ref> [[Barry Faulkner]] painted murals of maps into the walls of the Great Hall's niches.<ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\" /><ref name=\"nycland\" /> The [[pendentive]]s of the Great Hall's dome include depictions of oceanic explorers [[Leif Erikson]], [[Christopher Columbus]], [[Sebastian Cabot (explorer)|Sebastian Cabot]], and [[Francis Drake]].<ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Morris|1920|ps=.|p=6}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 6\" /> On the Great Hall's floor is a marble compass surrounded by a bronze frieze, designed by [[John Gregory (sculptor)|John Gregory]] as an \"allegory of the sea\".<ref>{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=7}}</ref>\n\n==== Upper stories ====\nEach of the office floors consisted of about {{Convert|48,000|ft2||abbr=}} of space,<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /> though the actual rentable space on each floor ranged from {{convert|20,000|to|30,000|ft2}}.<ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\"/> Because of the \"H\" shaped design, all offices had access to windows.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"RER-Features-1919\" />\n\nThe upper four floors were later converted for use by the [[L\u00e9man Manhattan Preparatory School]], which utilizes a side entrance at 1 Morris Street. The school space contains a cafeteria; 30 classrooms; a library; a 400-seat auditorium; and a {{convert|40,000|ft2|adj=on}} athletic complex with a gym, swimming pool, and rock climbing wall.<ref name=\"Shapiro 2010\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20100920/downtown/claremont-prep-opens-new-40-million-school-downtown|title=Claremont Prep Opens New $40 Million School Downtown|last=Shapiro|first=Julie|date=September 20, 2010|website=DNAinfo New York|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Context ===\nThe site of the Cunard Building was occupied by Dutch houses after the colony of [[New Amsterdam]] was founded in the 17th century.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/iconographyofma_02stok#page/220/mode/2up|title=The iconography of Manhattan Island, 1498\u20131909|last=Phelps Stokes|first=I.N.|date=1916|volume=2|pages=220\u2013222|access-date=January 28, 2020|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> In 1846, the future site of the Cunard Building became a hotel and restaurant operated by Joseph and Lorenzo Delmonico. This later became a hotel called the Stevens House which was popular among shipping and mercantile industry figures.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|p=2}}</ref> By the 1900s and 1910s, the Stevens House name applied to two 5-story buildings at the corner of Broadway and Morris Street.<ref name=\"NYT-Cunard-1919\" /> According to a 1910 photograph, the buildings on 13-27 Broadway were largely commercial and included a restaurant, art publishers, the [[Anchor Line (steamship company)|Anchor Line]] steamship company, hatters, and Stevens House.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/bothsidesofbroad00dele|title=Both sides of Broadway, from Bowling Green to Central Park, New York City.|last=De Leeuw|first=Rudolph M.|date=1910|publisher=De Leeuw Riehl publishing company|others=Columbia University Libraries|isbn=|location=|pages=42|oclc=7536624}}</ref><ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\"/> Meanwhile, the lots facing Greenwich and Morris Streets contained [[Manhattan Railway Company]]'s lost-property building and former vice president [[Aaron Burr]]'s old house.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref name=\"Architecture and Building 1920 p. 4\">{{cite book | title=Architecture and Building | publisher=W.T. Comstock Company | issue=v. 52 | year=1920 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nCznAAAAMAAJ&pg=RA4-PR54 | access-date=February 5, 2020 | pages=4\u20135}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Cunard Line]], for whom the Cunard Building was constructed, was one of the preeminent British transatlantic [[steamship]] companies of the 19th century. Its New York City office, which opened in 1846, had always been situated in or around Bowling Green.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /> After moving several times, the Cunard Line sought \"an adequate and permanent American headquarters\" by the 1910s.<ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\" /> Benjamin Wistar Morris started planning for a new office building for the Cunard Line by August 1917, before the site had even been purchased. His preliminary plans called for a grandiose ticket lobby for Cunard's ticket offices and a smaller elevator lobby for tenants of the upper floors. Despite subsequent modifications to the draft, the two separate lobbies remained in the final plan.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /> The individual lots comprising the future Cunard Building were then purchased by the Irons & Todd real-estate firm, which then formed the Todd, Irons & Robertson, Inc. construction company. Irons & Todd eventually hoped to turn over the land to the Twenty-Five Broadway Corporation, a subsidiary headed by an official for the Cunard Line.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" />\n\n=== Construction ===\n[[File:Pilot lore; from sail to steam (1922) (14779091221).jpg|thumb|1922 view from [[Whitehall Street]] to the south]]\nPlans for the Cunard Building were announced in February 1918. At the time, the building was supposed to be 26 stories and cost $10\u201315 million.<ref name=\"NYT-Cunard-1919\" /><ref name=\"Tribune-Cunard-1919\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43161159/|title=Cunard Line Will Build Skyscraper At Bowling Green: Home of Aaron Burr, Stevens House and Other Landmarks Bought|last=|first=|date=February 20, 1918|work=New York Tribune|access-date=January 28, 2020|url-status=live|page=13|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> One ''New York Times'' writer lamented that the plans would involve the destruction of the Stevens House, described as \"the last quaint landmark standing as an interesting connecting link between\" historic and modern New York City.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1918/03/03/archives/passing-of-the-stevens-house.html|title=Passing of the Stevens House|date=March 3, 1918|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Due to World War I, further planning was delayed until June 1919 when Morris was authorized to create \"working drawings, specifications and contracts\".<ref name=\"Morris p. 1\" /> The demolition of the Stevens House began in July 1919, at which point the Cunard Building's final plans were publicized, showing that it was to comprise only 21 stories.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1919/07/20/archives/monumental-broadway-building-for-cunard-steamship-company-a.html|title=Monumental Broadway Building For Cunard Steamship Company; A Structure of Twenty Stories, Representing an Investment of $10,000,000, to be Elected on Site of Old Stevens House on Lower Broadway, Facing Bowling Green|date=July 20, 1919|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Several details were revised in the final plans; for instance, a colonnade on the Broadway facade was replaced with arches.<ref name=\"Morris p. 4\" /> The [[New York City Department of Buildings]] received the blueprints for the Cunard Building in August 1919 and approved the project the next January, allowing construction to begin right afterward.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" />\n\nConstruction was hindered by the presence of [[New York City Subway|subway]] lines directly underneath the building site, as well as the irregular plot shape and \"unknowable\" costs.<ref name=\"Morris p. 1\" /> During construction, the underground BMT Broadway Line was carried on a concrete bed held by [[quicksand]] above the bottom of the Cunard Building's excavation site, in order to dampen the noise. The presence of the subways, combined with the fact that the Cunard site had been assembled from numerous separate plots, made construction more difficult.<ref name=\"Morris pp. 2-3\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Morris|1920|pp=2\u20133}}</ref><ref name=\"AR p. 22\" /> In one construction incident in February 1920, rock blasts from the building's excavation resulted in several subway passengers being injured.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1920/02/19/archives/six-hurt-in-subway-as-blast-hits-train-rocks-from-cunard-building.html|title=Six Hurt In Subway As Blast Hits Train; Rocks from Cunard Building Excavation Bombard B.R.T. Passengers Near Whitehall.|date=February 19, 1920|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The designs of the interior artworks were devised off-site and then transferred to a studio within the Cunard Building.<ref>{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|pp=9\u201310}}</ref> The paintings were then installed within the building in four months; the artists used scaffolds to paint the ceilings while the foundations were still being built beneath them.<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 4\" />\n\nThe Cunard Building opened in May 1921<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\" /><ref name=\"nytm51\" /> at a total cost of $15 million.<ref name=\"The Nautical Gazette 1921 p. 434\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mqk5AQAAIAAJ&pg=PA434|title=The Nautical Gazette|year=1921|page=434|access-date=January 29, 2020|issue=v. 100}}</ref> Despite increasing material costs at the end of World War I, the project had been completed on time, within 3% of its original budget.<ref name=\"AB p. 62\">{{harvnb|''Architecture and Building''|1921|ps=.|p=62}}</ref> The Cunard Building was one of several structures built on the lower section of Broadway in the early 20th century that would be affiliated with the maritime trade.<ref>{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995|ps=.|pp=4, 8}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1920/10/03/archives/lower-new-yorks-building-activity-recent-broadway-purchase-by.html|title=Lower New York's Building Activity; Recent Broadway Purchase by Harriman Interests, Near the New Cunard Structure an Object Lesson of Recent Trade Expansion|date=October 3, 1920|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n=== Usage ===\nAt opening, the Great Hall was the home of Cunard and Anchor Lines, which occupied the Great Hall, first three stories, basement, and top floors.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"AR-Cunard-1919\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"nytm51\" /> The remaining floors housed numerous other tenants,<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"nytm51\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1921/05/01/archives/new-cunard-building-imposing-office-structure-at-25-broadway-opens.html|title=New Cunard Building; Imposing Office Structure at 25 Broadway Opens Its Doors Tomorrow--Striking Architectural Features|date=May 1, 1921|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> including [[Atlas Portland Cement Company]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1921/02/10/archives/5000000-involved-in-two-big-leases-times-square-corner-leased-by.html|title=$5,000,000 Involved in Two Big Leases|date=February 10, 1921|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[Anaconda Copper]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/43288262/|title=Pay $4,200,000 For Space in Steamship Row|date=November 4, 1920|work=New-York Tribune|access-date=January 30, 2020|page=20|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> [[Merchant Shipbuilding Corporation]], [[Consolidated Steel Corporation]], [[International Motor Truck Company]], and Atlantic, Gulf & West Indies Steamship Lines.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> A branch of the [[Mechanics and Metals National Bank]] was located at the first floor, within the retail space on the northeast corner.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes-MM-1921\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1921/05/16/archives/bank-branch-moved-mechanics-and-metals-opens-an-office-in-the.html|title=Bank Branch Moved; Mechanics and Metals Opens an Office in the Cunard Building.|date=May 16, 1921|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Even before the Cunard Building's official opening, it was almost fully leased, with only {{Convert|24,000|ft2|m2|abbr=}} remaining unused by April 1921.<ref name=\"The Nautical Gazette 1921 p. 434\" /> Factors in the Cunard Building's near-complete occupancy included relatively low rents, the inclusion of 21-year leases, the timely completion of the project, and a shortage of available office space in the Financial District.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> In later years, other industries moved into the Cunard Building as well, such as attorneys, railroad and steamship companies, shipbuilding companies, brokers, engineers, and raw materials companies.<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /> These included the [[New York Central Railroad]], which moved into the building in 1946.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1946/04/10/archives/ny-central-in-lease-takes-floor-in-25-broadway-for-foreign-freight.html|title=N.Y. Central in Lease; Takes Floor in 25 Broadway for Foreign Freight and Marine|date=April 10, 1946|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThe building's owners were given a loan of $8 million in 1930,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1931/10/10/archives/lends-8000000-at-4-on-the-cunard-building.html|title=Lends $8,000,000 at 4 % On the Cunard Building|date=October 10, 1931|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and another $2.82 million in 1944.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/1282862777/D445EE0D35DD4530PQ|title=Loan of $2,820,000 For Cunard Building|date=April 18, 1944|work=New York Tribune|access-date=January 28, 2020|page=28|via=ProQuest|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1944/04/11/archives/2820000-loan-placed-on-the-cunard-building.html|title=$2,820,000 Loan Placed On the Cunard Building|date=April 11, 1944|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In subsequent years, the assessed taxes for the Cunard Building was reduced multiple times. The New York Supreme Court gave the building's owners tax reprieves in 1946,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1946/01/01/archives/cunard-building-gets-assessment-reduction.html|title=Cunard Building Gets Assessment Reduction|date=January 1, 1946|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> 1948,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1948/03/31/archives/cunard-building-valuations-cut.html|title=Cunard Building Valuations Cut|date=March 31, 1948|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and 1950.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1950/04/22/archives/court-cuts-valuations-lowers-assessments-on-hotel-lincoln-and.html|title=Court Cuts Valuation; Lowers Assessments on Hotel Lincoln and Cunard Building|date=April 22, 1950|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In 1955, the owners completed a $3 million project to add air conditioning to the Cunard Building, one of the largest such retrofits in an existing structure.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/1323294095/D445EE0D35DD4530PQ|title=Space in Cunard Building Cooled at $3,000,000 Cost|date=August 14, 1955|work=New York Tribune|access-date=January 28, 2020|page=3C|via=ProQuest|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1955/08/21/archives/cunard-building-aircooled.html|title=Cunard Building Air-Cooled|date=August 21, 1955|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 28, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nAshforth, Todd & Company purchased the building in 1962.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1962/11/09/archives/25-broadway-building-is-sold-by-cunard-line.html|title=25 Broadway Building Is Sold by Cunard Line|date=November 9, 1962|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Cunard Line continued to operate the ticket hall until 1968, when it moved to [[555 Fifth Avenue]];<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /> the vacant space was then leased by brokerage company Francis I. duPont Co.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1968/12/19/archives/news-of-realty-cunard-tenancy-francis-i-dupont-leases-space-at-25.html|title=News of Realty: Cunard Tenancy; Francis I. duPont Leases Space at 25 Broadway|date=December 19, 1968|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The building was sold again in 1971, this time to the Cementation Company of America, a subsidiary of [[Trafalgar House (company)|Trafalgar House Investment Group]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/07/01/archives/trafalgar-house-reveals-576million-cunard-bid.html|title=Trafalgar House Reveals $57.6\u2010Million Cunard Bid|date=July 1, 1971|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Initially, the owners had difficulty finding tenants for the Great Hall due to its vast size.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/119455656/F536749CA6244088PQ|title=Tenant Hunted for Cunard Building's 'Great Hall'|date=October 1, 1972|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|via=ProQuest|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The [[United States Postal Service]] leased the Great Hall in 1974, intending to relocate its post office from the nearby [[Alexander Hamilton U.S. Custom House]] two years later.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1974/09/16/archives/cunard-will-lease-its-great-hall-to-postal-service-move-planned-in.html|title=Cunard Will Lease Its Great Hall to Postal Service|last=Horsley|first=Carter B.|date=September 16, 1974|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> By 1977, the USPS had moved into the Great Hall, and [[Standard & Poor's]] had signed a 20-year lease for space at the Cunard Building.<ref name=\"Oser 1977\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/12/07/archives/about-real-estate-gradual-changes-for-the-old-cunard-building.html|title=About Real Estate|last=Oser|first=Alan S.|date=December 7, 1977|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The building was sold to Zev W. Wolfson for $15 million by 1979.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/10/10/archives/real-estate-a-foreign-interest-in-manhattan.html|title=Real Estate|date=1979-10-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The [[City College of New York]]'s Center For Worker Education was established on the seventh floor of the Cunard Building in 1981.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ccny.cuny.edu/news/%E2%80%9C-realm%E2%80%9D-opens-ccnys-sixth-annual-taffny-film-festival|title='The Realm' opens CCNY's sixth annual TAFFNY film festival|last=|first=|date=June 11, 2019|website=www.ccny.cuny.edu|publisher=The City College of New York|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Elizabeth Berger Plaza 78 - L\u00e9man Manhattan.jpg|alt=L\u00e9man Manhattan Preparatory School sign|thumb|[[L\u00e9man Manhattan Preparatory School]] sign outside the Morris Street entrance]]\n\nIn 1995, the exterior and the first floor interior of the Cunard Building, along with several other buildings on Bowling Green,{{efn|Namely [[26 Broadway]]; the [[Bowling Green Offices Building]]; and the [[International Mercantile Marine Company Building]]<ref name=\"Dunlap 1995\" />}} were formally designated as New York City landmarks.<ref name=\"Dunlap 1995\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/10/15/realestate/bringing-downtown-back-up.html|title=Bringing Downtown Back Up|last=Dunlap|first=David W.|date=1995-10-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>{{efn|The interior designation included the entrance vestibules and lobby, the passage to the Great Hall, and the Hall up to the height of its rotunda.<ref name=\"lpc95\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=1}}</ref>}} Two years later, S&P vacated its spaces at the Cunard Building, as well as at [[26 Broadway]] directly to the east, when the company started leasing space at nearby [[55 Water Street]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Oser|first=Alan S.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/08/03/realestate/downtown-is-looking-up.html|title=Downtown Is Looking Up|date=August 3, 1997|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>  The post office closed in 2000.<ref>{{cite web | last=Geier | first=Stephanie | title=A Look Inside the Opulent Cunard Building in NYC | website=Untapped New York | date=December 4, 2015 | url=https://untappedcities.com/2015/12/04/a-look-inside-the-opulent-cunard-building-in-nyc/ | access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> Afterward, the Great Hall went unused again for over a decade. ''The New York Times'' cited the hall's landmark status as a factor in the difficulty of leasing the space.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/23/realestate/commercial/the-tricky-task-of-renovating-a-buildings-landmark-interior.html|title=The Tricky Task of Renovating a Building Without Altering Its Landmark Insides|last=Hughes|first=C. J.|date=November 22, 2011|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 29, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The doors were locked, barring visitors from entering the Great Hall.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/20/nyregion/so-you-think-you-can-see-a-landmark.html|title=So, You Think You Can See a Landmark?|last=Dunlap|first=David W.|date=2006-01-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-30|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> During the mid-2000s, the [[Sports Museum of America]] considered opening within the Great Hall,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2004/11/02/sports-hall-switches-sides-founder-crosses-bway-to-keep-national-museum-in-play/|title=Sports Hall Switches Sides \u2013 Founder Crosses B'way To Keep National Museum In Play|last=Cuozzo|first=Steve|date=2004-11-02|website=New York Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Pennington|first=Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/13/sports/ncaafootball/sports-museum-and-heisman-find-place-in-lower-manhattan.html|title=Sports Museum and Heisman Find Place in Lower Manhattan|date=2005-04-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> but the museum ultimately opened in 2008 at 26 Broadway.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/12/arts/artsspecial/12sport.html|title=Luring Sports Fans of All Seasons to Lower Manhattan|date=2008-03-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-13|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In 2014, the Great Hall was leased to [[Cipriani S.A.]] for the operation of an event venue.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribecacitizen.com/2014/01/09/cipriani-is-adding-another-grand-space-to-its-empire/|title=Cipriani Is Adding Another Grand Space to Its Empire|date=January 9, 2014|website=Tribeca Citizen|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2015/02/16/lower-broadway-finally-blossoming-after-years-of-neglect/|title=Lower Broadway finally blossoming after years of neglect|last=Cuozzo|first=Steve|date=February 17, 2015|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe upper floors remained in use by multiple tenants, including school and college campuses. In 2002, [[Deloitte]] leased three floors of the Cunard Building after its previous offices at the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] were destroyed in the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/03/27/business/commercial-real-estate-deloitte-picks-light-flexibility-and-link-to-history.html|title=Commercial Real Estate; Deloitte Picks Light, Flexibility and Link to History|last=McDowell|first=Edwin|date=2002-03-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-30|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[L\u00e9man Manhattan Preparatory School]] moved to the Cunard Building in 2010,<ref name=\"Shapiro 2010\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/05/nyregion/05claremont.html|title=Claremont Prep Is Sold to For-Profit Firm|last=Anderson|first=Jenny|date=April 4, 2011|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 30, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>{{efn|At the time of the purchase, it was known as the Claremont Preparatory School;<ref name=\"Shapiro 2010\" /> the name was changed to L\u00e9man in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/08/31/in-private-school-world-a-rush-to-be-international/|title=In Private School World, a Rush to Be 'International'|last=Anderson|first=Jenny|date=2011-08-31|website=City Room|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>}} occupying the top four floors for its middle and high school campuses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2014/10/07/take-a-look-inside-manhattans-first-and-only-boarding-school/|title=Inside Manhattan's first & only boarding school|last=Ridley|first=Jane|date=October 7, 2014|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref> [[Relay Graduate School of Education]], a private graduate school for teachers, moved into the building in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/06/25/education-nonprofit-moves-into-historical-cunard-building/|title=Education nonprofit moves into historical Cunard Building|last=Weiss|first=Lois|date=June 26, 2019|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\nUpon its opening, writers praised the Cunard Building's design. ''[[Architectural Forum]]'' magazine published six pieces about the Cunard Building in its July 1921 volume alone.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" />{{efn|For a list of these pieces, see {{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.}}}} In one such piece, art historian [[Royal Cortissoz]] described the external plan as \"indeed organic architecture\", writing that the \"genuine architectural inspiration [sprang] straight from the personality of the designer\".<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref>{{harvnb|''Architectural Forum''|1921|ps=.|pp=4, 5, 8}}</ref> ''Architecture and Building'' called the site \"exceedingly well chosen\",<ref name=\"AB p. 61\" /> and the ''New-York Tribune'' called the Cunard Building \"one of the fine structures of the city\".<ref name=\"Tribune-Completed-1921\" /> Other critics praised the building's manner of construction, and how it had been built above the Broadway subway line.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" />\n\nThe interior was similarly regarded. In a piece for ''American Architect and Architecture'' in 1928, C.H. Blackall described the building as having \"a magnificent counting room\", and that the domed ceiling had \"individuality and a most charmingly successful decorative effect.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nKkwAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA11|title=American Architect and Architecture|publisher=J. R. Osgood & Company|year=1928|page=11|access-date=January 30, 2020|issue=v. 133}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995|ps=.|p=3}}</ref> David Dunlap of ''The New York Times'' said in 1991 that the Great Hall was \"one of New York's most magnificent\u2014and least appreciated\u2014public spaces\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/09/15/travel/hidden-corners-of-lower-manhattan.html|title=Hidden Corners of Lower Manhattan|last=Dunlap|first=David W.|date=1991-09-15|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-30|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Landmarks Preservation Commission, in its 1995 landmark-designation report, called the hall \"among New York's most impressive interiors\".<ref name=\"NYCL Interior p. 4\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|New York City|Architecture}}\n* [[List of buildings and structures on Broadway in Manhattan]]\n* [[List of New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan below 14th Street]]\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{notelist}}\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{commons category|25 Broadway Cunard Building}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite web |title=Cunard Building |url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1928.pdf |date=September 19, 1995 |publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] |ref={{harvid|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1995}}}}\n* {{cite web |title=Cunard Building, First Floor Interior |url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1929.pdf |date=September 19, 1995 |publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] |ref={{harvid|Landmarks Preservation Commission Interior|1995}}}}\n* {{cite journal|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|title=Cunard Building|ref={{harvid|''Architectural Forum''|1921}}|pages=1\u201324|postscript=:}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=11|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=Royal|last=Cortissoz|title=The Cunard Building|pages=1\u20138}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=29|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=Ezra|last=Winter|title=Mural Decorations of the Cunard Building|pages=9\u201316}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=49|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=S.O|last=Miller|title=Structural Features of the Cunard Building, New York|pages=17\u201320}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=53|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=Carlton S.|last=Proctor|title=Special Problems in Foundations of the Cunard Building|pages=21\u201322|via=}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=54|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=Henry C., Jr.|last=Meyer|title=Electrical, Heating and Ventilating Equipment of the Cunard Building|pages=22\u201323|via=}}\n** {{cite journal|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951000755263d&view=1up&seq=56|journal=Architectural Forum|date=July 1921|volume=35|first=Clyde R.|last=Place|title=Plumbing in the Cunard Building|pages=24|via=}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Morris|first=Benjamin Wistar|date=July 1920|title=The Cunard Building, New York|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015082471254&view=1up&seq=15|journal=Architectural Forum|volume=33|pages=1\u20136|ref={{harvid|Morris|1920}}}}\n* {{cite journal|year=1921|title=The Cunard Building, New York|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Hy_nAAAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PR19|journal=Architecture and Building|publisher=W.T. Comstock Company|volume=53|pages=61\u201364|ref={{sfnref |''Architecture and Building''| 1921}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Broadway (Manhattan)}}\n{{Financial District, Manhattan}}\n\n[[Category:Carr\u00e8re and Hastings buildings]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City interior landmarks]]\n[[Category:Financial District, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Broadway (Manhattan)]]\n[[Category:1921 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 1921]]\n[[Category:Bowling Green (New York City)]]\n", "name_user": "Vami IV", "label": "safe", "comment": "citto", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cunard_Building_(New_York_City)"}
{"title_page": "Alcohol and health", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n[[File:What Alcohol Does to Your Body.webm|thumb|upright=1.5|Alcohol and health (two minute video)]]\n[[Alcohol (drug)|Alcohol]] (also known as [[ethanol]]) has a number of effects on [[health]]. [[Short-term effects of alcohol consumption]] include [[Alcohol intoxication|intoxication]] and [[dehydration]]. [[Long-term effects of alcohol consumption]] include changes in the metabolism of the liver and brain and [[alcoholism]]. Alcohol intoxication affects the brain, causing slurred speech, clumsiness, and delayed reflexes. Alcohol stimulates [[insulin]] production, which speeds up [[glucose]] [[metabolism]] and can result in low [[blood sugar]], causing [[irritability]] and possibly death for [[Diabetes mellitus|diabetics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/diabetes/expert-blog/alcohol-and-diabetes/BGP-20056464|title=Alcohol and diabetes: Drinking safely \u2013 Mayo Clinic}}</ref>{{mcn|date=November 2015}}  Even light and moderate alcohol consumption increases cancer risk in individuals.<ref name=\"Weinstock2017\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/alcohol-consumption-increases-risk-of-breast-and-other-cancers-doctors-say/|title=Alcohol Consumption Increases Risk of Breast and Other Cancers, Doctors Say|author= Cheryl Platzman Weinstock|magazine=[[Scientific American]]|date=8 November 2017|accessdate=13 November 2018|quote=The ASCO statement, published in the Journal of Clinical Oncology, cautions that while the greatest risks are seen with heavy long-term use, even low alcohol consumption (defined as less than one drink per day) or moderate consumption (up to two drinks per day for men, and one drink per day for women because they absorb and metabolize it differently) can increase cancer risk. Among women, light drinkers have a four percent increased risk of breast cancer, while moderate drinkers have a 23 percent increased risk of the disease. }}</ref><ref name=\"LoConte2017\">{{cite journal |author=Noelle K. LoConte, Abenaa M. Brewster, Judith S. Kaur, Janette K. Merrill, and Anthony J. Alberg |title=Alcohol and Cancer: A Statement of the American Society of Clinical Oncology |journal=[[Journal of Clinical Oncology]] |date=7 November 2017 |volume=36 |issue=1|quote=Clearly, the greatest cancer risks are concentrated in the heavy and moderate drinker categories. Nevertheless, some cancer risk persists even at low levels of consumption. A meta-analysis that focused solely on cancer risks associated with drinking one drink or fewer per day observed that this level of alcohol consumption was still associated with some elevated risk for squamous cell carcinoma of the esophagus (sRR, 1.30; 95% CI, 1.09 to 1.56), oropharyngeal cancer (sRR, 1.17; 95% CI, 1.06 to 1.29), and breast cancer (sRR, 1.05; 95% CI, 1.02 to 1.08), but no discernable associations were seen for cancers of the colorectum, larynx, and liver.}}</ref> A 2014 [[World Health Organization]] report found that harmful alcohol consumption caused about 3.3 million deaths annually worldwide.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.who.int/substance_abuse/publications/global_alcohol_report/msb_gsr_2014_1.pdf | title=Global status report on alcohol and health | publisher=World Health Organization | date=2014 | accessdate=23 November 2015 | pages=vii}}</ref> Negative efforts are related to the amount consumed with no safe lower limit seen.<ref name=Lancet2018GBD>{{cite journal |title=Alcohol use and burden for 195 countries and territories, 1990\u20132016: a systematic analysis for the Global Burden of Disease Study 2016 |journal=The Lancet |volume=392 |issue=10152 |pages=1015\u20131035 |date=August 2018 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(18)31310-2|pmid=30146330 |pmc=6148333 |display-authors=5 |last1=Griswold |first1=MG |last2=Fullman |first2=N |last3=Hawley |first3=C |last4=Arian |first4=N |last5=Zimsen |first5=SM |last6=Tymeson |first6=HD|last7=Venkateswaran |first7=Vidhya |last8=Tapp |first8=Austin Douglas |last9=Forouzanfar |first9=Mohammad H. |last10=Salama |first10=Joseph S. |last11=Abate |first11=Kalkidan Hassen |last12=Abate |first12=Degu |last13=Abay |first13=Solomon M. |last14=Abbafati |first14=Cristiana |last15=Abdulkader |first15=Rizwan Suliankatchi |last16=Abebe |first16=Zegeye |last17=Aboyans |first17=Victor |last18=Abrar |first18=Mohammed Mehdi |last19=Acharya |first19=Pawan |last20=Adetokunboh |first20=Olatunji O. |last21=Adhikari |first21=Tara Ballav |last22=Adsuar |first22=Jose C. |last23=Afarideh |first23=Mohsen |last24=Agardh |first24=Emilie Elisabet |last25=Agarwal |first25=Gina |last26=Aghayan |first26=Sargis Aghasi |last27=Agrawal |first27=Sutapa |last28=Ahmed |first28=Muktar Beshir |last29=Akibu |first29=Mohammed |last30=Akinyemiju |first30=Tomi}}</ref> Some nations have introduced [[alcohol packaging warning messages]] that inform consumers about [[alcohol and cancer]], as well as [[foetal alcohol syndrome]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Cancer warning labels to be included on alcohol in Ireland, minister confirms |url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/republic-of-ireland/cancer-warning-labels-to-be-included-on-alcohol-in-ireland-minister-confirms-37357231.html |publisher=[[Belfast Telegraph]]|language=English|date=26 September 2018|newspaper=Belfasttelegraph.co.uk }}</ref>\n\nThe [[median lethal dose]] of alcohol in test animals is a [[blood alcohol content]] of 0.45%. This is about six times the level of ordinary intoxication (0.08%), but [[vomiting]] or unconsciousness may occur much sooner in people who have a low tolerance for alcohol.<ref name=\"psychopharm\">Meyer, Jerold S. and Linda F. Quenzer. Psychopharmacology: Drugs, the Brain, and Behavior. Sinauer Associates, Inc.: Sunderland, Massachusetts. 2005. Page 228.</ref> The high tolerance of chronic heavy drinkers may allow some of them to remain conscious at levels above 0.40%, although serious health hazards are incurred at this level.\n\nAlcohol also limits the production of [[vasopressin]] (ADH) from the [[hypothalamus]] and the secretion of this [[hormone]] from the [[posterior pituitary]] gland. This is what causes severe [[dehydration]] when alcohol is consumed in large amounts. It also causes a high concentration of water in the [[urine]] and vomit and the intense thirst that goes along with a [[hangover]].\n\n[[Stress (psychological)|Stress]], [[hangover]]s, and [[Combined oral contraceptive pill|the oral contraceptive pill]] may increase the desire<!--crave?--> for alcohol because these things will lower the level of testosterone and alcohol will acutely elevate it.<ref>[http://ethesis.helsinki.fi/julkaisut/laa/kliin/vk/sarkola/effectof.pdf helsinki.fi \u2013 Effect of alcohol on hormones in women], Helsinki 2001</ref> [[Tobacco]] has the same effect of increasing the craving for alcohol.<ref>[http://research.med.helsinki.fi/esbra2009/ESBRA2009_posters6.pdf helsinki.fi \u2013 Clinical studies on dependence and drug effects] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130221181921/http://research.med.helsinki.fi/esbra2009/ESBRA2009_posters6.pdf |date=21 February 2013 }}, ESBRA 2009</ref>\n\n==Short-term effects==\n{{Main|Short-term effects of alcohol consumption}}\nThe [[short-term effects of alcohol consumption]] range from a decrease in anxiety and motor skills at lower doses to unconsciousness, anterograde amnesia, and central nervous system depression at higher doses. [[Cell membrane]]s are highly permeable to alcohol, so once alcohol is in the bloodstream it can diffuse into nearly every cell in the body.\n\nThe [[concentration]] of alcohol in [[blood]] is measured via [[blood alcohol content]] (BAC). The amount and circumstances of consumption play a large part in determining the extent of [[alcohol intoxication|intoxication]]; for example, eating a heavy meal before alcohol consumption causes alcohol to absorb more slowly.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Horowitz M, Maddox A, Bochner M |display-authors=etal |title=Relationships between gastric emptying of solid and caloric liquid meals and alcohol absorption |journal=Am. J. Physiol. |volume=257 |issue=2 Pt 1 |pages=G291\u20136298 |date=1989 |pmid=2764113 |doi=10.1152/ajpgi.1989.257.2.G291 }}</ref> [[Dehydration|Hydration]] also plays a role, especially in determining the extent of [[hangover]]s. After [[binge drinking|excessive drinking]], [[unconsciousness]] can occur and extreme levels of consumption can lead to [[alcohol poisoning]] and death (a concentration in the blood stream of 0.40% will [[median lethal dose|kill half of those affected]]<ref name=\"BAC\">{{Cite web |url=http://apps.carleton.edu/campus/wellness/info/alcohol/bac/ |title=Carleton College: Wellness Center: Blood Alcohol Concentration (BAC) |access-date=29 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090914152127/http://apps.carleton.edu/campus/wellness/info/alcohol/bac/ |archive-date=14 September 2009 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>{{mcn|date=November 2015}}). Alcohol may also cause death indirectly, by [[asphyxiation]] from [[vomiting|vomit]].\n\nAlcohol can greatly exacerbate sleep problems. During [[abstinence]], residual disruptions in sleep regularity and sleep patterns{{Clarify|date=March 2010|reason=Sleep maintenance and architecture are meaningless phrases to 99.9% of our readers, who are not doctors.}} are the greatest predictors of [[relapse]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Feige B, Scaal S, Hornyak M, Gann H, Riemann D |title=Sleep electroencephalographic spectral power after withdrawal from alcohol in alcohol-dependent patients |journal=Alcohol. Clin. Exp. Res. |volume=31 |issue=1 |pages=19\u201327 |date=2007 |pmid=17207097 |doi=10.1111/j.1530-0277.2006.00260.x}}</ref>\n\n==Long-term effects==\n{{Main|Long-term effects of alcohol consumption}}\n[[File:Possible long-term effects of ethanol.svg|thumb|300px]]\n\nAccording to the World Health Organization's 2018 Global Status Report on Alcohol and Health, there are more than 3 million people who die from the harmful effects of alcohol each year, which amounts to more than 5% of the burden of disease world-wide.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.who.int/substance_abuse/publications/global_alcohol_report/en/ | title=WHO &#124; Global status report on alcohol and health 2018}}</ref> The US National Institutes of Health similarly estimates that 3.3 million deaths (5.9% of all deaths) were believed to be due to alcohol each year.<ref name=NIH2015Stats>{{cite web|title=Alcohol Facts and Statistics|url=http://www.niaaa.nih.gov/alcohol-health/overview-alcohol-consumption/alcohol-facts-and-statistics|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nGuidelines in the US and the UK advise that ''if'' people choose to drink, they should drink moderately.<ref>{{cite web |title=Appendix 9. Alcohol - 2015-2020 Dietary Guidelines - health.gov |url=https://health.gov/dietaryguidelines/2015/guidelines/appendix-9/ |publisher=U.S. Department of Health and Human Services |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New alcohol advice issued |url=https://www.nhs.uk/news/food-and-diet/new-alcohol-advice-issued/ |work=NHS |date=8 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nEven light and moderate alcohol consumption increases cancer risk in individuals, especially with respect to [[Esophageal cancer#Squamous-cell carcinoma|squamous cell carcinoma of the esophagus]], [[oropharyngeal cancer]], and [[breast cancer]].<ref name=\"Weinstock2017\"/><ref name=\"LoConte2017\"/>\n\nA systematic analysis of data from the [[Global Burden of Disease Study]], which was an [[observational study]], found that long term consumption of any amount of alcohol is associated with an increased of risk of death in all people, and that even moderate consumption appears to be risky.  Similar to prior analyses, it found an apparent benefit for older women in [[Alcohol and cardiovascular disease|reducing the risks of death from ischemic heart disease]] and from diabetes, but unlike prior studies it found those risks cancelled by an apparent increased risk of death from breast cancer and other causes.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Alcohol use and burden for 195 countries and territories, 1990-2016: a systematic analysis for the Global Burden of Disease Study 2016 |journal=Lancet |volume= 392|issue= 10152|pages= 1015\u20131035|date=August 2018 |pmid=30146330 |pmc=6148333 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(18)31310-2 |url=|author1=GBD 2016 Alcohol Collaborators }}</ref> A 2016 systematic review and meta-analysis found that moderate ethanol consumption brought no mortality benefit compared with lifetime abstention from ethanol consumption.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Stockwell T, Zhao J, Panwar S, Roemer A, Naimi T, Chikritzhs T |title=Do \"Moderate\" Drinkers Have Reduced Mortality Risk? A Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis of Alcohol Consumption and All-Cause Mortality |journal=J Stud Alcohol Drugs |volume=77 |issue=2 |pages=185\u2013198 |date=2016 |pmid=26997174 |pmc=4803651 |doi= 10.15288/jsad.2016.77.185|url=}}</ref>  Risk is greater in younger people due to [[binge drinking]] which may result in violence or accidents.<ref name=Kee2014>{{cite journal|last1=O'Keefe|first1=JH|last2=Bhatti|first2=SK|last3=Bajwa|first3=A|last4=DiNicolantonio|first4=JJ|last5=Lavie|first5=CJ|title=Alcohol and cardiovascular health: the dose makes the poison...or the remedy.|journal=Mayo Clinic Proceedings|date=2014|volume=89|issue=3|pages=382\u2013393|pmid=24582196|doi=10.1016/j.mayocp.2013.11.005}}</ref>\n\nLong-term heavy use of alcohol damages nearly every organ and system in the body.<ref>{{cite book|editor1-first=Woody|editor1-last=Caan|editor2-first=Jackie de|editor2-last=Belleroche|title=Drink, Drugs and Dependence: From Science to Clinical Practice|url=https://archive.org/details/drinkdrugsdepende00caan|url-access=registration|edition=1st|date=11 April 2002 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-415-27891-1 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/drinkdrugsdepende00caan/page/19 19]\u201320}}</ref> Risks include [[alcoholism]], [[malnutrition]], [[chronic pancreatitis]], [[alcoholic liver disease]] and [[cancer]].  In addition, damage to the [[central nervous system]] and [[peripheral nervous system]] can occur from chronic alcohol abuse.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=M\u00fcller D, Koch RD, von Specht H, V\u00f6lker W, M\u00fcnch EM|url=|title=Neurophysiologic findings in chronic alcohol abuse|language=German|journal=Psychiatr Neurol Med Psychol (Leipz)|volume=37|issue=3|pages=129\u201332|date=March 1985|pmid=2988001}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Testino G|title=Alcoholic diseases in hepato-gastroenterology: a point of view |journal=Hepatogastroenterology |volume=55 |issue=82\u201383 |pages=371\u2013377 |year=2008 |pmid=18613369}}</ref>\n\nThe developing adolescent brain is particularly vulnerable to the toxic effects of alcohol.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Guerri | first1 = C. | last2 = Pascual | first2 = M.A. | year = 2010 | title = Mechanisms involved in the neurotoxic, cognitive, and neurobehavioral effects of alcohol consumption during adolescence | url = | journal = Alcohol | volume = 44 | issue = 1| pages = 15\u201326 | doi = 10.1016/j.alcohol.2009.10.003 | pmid = 20113871 }}</ref>\n\n==Pregnancy==\n{{see also|Fetal alcohol spectrum disorders}}\nMedical organizations strongly discourage drinking alcohol during pregnancy.<ref name=SG>{{cite web|author1=Vice Admiral Richard H. Carmona|title=A 2005 Message to Women from the U.S. Surgeon General|url=https://www.cdc.gov/ncbddd/fasd/documents/sg-advisory.pdf|accessdate=12 June 2015|date=2005}}</ref><ref name=IOM>{{cite book|authors=Committee to Study Fetal Alcohol Syndrome, Division of Biobehavioral Sciences and Mental Disorders, Institute of Medicine|title=Fetal alcohol syndrome : diagnosis, epidemiology, prevention, and treatment|date=1995|publisher=National Academy Press|location=Washington, D.C.|isbn=978-0-309-05292-4|url=http://www.nap.edu/catalog/4991/fetal-alcohol-syndrome-diagnosis-epidemiology-prevention-and-treatment|doi=10.17226/4991}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Australian Government National Health and Medical Research Council |url=http://www.nhmrc.gov.au/your-health/alcohol-guidelines |accessdate=4 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105024533/http://www.nhmrc.gov.au/your-health/alcohol-guidelines |archive-date=5 November 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Alcohol passes easily from the mother's bloodstream through the placenta and into the bloodstream of the fetus,<ref name=\"Nathanson 857\">{{cite journal|last=Nathanson|first=Vivienne|author2=Nicky Jayesinghe |author3=George Roycroft |title=Is it all right for women to drink small amounts of alcohol in pregnancy? No|journal=BMJ|date=27 October 2007|volume=335|issue=7625|pages=857|doi=10.1136/bmj.39356.489340.AD|pmid=17962287|pmc=2043444}}</ref> which interferes with brain and organ development.<ref name=NIH2015/> Alcohol can affect the fetus at any stage during pregnancy, but the level of risk depends on the amount and frequency of alcohol consumed.<ref name=NIH2015>{{cite web|title=Fetal Alcohol Exposure|url=http://pubs.niaaa.nih.gov/publications/FASDFactsheet/FASDfact.htm|accessdate=10 June 2015|date=April 2015}}</ref> Regular heavy drinking and binge drinking (four or more drinks on any one occasion) pose the greatest risk for harm, but lesser amounts can cause problems as well.<ref name=NIH2015/> There is no known safe amount or safe time to drink during pregnancy, and the [[U.S. CDC]] recommends complete abstinence for women who are pregnant, trying to become pregnant, or are sexually active and not using birth control.<ref name=CDC2015Fact>{{cite web|title=Facts about FASDs|url=https://www.cdc.gov/ncbddd/fasd/facts.html|accessdate=10 June 2015|date=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/media/releases/2016/p0202-alcohol-exposed-pregnancy.html|title=More than 3 million US women at risk for alcohol-exposed pregnancy|work=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|access-date=3 March 2016 |quote='drinking ''any'' alcohol at ''any'' stage of pregnancy can cause a range of disabilities for their child,' said Coleen Boyle, Ph.D., director of CDC's National Center on Birth Defects and Developmental Disabilities.|date=2 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nPrenatal alcohol exposure can lead to [[fetal alcohol spectrum disorders]] (FASDs). The most severe form of FASD is fetal alcohol syndrome (FAS).<ref name=CDC2015Fact/> Problems associated with FASD include facial anomalies, [[low birth weight]], [[stunted growth]], [[microcephaly|small head size]], delayed or uncoordinated [[Motor skill#Development of motor skills|motor skill]]s, [[hearing impaired|hearing]] or [[visual impairment|vision problems]], [[learning disability|learning disabilities]], [[Behavioral disorder|behavior problems]], and inappropriate [[Social skills#Alcohol|social skill]]s compared to [[age appropriate|same-age peers]].<ref name=Cor2013>{{cite journal|last1=Coriale|title=Fetal Alcohol Spectrum Disorder (FASD): neurobehavioral profile, indications for diagnosis and treatment.|journal=Rivista di Psichiatria|date=2013|volume=48|issue=5|pages=359\u201369|pmid=24326748|doi=10.1708/1356.15062|display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref name=Canadian>{{citation|last=Chudley|title=Fetal alcohol spectrum disorder: Canadian guidelines for diagnosis|journal=CMAJ|volume=172|issue=5 Suppl|pages=S1\u2013S21|year=2005|pmid=15738468|doi=10.1503/cmaj.1040302|pmc=557121|display-authors=etal}}</ref> Those affected are more likely to have trouble in school, legal problems, participate in high-risk behaviors, and develop [[substance use disorder]]s themselves.<ref name=Cor2013/>\n\n==Cardiovascular disease==\n{{main|Alcohol and cardiovascular disease}}\nIn 2010, a systematic review reported that moderate consumption of alcohol does not cause harm to people with cardiovascular disease. However, the authors did not encourage people to start drinking alcohol in hope of benefit.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Costanzo S, Di Castelnuovo A, Donati MB, Iacoviello L, de Gaetano G |title=Alcohol consumption and mortality in patients with cardiovascular disease: a meta-analysis |journal=J. Am. Coll. Cardiol. |volume=55 |issue=13 |pages=1339\u20131347 |date=2010 |pmid=20338495 |doi=10.1016/j.jacc.2010.01.006 |url=}}</ref> The position of the American Heart Association is that people who are currently nondrinkers should not start drinking alcohol.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.heart.org/en/healthy-living/healthy-eating/eat-smart/nutrition-basics/alcohol-and-heart-health |title=Alcohol and Heart Health |publisher=American Heart Association |date=August 15, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n== Breastfeeding ==\nThe [[United Kingdom|UK]] [[National Health Service]] states that \"an occasional drink is unlikely to harm\" a breastfed baby, and recommends consumption of \"no more than one or two units of alcohol once or twice a week\" for breastfeeding mothers (where a pint of beer or 50&nbsp;ml drink of a spirit such as whisky corresponds to about ''two'' units of alcohol).<ref name=NHSguide/> The NHS also recommends to wait for a couple of hours before breastfeeding or express the milk into a bottle before drinking.<ref name=NHSguide>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhs.uk/chq/pages/958.aspx?CategoryID=54&SubCategoryID=135#close|title=Breastfeeding and drinking alcohol \u2013 Pregnancy and baby guide \u2013 NHS Choices|first=N. H. S.|last=Choices|date=1 May 2017}}</ref> Researchers have shown that intoxicated breastfeeding reduces the average milk expression but poses no immediate threat to the child as the amount of transferred alcohol is insignificant.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Haastrup|first1=MB|last2=Potteg\u00e5rd|first2=A|last3=Damkier|first3=P|title=Alcohol and Breastfeeding|journal=Basic & Clinical Pharmacology & Toxicology|date=2014|volume=114|issue=2|pages=168\u2013173|doi=10.1111/bcpt.12149|quote=even in a theoretical case of binge drinking, the children would not be subjected to clinically relevant amounts of alcohol|pmid=24118767|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/4bf55dfdbc932da175c501474a2e747da04d5f42}}</ref>\n\n==Alcohol education==\n{{Main|Alcohol education}}\nAlcohol education is the practice of disseminating information about the effects of alcohol on health, as well as society and the family unit.<ref name=\"MooreGerstein1981\">{{cite book |last1=Moore |first1=Mark Harrison |last2=Gerstein |first2=Dean R. |title=Alcohol and Public Policy |url=https://archive.org/details/alcoholpublicpol00moor |url-access=registration |date=1981 |publisher=National Academies |page=[https://archive.org/details/alcoholpublicpol00moor/page/90 90\u201393] |language=English}}</ref> It was introduced into the public schools by [[List of Temperance organizations|temperance organizations]] such as the [[Woman's Christian Temperance Union]] in the late 19th century.<ref name=\"MooreGerstein1981\"/> Initially, alcohol education focused  on how the consumption of alcoholic beverages affected society, as well as the family unit.<ref name=\"MooreGerstein1981\"/> In the 1930s, this came to also incorporate education pertaining to alcohol's effects on health.<ref name=\"MooreGerstein1981\"/> Organizations such as the [[National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism]] in the United States were founded to promulgate alcohol education alongside those of the [[temperance movement]], such as the [[American Council on Alcohol Problems]].<ref name=\"MooreGerstein1981\"/><ref name=\"Martin2014\">{{cite book |last1=Martin |first1=Scott C. |title=The SAGE Encyclopedia of Alcohol: Social, Cultural, and Historical Perspectives |date=2014 |publisher=SAGE Publications |isbn=9781483374383 |language=English}}</ref>\n\n==Alcohol expectations==\nAlcohol expectations are [[belief]]s and [[Attitude (psychology)|attitudes]] that people have about the effects they will experience when drinking alcoholic beverages. They are just largely beliefs about alcohol's effects on a person's behaviors, abilities, and emotions. Some people believe that if alcohol expectations can be changed, then [[Alcoholism|alcohol abuse]] might be reduced. Men tend to become more aggressive in laboratory studies in which they are drinking only [[tonic water]] but believe that it contains alcohol. They also become less aggressive when they believe they are drinking only tonic water, but are actually drinking tonic water that contains alcohol.<ref name=Grattan>{{cite journal |last1=Grattan |first1=Karen E. |last2=Vogel-Sprott |first2=M. |title=Maintaining Intentional Control of Behavior Under Alcohol |journal=Alcoholism: Clinical and Experimental Research |volume=25 |issue=2 |pages=192\u20137 |year=2001 |doi=10.1111/j.1530-0277.2001.tb02198.x |pmid=11236832}}</ref>\n\nThe phenomenon of alcohol expectations recognizes that intoxication has real physiological consequences that alter a drinker's perception of space and time, reduce psychomotor skills, and disrupt [[Equilibrioception|equilibrium]].<ref name=MacAndrew/> The manner and degree to which alcohol expectations interact with the physiological short-term effects of alcohol, resulting in specific behaviors, is unclear.\n\nA single study found that if a society believes that intoxication leads to [[Alcohol and sex|sexual behavior]], rowdy behavior, or aggression, then people tend to act that way when intoxicated. But if a society believes that intoxication leads to relaxation and tranquil behavior, then it usually leads to those outcomes. Alcohol expectations vary within a society, so these outcomes are not certain.<ref name=\"The think-drink effect\">{{cite journal | last1 = Marlatt | first1 = G. A. | last2 = Rosenow | name-list-format=vanc | year = 1981 | title = The think-drink effect | url = | journal = Psychology Today | volume = 15 | issue = | pages = 60\u201393 }}</ref>\n\nPeople tend to conform to social expectations, and some societies expect that drinking alcohol will cause disinhibition. However, in societies in which the people do not expect that alcohol will disinhibit, intoxication seldom leads to disinhibition and bad behavior.<ref name=MacAndrew>MacAndrew, C. and Edgerton. ''Drunken Comportment: A Social Explanation''. Chicago: Aldine, 1969.</ref>\n\nAlcohol expectations can operate in the absence of actual consumption of alcohol. Research in the United States over a period of decades has shown that men tend to become more sexually aroused when they think they have been drinking alcohol\u2014even when they have not been drinking it. Women report feeling more sexually aroused when they falsely believe the beverages they have been drinking contained alcohol (although one measure of their physiological arousal shows that they became less aroused).{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n\n===Drug treatment programs===\nMost addiction treatment programs encourage people with drinking problems to see themselves as having a chronic, relapsing disease that requires a lifetime of attendance at 12-step meetings to keep in check. However, some people do not develop lifelong problems.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n==Alcohol abuse==\n{{see also|Alcohol abuse|Substance abuse prevention}}\n[[File:Rational harm assessment of drugs radar plot.svg|thumb|Addiction experts in psychiatry, chemistry, pharmacology, forensic science, epidemiology, and the police and legal services engaged in [[Delphi method|delphic analysis]] regarding 20 popular recreational drugs. Alcohol was ranked 6th in dependence, 11th in physical harm, and 2nd in social harm.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Nutt|first1=D|last2=King|first2=LA|last3=Saulsbury|first3=W|last4=Blakemore|first4=C|title=Development of a rational scale to assess the harm of drugs of potential misuse.|journal=Lancet|date=24 March 2007|volume=369|issue=9566|pages=1047\u201353|pmid=17382831|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(07)60464-4}}</ref>]]\n\n===Alcohol abuse prevention programs===\nMore than 200 injuries and disease conditions are caused due to alcohol abuse.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/substance_abuse/safer/en/|title=WHO {{!}} THE SAFER INITIATIVE|website=WHO|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref> It is a causative agent influencing maternal health and development, noncommunicable diseases (including cancer and cardiovascular diseases), injuries, violence, mental health, and infectious diseases such as TB and HIV/AIDS.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Global status report on alcohol and health 2018.|last=World Health Organization.|others=World Health Organization,, World Health Organization. Management of Substance Abuse Team|isbn=978-92-4-156563-9|location=Geneva|oclc=1089229677|date=14 February 2019}}</ref> Harmful use of alcohol has been identified as a global health issue, and its management is a priority in the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nations|first=United|date=2015-12-31|title=Transforming governance for the 2030 agenda for sustainable development|url=https://www.un-ilibrary.org/democracy-and-governance/world-public-sector-report-2015_e5a72957-en|language=en|pages=73\u201387|doi=10.18356/e5a72957-en}}</ref> In 2018, WHO launched the initiative '''SAFER,''' to decrease the number of deaths, diseases and injuries caused by alcohol misuse. It has been developed to address the regional, country and global health and developmental goals using high-impact, cost-effective, evidence-based interventions.Using a set of WHO tools and resources SAFER will concentrate on the more cost-effective interventions to reduce and preventive alcohol related abuse.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Global action plan for the prevention and control of noncommunicable diseases : 2013-2020.|others=World Health Organization|isbn=978-92-4-150623-6|location=Geneva, Switzerland|oclc=960910741}}</ref> The five WHO \u201cbest buys\u201d for decreasing alcohol misuse are priority in this action plan:<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n* '''S'''trengthen restrictions on alcohol availability.\n* '''A'''dvance and enforce drink driving countermeasures.\n* '''F'''acilitate access to screening, brief interventions, and treatment.\n* '''E'''nforce bans or comprehensive restrictions on alcohol advertising, sponsorship, and promotion.\n* '''R'''aise prices on alcohol through excise taxes and pricing policies.\n\nThe promotion and success of the SAFER initiative is based on three key principles to implement, to monitor, and to protect.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Recommended maximum intake===\n{{Main|Recommended maximum intake of alcoholic beverages}}\n\nBinge drinking is becoming a major problem in the UK. Advice on weekly consumption is avoided in United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aim-digest.com/gateway/pages/guide/articles/biggy.htm |title=Sensible Drinking |publisher=Aim-digest.com |accessdate=5 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101119172727/http://aim-digest.com/gateway/pages/guide/articles/biggy.htm |archivedate=19 November 2010 }}</ref>\n\nSince 1995 the UK government has advised that regular consumption of three to four units (one unit equates to 10 mL of pure ethanol) a day for men and or two to three units for women, would not pose significant health risks. However, consistently drinking more than four units a day (for men) and three units (women), is not advisable.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dh.gov.uk/en/Publichealth/Healthimprovement/Alcoholmisuse/index.htm |title=Alcohol misuse : Department of Health |publisher=Dh.gov.uk |accessdate=5 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nPreviously (from 1992 until 1995), the advice was that men should drink no more than 21 units per week, and women no more than 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.drinkaware.co.uk/alcohol-facts/health-effects-of-alcohol/lifestyle/alcohol-and-your-health/ |title=Alcohol and health: how alcohol can affect your long and short term health |publisher=Drinkaware.co.uk |accessdate=5 February 2013}}</ref> (The difference between the sexes was due to the typically lower weight and water-to-body-mass ratio of women.) This was changed because a government study showed that many people were in effect \"saving up\" their units and using them at the end of the week, a phenomenon referred to as [[binge drinking]].{{Citation needed|date= October 2007}} ''[[The Times]]'' reported in October 2007 that these limits had been \"plucked out of the air\" and had no scientific basis.<ref>[http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/life/food/article1778774.ece Drink limits 'useless\u2019], The Times, 20 October 2007</ref>\n\n===Sobriety===\n{{see also|Sobriety}}\n\n[[File:Breathalyzer test 0013.png|right|thumb|A [[midshipman]] is subjected to a random [[breathalyzer]] test to determine sobriety.]]\nSobriety is the condition of not having any measurable levels, or effects from [[mood-altering drug]]s. According to WHO \"Lexicon of alcohol and drug terms...\" sobriety is continued abstinence from psychoactive drug use.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.who.int/substance_abuse/terminology/who_lexicon/en/ |title=Lexicon and drug terms |publisher=Who.int |date=9 December 2010 |accessdate=5 February 2013 }}</ref> Sobriety is also considered to be the natural state of a human being given at a birth. In a treatment setting, sobriety is the achieved goal of independence from consuming or craving mind-altering substances. As such, sustained abstinence is a prerequisite for sobriety. Early in abstinence, residual effects of mind-altering substances can preclude sobriety. These effects are labeled \"PAWS\", or \"post acute withdrawal syndrome\". Someone who abstains, but has a latent desire to resume use, is not considered truly sober. An abstainer may be subconsciously motivated to resume drug use, but for a variety of reasons, abstains (e.g. such as a medical or legal concern precluding use).<ref name=basharin>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.video.sbnt.ru/vl/Newspapers/Podsporie/Podsporie_111.pdf |title=Scientific grounding for sobriety: Western experience |author=MD Basharin K.G. |year=2010 |accessdate=5 February 2013 }}</ref> Sobriety has more specific meanings within specific contexts, such as the culture of [[Alcoholics Anonymous]], other 12 step programs, law enforcement, and some schools of psychology. In some cases, sobriety implies achieving \"life balance\".<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.stopdrinkingexpert.com/pdf/12steps.pdf |title=Twelve Steps and Twelve Traditions |publisher=Alcoholics Anonymous World Services |access-date=31 December 2018 |isbn= 978-0-916856-01-4 |date=April 1953}} (Electronic .PDF version, September 2005).</ref>\n\n== Injury and deaths ==\n[[Injury]] is defined as physical damage or harm that is done or sustained. The potential of injuring oneself or others can be increased after consuming alcohol due to the certain short term effects related to the substance such as lack of coordination, blurred vision, and slower reflexes to name a few.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.drinkwise.org.au/drinking-and-you/how-is-drinking-affecting-you/|title = Drinkwise Australia|date = |accessdate = |website = DrinkWise Australia}}</ref> Due to these effects the most common injuries include head, fall, and vehicle-related injuries. A study was conducted of patients admitted to the [[Ulster Hospital]] in Northern Ireland with fall related injuries. They found that 113 of those patients admitted to that hospital during that had consumed alcohol recently and that the injury severity was higher for those that had consumed alcohol compared to those that had not.<ref>{{Cite journal|url = http://emj.bmj.com/content/21/2/185.full|title = Alcohol related falls: an interesting pattern of injuries|vauthors = Johnson J, McGovern S |date =2003|journal = Emergency Medicine Journal|volume = 21|issue = 2|pages = 185\u2013188|doi = 10.1136/emj.2003.006130|pmid = 14988344|pmc = 1726307}}</ref> Another study showed that 21% of patients admitted to the Emergency Department of the [[Bristol Royal Infirmary]] had either direct or indirect alcohol related injuries. If these figures are extrapolated it shows that the estimated number of patients with alcohol related injuries are over 7,000 during the year at this emergency department alone.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = What is the burden of alcohol-related injuries in an inner city emergency department?|vauthors=Hoskins R, Benger J |date=2013|journal = Alcoholism: Clinical and Experimental Research|doi = 10.1111/j.1530-0277.2009.00981.x|pmid = 19485974|pmc=2757258 |volume=33|issue = 9|pages=1532\u20131538}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States alcohol resulted in about 88,000 deaths in 2010.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Alcohol-attributable deaths and years of potential life lost \u2014 11 states, 2006\u20132010|website=www.cdc.gov|url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm6310a2.htm}}</ref> The [[World Health Organization]] calculated that more than 3 million people, mostly men, died as a result of harmful use of alcohol in 2016. This was about 13.5% of the total deaths of people between 20 and 39. More than 5% of the global disease burden was caused by the harmful use of alcohol.<ref>{{cite news |title=Alcohol |url=http://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/alcohol |accessdate=5 November 2018 |publisher=World health Organization |date=21 September 2018}}</ref> There are even higher estimates for Europe.<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/41473801/Distilled_Spirits_Overconsumption_as_the_Most_Important_Factor_of_Excessive_Adult_Male_Mortality_in_Europe_Alcohol_and_Alcoholism_2018_53_6_742_752 Korotayev, A., Khaltourina, D., Meshcherina, K., & Zamiatnina, E. Distilled Spirits Overconsumption as the Most Important Factor of Excessive Adult Male Mortality in Europe. ''Alcohol and Alcoholism'', 2018, 53(6), 742-752].</ref>\n\n==Genetic differences==\n\n===Alcohol flush and respiratory reactions===\n{{see also|Alcohol flush reaction|Alcohol-induced respiratory reactions|Short-term effects of alcohol consumption}}\nAlcohol flush reaction is a condition in which an individual's face or body experiences flushes or blotches as a result of an accumulation of [[acetaldehyde]], a metabolic byproduct of the catabolic metabolism of alcohol. It is best known as a condition that is experienced by people of Asian descent. According to the analysis by [[HapMap Project]], the rs671 allele of the ALDH2 gene responsible for the flush reaction is rare among Europeans and Africans, and it is very rare among Mexican-Americans. 30% to 50% of people of Chinese and Japanese ancestry have at least one ALDH*2 allele.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.snpedia.com/index.php/Rs671 |title=Rs671 |website=SNPmedia }}</ref> The rs671 form of ALDH2, which accounts for most incidents of alcohol flush reaction worldwide, is native to East Asia and most common in southeastern China. It most likely originated among Han Chinese in central China,<ref>{{cite journal|title=Refined Geographic Distribution of the Oriental ALDH2*504Lys (nee 487Lys) Variant|author=Hui Li|journal=Ann Hum Genet |year=2009|pmc=2846302|pmid=19456322|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1809.2009.00517.x|volume=73|issue=Pt 3|pages=335\u2013345|display-authors=et al}}</ref> and it appears to have been positively selected in the past. Another analysis correlates the rise and spread of rice cultivation in Southern China with the spread of the allele.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Yi Peng |author2=Hong Shi |author3=Xue-bin Qi |author4=Chun-jie Xiao |author5=Hua Zhong |author6=Run-lin Z Ma |author7=Bing Su |title=The ADH1B Arg47His polymorphism in East Asian populations and expansion of rice domestication in history |journal=BMC Evolutionary Biology |volume=10 |page= 15|year=2010 |pmid=20089146 |pmc=2823730 |doi= 10.1186/1471-2148-10-15|issue=1}}</ref> The reasons for this positive selection aren't known, but it's been hypothesized that elevated concentrations of acetaldehyde may have conferred protection against certain parasitic infections, such as ''[[Entamoeba histolytica]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Oota H, Pakstis AJ, Bonne-Tamir B, Goldman D, Grigorenko E, Kajuna SL, et al |title=The evolution and population genetics of the ALDH2 locus: random genetic drift, selection, and low levels of recombination |journal=Ann. Hum. Genet. |volume=68 |issue=Pt 2 |pages=93\u2013109 |date=2004 |pmid=15008789 |doi= 10.1046/j.1529-8817.2003.00060.x|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/a982b046ccdf544c10368a284757121a0c727b40}}</ref> The same SNP allele of ALDH2, also termed glu487lys, and the abnormal accumulation of acetaldehyde following the drinking of alcohol, is associated with the [[alcohol-induced respiratory reactions]] of rhinitis and asthma that occur in Eastern Asian populations.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Adams|first1=KE|last2=Rans|first2=TS|title=Adverse reactions to alcohol and alcoholic beverages|journal=Annals of Allergy, Asthma & Immunology|date=2013|volume=111|issue=6|pages=439\u2013445|doi=10.1016/j.anai.2013.09.016|pmid=24267355}}</ref>\n{{alcohol metabolism formulae}}\n\n===American Indian alcoholism===\n{{main|Alcohol and Native Americans}}\nCompared with the United States population in general, the Native American population is much more susceptible to alcoholism and related diseases and deaths.<ref name = \"May\">[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK233103/pdf/Bookshelf_NBK233103.pdf Philip A. May, \"Overview of Alcohol Abuse Epidemiology for American Indian Populations,\" in ''Changing Numbers, Changing Needs: American Indian Demography and Public Health,'' Gary D. Sandefur, Ronald R. Rindfuss, Barney Cohen, Editors. Committee on Population, Commission on Behavioral and Social Sciences and Education National Research Council. National Academy Press: Washington, D.C. 1996]</ref> From 2006 to 2010, alcohol-attributed deaths accounted for 11.7 percent of all Native American deaths, more than twice the rates of the general U.S. population. The median alcohol-attributed death rate for Native Americans (60.6 per 100,000) was twice as high as the rate for any other racial or ethnic group.<ref name = \"MMWR\">{{cite journal| pmc=5779340 | pmid=24622285 | volume=63 | title=Alcohol-attributable deaths and years of potential life lost--11 States, 2006-2010 | year=2014 | journal=MMWR Morb Mortal Wkly Rep | pages=213\u20136 | last1 = Gonzales | first1 = K | last2 = Roeber | first2 = J | last3 = Kanny | first3 = D | last4 = Tran | first4 = A | last5 = Saiki | first5 = C | last6 = Johnson | first6 = H | last7 = Yeoman | first7 = K | last8 = Safranek | first8 = T | last9 = Creppage | first9 = K | last10 = Lepp | first10 = A | last11 = Miller | first11 = T | last12 = Tarkhashvili | first12 = N | last13 = Lynch | first13 = KE | last14 = Watson | first14 = JR | last15 = Henderson | first15 = D | last16 = Christenson | first16 = M | last17 = Geiger | first17 = SD}}</ref> Males are affected disproportionately more by alcohol-related conditions than females.<ref name = \"Whitesell\">{{cite journal| pmc=4436971 | pmid=22931069 | doi=10.3109/00952990.2012.694527 | volume=38 | title=Epidemiology and etiology of substance use among American Indians and Alaska Natives: risk, protection, and implications for prevention | year=2012 | journal=Am J Drug Alcohol Abuse | pages=376\u201382 | last1 = Whitesell | first1 = NR | last2 = Beals | first2 = J | last3 = Crow | first3 = CB | last4 = Mitchell | first4 = CM | last5 = Novins | first5 = DK| issue=5 }}</ref> The highest risk of alcohol-related deaths is between 45 and 64 years of age. Chronic liver disease and [[cirrhosis]] are 3.9 times as prevalent in the Native American population than the general US population. Of all alcohol-attributable deaths, motor vehicle accidents account for 27.5% and [[alcoholic liver disease]] accounts for 25.2%. [[Driving under the influence|Alcohol-related fatal car accidents]] are three times more prevalent among Native Americans than in other ethnicities.\n\nNative American populations exhibit genetic differences in the alcohol-metabolizing enzymes [[alcohol dehydrogenase]] and [[ALDH]],<ref>{{cite journal| pmc=3860438 | pmid=17718395 | volume=30 | title=Variations in ADH and ALDH in Southwest California Indians | year=2007 | journal=Alcohol Res Health | pages=14\u20137 | last1 = Ehlers | first1 = CL}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| pmc=3498484 | pmid=22931071 | doi=10.3109/00952990.2012.694526 | volume=38 | title=ADH and ALDH polymorphisms and alcohol dependence in Mexican and Native Americans | year=2012 | journal=Am J Drug Alcohol Abuse | pages=389\u201394 | last1 = Ehlers | first1 = CL | last2 = Liang | first2 = T | last3 = Gizer | first3 = IR| issue=5 }}</ref> although evidence that these genetic factors are more prevalent in Native Americans than other ethnic groups has been a subject of debate.<ref name = \"Ehlers\">[https://ajp.psychiatryonline.org/doi/full/10.1176/appi.ajp.2012.12010113 Ehlers CL, Gizer IR. \"Evidence for a genetic component for substance dependence in Native Americans.\" ''Am J Psychiatry.'' 1 Feb 2013;170(2):154\u2013164.]</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Caetano | first1 = Raul | last2 = Clark | first2 = Catherine L. | last3 = Tam | first3 = Tammy | year = 1998 | title = Alcohol consumption among racial/ethnic minorities | journal = Alcohol Health and Research World | volume = 22 | issue = 4| pages = 233\u2013241 | citeseerx = 10.1.1.556.6875 }}</ref><ref name = \"Ethnicity\">[https://pubs.niaaa.nih.gov/publications/arh40/152-160.htm Karen Chartier and Raul Caetano, \"Ethnicity and health disparities in alcohol research,\" ''Alcohol Res Health'' 2010, vol. 33: 1-2 pp. 152-160]</ref> According to one 2013 review of academic literature on the issue, there is a \"substantial genetic component in Native Americans\" and that \"most Native Americans lack protective variants seen in other populations.\"<ref name = \"Ehlers\"/> Many scientists have provided evidence of the genetic component of alcoholism by the [[biopsychosocial model]] of alcoholism, but the [[molecular genetics]] research currently has not found one specific gene that is responsible for the rates of alcoholism among Native Americans, implying the phenomenon may be due to an interplay of multiple genes and environmental factors.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Wall | first1 = Tamara L. | last2 = Carr | first2 = Lucinda G. | last3 = Ehlers | first3 = Cindy L. | year = 2003 | title = Protective association of genetic variation in alcohol dehydrogenase with alcohol dependence in Native American Mission Indians | journal = American Journal of Psychiatry | volume = 160 | issue = 1| pages = 41\u201346 | doi = 10.1176/appi.ajp.160.1.41 | pmid = 12505800 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| pmid=15900224 | doi=10.1097/00041444-200506000-00006 | volume=15 | title=Heritability of substance dependence in a native American population | year=2005 | journal=Psychiatr Genet | pages=101\u20137 | last1 = Wilhelmsen | first1 = KC | last2 = Ehlers | first2 = C| issue=2 }}</ref> Research on [[alcoholism in family systems]] suggests that learned behavior augments genetic factors in increasing the probability that children of alcoholics will themselves have problems with alcohol.<ref>{{cite journal| pmc=3872279 | pmid=24386563 | doi=10.1155/2013/410395 | volume=2013 | title=A Framework to Examine the Role of Epigenetics in Health Disparities among Native Americans | year=2013 | journal=Nurs Res Pract | page=410395 | last1 = Brockie | first1 = TN | last2 = Heinzelmann | first2 = M | last3 = Gill | first3 = J}}</ref>\n\n=== Genetics and amount of consumption ===\nHaving a particular genetic variant (A-allele of ADH1B rs1229984) is associated with non-drinking and lower alcohol consumption. This variant is also associated with favorable cardiovascular profile and a reduced risk of coronary heart disease compared to those without the genetic variant, but it is unknown whether this may be caused by differences in alcohol consumption or by additional [[confounder|confounding]] effects of the genetic variant itself.<ref name=\"Holmes et al.\">{{cite journal | last1 = Holmes | first = Michael V. | display-authors = etal   | year = 2014 | title = Association between alcohol and cardiovascular disease: Mendelian randomisation analysis based on individual participant data | url = http://www.bmj.com/content/349/bmj.g4164 | journal = BMJ | volume = 349 | issue = | page = g4164 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.g4164 | pmid=25011450 | pmc=4091648}}</ref>\n\n==Gender differences==\n\nHistorically, according to the ''[[British Medical Journal]]'', \"men have been far more likely than women to drink alcohol and to drink it in quantities that damage their health, with some figures suggesting up to a 12-fold difference between the sexes\".<ref name=\"Women catching up\">{{cite press release |title=Women catching up with men in alcohol consumption and its associated harms |work=BMJ Open |date=25 October 2016 |url=http://www.bmj.com/company/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/bmj-open-alcohol-women.pdf}}</ref> However, analysis of data collected over a century from multiple countries suggests that the [[wiktionary:Gender gap|gender gap]] in [[alcohol consumption]] is narrowing, and that young women (born after 1981) are consuming alcohol more than their male counterparts. Such findings have implications for the way in which alcohol-use prevention and intervention programs are designed and implemented.<ref name=Slade2016>{{cite journal |vauthors=Slade T, Chapman C, Swift W, Keyes K, Tonks Z, Teesson M |title=Birth cohort trends in the global epidemiology of alcohol use and alcohol-related harms in men and women: systematic review and metaregression |journal=BMJ Open|date=2016 |volume=6 |issue=10 |pages=e011827 |doi=10.1136/bmjopen-2016-011827 |pmid=27797998 |pmc=5093369 |url=http://bmjopen.bmj.com/content/6/10/e011827.full.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Alcoholism===\nBased on combined data from SAMHSA's 2004-2005 National Surveys on Drug Use & Health, the rate of past year [[alcohol dependence]] or abuse among people aged 12 or older varied by level of alcohol use: 44.7% of past month heavy drinkers, 18.5% binge drinkers, 3.8% past month non-binge drinkers, and 1.3% of those who did not drink alcohol in the past month met the criteria for alcohol dependence or abuse in the past year. Males had higher rates than females for all measures of drinking in the past month: any alcohol use (57.5% vs. 45%), binge drinking (30.8% vs. 15.1%), and heavy alcohol use (10.5% vs. 3.3%), and males were twice as likely as females to have met the criteria for alcohol dependence or abuse in the past year (10.5% vs. 5.1%).<ref>\"Gender differences in alcohol use and alcohol dependence or abuse: 2004 or 2005.\" The NSDUH Report. Accessed 22 June 2012.</ref>\nOver time the difference between males and females has narrowed. According to a 2016 systematic review, for those born at the end of the 20th century men were 1.2 times as likely to drink to problematic levels, and 1.3 times as likely to develop health problems from drinking.<ref name=Slade2016 />\n\n===Sensitivity===\nSeveral biological factors make women more vulnerable to the effects of alcohol than men.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.helpguide.org/harvard/women_alcohol.htm |title=Women & Alcohol: The Hidden Risks of Drinking |publisher=Helpguide.org |accessdate=5 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130103092219/http://www.helpguide.org/harvard/women_alcohol.htm |archivedate=3 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\n* Body fat. Women tend to weigh less than men, and\u2014pound for pound\u2014a woman's body contains less water and more fatty tissue than a man's. Because fat retains alcohol while water dilutes it, alcohol remains at higher concentrations for longer periods of time in a woman's body, exposing her brain and other organs to more alcohol.\n* Enzymes. Women have lower levels of two enzymes\u2014alcohol dehydrogenase and aldehyde dehydrogenase\u2014that metabolize (break down) alcohol in the stomach and liver. As a result, women absorb more alcohol into their bloodstreams than men.\n* Hormones. Changes in hormone levels during the menstrual cycle may also affect how a woman metabolizes alcohol.\n\n===Metabolism===\nFemales demonstrated a higher average rate of elimination (mean, 0.017; range, 0.014\u20130.021 g/210 L) than males (mean, 0.015; range, 0.013\u20130.017 g/210 L). Female subjects on average had a higher percentage of body fat (mean, 26.0; range, 16.7\u201336.8%) than males (mean, 18.0; range, 10.2\u201325.3%).<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 8872236 | volume=20 | issue=5 | title=Determination of volume of distribution for ethanol in male and female subjects. | date=Sep 1996 | pages=287\u201390 | journal=J Anal Toxicol | doi=10.1093/jat/20.5.287 | last1 = Cowan | first1 = JM Jr | last2 = Weathermon | first2 = A | last3 = McCutcheon | first3 = JR | last4 = Oliver | first4 = RD}}</ref>\n\n===Depression===\nThe link between alcohol consumption, depression, and gender was examined by the Centre for Addiction and Mental Health (Canada). The study found that women taking antidepressants consumed more alcohol than women who did not experience depression as well as men taking antidepressants. The researchers, Dr. Kathryn Graham and a PhD Student Agnes Massak analyzed the responses to a survey by 14,063 Canadian residents aged 18\u201376 years. The survey included measures of quantity, frequency of drinking, depression and antidepressants use, over the period of a year. The researchers used data from the GENACIS Canada survey, part of an international collaboration to investigate the influence of cultural variation on gender differences in alcohol use and related problems. The purpose of the study was to examine whether, like in other studies already conducted on male depression and alcohol consumption, depressed women also consumed less alcohol when taking anti-depressants. According to the study, both men and women experiencing depression (but not on anti-depressants) drank more than non-depressed counterparts. Men taking antidepressants consumed significantly less alcohol than depressed men who did not use antidepressants. Non-depressed men consumed 436 drinks per year, compared to 579 drinks for depressed men not using antidepressants, and 414 drinks for depressed men who used antidepressants. Alcohol consumption remained higher whether the depressed women were taking anti-depressants or not. 179 drinks per year for non-depressed women, 235 drinks for depressed women not using antidepressants, and 264 drinks for depressed women who used antidepressants. The lead researcher argued that the study \"suggests that the use of antidepressants is associated with lower alcohol consumption among men suffering from depression. But this does not appear to be true for women.\"<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1503/cmaj.060446 | pmid=17325328 | pmc=1800314 | volume=176 | title=Alcohol consumption and the use of antidepressants | journal=Canadian Medical Association Journal | pages=633\u2013637  | last1 = Graham | first1 = K. | last2 = Massak | first2 = A.| issue=5 | year=2007 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Alcoholic beverage]]\n* [[Short-term effects of alcohol consumption]]\n* [[Long-term effects of alcohol consumption]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.sciencealert.com/global-burden-of-disease-alcohol-assessment-global-death-disability-rate  Massive Study Finds Alcohol Is a Leading Contributor to Death And Disease Worldwide]\n\n{{Alcohealth}}\n{{Psychoactive substance use}}\n\n[[Category:Alcohol and health]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n[[File:What Alcohol Does to Your Body.webm|thumb|upright=1.5|Alcohol and health (two minute video)]]\n[[Alcohol (drug)|Alcohol]] (also known as [[ethanol]]) has a number of effects on [[health]]. [[Short-term effects of alcohol consumption]] include [[Alcohol intoxication|intoxication]] and [[dehydration]]. [[Long-term effects of alcohol consumption]] include changes in the metabolism of the liver and brain and [[alcoholism]]. Alcohol intoxication affects the brain, causing slurred speech, clumsiness, and delayed reflexes. Alcohol stimulates [[insulin]] production, which speeds up [[glucose]] [[metabolism]] and can result in low [[blood sugar]], causing [[irritability]] and possibly death for [[Diabetes mellitus|diabetics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/diabetes/expert-blog/alcohol-and-diabetes/BGP-20056464|title=Alcohol and diabetes: Drinking safely \u2013 Mayo Clinic}}</ref>{{mcn|date=November 2015}}  Even light and moderate alcohol consumption increases cancer risk in individuals.<ref name=\"Weinstock2017\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/alcohol-consumption-increases-risk-of-breast-and-other-cancers-doctors-say/|title=Alcohol Consumption Increases Risk of Breast and Other Cancers, Doctors Say|author= Cheryl Platzman Weinstock|magazine=[[Scientific American]]|date=8 November 2017|accessdate=13 November 2018|quote=The ASCO statement, published in the Journal of Clinical Oncology, cautions that while the greatest risks are seen with heavy long-term use, even low alcohol consumption (defined as less than one drink per day) or moderate consumption (up to two drinks per day for men, and one drink per day for women because they absorb and metabolize it differently) can increase cancer risk. Among women, light drinkers have a four percent increased risk of breast cancer, while moderate drinkers have a 23 percent increased risk of the disease. }}</ref><ref name=\"LoConte2017\">{{cite journal |author=Noelle K. LoConte, Abenaa M. Brewster, Judith S. Kaur, Janette K. Merrill, and Anthony J. Alberg |title=Alcohol and Cancer: A Statement of the American Society of Clinical Oncology |journal=[[Journal of Clinical Oncology]] |date=7 November 2017 |volume=36 |issue=1|quote=Clearly, the greatest cancer risks are concentrated in the heavy and moderate drinker categories. Nevertheless, some cancer risk persists even at low levels of consumption. A meta-analysis that focused solely on cancer risks associated with drinking one drink or fewer per day observed that this level of alcohol consumption was still associated with some elevated risk for squamous cell carcinoma of the esophagus (sRR, 1.30; 95% CI, 1.09 to 1.56), oropharyngeal cancer (sRR, 1.17; 95% CI, 1.06 to 1.29), and breast cancer (sRR, 1.05; 95% CI, 1.02 to 1.08), but no discernable associations were seen for cancers of the colorectum, larynx, and liver.}}</ref> A 2014 [[World Health Organization]] report found that harmful alcohol consumption caused about 3.3 million deaths annually worldwide.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.who.int/substance_abuse/publications/global_alcohol_report/msb_gsr_2014_1.pdf | title=Global status report on alcohol and health | publisher=World Health Organization | date=2014 | accessdate=23 November 2015 | pages=vii}}</ref> Negative efforts are related to the amount consumed with no safe lower limit seen.<ref name=Lancet2018GBD>{{cite journal |title=Alcohol use and burden for 195 countries and territories, 1990\u20132016: a systematic analysis for the Global Burden of Disease Study 2016 |journal=The Lancet |volume=392 |issue=10152 |pages=1015\u20131035 |date=August 2018 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(18)31310-2|pmid=30146330 |pmc=6148333 |display-authors=5 |last1=Griswold |first1=MG |last2=Fullman |first2=N |last3=Hawley |first3=C |last4=Arian |first4=N |last5=Zimsen |first5=SM |last6=Tymeson |first6=HD|last7=Venkateswaran |first7=Vidhya |last8=Tapp |first8=Austin Douglas |last9=Forouzanfar |first9=Mohammad H. |last10=Salama |first10=Joseph S. |last11=Abate |first11=Kalkidan Hassen |last12=Abate |first12=Degu |last13=Abay |first13=Solomon M. |last14=Abbafati |first14=Cristiana |last15=Abdulkader |first15=Rizwan Suliankatchi |last16=Abebe |first16=Zegeye |last17=Aboyans |first17=Victor |last18=Abrar |first18=Mohammed Mehdi |last19=Acharya |first19=Pawan |last20=Adetokunboh |first20=Olatunji O. |last21=Adhikari |first21=Tara Ballav |last22=Adsuar |first22=Jose C. |last23=Afarideh |first23=Mohsen |last24=Agardh |first24=Emilie Elisabet |last25=Agarwal |first25=Gina |last26=Aghayan |first26=Sargis Aghasi |last27=Agrawal |first27=Sutapa |last28=Ahmed |first28=Muktar Beshir |last29=Akibu |first29=Mohammed |last30=Akinyemiju |first30=Tomi}}</ref> Some nations have introduced [[alcohol packaging warning messages]] that inform consumers about [[alcohol and cancer]], as well as [[foetal alcohol syndrome]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Cancer warning labels to be included on alcohol in Ireland, minister confirms |url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/republic-of-ireland/cancer-warning-labels-to-be-included-on-alcohol-in-ireland-minister-confirms-37357231.html |publisher=[[Belfast Telegraph]]|language=English|date=26 September 2018|newspaper=Belfasttelegraph.co.uk }}</ref>\n\nThe [[median lethal dose]] of alcohol in test animals is a [[blood alcohol content]] of 0.45%. This is about six times the level of ordinary intoxication (0.08%), but [[vomiting]] or unconsciousness may occur much sooner in people who have a low tolerance for alcohol.<ref name=\"psychopharm\">Meyer, Jerold S. and Linda F. Quenzer. Psychopharmacology: Drugs, the Brain, and Behavior. Sinauer Associates, Inc.: Sunderland, Massachusetts. 2005. Page 228.</ref> The high tolerance of chronic heavy drinkers may allow some of them to remain conscious at levels above 0.40%, although serious health hazards are incurred at this level.\n\nAlcohol also limits the production of [[vasopressin]] (ADH) from the [[hypothalamus]] and the secretion of this [[hormone]] from the [[posterior pituitary]] gland. This is what causes severe [[dehydration]] when alcohol is consumed in large amounts. It also causes a high concentration of water in the [[urine]] and vomit and the intense thirst that goes along with a [[hangover]].\n\n[[Stress (psychological)|Stress]], [[hangover]]s, and [[Combined oral contraceptive pill|the oral contraceptive pill]] may increase the desire<!--crave?--> for alcohol because these things will lower the level of testosterone and alcohol will acutely elevate it.<ref>[http://ethesis.helsinki.fi/julkaisut/laa/kliin/vk/sarkola/effectof.pdf helsinki.fi \u2013 Effect of alcohol on hormones in women], Helsinki 2001</ref> [[Tobacco]] has the same effect of increasing the craving for alcohol.<ref>[http://research.med.helsinki.fi/esbra2009/ESBRA2009_posters6.pdf helsinki.fi \u2013 Clinical studies on dependence and drug effects] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130221181921/http://research.med.helsinki.fi/esbra2009/ESBRA2009_posters6.pdf |date=21 February 2013 }}, ESBRA 2009</ref>\n\n==Short-term effects==\n{{Main|Short-term effects of alcohol consumption}}\nThe [[short-term effects of alcohol consumption]] range from a decrease in anxiety and motor skills at lower doses to unconsciousness, anterograde amnesia, and central nervous system depression at higher doses. [[Cell membrane]]s are highly permeable to alcohol, so once alcohol is in the bloodstream it can diffuse into nearly every cell in the body.\n\nThe [[concentration]] of alcohol in [[blood]] is measured via [[blood alcohol content]] (BAC). The amount and circumstances of consumption play a large part in determining the extent of [[alcohol intoxication|intoxication]]; for example, eating a heavy meal before alcohol consumption causes alcohol to absorb more slowly.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Horowitz M, Maddox A, Bochner M |display-authors=etal |title=Relationships between gastric emptying of solid and caloric liquid meals and alcohol absorption |journal=Am. J. Physiol. |volume=257 |issue=2 Pt 1 |pages=G291\u20136298 |date=1989 |pmid=2764113 |doi=10.1152/ajpgi.1989.257.2.G291 }}</ref> [[Dehydration|Hydration]] also plays a role, especially in determining the extent of [[hangover]]s. After [[binge drinking|excessive drinking]], [[unconsciousness]] can occur and extreme levels of consumption can lead to [[alcohol poisoning]] and death (a concentration in the blood stream of 0.40% will [[median lethal dose|kill half of those affected]]<ref name=\"BAC\">{{Cite web |url=http://apps.carleton.edu/campus/wellness/info/alcohol/bac/ |title=Carleton College: Wellness Center: Blood Alcohol Concentration (BAC) |access-date=29 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090914152127/http://apps.carleton.edu/campus/wellness/info/alcohol/bac/ |archive-date=14 September 2009 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>{{mcn|date=November 2015}}). Alcohol may also cause death indirectly, by [[asphyxiation]] from [[vomiting|vomit]].\n\nAlcohol can greatly exacerbate sleep problems. During [[abstinence]], residual disruptions in sleep regularity and sleep patterns{{Clarify|date=March 2010|reason=Sleep maintenance and architecture are meaningless phrases to 99.9% of our readers, who are not doctors.}} are the greatest predictors of [[relapse]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Feige B, Scaal S, Hornyak M, Gann H, Riemann D |title=Sleep electroencephalographic spectral power after withdrawal from alcohol in alcohol-dependent patients |journal=Alcohol. Clin. Exp. Res. |volume=31 |issue=1 |pages=19\u201327 |date=2007 |pmid=17207097 |doi=10.1111/j.1530-0277.2006.00260.x}}</ref>\n\n==Long-term effects==\n{{Main|Long-term effects of alcohol consumption}}\n[[File:Possible long-term effects of ethanol.svg|thumb|300px]]\n\nAccording to the World Health Organization's 2018 Global Status Report on Alcohol and Health, there are more than 3 million people who die from the harmful effects of alcohol each year, which amounts to more than 5% of the burden of disease world-wide.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.who.int/substance_abuse/publications/global_alcohol_report/en/ | title=WHO &#124; Global status report on alcohol and health 2018}}</ref> The US National Institutes of Health similarly estimates that 3.3 million deaths (5.9% of all deaths) were believed to be due to alcohol each year.<ref name=NIH2015Stats>{{cite web|title=Alcohol Facts and Statistics|url=http://www.niaaa.nih.gov/alcohol-health/overview-alcohol-consumption/alcohol-facts-and-statistics|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref> \n\nGuidelines in the US and the UK advise that ''if'' people choose to drink, they should drink moderately.<ref>{{cite web |title=Appendix 9. Alcohol - 2015-2020 Dietary Guidelines - health.gov |url=https://health.gov/dietaryguidelines/2015/guidelines/appendix-9/ |publisher=U.S. Department of Health and Human Services |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New alcohol advice issued |url=https://www.nhs.uk/news/food-and-diet/new-alcohol-advice-issued/ |work=NHS |date=8 January 2016}}</ref>  \n\nEven light and moderate alcohol consumption increases cancer risk in individuals, especially with respect to [[Esophageal_cancer#Squamous-cell_carcinoma|squamous cell carcinoma of the esophagus]], [[oropharyngeal cancer]], and [[breast cancer]].<ref name=\"Weinstock2017\"/><ref name=\"LoConte2017\"/>\n\nA systematic analysis of data from the [[Global Burden of Disease Study]], which was an [[observational study]], found that long term consumption of any amount of alcohol is associated with an increased of risk of death in all people, and that even moderate consumption appears to be risky.  Similar to prior analyses, it found an apparent benefit for older women in [[Alcohol and cardiovascular disease|reducing the risks of death from ischemic heart disease]] and from diabetes, but unlike prior studies it found those risks cancelled by an apparent increased risk of death from breast cancer and other causes.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Alcohol use and burden for 195 countries and territories, 1990-2016: a systematic analysis for the Global Burden of Disease Study 2016 |journal=Lancet |volume= 392|issue= 10152|pages= 1015\u20131035|date=August 2018 |pmid=30146330 |pmc=6148333 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(18)31310-2 |url=|author1=GBD 2016 Alcohol Collaborators }}</ref> A 2016 systematic review and meta-analysis found that moderate ethanol consumption brought no mortality benefit compared with lifetime abstention from ethanol consumption.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Stockwell T, Zhao J, Panwar S, Roemer A, Naimi T, Chikritzhs T |title=Do \"Moderate\" Drinkers Have Reduced Mortality Risk? A Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis of Alcohol Consumption and All-Cause Mortality |journal=J Stud Alcohol Drugs |volume=77 |issue=2 |pages=185\u2013198 |date=2016 |pmid=26997174 |pmc=4803651 |doi= 10.15288/jsad.2016.77.185|url=}}</ref>  Risk is greater in younger people due to [[binge drinking]] which may result in violence or accidents.<ref name=Kee2014>{{cite journal|last1=O'Keefe|first1=JH|last2=Bhatti|first2=SK|last3=Bajwa|first3=A|last4=DiNicolantonio|first4=JJ|last5=Lavie|first5=CJ|title=Alcohol and cardiovascular health: the dose makes the poison...or the remedy.|journal=Mayo Clinic Proceedings|date=2014|volume=89|issue=3|pages=382\u2013393|pmid=24582196|doi=10.1016/j.mayocp.2013.11.005}}</ref> \n\nLong-term heavy use of alcohol damages nearly every organ and system in the body.<ref>{{cite book|editor1-first=Woody|editor1-last=Caan|editor2-first=Jackie de|editor2-last=Belleroche|title=Drink, Drugs and Dependence: From Science to Clinical Practice|url=https://archive.org/details/drinkdrugsdepende00caan|url-access=registration|edition=1st|date=11 April 2002 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-415-27891-1 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/drinkdrugsdepende00caan/page/19 19]\u201320}}</ref> Risks include [[alcoholism]], [[malnutrition]], [[chronic pancreatitis]], [[alcoholic liver disease]] and [[cancer]].  In addition, damage to the [[central nervous system]] and [[peripheral nervous system]] can occur from chronic alcohol abuse.<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=M\u00fcller D, Koch RD, von Specht H, V\u00f6lker W, M\u00fcnch EM|url=|title=Neurophysiologic findings in chronic alcohol abuse|language=German|journal=Psychiatr Neurol Med Psychol (Leipz)|volume=37|issue=3|pages=129\u201332|date=March 1985|pmid=2988001}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Testino G|title=Alcoholic diseases in hepato-gastroenterology: a point of view |journal=Hepatogastroenterology |volume=55 |issue=82\u201383 |pages=371\u2013377 |year=2008 |pmid=18613369}}</ref>  \n\nThe developing adolescent brain is particularly vulnerable to the toxic effects of alcohol.<ref>Guerri, C.; Pascual, M.A. (2010).\"Mechanisms involved in the neurotoxic, cognitive, and neurobehavioral effects of alcohol consumption during adolescence\". ''Alcohol'' 44 (1) 15\u201326. doi:10.1016/j.alcohol.2009.10.003. {{PMID|20113871}}</ref>\n\n==Pregnancy==\n{{see also|Fetal alcohol spectrum disorders}}\nMedical organizations strongly discourage drinking alcohol during pregnancy.<ref name=SG>{{cite web|author1=Vice Admiral Richard H. Carmona|title=A 2005 Message to Women from the U.S. Surgeon General|url=https://www.cdc.gov/ncbddd/fasd/documents/sg-advisory.pdf|accessdate=12 June 2015|date=2005}}</ref><ref name=IOM>{{cite book|authors=Committee to Study Fetal Alcohol Syndrome, Division of Biobehavioral Sciences and Mental Disorders, Institute of Medicine|title=Fetal alcohol syndrome : diagnosis, epidemiology, prevention, and treatment|date=1995|publisher=National Academy Press|location=Washington, D.C.|isbn=978-0-309-05292-4|url=http://www.nap.edu/catalog/4991/fetal-alcohol-syndrome-diagnosis-epidemiology-prevention-and-treatment|doi=10.17226/4991}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Australian Government National Health and Medical Research Council |url=http://www.nhmrc.gov.au/your-health/alcohol-guidelines |accessdate=4 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105024533/http://www.nhmrc.gov.au/your-health/alcohol-guidelines |archive-date=5 November 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Alcohol passes easily from the mother's bloodstream through the placenta and into the bloodstream of the fetus,<ref name=\"Nathanson 857\">{{cite journal|last=Nathanson|first=Vivienne|author2=Nicky Jayesinghe |author3=George Roycroft |title=Is it all right for women to drink small amounts of alcohol in pregnancy? No|journal=BMJ|date=27 October 2007|volume=335|issue=7625|pages=857|doi=10.1136/bmj.39356.489340.AD|pmid=17962287|pmc=2043444}}</ref> which interferes with brain and organ development.<ref name=NIH2015/> Alcohol can affect the fetus at any stage during pregnancy, but the level of risk depends on the amount and frequency of alcohol consumed.<ref name=NIH2015>{{cite web|title=Fetal Alcohol Exposure|url=http://pubs.niaaa.nih.gov/publications/FASDFactsheet/FASDfact.htm|accessdate=10 June 2015|date=April 2015}}</ref> Regular heavy drinking and binge drinking (four or more drinks on any one occasion) pose the greatest risk for harm, but lesser amounts can cause problems as well.<ref name=NIH2015/> There is no known safe amount or safe time to drink during pregnancy, and the [[U.S. CDC]] recommends complete abstinence for women who are pregnant, trying to become pregnant, or are sexually active and not using birth control.<ref name=CDC2015Fact>{{cite web|title=Facts about FASDs|url=https://www.cdc.gov/ncbddd/fasd/facts.html|accessdate=10 June 2015|date=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/media/releases/2016/p0202-alcohol-exposed-pregnancy.html|title=More than 3 million US women at risk for alcohol-exposed pregnancy|work=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|access-date=3 March 2016 |quote='drinking ''any'' alcohol at ''any'' stage of pregnancy can cause a range of disabilities for their child,' said Coleen Boyle, Ph.D., director of CDC's National Center on Birth Defects and Developmental Disabilities.|date=2 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nPrenatal alcohol exposure can lead to [[fetal alcohol spectrum disorders]] (FASDs). The most severe form of FASD is fetal alcohol syndrome (FAS).<ref name=CDC2015Fact/> Problems associated with FASD include facial anomalies, [[low birth weight]], [[stunted growth]], [[microcephaly|small head size]], delayed or uncoordinated [[Motor skill#Development of motor skills|motor skill]]s, [[hearing impaired|hearing]] or [[visual impairment|vision problems]], [[learning disability|learning disabilities]], [[Behavioral disorder|behavior problems]], and inappropriate [[Social skills#Alcohol|social skill]]s compared to [[age appropriate|same-age peers]].<ref name=Cor2013>{{cite journal|last1=Coriale|title=Fetal Alcohol Spectrum Disorder (FASD): neurobehavioral profile, indications for diagnosis and treatment.|journal=Rivista di Psichiatria|date=2013|volume=48|issue=5|pages=359\u201369|pmid=24326748|doi=10.1708/1356.15062|display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref name=Canadian>{{citation|last=Chudley|title=Fetal alcohol spectrum disorder: Canadian guidelines for diagnosis|journal=CMAJ|volume=172|issue=5 Suppl|pages=S1\u2013S21|year=2005|pmid=15738468|doi=10.1503/cmaj.1040302|pmc=557121|display-authors=etal}}</ref> Those affected are more likely to have trouble in school, legal problems, participate in high-risk behaviors, and develop [[substance use disorder]]s themselves.<ref name=Cor2013/>\n\n==Cardiovascular disease==\n{{main|Alcohol and cardiovascular disease}}\nIn 2010, a systematic review reported that moderate consumption of alcohol does not cause harm to people with cardiovascular disease. However, the authors did not encourage people to start drinking alcohol in hope of benefit.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Costanzo S, Di Castelnuovo A, Donati MB, Iacoviello L, de Gaetano G |title=Alcohol consumption and mortality in patients with cardiovascular disease: a meta-analysis |journal=J. Am. Coll. Cardiol. |volume=55 |issue=13 |pages=1339\u20131347 |date=2010 |pmid=20338495 |doi=10.1016/j.jacc.2010.01.006 |url=}}</ref> The position of the American Heart Association is that people who are currently nondrinkers should not start drinking alcohol.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.heart.org/en/healthy-living/healthy-eating/eat-smart/nutrition-basics/alcohol-and-heart-health |title=Alcohol and Heart Health |publisher=American Heart Association |date=August 15, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n== Breastfeeding ==\nThe [[United Kingdom|UK]] [[National Health Service]] states that \"an occasional drink is unlikely to harm\" a breastfed baby, and recommends consumption of \"no more than one or two units of alcohol once or twice a week\" for breastfeeding mothers (where a pint of beer or 50&nbsp;ml drink of a spirit such as whisky corresponds to about ''two'' units of alcohol).<ref name=NHSguide/> The NHS also recommends to wait for a couple of hours before breastfeeding or express the milk into a bottle before drinking.<ref name=NHSguide>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhs.uk/chq/pages/958.aspx?CategoryID=54&SubCategoryID=135#close|title=Breastfeeding and drinking alcohol \u2013 Pregnancy and baby guide \u2013 NHS Choices|first=N. H. S.|last=Choices|date=1 May 2017}}</ref> Researchers have shown that intoxicated breastfeeding reduces the average milk expression but poses no immediate threat to the child as the amount of transferred alcohol is insignificant.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Haastrup|first1=MB|last2=Potteg\u00e5rd|first2=A|last3=Damkier|first3=P|title=Alcohol and Breastfeeding|journal=Basic & Clinical Pharmacology & Toxicology|date=2014|volume=114|issue=2|pages=168\u2013173|doi=10.1111/bcpt.12149|quote=even in a theoretical case of binge drinking, the children would not be subjected to clinically relevant amounts of alcohol|pmid=24118767|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/4bf55dfdbc932da175c501474a2e747da04d5f42}}</ref>\n\n==Alcohol education==\n{{Main|Alcohol education}}\nAlcohol education is the practice of disseminating information about the effects of alcohol on health, as well as society and the family unit.<ref name=\"MooreGerstein1981\">{{cite book |last1=Moore |first1=Mark Harrison |last2=Gerstein |first2=Dean R. |title=Alcohol and Public Policy |url=https://archive.org/details/alcoholpublicpol00moor |url-access=registration |date=1981 |publisher=National Academies |page=[https://archive.org/details/alcoholpublicpol00moor/page/90 90\u201393] |language=English}}</ref> It was introduced into the public schools by [[List of Temperance organizations|temperance organizations]] such as the [[Woman's Christian Temperance Union]] in the late 19th century.<ref name=\"MooreGerstein1981\"/> Initially, alcohol education focused  on how the consumption of alcoholic beverages affected society, as well as the family unit.<ref name=\"MooreGerstein1981\"/> In the 1930s, this came to also incorporate education pertaining to alcohol's effects on health.<ref name=\"MooreGerstein1981\"/> Organizations such as the [[National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism]] in the United States were founded to promulgate alcohol education alongside those of the [[temperance movement]], such as the [[American Council on Alcohol Problems]].<ref name=\"MooreGerstein1981\"/><ref name=\"Martin2014\">{{cite book |last1=Martin |first1=Scott C. |title=The SAGE Encyclopedia of Alcohol: Social, Cultural, and Historical Perspectives |date=2014 |publisher=SAGE Publications |isbn=9781483374383 |language=English}}</ref>\n\n==Alcohol expectations==\nAlcohol expectations are [[belief]]s and [[Attitude (psychology)|attitudes]] that people have about the effects they will experience when drinking alcoholic beverages. They are just largely beliefs about alcohol's effects on a person's behaviors, abilities, and emotions. Some people believe that if alcohol expectations can be changed, then [[Alcoholism|alcohol abuse]] might be reduced. Men tend to become more aggressive in laboratory studies in which they are drinking only [[tonic water]] but believe that it contains alcohol. They also become less aggressive when they believe they are drinking only tonic water, but are actually drinking tonic water that contains alcohol.<ref name=Grattan>{{cite journal |last1=Grattan |first1=Karen E. |last2=Vogel-Sprott |first2=M. |title=Maintaining Intentional Control of Behavior Under Alcohol |journal=Alcoholism: Clinical and Experimental Research |volume=25 |issue=2 |pages=192\u20137 |year=2001 |doi=10.1111/j.1530-0277.2001.tb02198.x |pmid=11236832}}</ref>\n\nThe phenomenon of alcohol expectations recognizes that intoxication has real physiological consequences that alter a drinker's perception of space and time, reduce psychomotor skills, and disrupt [[Equilibrioception|equilibrium]].<ref name=MacAndrew/> The manner and degree to which alcohol expectations interact with the physiological short-term effects of alcohol, resulting in specific behaviors, is unclear.\n\nA single study found that if a society believes that intoxication leads to [[Alcohol and sex|sexual behavior]], rowdy behavior, or aggression, then people tend to act that way when intoxicated. But if a society believes that intoxication leads to relaxation and tranquil behavior, then it usually leads to those outcomes. Alcohol expectations vary within a society, so these outcomes are not certain.<ref name=\"The think-drink effect\">{{cite journal | last1 = Marlatt | first1 = G. A. | last2 = Rosenow | name-list-format=vanc | year = 1981 | title = The think-drink effect | url = | journal = Psychology Today | volume = 15 | issue = | pages = 60\u201393 }}</ref>\n\nPeople tend to conform to social expectations, and some societies expect that drinking alcohol will cause disinhibition. However, in societies in which the people do not expect that alcohol will disinhibit, intoxication seldom leads to disinhibition and bad behavior.<ref name=MacAndrew>MacAndrew, C. and Edgerton. ''Drunken Comportment: A Social Explanation''. Chicago: Aldine, 1969.</ref>\n\nAlcohol expectations can operate in the absence of actual consumption of alcohol. Research in the United States over a period of decades has shown that men tend to become more sexually aroused when they think they have been drinking alcohol\u2014even when they have not been drinking it. Women report feeling more sexually aroused when they falsely believe the beverages they have been drinking contained alcohol (although one measure of their physiological arousal shows that they became less aroused).{{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n\n===Drug treatment programs===\nMost addiction treatment programs encourage people with drinking problems to see themselves as having a chronic, relapsing disease that requires a lifetime of attendance at 12-step meetings to keep in check. However, some people do not develop lifelong problems.{{cn|date=April 2019}}\n\n==Alcohol abuse==\n{{see also|Alcohol abuse|Substance abuse prevention}}\n[[File:Rational harm assessment of drugs radar plot.svg|thumb|Addiction experts in psychiatry, chemistry, pharmacology, forensic science, epidemiology, and the police and legal services engaged in [[Delphi method|delphic analysis]] regarding 20 popular recreational drugs. Alcohol was ranked 6th in dependence, 11th in physical harm, and 2nd in social harm.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Nutt|first1=D|last2=King|first2=LA|last3=Saulsbury|first3=W|last4=Blakemore|first4=C|title=Development of a rational scale to assess the harm of drugs of potential misuse.|journal=Lancet|date=24 March 2007|volume=369|issue=9566|pages=1047\u201353|pmid=17382831|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(07)60464-4}}</ref>]]\n\n===Alcohol abuse prevention programs===\nMore than 200 injuries and disease conditions are caused due to alcohol abuse.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.who.int/substance_abuse/safer/en/|title=WHO {{!}} THE SAFER INITIATIVE|website=WHO|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref> It is a causative agent influencing maternal health and development, noncommunicable diseases (including cancer and cardiovascular diseases), injuries, violence, mental health, and infectious diseases such as TB and HIV/AIDS. <ref>{{Cite book|title=Global status report on alcohol and health 2018.|last=World Health Organization.|others=World Health Organization,, World Health Organization. Management of Substance Abuse Team|isbn=978-92-4-156563-9|location=Geneva|oclc=1089229677|date=14 February 2019}}</ref>Harmful use of alcohol has been identified as a global health issue, and its management is a priority in the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nations|first=United|date=2015-12-31|title=Transforming governance for the 2030 agenda for sustainable development|url=https://www.un-ilibrary.org/democracy-and-governance/world-public-sector-report-2015_e5a72957-en|language=en|pages=73\u201387|doi=10.18356/e5a72957-en}}</ref> In 2018, WHO launched the initiative '''SAFER,''' to decrease the number of deaths, diseases and injuries caused by alcohol misuse. It has been developed to address the regional, country and global health and developmental goals using high-impact, cost-effective, evidence-based interventions.Using a set of WHO tools and resources SAFER will concentrate on the more cost-effective interventions to reduce and preventive alcohol related abuse.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Global action plan for the prevention and control of noncommunicable diseases : 2013-2020.|others=World Health Organization|isbn=978-92-4-150623-6|location=Geneva, Switzerland|oclc=960910741}}</ref> The five WHO \u201cbest buys\u201d for decreasing alcohol misuse are priority in this action plan<ref name=\":0\" />:\n\n* '''S'''trengthen restrictions on alcohol availability.\n* '''A'''dvance and enforce drink driving countermeasures.\n* '''F'''acilitate access to screening, brief interventions, and treatment.\n* '''E'''nforce bans or comprehensive restrictions on alcohol advertising, sponsorship, and promotion.\n* '''R'''aise prices on alcohol through excise taxes and pricing policies.\n\nThe promotion and success of the SAFER initiative is based on three key principles to implement, to monitor, and to protect.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Recommended maximum intake===\n{{Main|Recommended maximum intake of alcoholic beverages}}\n\nBinge drinking is becoming a major problem in the UK. Advice on weekly consumption is avoided in United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aim-digest.com/gateway/pages/guide/articles/biggy.htm |title=Sensible Drinking |publisher=Aim-digest.com |accessdate=5 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101119172727/http://aim-digest.com/gateway/pages/guide/articles/biggy.htm |archivedate=19 November 2010 }}</ref>\n\nSince 1995 the UK government has advised that regular consumption of three to four units (one unit equates to 10 mL of pure ethanol) a day for men and or two to three units for women, would not pose significant health risks. However, consistently drinking more than four units a day (for men) and three units (women), is not advisable.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dh.gov.uk/en/Publichealth/Healthimprovement/Alcoholmisuse/index.htm |title=Alcohol misuse : Department of Health |publisher=Dh.gov.uk |accessdate=5 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nPreviously (from 1992 until 1995), the advice was that men should drink no more than 21 units per week, and women no more than 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.drinkaware.co.uk/alcohol-facts/health-effects-of-alcohol/lifestyle/alcohol-and-your-health/ |title=Alcohol and health: how alcohol can affect your long and short term health |publisher=Drinkaware.co.uk |accessdate=5 February 2013}}</ref> (The difference between the sexes was due to the typically lower weight and water-to-body-mass ratio of women.) This was changed because a government study showed that many people were in effect \"saving up\" their units and using them at the end of the week, a phenomenon referred to as [[binge drinking]].{{Citation needed|date= October 2007}} ''[[The Times]]'' reported in October 2007 that these limits had been \"plucked out of the air\" and had no scientific basis.<ref>[http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/life/food/article1778774.ece Drink limits \u2018useless\u2019], The Times, 20 October 2007</ref>\n\n===Sobriety===\n{{see also|Sobriety}}\n\n[[File:Breathalyzer test 0013.png|right|thumb|A [[midshipman]] is subjected to a random [[breathalyzer]] test to determine sobriety.]]\nSobriety is the condition of not having any measurable levels, or effects from [[mood-altering drug]]s. According to WHO \"Lexicon of alcohol and drug terms...\" sobriety is continued abstinence from psychoactive drug use.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.who.int/substance_abuse/terminology/who_lexicon/en/ |title=Lexicon and drug terms |publisher=Who.int |date=9 December 2010 |accessdate=5 February 2013 }}</ref> Sobriety is also considered to be the natural state of a human being given at a birth. In a treatment setting, sobriety is the achieved goal of independence from consuming or craving mind-altering substances. As such, sustained abstinence is a prerequisite for sobriety. Early in abstinence, residual effects of mind-altering substances can preclude sobriety. These effects are labeled \"PAWS\", or \"post acute withdrawal syndrome\". Someone who abstains, but has a latent desire to resume use, is not considered truly sober. An abstainer may be subconsciously motivated to resume drug use, but for a variety of reasons, abstains (e.g. such as a medical or legal concern precluding use).<ref name=basharin>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.video.sbnt.ru/vl/Newspapers/Podsporie/Podsporie_111.pdf |title=Scientific grounding for sobriety: Western experience |author=MD Basharin K.G. |year=2010 |accessdate=5 February 2013 }}</ref> Sobriety has more specific meanings within specific contexts, such as the culture of [[Alcoholics Anonymous]], other 12 step programs, law enforcement, and some schools of psychology. In some cases, sobriety implies achieving \"life balance\".<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.stopdrinkingexpert.com/pdf/12steps.pdf |title=Twelve Steps and Twelve Traditions |publisher=Alcoholics Anonymous World Services |access-date=31 December 2018 |isbn= 978-0-916856-01-4 |date=April 1953}} (Electronic .PDF version, September 2005).</ref>\n\n== Injury and deaths ==\n[[Injury]] is defined as physical damage or harm that is done or sustained. The potential of injuring oneself or others can be increased after consuming alcohol due to the certain short term effects related to the substance such as lack of coordination, blurred vision, and slower reflexes to name a few.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.drinkwise.org.au/drinking-and-you/how-is-drinking-affecting-you/|title = Drinkwise Australia|date = |accessdate = |website = DrinkWise Australia}}</ref> Due to these effects the most common injuries include head, fall, and vehicle-related injuries. A study was conducted of patients admitted to the [[Ulster Hospital]] in Northern Ireland with fall related injuries. They found that 113 of those patients admitted to that hospital during that had consumed alcohol recently and that the injury severity was higher for those that had consumed alcohol compared to those that had not.<ref>{{Cite journal|url = http://emj.bmj.com/content/21/2/185.full|title = Alcohol related falls: an interesting pattern of injuries|vauthors = Johnson J, McGovern S |date =2003|journal = Emergency Medicine Journal|volume = 21|issue = 2|pages = 185\u2013188|doi = 10.1136/emj.2003.006130|pmid = 14988344|pmc = 1726307}}</ref> Another study showed that 21% of patients admitted to the Emergency Department of the [[Bristol Royal Infirmary]] had either direct or indirect alcohol related injuries. If these figures are extrapolated it shows that the estimated number of patients with alcohol related injuries are over 7,000 during the year at this emergency department alone.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = What is the burden of alcohol-related injuries in an inner city emergency department?|vauthors=Hoskins R, Benger J |date=2013|journal = Alcoholism: Clinical and Experimental Research|doi = 10.1111/j.1530-0277.2009.00981.x|pmid = 19485974|pmc=2757258 |volume=33|issue = 9|pages=1532\u20131538}}</ref> \n\nIn the United States alcohol resulted in about 88,000 deaths in 2010.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Alcohol-attributable deaths and years of potential life lost \u2014 11 states, 2006\u20132010|website=www.cdc.gov|url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm6310a2.htm}}</ref> The [[World Health Organization]] calculated that more than 3 million people, mostly men, died as a result of harmful use of alcohol in 2016. This was about 13.5 % of the total deaths of people between 20 and 39. More than 5% of the global disease burden was caused by the harmful use of alcohol.<ref>{{cite news |title=Alcohol |url=http://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/alcohol |accessdate=5 November 2018 |publisher=World health Organization |date=21 September 2018}}</ref> There are even higher estimates for Europe.<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/41473801/Distilled_Spirits_Overconsumption_as_the_Most_Important_Factor_of_Excessive_Adult_Male_Mortality_in_Europe_Alcohol_and_Alcoholism_2018_53_6_742_752 Korotayev, A., Khaltourina, D., Meshcherina, K., & Zamiatnina, E. Distilled Spirits Overconsumption as the Most Important Factor of Excessive Adult Male Mortality in Europe. ''Alcohol and Alcoholism'', 2018, 53(6), 742-752].</ref>\n\n==Genetic differences==\n\n===Alcohol flush and respiratory reactions===\n{{see also|Alcohol flush reaction|Alcohol-induced respiratory reactions|Short-term effects of alcohol consumption}}\nAlcohol flush reaction is a condition in which an individual's face or body experiences flushes or blotches as a result of an accumulation of [[acetaldehyde]], a metabolic byproduct of the catabolic metabolism of alcohol. It is best known as a condition that is experienced by people of Asian descent. According to the analysis by [[HapMap Project]], the rs671 allele of the ALDH2 gene responsible for the flush reaction is rare among Europeans and Africans, and it is very rare among Mexican-Americans. 30% to 50% of people of Chinese and Japanese ancestry have at least one ALDH*2 allele.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.snpedia.com/index.php/Rs671 |title=Rs671 |website=SNPmedia }}</ref> The rs671 form of ALDH2, which accounts for most incidents of alcohol flush reaction worldwide, is native to East Asia and most common in southeastern China. It most likely originated among Han Chinese in central China,<ref>{{cite journal|title=Refined Geographic Distribution of the Oriental ALDH2*504Lys (nee 487Lys) Variant|author=Hui Li|journal=Ann Hum Genet |year=2009|pmc=2846302|pmid=19456322|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1809.2009.00517.x|volume=73|issue=Pt 3|pages=335\u2013345|display-authors=et al}}</ref> and it appears to have been positively selected in the past. Another analysis correlates the rise and spread of rice cultivation in Southern China with the spread of the allele.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Yi Peng |author2=Hong Shi |author3=Xue-bin Qi |author4=Chun-jie Xiao |author5=Hua Zhong |author6=Run-lin Z Ma |author7=Bing Su |title=The ADH1B Arg47His polymorphism in East Asian populations and expansion of rice domestication in history |journal=BMC Evolutionary Biology |volume=10 |page= 15|year=2010 |pmid=20089146 |pmc=2823730 |doi= 10.1186/1471-2148-10-15|issue=1}}</ref> The reasons for this positive selection aren't known, but it's been hypothesized that elevated concentrations of acetaldehyde may have conferred protection against certain parasitic infections, such as ''[[Entamoeba histolytica]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Oota H, Pakstis AJ, Bonne-Tamir B, Goldman D, Grigorenko E, Kajuna SL, et al |title=The evolution and population genetics of the ALDH2 locus: random genetic drift, selection, and low levels of recombination |journal=Ann. Hum. Genet. |volume=68 |issue=Pt 2 |pages=93\u2013109 |date=2004 |pmid=15008789 |doi= 10.1046/j.1529-8817.2003.00060.x|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/a982b046ccdf544c10368a284757121a0c727b40}}</ref> The same SNP allele of ALDH2, also termed glu487lys, and the abnormal accumulation of acetaldehyde following the drinking of alcohol, is associated with the [[alcohol-induced respiratory reactions]] of rhinitis and asthma that occur in Eastern Asian populations.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Adams|first1=KE|last2=Rans|first2=TS|title=Adverse reactions to alcohol and alcoholic beverages|journal=Annals of Allergy, Asthma & Immunology|date=2013|volume=111|issue=6|pages=439\u2013445|doi=10.1016/j.anai.2013.09.016|pmid=24267355}}</ref>\n{{alcohol metabolism formulae}}\n\n===American Indian alcoholism===\n{{main|Alcohol and Native Americans}}\nCompared with the United States population in general, the Native American population is much more susceptible to alcoholism and related diseases and deaths.<ref name = \"May\">[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK233103/pdf/Bookshelf_NBK233103.pdf Philip A. May, \"Overview of Alcohol Abuse Epidemiology for American Indian Populations,\" in ''Changing Numbers, Changing Needs: American Indian Demography and Public Health,'' Gary D. Sandefur, Ronald R. Rindfuss, Barney Cohen, Editors. Committee on Population, Commission on Behavioral and Social Sciences and Education National Research Council. National Academy Press: Washington, D.C. 1996]</ref> From 2006 to 2010, alcohol-attributed deaths accounted for 11.7 percent of all Native American deaths, more than twice the rates of the general U.S. population. The median alcohol-attributed death rate for Native Americans (60.6 per 100,000) was twice as high as the rate for any other racial or ethnic group.<ref name = \"MMWR\">{{cite journal| pmc=5779340 | pmid=24622285 | volume=63 | title=Alcohol-attributable deaths and years of potential life lost--11 States, 2006-2010 | year=2014 | journal=MMWR Morb Mortal Wkly Rep | pages=213\u20136 | last1 = Gonzales | first1 = K | last2 = Roeber | first2 = J | last3 = Kanny | first3 = D | last4 = Tran | first4 = A | last5 = Saiki | first5 = C | last6 = Johnson | first6 = H | last7 = Yeoman | first7 = K | last8 = Safranek | first8 = T | last9 = Creppage | first9 = K | last10 = Lepp | first10 = A | last11 = Miller | first11 = T | last12 = Tarkhashvili | first12 = N | last13 = Lynch | first13 = KE | last14 = Watson | first14 = JR | last15 = Henderson | first15 = D | last16 = Christenson | first16 = M | last17 = Geiger | first17 = SD}}</ref> Males are affected disproportionately more by alcohol-related conditions than females.<ref name = \"Whitesell\">{{cite journal| pmc=4436971 | pmid=22931069 | doi=10.3109/00952990.2012.694527 | volume=38 | title=Epidemiology and etiology of substance use among American Indians and Alaska Natives: risk, protection, and implications for prevention | year=2012 | journal=Am J Drug Alcohol Abuse | pages=376\u201382 | last1 = Whitesell | first1 = NR | last2 = Beals | first2 = J | last3 = Crow | first3 = CB | last4 = Mitchell | first4 = CM | last5 = Novins | first5 = DK| issue=5 }}</ref> The highest risk of alcohol-related deaths is between 45 and 64 years of age. Chronic liver disease and [[cirrhosis]] are 3.9 times as prevalent in the Native American population than the general US population. Of all alcohol-attributable deaths, motor vehicle accidents account for 27.5% and [[alcoholic liver disease]] accounts for 25.2%. [[Driving under the influence|Alcohol-related fatal car accidents]] are three times more prevalent among Native Americans than in other ethnicities.\n\nNative American populations exhibit genetic differences in the alcohol-metabolizing enzymes [[alcohol dehydrogenase]] and [[ALDH]],<ref>{{cite journal| pmc=3860438 | pmid=17718395 | volume=30 | title=Variations in ADH and ALDH in Southwest California Indians | year=2007 | journal=Alcohol Res Health | pages=14\u20137 | last1 = Ehlers | first1 = CL}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| pmc=3498484 | pmid=22931071 | doi=10.3109/00952990.2012.694526 | volume=38 | title=ADH and ALDH polymorphisms and alcohol dependence in Mexican and Native Americans | year=2012 | journal=Am J Drug Alcohol Abuse | pages=389\u201394 | last1 = Ehlers | first1 = CL | last2 = Liang | first2 = T | last3 = Gizer | first3 = IR| issue=5 }}</ref> although evidence that these genetic factors are more prevalent in Native Americans than other ethnic groups has been a subject of debate.<ref name = \"Ehlers\">[https://ajp.psychiatryonline.org/doi/full/10.1176/appi.ajp.2012.12010113 Ehlers CL, Gizer IR. \"Evidence for a genetic component for substance dependence in Native Americans.\" ''Am J Psychiatry.'' 1 Feb 2013;170(2):154\u2013164.]</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Caetano | first1 = Raul | last2 = Clark | first2 = Catherine L. | last3 = Tam | first3 = Tammy | year = 1998 | title = Alcohol consumption among racial/ethnic minorities | journal = Alcohol Health and Research World | volume = 22 | issue = 4| pages = 233\u2013241 | citeseerx = 10.1.1.556.6875 }}</ref><ref name = \"Ethnicity\">[https://pubs.niaaa.nih.gov/publications/arh40/152-160.htm Karen Chartier and Raul Caetano, \"Ethnicity and health disparities in alcohol research,\" ''Alcohol Res Health'' 2010, vol. 33: 1-2 pp. 152-160]</ref> According to one 2013 review of academic literature on the issue, there is a \"substantial genetic component in Native Americans\" and that \"most Native Americans lack protective variants seen in other populations.\"<ref name = \"Ehlers\"/> Many scientists have provided evidence of the genetic component of alcoholism by the [[biopsychosocial model]] of alcoholism, but the [[molecular genetics]] research currently has not found one specific gene that is responsible for the rates of alcoholism among Native Americans, implying the phenomenon may be due to an interplay of multiple genes and environmental factors.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Wall | first1 = Tamara L. | last2 = Carr | first2 = Lucinda G. | last3 = Ehlers | first3 = Cindy L. | year = 2003 | title = Protective association of genetic variation in alcohol dehydrogenase with alcohol dependence in Native American Mission Indians | journal = American Journal of Psychiatry | volume = 160 | issue = 1| pages = 41\u201346 | doi = 10.1176/appi.ajp.160.1.41 | pmid = 12505800 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| pmid=15900224 | doi=10.1097/00041444-200506000-00006 | volume=15 | title=Heritability of substance dependence in a native American population | year=2005 | journal=Psychiatr Genet | pages=101\u20137 | last1 = Wilhelmsen | first1 = KC | last2 = Ehlers | first2 = C| issue=2 }}</ref> Research on [[alcoholism in family systems]] suggests that learned behavior augments genetic factors in increasing the probability that children of alcoholics will themselves have problems with alcohol.<ref>{{cite journal| pmc=3872279 | pmid=24386563 | doi=10.1155/2013/410395 | volume=2013 | title=A Framework to Examine the Role of Epigenetics in Health Disparities among Native Americans | year=2013 | journal=Nurs Res Pract | page=410395 | last1 = Brockie | first1 = TN | last2 = Heinzelmann | first2 = M | last3 = Gill | first3 = J}}</ref>\n\n=== Genetics and amount of consumption ===\nHaving a particular genetic variant (A-allele of ADH1B rs1229984) is associated with non-drinking and lower alcohol consumption. This variant is also associated with favorable cardiovascular profile and a reduced risk of coronary heart disease compared to those without the genetic variant, but it is unknown whether this may be caused by differences in alcohol consumption or by additional [[confounder|confounding]] effects of the genetic variant itself.<ref name=\"Holmes et al.\">{{cite journal | last1 = Holmes | first = Michael V. | display-authors = etal   | year = 2014 | title = Association between alcohol and cardiovascular disease: Mendelian randomisation analysis based on individual participant data | url = http://www.bmj.com/content/349/bmj.g4164 | journal = BMJ | volume = 349 | issue = | page = g4164 | doi = 10.1136/bmj.g4164 | pmid=25011450 | pmc=4091648}}</ref>\n\n==Gender differences==\n\nHistorically, according to the ''[[British Medical Journal]]'', \"men have been far more likely than women to drink alcohol and to drink it in quantities that damage their health, with some figures suggesting up to a 12-fold difference between the sexes\".<ref name=\"Women catching up\">{{cite press release |title=Women catching up with men in alcohol consumption and its associated harms |work=BMJ Open |date=25 October 2016 |url=http://www.bmj.com/company/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/bmj-open-alcohol-women.pdf}}</ref> However, analysis of data collected over a century from multiple countries suggests that the [[wiktionary:Gender gap|gender gap]] in [[alcohol consumption]] is narrowing, and that young women (born after 1981) are consuming alcohol more than their male counterparts. Such findings have implications for the way in which alcohol-use prevention and intervention programs are designed and implemented.<ref name=Slade2016>{{cite journal |vauthors=Slade T, Chapman C, Swift W, Keyes K, Tonks Z, Teesson M |title=Birth cohort trends in the global epidemiology of alcohol use and alcohol-related harms in men and women: systematic review and metaregression |journal=BMJ Open|date=2016 |volume=6 |issue=10 |pages=e011827 |doi=10.1136/bmjopen-2016-011827 |pmid=27797998 |pmc=5093369 |url=http://bmjopen.bmj.com/content/6/10/e011827.full.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Alcoholism===\nBased on combined data from SAMHSA's 2004-2005 National Surveys on Drug Use & Health, the rate of past year [[alcohol dependence]] or abuse among people aged 12 or older varied by level of alcohol use: 44.7% of past month heavy drinkers, 18.5% binge drinkers, 3.8% past month non-binge drinkers, and 1.3% of those who did not drink alcohol in the past month met the criteria for alcohol dependence or abuse in the past year. Males had higher rates than females for all measures of drinking in the past month: any alcohol use (57.5% vs. 45%), binge drinking (30.8% vs. 15.1%), and heavy alcohol use (10.5% vs. 3.3%), and males were twice as likely as females to have met the criteria for alcohol dependence or abuse in the past year (10.5% vs. 5.1%).<ref>\"Gender differences in alcohol use and alcohol dependence or abuse: 2004 or 2005.\" The NSDUH Report. Accessed 22 June 2012.</ref>\nOver time the difference between males and females has narrowed. According to a 2016 systematic review, for those born at the end of the 20th century men were 1.2 times as likely to drink to problematic levels, and 1.3 times as likely to develop health problems from drinking.<ref name=Slade2016 />\n\n===Sensitivity===\nSeveral biological factors make women more vulnerable to the effects of alcohol than men.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.helpguide.org/harvard/women_alcohol.htm |title=Women & Alcohol: The Hidden Risks of Drinking |publisher=Helpguide.org |accessdate=5 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130103092219/http://www.helpguide.org/harvard/women_alcohol.htm |archivedate=3 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\n* Body fat. Women tend to weigh less than men, and\u2014pound for pound\u2014a woman's body contains less water and more fatty tissue than a man's. Because fat retains alcohol while water dilutes it, alcohol remains at higher concentrations for longer periods of time in a woman's body, exposing her brain and other organs to more alcohol.\n* Enzymes. Women have lower levels of two enzymes\u2014alcohol dehydrogenase and aldehyde dehydrogenase\u2014that metabolize (break down) alcohol in the stomach and liver. As a result, women absorb more alcohol into their bloodstreams than men.\n* Hormones. Changes in hormone levels during the menstrual cycle may also affect how a woman metabolizes alcohol.\n\n===Metabolism===\nFemales demonstrated a higher average rate of elimination (mean, 0.017; range, 0.014\u20130.021 g/210 L) than males (mean, 0.015; range, 0.013\u20130.017 g/210 L). Female subjects on average had a higher percentage of body fat (mean, 26.0; range, 16.7\u201336.8%) than males (mean, 18.0; range, 10.2\u201325.3%).<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 8872236 | volume=20 | issue=5 | title=Determination of volume of distribution for ethanol in male and female subjects. | date=Sep 1996 | pages=287\u201390 | journal=J Anal Toxicol | doi=10.1093/jat/20.5.287 | last1 = Cowan | first1 = JM Jr | last2 = Weathermon | first2 = A | last3 = McCutcheon | first3 = JR | last4 = Oliver | first4 = RD}}</ref>\n\n===Depression===\nThe link between alcohol consumption, depression, and gender was examined by the Centre for Addiction and Mental Health (Canada). The study found that women taking antidepressants consumed more alcohol than women who did not experience depression as well as men taking antidepressants. The researchers, Dr. Kathryn Graham and a PhD Student Agnes Massak analyzed the responses to a survey by 14,063 Canadian residents aged 18\u201376 years. The survey included measures of quantity, frequency of drinking, depression and antidepressants use, over the period of a year. The researchers used data from the GENACIS Canada survey, part of an international collaboration to investigate the influence of cultural variation on gender differences in alcohol use and related problems. The purpose of the study was to examine whether, like in other studies already conducted on male depression and alcohol consumption, depressed women also consumed less alcohol when taking anti-depressants. According to the study, both men and women experiencing depression (but not on anti-depressants) drank more than non-depressed counterparts. Men taking antidepressants consumed significantly less alcohol than depressed men who did not use antidepressants. Non-depressed men consumed 436 drinks per year, compared to 579 drinks for depressed men not using antidepressants, and 414 drinks for depressed men who used antidepressants. Alcohol consumption remained higher whether the depressed women were taking anti-depressants or not. 179 drinks per year for non-depressed women, 235 drinks for depressed women not using antidepressants, and 264 drinks for depressed women who used antidepressants. The lead researcher argued that the study \"suggests that the use of antidepressants is associated with lower alcohol consumption among men suffering from depression. But this does not appear to be true for women.\"<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1503/cmaj.060446 | pmid=17325328 | pmc=1800314 | volume=176 | title=Alcohol consumption and the use of antidepressants | journal=Canadian Medical Association Journal | pages=633\u2013637  | last1 = Graham | first1 = K. | last2 = Massak | first2 = A.| issue=5 | year=2007 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Alcoholic beverage]]\n* [[Short-term effects of alcohol consumption]]\n* [[Long-term effects of alcohol consumption]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.sciencealert.com/global-burden-of-disease-alcohol-assessment-global-death-disability-rate  Massive Study Finds Alcohol Is a Leading Contributor to Death And Disease Worldwide]\n\n{{Alcohealth}}\n{{Psychoactive substance use}}\n\n[[Category:Alcohol and health]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alcohol_and_health"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Washington, D.C.", "text_new": "{{short description|Pandemic in Washington, D.C., United States}}\n{{Current event|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Washington, D.C.\n| width           = \n| image           = National Gallery of Art (49656625722).jpg\n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = Visitors wearing masks in the [[National Gallery of Art]], the day before it closed as a precaution against COVID-19\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n| first_case      = March 7, 2020\n| arrival_date    = \n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 902\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| deaths          = 21\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://coronavirus.dc.gov/}}\n}}\n\nThe first cases of [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the global pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in [[Washington, D.C.]] were reported on March 7, 2020. {{As of|2020|04|02|df=US}}, there are 902 confirmed cases and 21 deaths in Washington, D.C. alone, with other cases in the surrounding counties of the [[Washington metropolitan area]].<ref name=\"dcgovdata\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Data |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/page/coronavirus-data |website=DC.Gov |publisher=Government of the District of Columbia |accessdate=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323134324/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/page/coronavirus-data |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Washington, D.C. medical cases chart}}\n\n==Timeline==\n\n=== February ===\nMayor [[Muriel Bowser]] signed an executive order that began to prepare Washington D.C. for coronavirus impacts on February 28. It was announced in the executive order that the District's Emergency Operations Center (EOC) would be activated on March 2, 2020 at 9:00&nbsp;a.m. to begin to \"coordinate inter-agency information sharing and identify logistical needs for critical incident responses.\" It was also announced that the Washington D.C. Department of Health and the Homeland Security and Emergency Management Agency would be responsible for the response planning for COVID-19.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayors-order-district-government-preparations-coronavirus|title=Mayor's Order: District Government Preparations for the Coronavirus {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329193351/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayors-order-district-government-preparations-coronavirus|archive-date=2020-03-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n\n==== March 1\u20134 ====\nOn March 2 at 9:00&nbsp;a.m., the D.C. Emergency Operations Center was activated at an Enhanced Watch status, as per the executive order signed on February 28.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn March 3, Mayor Bowser, the D.C. Department of Health, and the D.C. Homeland Security and Emergency Management Agency held a public briefing on the coronavirus and the District's \"monitoring, preparation, and response\" to it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-hold-briefing-district%E2%80%99s-coronavirus-monitoring-preparation-and-response|title=Mayor Bowser to Hold Briefing on the District's Coronavirus Monitoring, Preparation, and Response {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308004155/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-hold-briefing-district%E2%80%99s-coronavirus-monitoring-preparation-and-response|archive-date=2020-03-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====March 5\u20137====\nOn March 7, the first two cases of COVID-19 in Washington, D.C. were confirmed. The first case was a [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|rector]] at [[Christ Church (Georgetown, Washington, D.C.)|Christ Church Georgetown]] who had not traveled outside the United States recently or had contact with another infected coronavirus patient. He participated in church services on February 23 and March 1. The rector felt better initially, but his condition deteriorated to the point of hospitalization, when it was confirmed he had coronavirus. After it was confirmed the rector contracted the virus, the church cancelled services indefinitely. The second case was a [[Nigeria]]n national who traveled to D.C. and went to a hospital in [[Maryland]] for treatment. Although the second man was being treated at a Maryland hospital, he was counted as the District's second case by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC).<ref>{{cite news |title=Georgetown Church Rector, Traveler Diagnosed as DC's First 2 Coronavirus Cases |url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-has-first-presumptive-coronavirus-case/2234068/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=NBC4 Washington |date=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316154326/https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-has-first-presumptive-coronavirus-case/2234068/ |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|user=MayorBowser|number=1236422174958895104|title=Late this afternoon, testing at the Public Health Lab at the DC Department of Forensic Sciences yielded its first presumptive positive coronavirus (COVID-19) case. Join me live at 7:30 p.m. for a briefing at the John A. Wilson Building.|date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====March 8\u201310====\nOn March 9, [[School Without Walls (Washington, D.C.)|School Without Walls]], a public school in [[Foggy Bottom]], was closed by [[District of Columbia Public Schools]] (DCPS) for a full-day deep cleaning and disinfecting by a third-party contractor after an employee was exposed to COVID-19 the week before. The employee tested negative and entered a two-week quarantine. DCPS chancellor Lewis Ferebee announced the closing over Twitter the previous day.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1236819215920832513|date=8 Mar 2020|title=Tomorrow - 3/9 - School Without Walls High School will be closed. DCPS is conducting a deep cleaning and disinfecting of the building following an employee being exposed to COVID-19. Test results were negative, and there is no immediate risk to students and staff. cc: @SWWHSA}}</ref>\n\nThree more coronavirus cases in D.C. were confirmed the night of March 9, including an attendee of Christ Church Georgetown. D.C. officials recommended a two-week self-quarantine per CDC guidelines for anyone who attended Christ Church on February 24 or between February 28 and March 3. At that time, $1.5 million had been allocated to the pandemic response by the D.C. government.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gelman |first1=Scott |last2=Alvarez |first2=Alejandro |title=16 coronavirus cases confirmed in DC, Md. and Va. |url=https://wtop.com/local/2020/03/bowser-hogan-to-deliver-update-on-coronavirus-as-dc-area-officials-investigate-9-cases/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=WTOP |date=9 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313023822/https://wtop.com/local/2020/03/bowser-hogan-to-deliver-update-on-coronavirus-as-dc-area-officials-investigate-9-cases/ |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, [[George Washington University]] announced classes will be moved online after spring break, starting on March 23 and continuing until at least April 5. In addition, all residential students were expected to no longer be living on campus beginning March 21. It was stated that an opening date would not be announced until the end of the instructional continuity period when a decision for the rest of the semester would be made.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fox5dc.com/news/george-washington-university-moving-to-online-classes-after-spring-break|title=George Washington University moving to online classes after spring break|date=2020-03-10|website=Fox 5 DC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311103004/https://www.fox5dc.com/news/george-washington-university-moving-to-online-classes-after-spring-break|archive-date=2020-03-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.georgetown.edu/coronavirus/|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) Resource Center|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312130006/https://www.georgetown.edu/coronavirus/|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAlso on March 10, [[Georgetown Day School]], a private school, closed indefinitely and began a deep clean citing concerns about community members affiliated with [[Christ Church (Georgetown, Washington, D.C.)|Christ Church Georgetown]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Volou |first1=Khalida |title=DC school closed due to coronavirus exposure linked to Christ Church Georgetown |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-day-school-closed-tuesday-due-to-coronavirus/65-e374b3e9-a496-42ed-9043-d4bd0b9c45c9 |agency=WUSA9 |date=10 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311195837/https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-day-school-closed-tuesday-due-to-coronavirus/65-e374b3e9-a496-42ed-9043-d4bd0b9c45c9 |archive-date=11 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====March 11\u201314====\nOn March 11, [[Maria Cantwell]], a U.S. senator from Washington state, closed her D.C. office due to one of her aides testing positive for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/politics-government/article241118946.html|title=Aide to Maria Cantwell tests positive for coronavirus. Senator closes her D.C. office|last=Lightman|first=David|website=thenewstribune|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313030257/https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/politics-government/article241118946.html|archive-date=2020-03-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Georgetown University]] announced that it would be moving to virtual learning entirely beginning on March 16, and while campus would remain open and key services would remain accessible the university strongly suggested that students return to their homes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khan |first1=Saliqa |title=Georgetown University moves to virtual learning amid coronavirus concerns |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-university-moves-to-virtual-learning-amid-coronavirus-concerns/65-60c60f1b-9838-4090-80e9-dffa49d92737 |work=WUSA9 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318192012/https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-university-moves-to-virtual-learning-amid-coronavirus-concerns/65-60c60f1b-9838-4090-80e9-dffa49d92737 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, the [[United States Capitol]], the [[White House]], and the [[United States Supreme Court Building]] closed to most of the public until April after several offices closed and multiple lawmakers went into precautionary quarantines.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zengerle |first1=Patricia |last2=Heavey |first2=Susan |title=UPDATE 5-U.S. federal buildings put away the welcome mat as coronavirus hits |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-usa-capitol/update-5-us-federal-buildings-put-away-the-welcome-mat-as-coronavirus-hits-idUSL1N2B50S4 |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, [[District of Columbia Public Schools|DCPS]] announced that they will cancel classes until April 1, implementing online distance learning.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1238430012417748993|date=13 March 2020|title=DCPS will modify operations from Monday, March 16 through Tuesday, March 31 to help limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19) in our region. For more info about the closure schedule, meal locations for students & distance learning details, please visit: https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus}}</ref> Also on March 13, the [[Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]] (WMATA) escalated its operations to level 3 of its pandemic flu plan, announcing that service on the [[Washington Metro]] would be reduced to one train every 12 minutes from Monday to Saturday and one train every 15 minutes on Sunday beginning on March 17. In addition, [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]] service would change to a Saturday supplemental schedule on weekdays beginning on March 17.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmata.com/service/status/details/COVID-19.cfm#main-content|title=Metro takes additional steps, coordinates with public health authorities on COVID-19 {{!}} WMATA|website=wmata.com|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314155101/https://wmata.com/service/status/details/COVID-19.cfm#main-content|archive-date=2020-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/transportation/2020/03/13/metro-reduces-transit-service-response-coronavirus/|title=Metro to reduce transit service in response to the coronavirus outbreak|last=George|first=Justin|date=13 March 2020|website=Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314134151/https://www.washingtonpost.com/transportation/2020/03/13/metro-reduces-transit-service-response-coronavirus/|archive-date=14 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMayor [[Muriel Bowser]] held a press conference, announcing that gatherings of people over 60 years of age or with preexisting health issues would be limited to 10 people. The restriction would not apply to residences, schools, or places of work. For populations not at-risk the government promoted [[social distancing]] measures to limit the spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vitka |first1=Will |last2=Bonk |first2=Valerie |title=Trump declares national emergency; DC bans mass gatherings |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-dc-area/ |work=WTOP |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314183154/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-dc-area/ |archive-date=14 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, Mayor Bowser issued a statement confirming 6 more positive cases in Washington, D.C., bringing the total number of cases up to 16.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-14|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 14 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316100728/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-14|archive-date=2020-03-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====March 15\u201316====\nOn March 15, Bowser's office announced one more positive case in Washington D.C., bringing the total cumulative number of cases to 17. The patient in this case is a 38-year-old woman who came into contact with another case.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-15|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 15|work=Government of the District of Columbia|accessdate=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324170918/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-15|archive-date=2020-03-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Hill Restaurant Group (HRG) said on March 16 they would comply would restrictions on bars and restaurants ordered by Mayor Bowser on March 15. Tom Johnson, the managing director of the group, had earlier said he would ignore the order, saying it would force his company into bankruptcy.<ref>[https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/487826-dc-restaurant-group-says-it-will-comply-with-restrictions-after-mayor DC restaurant group says it will comply with restrictions after mayor's warning] The Hill, 16 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nOn the evening of March 16, Mayor Bowser's office released an update that confirmed five more positive cases of coronavirus in the District. The patients involved were a 23-year-old man, a 42-year-old woman with a history of travel to Europe, a 54-year-old woman, a 54-year-old man, and a 56-year-old man. These five cases brought the cumulative number of cases in D.C. to 22.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-16|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 16 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317204518/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-16|archive-date=2020-03-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== March 17\u201318 ====\nLate on March 17, Mayor Bowser's office announced the confirmation of nine more positive cases in the District, bringing the total number of positive cases to 31. The patients were all male and between the ages of 23 and 61. The 23-year-old patient was confirmed to have attended the [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC) in [[National Harbor, Maryland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-17|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 17 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319072119/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-17|archive-date=2020-03-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, at least 8 more cases were found, including a [[District of Columbia Fire and Emergency Medical Services Department|DC FEMS]] employee (leading to a quarantine of 73 firefighters), a [[U.S. marshal]] at the [[Superior Court of the District of Columbia]], and an undergraduate student at the George Washington University who lives off-campus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moore |first1=Jack |title=Coronavirus: Jump in new cases around region; DC first responder, US Marshal test positive |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-updates-dc-maryland-virginia/ |work=WTOP |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319002447/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-updates-dc-maryland-virginia/ |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Metropolitan Police Department of the District of Columbia]] announced new [[social distancing]] precautions in dealing with callers reporting flu-like symptoms as well as changes to police protocol for citations and warning notices in light of the restriction of certain services in the D.C. government.<ref>{{cite web |title=Metropolitan Police Department Operational Adjustments During COVID-19 |url=https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/metropolitan-police-department-operational-adjustments-during-covid-19 |website=Metropolitan Police Department |publisher=DC.Gov |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319002500/https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/metropolitan-police-department-operational-adjustments-during-covid-19 |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== March 19\u201320 ====\nAs of March 19, the number of confirmed cases sharply jumped to 71 as the supply of tests was expanded, an increase of 32 over one day.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1240791217647976448|user=MayorBowser|title=As of 8:00 p.m. on Thursday, March 19, the District\u2019s coronavirus (COVID-19) data includes 32 new positive cases, bringing the District\u2019s overall positive case total to 71 individuals. For more information visit:|date=19 March 2020}}</ref> This includes two more DC FEMS members and an eight-year-old.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Massimo |first1=Rick |title=Coronavirus: As more tests become available, DC sees jump in coronavirus cases |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-all-md-malls-entertainment-venues-to-close-at-5-p-m-thursday/ |work=WTOP |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320014753/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-all-md-malls-entertainment-venues-to-close-at-5-p-m-thursday/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe same day, [[Washington Metro]] closed the [[Smithsonian station|Smithsonian]] and [[Arlington Cemetery station|Arlington Cemetery]] stations until further notice. Metro ridership reduced by 85% due to the pandemic, leading to general manager Paul Wiedefeld submitting a request to Congress for emergency funding.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Augenstein |first1=Neal |title=Coronavirus: Metro asks Congress for emergency funding after ridership drops 85% |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-metro-asks-congress-for-emergency-funding-after-ridership-drops-85/ |work=WTOP |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320014754/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-metro-asks-congress-for-emergency-funding-after-ridership-drops-85/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Mayor Bowser announced the first death related to COVID-19 in the District, a 59-year-old male, Deacon Brother John-Sebastian Laird-Hammond, [[Order of Friars Minor|OFM]], a [[Franciscan]] [[friar]] and [[permanent deacon]], a native of [[Minonk, Illinois]], with underlying medical conditions, specifically a multi-year battle with a type of [[leukemia]] who had been undergoing cancer treatments and was therefore more vulnerable to the virus.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/a-franciscan-friar-is-dcs-first-known-coronavirus-fatality-32938 | title=A Franciscan friar and deacon is DC's first known coronavirus fatality | access-date=2020-03-26 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329041046/https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/a-franciscan-friar-is-dcs-first-known-coronavirus-fatality-32938 | archive-date=2020-03-29 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Bowser tweet first death\">{{cite tweet|last=Bowser |first=Muriel |author-link=Muriel Bowser |user=MayorBowser |number=1241051533631946752 |date=2020-03-20 |title=It is with great sadness that we announce a tragic death and, on behalf of our residents, I share our love and condolences with the patient\u2019s family and friends. |access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> The number of cases rose to 77.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\nDCPS extended the school shutdown to April 24, meaning classes would be scheduled to resume on Monday, April 27. In preparation for the beginning of distance learning on March 24, the DCPS Distance Learning platform was released, publicly accessible at {{URL|https://dcps.instructure.com/courses/179580}}. Certain schools would continue to provide lunch on weekdays.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1241081893656956931|title=\ud83d\udea8UPDATE\ud83d\udea8 DCPS will be closed to all staff and students through Friday, April 24 to help mitigate the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19) in our region. Classes will resume for all students on Monday, April 27. For more info please visit: http://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus.|date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== March 21\u201322 ====\n\nOn March 21, the D.C. government, operating through the Metropolitan Police Department and the [[National Park Service]] announced several road closures around beginning on March 22, 7:00 AM to 8:00 PM, in an effort to reduce congregation of tourists around monuments during the [[National Cherry Blossom Festival]]. These crowds had not been conforming to social distancing guidelines and thus presented a possible vector for the transmission of coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Corse |first1=Alexa |title=Washington, D.C., Closes Streets to Prevent Coronavirus Transmission |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/washington-d-c-closes-streets-to-prevent-coronavirus-transmission-11584850717 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=22 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322213549/https://www.wsj.com/articles/washington-d-c-closes-streets-to-prevent-coronavirus-transmission-11584850717 |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=TRAFFIC ADVISORY: Street Closures |url=https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/traffic-advisory-street-closures?mod=article_inline |website=Metropolitan Police Department |publisher=DC.Gov |date=21 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322213607/https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/traffic-advisory-street-closures?mod=article_inline |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[District of Columbia Department of Parks and Recreation|DC Department of Parks and Recreation]] closed all of its facilities including parks, playgrounds, and athletic fields. Only dog parks remained open.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1241457230349811712|user=DCDPR|title=!!ALERT - All DPR facilities including Playgrounds + Gated Parks and Athletic Fields are CLOSED. Dog parks remain open. Stay informed http://coronavirus.dc.gov.|date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe same day, [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]] announced reduced operation from 325 routes to only 20 high-use corridors. Real-time bus data would no longer be available and drivers may bypass stops in order to observe social distancing guidelines on buses. [[WMATA]] said it hoped to restore some routes with limited operation hours soon.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Delaney |first1=Matthew |title=Coronavirus: 2nd death in DC; cases surge throughout region with more testing |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-positive-cases-continue-to-surge-transit-changes-enforce-social-distancing/ |work=WTOP |date=22 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322235143/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-positive-cases-continue-to-surge-transit-changes-enforce-social-distancing/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe number of cases as of 7:30 PM that day was 98.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\nOn March 22, the second death due to COVID-19 was reported in the District, a 65-year-old woman with underlying medical conditions.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=MayorBowser|number=1241783602830020615|title=1/ I am saddened to announce a second death related to COVID-19 in our community. The hearts and prayers of our entire city are with her family and loved ones.|date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe number of cases as of 7:00 PM that day was 116.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\n==== March 23\u201324 ====\nOn March 23, Mayor Bowser and Chief Financial Officer [[Jeffrey DeWitt]] announced that the 2019 tax filing deadlines would be pushed to July 15, instead of the upcoming April 15.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Bowser and Chief Financial Officer DeWitt Announce 2019 Tax Filings and Payment Deadline Extended to July 15, 2020 |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-and-chief-financial-officer-dewitt-announce-2019-tax-filings-and-payment |website=coronavirus.dc.gov |publisher=DC.Gov |date=23 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323215938/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-and-chief-financial-officer-dewitt-announce-2019-tax-filings-and-payment |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Mayor also urged D.C. residents to remain at home except for \"essential activities,\" clarifying that she would not be issuing a [[shelter-in-place order]] as of now.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Katz |first1=Jeffrey |last2=Austermuhle |first2=Martin |last3=Pascale |first3=Jordan |last4=Chamberlin |first4=Victoria |title=UPDATED: D.C.-Area Residents Are Being Asked To Stay In Their Homes If They Can. How Is That Going To Work? |url=https://wamu.org/story/20/03/22/what-happens-if-d-c-declares-a-shelter-in-place-your-questions-answered/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=WAMU |date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323234638/https://wamu.org/story/20/03/22/what-happens-if-d-c-declares-a-shelter-in-place-your-questions-answered/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn that day, Mayor Bowser also commissioned [[Republic Restoratives Distillery]] and [[Compass Coffee]], two locally owned companies, for the production of {{convert|2000|gal}} of [[hand sanitizer]] ({{convert|1000|gal}} each) for use by D.C. government workers and emergency responders.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1242193836014796806|user=MayorBowser|title=1/ DC Government has commissioned 2,000 gallons of hand sanitizer from @RepublicRestore and @CompassCoffeeDC (1,000 each) as part of our response to the coronavirus (COVID-19).|date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 7:00 PM that day, the number of cases was 137.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\n==== March 25 ====\nOn March 25, the third death in Washington, D.C. was a 75-year-old female with underlying health conditions.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1242969615283740673|user=mayorbowser|date=25 March 2020|title=There's a third death in DC due to coronavirus (COVID-19). The patient, a 75-year-old female, was admitted to a hospital with underlying health conditions and passed away on March 25. She tested positive for COVID-19 and was included among the District\u2019s reporting data.}}</ref>\n\n==== March 30 ====\nOn March 30, Mayor Bowser announced a [[stay-at-home order]] that would go into effect on April 1. The order stated that residents may only leave their residences to engage in essential activities, including obtaining medical care that cannot be provided through telehealth and obtaining food and essential household goods, to perform or access essential governmental functions, to work at essential businesses, to engage in essential travel and to \nengage in specific recreational activities that the order defined.<ref name=\"stay at home\">(1) {{cite web|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-issues-stay-home-order|title=Mayor Bowser Issues Stay-At-Home Order|work=News Release|date=March 30, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}<br>(2) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/coronavirus/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-054%20Stay%20at%20Home.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-054: Stay At Home Order|work=Administrative Issuance System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> \n\nAnyone found to be violating the order would be charged with a [[misdemeanor]] and subject to a $5,000 fine and/or 90 days in prison. Bowser said, \"Staying at home is the best way to flatten the curve and protect yourself, your family, and our entire community from COVID-19.\"<ref name=Franklin>{{cite news |last1=Franklin |first1=Jonathan |title=DC issues Stay-At-Home order: Here's what you can leave your house for |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/dc-stay-at-home-order-why-and-what-you-can-leave-your-house-for/65-7f0f0bf1-1cb6-4921-a4a5-bbf7ddbaa88b |work=[[WUSA (TV)|WUSA9]]|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn the same day, [[Maryland]]'s Governor [[Larry Hogan]] and [[Virginia]]'s Governor [[Ralph Northam]] issued similar stay-at-home orders (see [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maryland]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Virginia|in Virginia]]). However, the penalties for violating those orders were different from those in the District.<ref name=\"Post March 30\">{{cite web|first1=Antonio|last=Olivo|first2=Ovetta|last2=Wiggins|first3=Gregory S.|last3=Schneider|date=March 30, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/hogan-northam-coronavirus-stay-home-orders/2020/03/30/5f36e146-722f-11ea-85cb-8670579b863d_story.html|title=Hogan, Northam, Bowser order residents in Maryland, Virginia, D.C. to stay at home|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government response==\nOn March 11, Mayor Muriel Bowser declared a state of emergency for the District of Columbia. The declaration allowed Bowser to request federal disaster funds and to address price gouging. The order also gave her additional authorities, including the ordering of quarantines without court approval.<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-declares-public-health-emergency|title=Mayor Bowser Declares Public Health Emergency|work=News Release|date=March 11, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331050450/https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-declares-public-health-emergency|archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(2) {{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/politics/washington-dc-state-of-emergency-coronavirus/index.html|title=DC mayor declares state of emergency due to coronavirus|first1=Jamiel|last1=Lynch|first2=Paul|last2=LeBlanc|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311230011/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/politics/washington-dc-state-of-emergency-coronavirus/index.html|archive-date=2020-03-11|url-status=live}}<br>(3) {{Cite news|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/487112-washington-dc-declares-state-of-emergency-over-coronavirus|title=Washington, DC, declares state of emergency over coronavirus|last=Moreno|first=J. Edward|date=2020-03-11|website=TheHill|language=en|accessdate=2020-03-12}}<br>(4) {{cite news|first1=Jenna|last1=Portnoy|first2=Fenit|last2=Nirappil|first3=Darran|last3=Simon|date=March 12, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-dc-maryland-coronavirus-news-wednesday/2020/03/11/50a0d822-6342-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html|title=D.C. declares state of emergency as concerts, parades, church services are canceled|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327105804/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-dc-maryland-coronavirus-news-wednesday/2020/03/11/50a0d822-6342-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(5) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicEmergency03.11.20.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-045: Declaration of Public Emergency: Coronavirus (COVID-19)|date=March 20, 2020|work=Administrative Infomation System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329201523/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicEmergency03.11.20.pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(6) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicHealthEmergency03.11.20.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-046: Declaration of Public Emergency: Coronavirus (COVID-19)|date=March 20, 2020|work=Administrative Infomation System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329201521/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicHealthEmergency03.11.20.pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, [[District of Columbia Public Schools]] (DCPS) shut down schools from March 16 to March 31. March 16 was reserved for professional development for teachers in preparation for the implementation of [[distance learning]]. The April Spring Break period was moved to March 17 to March 23, after which classes were set to resume online. DCPS-sponsored out-of-state travel for students was suspended until May 1 and staff travel was restricted. During the closure, several schools were set to offer meals to students from 10 am to 2 pm on weekdays.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) Updates |url=https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus |website=District of Columbia Public Schools |publisher=DC.Gov |accessdate=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313221000/https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, the District government suspended on-site bar and restaurant service and shut down movie theaters and gyms. Restaurants could still offer food for carryout and delivery, but customers could not dine in.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/03/16/2362519a-6777-11ea-abef-020f086a3fab_story.html |title=Second Va. man dies, D.C., Maryland restaurants, bars close as toll passes 100 |work=[[Washington Post]] |date=2020-03-16 |accessdate=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316234751/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/03/16/2362519a-6777-11ea-abef-020f086a3fab_story.html |archive-date=2020-03-16 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Mayor Bowser issued an order that prohibited mass gatherings of 50 or more people. The order also prohibited table service and service to standing customers at restaurants, bars and multi-purpose facilities, including seated, fast food and fast casual restaurants. Those businesses could only operate for take-out, \"grab-and-go\" and delivery operations.<ref name=\"March 20 order\">(1) {{cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor\u2019s-order-2020-051-prohibition-mass-gatherings-during-public-health-emergency|title=Prohibition on Mass Gatherings During Public Health Emergency - Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=News Release|date=March 20, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330150520/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor%E2%80%99s-order-2020-051-prohibition-mass-gatherings-during-public-health-emergency|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(2) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/u23/Mayor%60s%20Order%202020-51.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-051: Prohibition on Mass Gatherings During Public Health Emergency - Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 20, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330201113/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/u23/Mayor%60s%20Order%202020-51.pdf|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThe Mayor's March 20 order also required nightclubs, health clubs, health spas, massage parlors and theaters to continue their suspension of operations, which the District's government had initially ordered on March 17. The order further closed to the public all facilities that the District's Department of Recreation operated, including playgrounds, parks and athletic fields.<ref name=\"March 20 order\"/>\n\nThe District of Columbia Medical Reserve Corps (DC MRC), a volunteer organization under the [[District of Columbia Department of Health]], was mobilized to aid emergency workers in responding to the coronavirus pandemic throughout D.C. On March 21, Mayor Bowser called for more volunteers to join the task force.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Bowser Encourages Volunteers to Join the DC Medical Reserve Corps |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-encourages-volunteers-join-dc-medical-reserve-corps |website=coronavirus.dc.gov |publisher=DC.Gov |date=21 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323215101/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-encourages-volunteers-join-dc-medical-reserve-corps |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, Mayor Bowser issued an order \"to temporarily cease all non-essential business activities, including tour guides and touring services; gyms, health clubs, spas, and massage establishments; theaters, auditoriums, and other places of large gatherings; nightclubs; hair, nail, and tanning salons and barbershops; tattoo parlors; sales not involved in essential services; retail clothing stores; and professional services not devoted to assisting essential business operations.\"<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-orders-closure-non-essential-businesses|title=New Mayor\u2019s Order Requires Temporary Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibits Gatherings of Ten or More People|work=News Release|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330200918/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-orders-closure-non-essential-businesses|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}} <br>(2) {{cite news|last=Barnes|first=Sophia|url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-closes-nonessential-businesses-dmv-latest-tuesday-march-23-whats-closed-washington/2252010/|title=DC Closes Nonessential Businesses, DMV Centers to Stop Coronavirus|date=March 25, 2020|work=Coronavirus|publisher=[[WRC-TV|NBC4 Washington]]|accessdate=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327133947/https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-closes-nonessential-businesses-dmv-latest-tuesday-march-23-whats-closed-washington/2252010/|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(3) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|title=Mayor\u2019s Order 2020-053: Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibition on Large Gatherings During Public Health Emergency for the 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329184808/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBowser's March 24 order defined \"Construction and Building Trades\" as \"essential businesses\", but did not define private construction projects themselves as being \"essential\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|title=Mayor\u2019s Order 2020-053: Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibition on Large Gatherings During Public Health Emergency for the 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329184808/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> However, [[The Washington Post]] reported on March 28 that the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia had designated construction as \"essential,\" along with hospitals, grocery stores, banks and several other types of businesses. The ''Post'' reported that each of these jurisdictions had allowed private construction, including home building and commercial developments, to continue.<ref name=Lazo>{{cite news|first1=Luz|last1=Lazo|first2=Katherine|last2=Shaver|date=March 28, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/work-on-regions-big-projects-continues-amid-coronavirus-with-construction-an-essential-business/2020/03/28/e4af8b38-6dfd-11ea-a3ec-70d7479d83f0_story.html|title=Work on region\u2019s big projects continues amid coronavirus, with construction an \u2018essential\u2019 business|work=Transportation|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401022830/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/work-on-regions-big-projects-continues-amid-coronavirus-with-construction-an-essential-business/2020/03/28/e4af8b38-6dfd-11ea-a3ec-70d7479d83f0_story.html|archive-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  \n\nThe ''Post'' reported that John Falcicchio, Bowser's chief of staff, had stated that the District, Maryland and Virginia had agreed to follow the federal guidance declaring construction to be essential work. However, the ''Post'' reported that several states, including Pennsylvania and Vermont, had suspended or prohibited all construction work (except for emergencies) as unnecessary during a public health crisis. The Post further reported that the State of Washington's transportation department had suspended work on nearly all of its projects and that Washington's governor had clarified his [[Stay-at-home order|stay-at-home]] order to state that commercial and residential construction were generally prohibited \"because construction is not considered to be an essential activity.\"<ref name=Lazo/>\n\nThe [[United States Department of Homeland Security]]'s March 28 guidance on essential critical infrastructure lists as \"essential\" the construction of residential/shelter facilities and services, energy-related facilities, communications and information technology, public works including the  construction of critical or strategic infrastructure and infrastructure that is temporarily required to support COVID-19 response, is for certain other types of community- or government-based operations, or is otherwise critical, strategic, or essential. The guidance does not contain any such listings for other types of construction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cisa.gov/sites/default/files/publications/CISA_Guidance_on_the_Essential_Critical_Infrastructure_Workforce_Version_2.0_Updated.pdf|title=Guidance on the Essential Critical Infrastructure Workforce: Ensuring Community and National Resilience in COVID-19 Response|date=March 28, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[United States Department of Homeland Security]]: [[Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency]]: Office of the Director|accessdate=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402033910/https://www.cisa.gov/sites/default/files/publications/CISA_Guidance_on_the_Essential_Critical_Infrastructure_Workforce_Version_2.0_Updated.pdf|archive-date=April 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, Bowser announced a stay-at-home order that would go into effect on April 1. The order stated that residents may only leave their residences to engage in essential activities, including obtaining medical care that cannot be provided through telehealth and obtaining food and essential household goods, to perform or access essential governmental functions, to work at essential businesses, to engage in essential travel and to engage in specific recreational activities that the order defined.<ref name=\"stay at home\"/><ref name=\"Post March 30\"/> Anyone found to be violating the order would be charged with a [[misdemeanor]] and subject to a $5,000 fine and/or 90 days in prison.<ref name=Franklin/>\n\n==Impact on sports==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nThe pandemic affected several sports in the district. On March 12, [[Major League Baseball]] cancelled the remainder of [[spring training]], and on March 16, they announced that the season will be postponed indefinitely, after the recommendations from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] to restrict events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, affecting the [[2020 Washington Nationals season|Washington Nationals]].<ref name=\"mlb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |title=Opening of regular season to be pushed back |first=Mark |last=Feinsand |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317025811/https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Washington Wizards season|Washington Wizards]].<ref name=nba>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=March 13, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313004850/https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the [[National Hockey League]], the season was suspended for an indefinite amount of time, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Washington Capitals season|Washington Capitals]].<ref name=nhl>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314025848/https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 |date=2020-03-14 }} NHL, March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities districtwide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312213051/http://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships |date=2020-03-12 }} NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318182102/https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html |date=2020-03-18 }} MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maryland]] \u2013 for impact on Maryland counties in the Washington metropolitan area\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Virginia]] \u2013 for impact on Virginia counties in the Washington metropolitan area\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://coronavirus.dc.gov/ Coronavirus information] from the [[Government of the District of Columbia]]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by city|Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:2020 in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Pandemic in Washington, D.C., United States}}\n{{Current event|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Washington, D.C.\n| width           = \n| image           = National Gallery of Art (49656625722).jpg\n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = Visitors wearing masks in the [[National Gallery of Art]], the day before it closed as a precaution against COVID-19\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n| first_case      = March 7, 2020\n| arrival_date    = \n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 902\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| deaths          = 21\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://coronavirus.dc.gov/}}\n}}\n\nThe first cases of [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the global pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in [[Washington, D.C.]] were reported on March 7, 2020. {{As of|2020|04|02|df=US}}, there are 902 confirmed cases and 21 deaths in Washington, D.C. alone, with other cases in the surrounding counties of the [[Washington metropolitan area]].<ref name=\"dcgovdata\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus Data |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/page/coronavirus-data |website=DC.Gov |publisher=Government of the District of Columbia |accessdate=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323134324/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/page/coronavirus-data |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Washington, D.C. medical cases chart}}\n\n==Timeline==\n\n=== February ===\nMayor [[Muriel Bowser]] signed an executive order that began to prepare Washington D.C. for coronavirus impacts on February 28. It was announced in the executive order that the District's Emergency Operations Center (EOC) would be activated on March 2, 2020 at 9:00&nbsp;a.m. to begin to \"coordinate inter-agency information sharing and identify logistical needs for critical incident responses.\" It was also announced that the Washington D.C. Department of Health and the Homeland Security and Emergency Management Agency would be responsible for the response planning for COVID-19.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayors-order-district-government-preparations-coronavirus|title=Mayor's Order: District Government Preparations for the Coronavirus {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329193351/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayors-order-district-government-preparations-coronavirus|archive-date=2020-03-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n\n==== March 1\u20134 ====\nOn March 2 at 9:00&nbsp;a.m., the D.C. Emergency Operations Center was activated at an Enhanced Watch status, as per the executive order signed on February 28.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn March 3, Mayor Bowser, the D.C. Department of Health, and the D.C. Homeland Security and Emergency Management Agency held a public briefing on the coronavirus and the District's \"monitoring, preparation, and response\" to it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-hold-briefing-district%E2%80%99s-coronavirus-monitoring-preparation-and-response|title=Mayor Bowser to Hold Briefing on the District's Coronavirus Monitoring, Preparation, and Response {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308004155/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-hold-briefing-district%E2%80%99s-coronavirus-monitoring-preparation-and-response|archive-date=2020-03-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====March 5\u20137====\nOn March 7, the first two cases of COVID-19 in Washington, D.C. were confirmed. The first case was a [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|rector]] at [[Christ Church (Georgetown, Washington, D.C.)|Christ Church Georgetown]] who had not traveled outside the United States recently or had contact with another infected coronavirus patient. He participated in church services on February 23 and March 1. The rector felt better initially, but his condition deteriorated to the point of hospitalization, when it was confirmed he had coronavirus. After it was confirmed the rector contracted the virus, the church cancelled services indefinitely. The second case was a [[Nigeria]]n national who traveled to D.C. and went to a hospital in [[Maryland]] for treatment. Although the second man was being treated at a Maryland hospital, he was counted as the District's second case by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC).<ref>{{cite news |title=Georgetown Church Rector, Traveler Diagnosed as DC's First 2 Coronavirus Cases |url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-has-first-presumptive-coronavirus-case/2234068/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=NBC4 Washington |date=7 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316154326/https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-has-first-presumptive-coronavirus-case/2234068/ |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|user=MayorBowser|number=1236422174958895104|title=Late this afternoon, testing at the Public Health Lab at the DC Department of Forensic Sciences yielded its first presumptive positive coronavirus (COVID-19) case. Join me live at 7:30 p.m. for a briefing at the John A. Wilson Building.|date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====March 8\u201310====\nOn March 9, [[School Without Walls (Washington, D.C.)|School Without Walls]], a public school in [[Foggy Bottom]], was closed by [[District of Columbia Public Schools]] (DCPS) for a full-day deep cleaning and disinfecting by a third-party contractor after an employee was exposed to COVID-19 the week before. The employee tested negative and entered a two-week quarantine. DCPS chancellor Lewis Ferebee announced the closing over Twitter the previous day.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1236819215920832513|date=8 Mar 2020|title=Tomorrow - 3/9 - School Without Walls High School will be closed. DCPS is conducting a deep cleaning and disinfecting of the building following an employee being exposed to COVID-19. Test results were negative, and there is no immediate risk to students and staff. cc: @SWWHSA}}</ref>\n\nThree more coronavirus cases in D.C. were confirmed the night of March 9, including an attendee of Christ Church Georgetown. D.C. officials recommended a two-week self-quarantine per CDC guidelines for anyone who attended Christ Church on February 24 or between February 28 and March 3. At that time, $1.5 million had been allocated to the pandemic response by the D.C. government.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gelman |first1=Scott |last2=Alvarez |first2=Alejandro |title=16 coronavirus cases confirmed in DC, Md. and Va. |url=https://wtop.com/local/2020/03/bowser-hogan-to-deliver-update-on-coronavirus-as-dc-area-officials-investigate-9-cases/ |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=WTOP |date=9 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313023822/https://wtop.com/local/2020/03/bowser-hogan-to-deliver-update-on-coronavirus-as-dc-area-officials-investigate-9-cases/ |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, [[George Washington University]] announced classes will be moved online after spring break, starting on March 23 and continuing until at least April 5. In addition, all residential students were expected to no longer be living on campus beginning March 21. It was stated that an opening date would not be announced until the end of the instructional continuity period when a decision for the rest of the semester would be made.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fox5dc.com/news/george-washington-university-moving-to-online-classes-after-spring-break|title=George Washington University moving to online classes after spring break|date=2020-03-10|website=Fox 5 DC|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311103004/https://www.fox5dc.com/news/george-washington-university-moving-to-online-classes-after-spring-break|archive-date=2020-03-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.georgetown.edu/coronavirus/|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) Resource Center|accessdate=March 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312130006/https://www.georgetown.edu/coronavirus/|archive-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAlso on March 10, [[Georgetown Day School]], a private school, closed indefinitely and began a deep clean citing concerns about community members affiliated with [[Christ Church (Georgetown, Washington, D.C.)|Christ Church Georgetown]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Volou |first1=Khalida |title=DC school closed due to coronavirus exposure linked to Christ Church Georgetown |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-day-school-closed-tuesday-due-to-coronavirus/65-e374b3e9-a496-42ed-9043-d4bd0b9c45c9 |agency=WUSA9 |date=10 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311195837/https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-day-school-closed-tuesday-due-to-coronavirus/65-e374b3e9-a496-42ed-9043-d4bd0b9c45c9 |archive-date=11 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====March 11\u201314====\nOn March 11, [[Maria Cantwell]], a U.S. senator from Washington state, closed her D.C. office due to one of her aides testing positive for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/politics-government/article241118946.html|title=Aide to Maria Cantwell tests positive for coronavirus. Senator closes her D.C. office|last=Lightman|first=David|website=thenewstribune|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313030257/https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/politics-government/article241118946.html|archive-date=2020-03-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Georgetown University]] announced that it would be moving to virtual learning entirely beginning on March 16, and while campus would remain open and key services would remain accessible the university strongly suggested that students return to their homes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khan |first1=Saliqa |title=Georgetown University moves to virtual learning amid coronavirus concerns |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-university-moves-to-virtual-learning-amid-coronavirus-concerns/65-60c60f1b-9838-4090-80e9-dffa49d92737 |work=WUSA9 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318192012/https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/georgetown-university-moves-to-virtual-learning-amid-coronavirus-concerns/65-60c60f1b-9838-4090-80e9-dffa49d92737 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, the [[United States Capitol]], the [[White House]], and the [[United States Supreme Court Building]] closed to most of the public until April after several offices closed and multiple lawmakers went into precautionary quarantines.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zengerle |first1=Patricia |last2=Heavey |first2=Susan |title=UPDATE 5-U.S. federal buildings put away the welcome mat as coronavirus hits |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-usa-capitol/update-5-us-federal-buildings-put-away-the-welcome-mat-as-coronavirus-hits-idUSL1N2B50S4 |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=Reuters |date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, [[District of Columbia Public Schools|DCPS]] announced that they will cancel classes until April 1, implementing online distance learning.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1238430012417748993|date=13 March 2020|title=DCPS will modify operations from Monday, March 16 through Tuesday, March 31 to help limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19) in our region. For more info about the closure schedule, meal locations for students & distance learning details, please visit: https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus}}</ref> Also on March 13, the [[Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]] (WMATA) escalated its operations to level 3 of its pandemic flu plan, announcing that service on the [[Washington Metro]] would be reduced to one train every 12 minutes from Monday to Saturday and one train every 15 minutes on Sunday beginning on March 17. In addition, [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]] service would change to a Saturday supplemental schedule on weekdays beginning on March 17.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wmata.com/service/status/details/COVID-19.cfm#main-content|title=Metro takes additional steps, coordinates with public health authorities on COVID-19 {{!}} WMATA|website=wmata.com|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314155101/https://wmata.com/service/status/details/COVID-19.cfm#main-content|archive-date=2020-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/transportation/2020/03/13/metro-reduces-transit-service-response-coronavirus/|title=Metro to reduce transit service in response to the coronavirus outbreak|last=George|first=Justin|date=13 March 2020|website=Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314134151/https://www.washingtonpost.com/transportation/2020/03/13/metro-reduces-transit-service-response-coronavirus/|archive-date=14 March 2020|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nMayor [[Muriel Bowser]] held a press conference, announcing that gatherings of people over 60 years of age or with preexisting health issues would be limited to 10 people. The restriction would not apply to residences, schools, or places of work. For populations not at-risk the government promoted [[social distancing]] measures to limit the spread of the virus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vitka |first1=Will |last2=Bonk |first2=Valerie |title=Trump declares national emergency; DC bans mass gatherings |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-dc-area/ |work=WTOP |date=13 March 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314183154/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-dc-area/ |archive-date=14 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, Mayor Bowser issued a statement confirming 6 more positive cases in Washington, D.C., bringing the total number of cases up to 16.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-14|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 14 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316100728/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-14|archive-date=2020-03-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====March 15\u201316====\nOn March 15, Bowser's office announced one more positive case in Washington D.C., bringing the total cumulative number of cases to 17. The patient in this case is a 38-year-old woman who came into contact with another case.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-15|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 15|work=Government of the District of Columbia|accessdate=2020-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324170918/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-15|archive-date=2020-03-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Hill Restaurant Group (HRG) said on March 16 they would comply would restrictions on bars and restaurants ordered by Mayor Bowser on March 15. Tom Johnson, the managing director of the group, had earlier said he would ignore the order, saying it would force his company into bankruptcy.<ref>[https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/487826-dc-restaurant-group-says-it-will-comply-with-restrictions-after-mayor DC restaurant group says it will comply with restrictions after mayor's warning] The Hill, 16 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nOn the evening of March 16, Mayor Bowser's office released an update that confirmed five more positive cases of coronavirus in the District. The patients involved were a 23-year-old man, a 42-year-old woman with a history of travel to Europe, a 54-year-old woman, a 54-year-old man, and a 56-year-old man. These five cases brought the cumulative number of cases in D.C. to 22.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-16|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 16 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317204518/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-16|archive-date=2020-03-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==== March 17\u201318 ====\nLate on March 17, Mayor Bowser's office announced the confirmation of nine more positive cases in the District, bringing the total number of positive cases to 31. The patients were all male and between the ages of 23 and 61. The 23-year-old patient was confirmed to have attended the [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC) in [[National Harbor, Maryland]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-17|title=Coronavirus Data Update: March 17 {{!}} coronavirus|website=coronavirus.dc.gov|access-date=2020-03-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319072119/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/coronavirus-data-update-march-17|archive-date=2020-03-19|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, at least 8 more cases were found, including a [[District of Columbia Fire and Emergency Medical Services Department|DC FEMS]] employee (leading to a quarantine of 73 firefighters), a [[U.S. marshal]] at the [[Superior Court of the District of Columbia]], and an undergraduate student at the George Washington University who lives off-campus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moore |first1=Jack |title=Coronavirus: Jump in new cases around region; DC first responder, US Marshal test positive |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-updates-dc-maryland-virginia/ |work=WTOP |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319002447/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-updates-dc-maryland-virginia/ |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Metropolitan Police Department of the District of Columbia]] announced new [[social distancing]] precautions in dealing with callers reporting flu-like symptoms as well as changes to police protocol for citations and warning notices in light of the restriction of certain services in the D.C. government.<ref>{{cite web |title=Metropolitan Police Department Operational Adjustments During COVID-19 |url=https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/metropolitan-police-department-operational-adjustments-during-covid-19 |website=Metropolitan Police Department |publisher=DC.Gov |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319002500/https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/metropolitan-police-department-operational-adjustments-during-covid-19 |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==== March 19\u201320 ====\nAs of March 19, the number of confirmed cases sharply jumped to 71 as the supply of tests was expanded, an increase of 32 over one day.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1240791217647976448|user=MayorBowser|title=As of 8:00 p.m. on Thursday, March 19, the District\u2019s coronavirus (COVID-19) data includes 32 new positive cases, bringing the District\u2019s overall positive case total to 71 individuals. For more information visit:|date=19 March 2020}}</ref> This includes two more DC FEMS members and an eight-year-old.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Massimo |first1=Rick |title=Coronavirus: As more tests become available, DC sees jump in coronavirus cases |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-all-md-malls-entertainment-venues-to-close-at-5-p-m-thursday/ |work=WTOP |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320014753/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-all-md-malls-entertainment-venues-to-close-at-5-p-m-thursday/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe same day, [[Washington Metro]] closed the [[Smithsonian station|Smithsonian]] and [[Arlington Cemetery station|Arlington Cemetery]] stations until further notice. Metro ridership reduced by 85% due to the pandemic, leading to general manager Paul Wiedefeld submitting a request to Congress for emergency funding.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Augenstein |first1=Neal |title=Coronavirus: Metro asks Congress for emergency funding after ridership drops 85% |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-metro-asks-congress-for-emergency-funding-after-ridership-drops-85/ |work=WTOP |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320014754/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-metro-asks-congress-for-emergency-funding-after-ridership-drops-85/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Mayor Bowser announced the first death related to COVID-19 in the District, a 59-year-old male, Deacon Brother John-Sebastian Laird-Hammond, [[OFM]], a [[Franciscan]] [[friar]] and [[permanent deacon]], a native of [[Minonk, Illinois]], with underlying medical conditions, specifically a multi-year battle with a type of [[leukemia]] who had been undergoing cancer treatments and was therefore more vulnerable to the virus.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/a-franciscan-friar-is-dcs-first-known-coronavirus-fatality-32938 | title=A Franciscan friar and deacon is DC's first known coronavirus fatality | access-date=2020-03-26 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329041046/https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/a-franciscan-friar-is-dcs-first-known-coronavirus-fatality-32938 | archive-date=2020-03-29 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Bowser tweet first death\">{{cite tweet|last=Bowser |first=Muriel |author-link=Muriel Bowser |user=MayorBowser |number=1241051533631946752 |date=2020-03-20 |title=It is with great sadness that we announce a tragic death and, on behalf of our residents, I share our love and condolences with the patient\u2019s family and friends. |access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> The number of cases rose to 77.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\nDCPS extended the school shutdown to April 24, meaning classes would be scheduled to resume on Monday, April 27. In preparation for the beginning of distance learning on March 24, the DCPS Distance Learning platform was released, publicly accessible at {{URL|https://dcps.instructure.com/courses/179580}}. Certain schools would continue to provide lunch on weekdays.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=dcpublicschools|number=1241081893656956931|title=\ud83d\udea8UPDATE\ud83d\udea8 DCPS will be closed to all staff and students through Friday, April 24 to help mitigate the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19) in our region. Classes will resume for all students on Monday, April 27. For more info please visit: http://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus.|date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== March 21\u201322 ====\n\nOn March 21, the D.C. government, operating through the Metropolitan Police Department and the [[National Park Service]] announced several road closures around beginning on March 22, 7:00 AM to 8:00 PM, in an effort to reduce congregation of tourists around monuments during the [[National Cherry Blossom Festival]]. These crowds had not been conforming to social distancing guidelines and thus presented a possible vector for the transmission of coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Corse |first1=Alexa |title=Washington, D.C., Closes Streets to Prevent Coronavirus Transmission |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/washington-d-c-closes-streets-to-prevent-coronavirus-transmission-11584850717 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=22 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322213549/https://www.wsj.com/articles/washington-d-c-closes-streets-to-prevent-coronavirus-transmission-11584850717 |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=TRAFFIC ADVISORY: Street Closures |url=https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/traffic-advisory-street-closures?mod=article_inline |website=Metropolitan Police Department |publisher=DC.Gov |date=21 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322213607/https://mpdc.dc.gov/release/traffic-advisory-street-closures?mod=article_inline |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[District of Columbia Department of Parks and Recreation|DC Department of Parks and Recreation]] closed all of its facilities including parks, playgrounds, and athletic fields. Only dog parks remained open.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1241457230349811712|user=DCDPR|title=!!ALERT - All DPR facilities including Playgrounds + Gated Parks and Athletic Fields are CLOSED. Dog parks remain open. Stay informed http://coronavirus.dc.gov.|date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe same day, [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]] announced reduced operation from 325 routes to only 20 high-use corridors. Real-time bus data would no longer be available and drivers may bypass stops in order to observe social distancing guidelines on buses. [[WMATA]] said it hoped to restore some routes with limited operation hours soon.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Delaney |first1=Matthew |title=Coronavirus: 2nd death in DC; cases surge throughout region with more testing |url=https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-positive-cases-continue-to-surge-transit-changes-enforce-social-distancing/ |work=WTOP |date=22 March 2020 |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322235143/https://wtop.com/coronavirus/2020/03/coronavirus-positive-cases-continue-to-surge-transit-changes-enforce-social-distancing/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe number of cases as of 7:30 PM that day was 98.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\nOn March 22, the second death due to COVID-19 was reported in the District, a 65-year-old woman with underlying medical conditions.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=MayorBowser|number=1241783602830020615|title=1/ I am saddened to announce a second death related to COVID-19 in our community. The hearts and prayers of our entire city are with her family and loved ones.|date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe number of cases as of 7:00 PM that day was 116.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\n==== March 23\u201324 ====\nOn March 23, Mayor Bowser and Chief Financial Officer [[Jeffrey DeWitt]] announced that the 2019 tax filing deadlines would be pushed to July 15, instead of the upcoming April 15.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Bowser and Chief Financial Officer DeWitt Announce 2019 Tax Filings and Payment Deadline Extended to July 15, 2020 |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-and-chief-financial-officer-dewitt-announce-2019-tax-filings-and-payment |website=coronavirus.dc.gov |publisher=DC.Gov |date=23 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323215938/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-and-chief-financial-officer-dewitt-announce-2019-tax-filings-and-payment |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Mayor also urged D.C. residents to remain at home except for \"essential activities,\" clarifying that she would not be issuing a [[shelter-in-place order]] as of now.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Katz |first1=Jeffrey |last2=Austermuhle |first2=Martin |last3=Pascale |first3=Jordan |last4=Chamberlin |first4=Victoria |title=UPDATED: D.C.-Area Residents Are Being Asked To Stay In Their Homes If They Can. How Is That Going To Work? |url=https://wamu.org/story/20/03/22/what-happens-if-d-c-declares-a-shelter-in-place-your-questions-answered/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=WAMU |date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323234638/https://wamu.org/story/20/03/22/what-happens-if-d-c-declares-a-shelter-in-place-your-questions-answered/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn that day, Mayor Bowser also commissioned [[Republic Restoratives Distillery]] and [[Compass Coffee]], two locally owned companies, for the production of {{convert|2000|gal}} of [[hand sanitizer]] ({{convert|1000|gal}} each) for use by D.C. government workers and emergency responders.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1242193836014796806|user=MayorBowser|title=1/ DC Government has commissioned 2,000 gallons of hand sanitizer from @RepublicRestore and @CompassCoffeeDC (1,000 each) as part of our response to the coronavirus (COVID-19).|date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 7:00 PM that day, the number of cases was 137.<ref name=\"dcgovdata\"/>\n\n==== March 25 ====\nOn March 25, the third death in Washington, D.C. was a 75-year-old female with underlying health conditions.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1242969615283740673|user=mayorbowser|date=25 March 2020|title=There's a third death in DC due to coronavirus (COVID-19). The patient, a 75-year-old female, was admitted to a hospital with underlying health conditions and passed away on March 25. She tested positive for COVID-19 and was included among the District\u2019s reporting data.}}</ref>\n\n==== March 30 ====\nOn March 30, Mayor Bowser announced a [[stay-at-home order]] that would go into effect on April 1. The order stated that residents may only leave their residences to engage in essential activities, including obtaining medical care that cannot be provided through telehealth and obtaining food and essential household goods, to perform or access essential governmental functions, to work at essential businesses, to engage in essential travel and to \nengage in specific recreational activities that the order defined.<ref name=\"stay at home\">(1) {{cite web|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-issues-stay-home-order|title=Mayor Bowser Issues Stay-At-Home Order|work=News Release|date=March 30, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}<br>(2) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/coronavirus/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-054%20Stay%20at%20Home.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-054: Stay At Home Order|work=Administrative Issuance System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> \n\nAnyone found to be violating the order would be charged with a [[misdemeanor]] and subject to a $5,000 fine and/or 90 days in prison. Bowser said, \"Staying at home is the best way to flatten the curve and protect yourself, your family, and our entire community from COVID-19.\"<ref name=Franklin>{{cite news |last1=Franklin |first1=Jonathan |title=DC issues Stay-At-Home order: Here's what you can leave your house for |url=https://www.wusa9.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/dc-stay-at-home-order-why-and-what-you-can-leave-your-house-for/65-7f0f0bf1-1cb6-4921-a4a5-bbf7ddbaa88b |work=[[WUSA (TV)|WUSA9]]|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn the same day, [[Maryland]]'s Governor [[Larry Hogan]] and [[Virginia]]'s Governor [[Ralph Northam]] issued similar stay-at-home orders (see [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maryland]] and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Virginia|in Virginia]]). However, the penalties for violating those orders were different from those in the District.<ref name=\"Post March 30\">{{cite web|first1=Antonio|last=Olivo|first2=Ovetta|last2=Wiggins|first3=Gregory S.|last3=Schneider|date=March 30, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/hogan-northam-coronavirus-stay-home-orders/2020/03/30/5f36e146-722f-11ea-85cb-8670579b863d_story.html|title=Hogan, Northam, Bowser order residents in Maryland, Virginia, D.C. to stay at home|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Government response==\nOn March 11, Mayor Muriel Bowser declared a state of emergency for the District of Columbia. The declaration allowed Bowser to request federal disaster funds and to address price gouging. The order also gave her additional authorities, including the ordering of quarantines without court approval.<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-declares-public-health-emergency|title=Mayor Bowser Declares Public Health Emergency|work=News Release|date=March 11, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331050450/https://mayor.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-declares-public-health-emergency|archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(2) {{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/politics/washington-dc-state-of-emergency-coronavirus/index.html|title=DC mayor declares state of emergency due to coronavirus|first1=Jamiel|last1=Lynch|first2=Paul|last2=LeBlanc|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311230011/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/11/politics/washington-dc-state-of-emergency-coronavirus/index.html|archive-date=2020-03-11|url-status=live}}<br>(3) {{Cite news|url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/487112-washington-dc-declares-state-of-emergency-over-coronavirus|title=Washington, DC, declares state of emergency over coronavirus|last=Moreno|first=J. Edward|date=2020-03-11|website=TheHill|language=en|accessdate=2020-03-12}}<br>(4) {{cite news|first1=Jenna|last1=Portnoy|first2=Fenit|last2=Nirappil|first3=Darran|last3=Simon|date=March 12, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-dc-maryland-coronavirus-news-wednesday/2020/03/11/50a0d822-6342-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html|title=D.C. declares state of emergency as concerts, parades, church services are canceled|work=Local|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327105804/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/virginia-dc-maryland-coronavirus-news-wednesday/2020/03/11/50a0d822-6342-11ea-acca-80c22bbee96f_story.html|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(5) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicEmergency03.11.20.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-045: Declaration of Public Emergency: Coronavirus (COVID-19)|date=March 20, 2020|work=Administrative Infomation System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329201523/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicEmergency03.11.20.pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(6) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicHealthEmergency03.11.20.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-046: Declaration of Public Emergency: Coronavirus (COVID-19)|date=March 20, 2020|work=Administrative Infomation System|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329201521/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/MO.DeclarationofPublicHealthEmergency03.11.20.pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, [[District of Columbia Public Schools]] (DCPS) shut down schools from March 16 to March 31. March 16 was reserved for professional development for teachers in preparation for the implementation of [[distance learning]]. The April Spring Break period was moved to March 17 to March 23, after which classes were set to resume online. DCPS-sponsored out-of-state travel for students was suspended until May 1 and staff travel was restricted. During the closure, several schools were set to offer meals to students from 10 am to 2 pm on weekdays.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) Updates |url=https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus |website=District of Columbia Public Schools |publisher=DC.Gov |accessdate=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313221000/https://dcps.dc.gov/coronavirus |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, the District government suspended on-site bar and restaurant service and shut down movie theaters and gyms. Restaurants could still offer food for carryout and delivery, but customers could not dine in.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/03/16/2362519a-6777-11ea-abef-020f086a3fab_story.html |title=Second Va. man dies, D.C., Maryland restaurants, bars close as toll passes 100 |work=[[Washington Post]] |date=2020-03-16 |accessdate=2020-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316234751/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/coronavirus-dc-maryland-virginia/2020/03/16/2362519a-6777-11ea-abef-020f086a3fab_story.html |archive-date=2020-03-16 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, Mayor Bowser issued an order that prohibited mass gatherings of 50 or more people. The order also prohibited table service and service to standing customers at restaurants, bars and multi-purpose facilities, including seated, fast food and fast casual restaurants. Those businesses could only operate for take-out, \"grab-and-go\" and delivery operations.<ref name=\"March 20 order\">(1) {{cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor\u2019s-order-2020-051-prohibition-mass-gatherings-during-public-health-emergency|title=Prohibition on Mass Gatherings During Public Health Emergency - Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=News Release|date=March 20, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330150520/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor%E2%80%99s-order-2020-051-prohibition-mass-gatherings-during-public-health-emergency|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(2) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/u23/Mayor%60s%20Order%202020-51.pdf|title=Mayor's Order 2020-051: Prohibition on Mass Gatherings During Public Health Emergency - Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 20, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330201113/https://mayor.dc.gov/sites/default/files/u23/Mayor%60s%20Order%202020-51.pdf|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThe Mayor's March 20 order also required nightclubs, health clubs, health spas, massage parlors and theaters to continue their suspension of operations, which the District's government had initially ordered on March 17. The order further closed to the public all facilities that the District's Department of Recreation operated, including playgrounds, parks and athletic fields.<ref name=\"March 20 order\"/>\n\nThe District of Columbia Medical Reserve Corps (DC MRC), a volunteer organization under the [[District of Columbia Department of Health]], was mobilized to aid emergency workers in responding to the coronavirus pandemic throughout D.C. On March 21, Mayor Bowser called for more volunteers to join the task force.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mayor Bowser Encourages Volunteers to Join the DC Medical Reserve Corps |url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-encourages-volunteers-join-dc-medical-reserve-corps |website=coronavirus.dc.gov |publisher=DC.Gov |date=21 March 2020 |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323215101/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-encourages-volunteers-join-dc-medical-reserve-corps |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, Mayor Bowser issued an order \"to temporarily cease all non-essential business activities, including tour guides and touring services; gyms, health clubs, spas, and massage establishments; theaters, auditoriums, and other places of large gatherings; nightclubs; hair, nail, and tanning salons and barbershops; tattoo parlors; sales not involved in essential services; retail clothing stores; and professional services not devoted to assisting essential business operations.\"<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-orders-closure-non-essential-businesses|title=New Mayor\u2019s Order Requires Temporary Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibits Gatherings of Ten or More People|work=News Release|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330200918/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/release/mayor-bowser-orders-closure-non-essential-businesses|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}} <br>(2) {{cite news|last=Barnes|first=Sophia|url=https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-closes-nonessential-businesses-dmv-latest-tuesday-march-23-whats-closed-washington/2252010/|title=DC Closes Nonessential Businesses, DMV Centers to Stop Coronavirus|date=March 25, 2020|work=Coronavirus|publisher=[[WRC-TV|NBC4 Washington]]|accessdate=March 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327133947/https://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/dc-closes-nonessential-businesses-dmv-latest-tuesday-march-23-whats-closed-washington/2252010/|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}<br>(3) {{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|title=Mayor\u2019s Order 2020-053: Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibition on Large Gatherings During Public Health Emergency for the 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329184808/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBowser's March 24 order defined \"Construction and Building Trades\" as \"essential businesses\", but did not define private construction projects themselves as being \"essential\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Bowser|first=Muriel, Mayor|url=https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|title=Mayor\u2019s Order 2020-053: Closure of Non-Essential Businesses and Prohibition on Large Gatherings During Public Health Emergency for the 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)|work=Administrative Infomation System|date=March 24, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Government of the District of Columbia: Office of the Mayor|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329184808/https://coronavirus.dc.gov/sites/default/files/dc/sites/mayormb/release_content/attachments/Mayor%27s%20Order%202020-053%20Closure%20of%20Non-Essential%20Businesses%20and%20Prohibiti....pdf|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> However, [[The Washington Post]] reported on March 28 that the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia had designated construction as \"essential,\" along with hospitals, grocery stores, banks and several other types of businesses. The ''Post'' reported that each of these jurisdictions had allowed private construction, including home building and commercial developments, to continue.<ref name=Lazo>{{cite news|first1=Luz|last1=Lazo|first2=Katherine|last2=Shaver|date=March 28, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/work-on-regions-big-projects-continues-amid-coronavirus-with-construction-an-essential-business/2020/03/28/e4af8b38-6dfd-11ea-a3ec-70d7479d83f0_story.html|title=Work on region\u2019s big projects continues amid coronavirus, with construction an \u2018essential\u2019 business|work=Transportation|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=April 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401022830/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/work-on-regions-big-projects-continues-amid-coronavirus-with-construction-an-essential-business/2020/03/28/e4af8b38-6dfd-11ea-a3ec-70d7479d83f0_story.html|archive-date=April 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  \n\nThe ''Post'' reported that John Falcicchio, Bowser's chief of staff, had stated that the District, Maryland and Virginia had agreed to follow the federal guidance declaring construction to be essential work. However, the ''Post'' reported that several states, including Pennsylvania and Vermont, had suspended or prohibited all construction work (except for emergencies) as unnecessary during a public health crisis. The Post further reported that the State of Washington's transportation department had suspended work on nearly all of its projects and that Washington's governor had clarified his [[Stay-at-home order|stay-at-home]] order to state that commercial and residential construction were generally prohibited \"because construction is not considered to be an essential activity.\"<ref name=Lazo/>\n\nThe [[United States Department of Homeland Security]]'s March 28 guidance on essential critical infrastructure lists as \"essential\" the construction of residential/shelter facilities and services, energy-related facilities, communications and information technology, public works including the  construction of critical or strategic infrastructure and infrastructure that is temporarily required to support COVID-19 response, is for certain other types of community- or government-based operations, or is otherwise critical, strategic, or essential. The guidance does not contain any such listings for other types of construction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cisa.gov/sites/default/files/publications/CISA_Guidance_on_the_Essential_Critical_Infrastructure_Workforce_Version_2.0_Updated.pdf|title=Guidance on the Essential Critical Infrastructure Workforce: Ensuring Community and National Resilience in COVID-19 Response|date=March 28, 2020|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[United States Department of Homeland Security]]: [[Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency]]: Office of the Director|accessdate=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402033910/https://www.cisa.gov/sites/default/files/publications/CISA_Guidance_on_the_Essential_Critical_Infrastructure_Workforce_Version_2.0_Updated.pdf|archive-date=April 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, Bowser announced a stay-at-home order that would go into effect on April 1. The order stated that residents may only leave their residences to engage in essential activities, including obtaining medical care that cannot be provided through telehealth and obtaining food and essential household goods, to perform or access essential governmental functions, to work at essential businesses, to engage in essential travel and to engage in specific recreational activities that the order defined.<ref name=\"stay at home\"/><ref name=\"Post March 30\"/> Anyone found to be violating the order would be charged with a [[misdemeanor]] and subject to a $5,000 fine and/or 90 days in prison.<ref name=Franklin/>\n\n==Impact on sports==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nThe pandemic affected several sports in the district. On March 12, [[Major League Baseball]] cancelled the remainder of [[spring training]], and on March 16, they announced that the season will be postponed indefinitely, after the recommendations from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] to restrict events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, affecting the [[2020 Washington Nationals season|Washington Nationals]].<ref name=\"mlb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |title=Opening of regular season to be pushed back |first=Mark |last=Feinsand |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317025811/https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Washington Wizards season|Washington Wizards]].<ref name=nba>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=March 13, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313004850/https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the [[National Hockey League]], the season was suspended for an indefinite amount of time, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Washington Capitals season|Washington Capitals]].<ref name=nhl>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314025848/https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 |date=2020-03-14 }} NHL, March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities districtwide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312213051/http://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships |date=2020-03-12 }} NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318182102/https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html |date=2020-03-18 }} MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maryland]] \u2013 for impact on Maryland counties in the Washington metropolitan area\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Virginia]] \u2013 for impact on Virginia counties in the Washington metropolitan area\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://coronavirus.dc.gov/ Coronavirus information] from the [[Government of the District of Columbia]]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by city|Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:2020 in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health in Washington, D.C.]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toOFM(link changed toOrder of Friars Minor) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Washington,_D.C."}
{"title_page": "Amzie Moore", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Amzie Moore\n| image         = File:Amzie Moore 1963.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Amzie Moore photographed in 1963 by [[Harvey Richards]].\n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1911|09|23}} \n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1982|02|01|1911|9|23}}\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| years_active  =\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works =\n}}\n\n'''Amzie Moore''' (September 23, 1911 \u2013 February 1, 1982) was an [[African-American]] [[Civil rights movement|civil rights leader]] and [[entrepreneur]] in the [[Mississippi Delta]].\n\n==Early life==\n\nAmzie Moore is one of the lesser known [[Civil rights movement|Civil Rights Movement]] leaders, but was extremely influential in advocating and registering African Americans in Mississippi to exercise their right to vote as American citizens. Born September 23, 1911 on Wilkin Plantation in [[Grenada County, Mississippi]], at the age of fourteen was left to fend for himself after his parents split, and his father abandoned him. The furthest he went in his education was tenth grade at Stone Street High School in [[Greenwood, Mississippi]]<ref name=\":0\">Payne, C. (2007). TESTING THE LIMITS: Black Activism in Postwar Mississippi. In I've Got the Light of Freedom: The Organizing Tradition and the Mississippi Freedom Struggle, With a New Preface (pp. 29-66). University of California Press. Retrieved March 27, 2020, from www.jstor.org/stable/10.1525/j.ctt1ppcgt.7</ref>\n\nIn 1935 he moved to [[Bolivar County, Mississippi|Bolivar County]] and got a job as a custodian at the local [[Post office|Post Office]]; in the midst of the [[Great Depression]], this was considered a \u201chigh status job\u201d for an African American man in the deep South. Having been involved in politics from a young age, he became a member of the [[Black-and-tan faction|Black and Tan Party]] which was an organization of African American Republicans. Although he was able to register to vote in 1936, he was unable to vote in the primaries, which heavily determined the outcomes of elections<ref name=\":0\" />. [[Freedom movement|The Freedom Movement]], as it was deemed during the times, came to the Mississippi Delta in 1940, and Moore became involved in meetings beginning to draft the explicit demands that African Americans in the state wanted<ref>Selbert, P. (2015, February 8). African-American heritage sites Mississippi. St. Louis Post-Dispatch, pp. H1\u2013H5.</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== World War II ==\nIn 1942, upon being drafted for [[World War II]], as he put it, \u201cI really didn\u2019t know what segregation was before I went into the Army. It was the first time I really knew how evil segregation was\u201d<ref name=\":1\">Fraser, C. G. (1982, February 7). Amzie Moore, 1960's Leader For Voting Registration, Dies. The New York Times, p. 48.</ref>.\u00a0 He continued to experience systematic segregation throughout his Southern stations; even in [[Kolkata|Calcutta, India]] there were still segregated enlisted men\u2019s clubs etc. \u201cWhy were we fighting? Why were we there? If we were fighting for the four freedoms that [[Franklin D. Roosevelt|Roosevelt]] and [[Winston Churchill|Churchill]] had talked about, then certainly we felt that the American soldier should be free first.\u201d The Japanese were capitalizing on the racism of the US and were actively using segregation as a point to discourage African American soldiers. Ironically, Moore\u2019s job was to counteract this propaganda and encourage African American soldiers that they played an important role in the fight against the [[Axis powers|Axis Powers]]. Once he arrived home, many whites had started a \u201chome guard\u201d to protect themselves against returning African American veterans; a FBI investigation into the numerous murders that occurred eventually led to the end of this particular type of aggression<ref name=\":1\" />. Moore was more angry and outraged at the oppression of his race, and began to become more active in voter registration in Mississippi<ref name=\":0\" />.\n<br />\n\n== Regional Council of Negro Leadership ==\nPurchasing property, building a home, and starting a service station/restaurant, while continuing to be involved in local affairs established Moore as a leader in the community. In 1951, [[T. R. M. Howard|Dr. T.R.M. Howard]] founded the [[Regional Council of Negro Leadership]] (RCNL) with hopes to be the African American equivalent of the white Delta Council. Wanting to be the united voice of the African Americans in [[Mound Bayou, Mississippi|Mound Bayou]] and surrounding areas, the RCNL quickly gained massive popularity, convincing the state police to not stop harassing drivers and began encouraging people to register to vote. At their first mass meeting, over thirteen thousand people attended; \u201cWe decided that the purpose of the Regional Council was to teach Negroes first-class citizenship, the preservation of property, the paying of taxes, the holding of public office, the changing of the economic standpoint\u201d<ref name=\":1\" />. Moore and a few other leaders of the RCNL were also active participants in the NAACP, but throughout both organizations existence there was always underlying tension between viewpoints on how to bring freedom. The NAACP typically wanted to use legal measures to change the culture, with the RCNL focused more on the economic issues that plagued those living in the Delta. However they did work together when it came to voter registration; strongly stimulated by Bob Moses tapping Moore to lead the project in the Delta<ref>Browne, G. (2001, Mar 28). Changing mississippi: Part 1 of 4; A cause to die for; the robert moses story. Mississippi Link Retrieved from <nowiki>https://search.proquest.com/docview/363201699?accountid=11667</nowiki></ref>.\n\n==NAACP==\nIn 1955, at an [[NAACP]] meeting that he was not at, the Cleveland chapter nominated him as their president, and throughout the next year extensively built up that chapter making it the second largest in the state. He then became the vice president of the state conferences of the NAACP. When the Supreme Court desegregated public schools, the White Citizens Council began their ramage throughout the state, instilling even more fear in the African American community. There were many murders throughout the state of people who refused to take their name off the voting list, and Moore, along with many other leaders, received numerous death threats. In 1960, Moore brought the [[Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee]] to focus their voter registration efforts in Mississippi, ultimately enfranchising thousands of African American Mississippians<ref name=\":1\" />.\n\n* \n\n{{Civil rights movement}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, Amzie}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:1982 deaths]]\n[[Category:Activists for African-American civil rights]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople in retailing]]\n[[Category:African-American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century African-American activists]]\n[[Category:People from Cleveland, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:African-American military personnel]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Amzie Moore\n| image         = File:Amzie Moore 1963.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Amzie Moore photographed in 1963 by [[Harvey Richards]].\n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1911|09|23}} \n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1982|02|01|1911|9|23}}\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| years_active  =\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works =\n}}\n\n'''Amzie Moore''' (September 23, 1911 \u2013 February 1, 1982) was an [[African-American]] [[Civil rights movement|civil rights leader]] and [[entrepreneur]] in the [[Mississippi Delta]].\n\n==Early life==\n\nAmzie Moore is one of the lesser known [[Civil rights movement|Civil Rights Movement]] leaders, but was extremely influential in advocating and registering African Americans in Mississippi to exercise their right to vote as American citizens. Born September 23, 1911 on Wilkin Plantation in [[Grenada County, Mississippi]], at the age of fourteen was left to fend for himself after his parents split, and his father abandoned him. The furthest he went in his education was tenth grade at Stone Street High School in [[Greenwood, Mississippi]]<ref name=\":0\">Payne, C. (2007). TESTING THE LIMITS: Black Activism in Postwar Mississippi. In I've Got the Light of Freedom: The Organizing Tradition and the Mississippi Freedom Struggle, With a New Preface (pp. 29-66). University of California Press. Retrieved March 27, 2020, from www.jstor.org/stable/10.1525/j.ctt1ppcgt.7</ref>\n\nIn 1935 he moved to [[Bolivar County, Mississippi|Bolivar County]] and got a job as a custodian at the local [[Post office|Post Office]]; in the midst of the [[Great Depression]], this was considered a \u201chigh status job\u201d for an African American man in the deep South. Having been involved in politics from a young age, he became a member of the [[Black-and-tan faction|Black and Tan Party]] which was an organization of African American Republicans. Although he was able to register to vote in 1936, he was unable to vote in the primaries, which heavily determined the outcomes of elections<ref name=\":0\" />. [[Freedom movement|The Freedom Movement]], as it was deemed during the times, came to the Mississippi Delta in 1940, and Moore became involved in meetings beginning to draft the explicit demands that African Americans in the state wanted<ref>Selbert, P. (2015, February 8). African-American heritage sites Mississippi. St. Louis Post-Dispatch, pp. H1\u2013H5.</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== World War II ==\nIn 1942, upon being drafted for [[World War II]], as he put it, \u201cI really didn\u2019t know what segregation was before I went into the Army. It was the first time I really knew how evil segregation was\u201d<ref name=\":1\">Fraser, C. G. (1982, February 7). Amzie Moore, 1960's Leader For Voting Registration, Dies. The New York Times, p. 48.</ref>.\u00a0 He continued to experience systematic segregation throughout his Southern stations; even in [[Kolkata|Calcutta, India]] there were still segregated enlisted men\u2019s clubs etc. \u201cWhy were we fighting? Why were we there? If we were fighting for the four freedoms that [[Franklin D. Roosevelt|Roosevelt]] and [[Winston Churchill|Churchill]] had talked about, then certainly we felt that the American soldier should be free first.\u201d The Japanese were capitalizing on the racism of the US and were actively using segregation as a point to discourage African American soldiers. Ironically, Moore\u2019s job was to counteract this propaganda and encourage African American soldiers that they played an important role in the fight against the [[Axis powers|Axis Powers]]. Once he arrived home, many whites had started a \u201chome guard\u201d to protect themselves against returning African American veterans; a FBI investigation into the numerous murders that occured eventually led to the end of this particular type of aggression<ref name=\":1\" />. Moore was more angry and outraged at the oppression of his race, and began to become more active in voter registration in Mississippi<ref name=\":0\" />.\n<br />\n\n== Regional Council of Negro Leadership ==\nPurchasing property, building a home, and starting a service station/restaurant, while continuing to be involved in local affairs established Moore as a leader in the community. In 1951, [[T. R. M. Howard|Dr. T.R.M. Howard]] founded the [[Regional Council of Negro Leadership]] (RCNL) with hopes to be the African American equivalent of the white Delta Council. Wanting to be the united voice of the African Americans in [[Mound Bayou, Mississippi|Mound Bayou]] and surrounding areas, the RCNL quickly gained massive popularity, convincing the state police to not stop harassing drivers and began encouraging people to register to vote. At their first mass meeting, over thirteen thousand people attended; \u201cWe decided that the purpose of the Regional Council was to teach Negroes first-class citizenship, the preservation of property, the paying of taxes, the holding of public office, the changing of the economic standpoint\u201d<ref name=\":1\" />. Moore and a few other leaders of the RCNL were also active participants in the NAACP, but throughout both organizations existence there was always underlying tension between viewpoints on how to bring freedom. The NAACP typically wanted to use legal measures to change the culture, with the RCNL focused more on the economic issues that plagued those living in the Delta. However they did work together when it came to voter registration; strongly stimulated by Bob Moses tapping Moore to lead the project in the Delta<ref>Browne, G. (2001, Mar 28). Changing mississippi: Part 1 of 4; A cause to die for; the robert moses story. Mississippi Link Retrieved from <nowiki>https://search.proquest.com/docview/363201699?accountid=11667</nowiki></ref>.\n\n==NAACP==\nIn 1955, at an [[NAACP]] meeting that he was not at, the Cleveland chapter nominated him as their president, and throughout the next year extensively built up that chapter making it the second largest in the state. He then became the vice president of the state conferences of the NAACP. When the Supreme Court desegregated public schools, the White Citizens Council began their ramage throughout the state, instilling even more fear in the African American community. There were many murders throughout the state of people who refused to take their name off the voting list, and Moore, along with many other leaders, received numerous death threats. In 1960, Moore brought the [[Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee]] to focus their voter registration efforts in Mississippi, ultimately enfranchising thousands of African American Mississippians<ref name=\":1\" />.\n\n* \n\n{{Civil rights movement}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, Amzie}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:1982 deaths]]\n[[Category:Activists for African-American civil rights]]\n[[Category:American military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople in retailing]]\n[[Category:African-American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century African-American activists]]\n[[Category:People from Cleveland, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:African-American military personnel]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n", "name_user": "Orenburg1", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amzie_Moore"}
