{"title_page": "Enthiran", "text_new": "{{short description|2010 Tamil film directed by Shankar}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Enthiran\n| image          = Enthiran poster.jpg\n| alt            = Theatrical release poster of the film Enthiran.\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[S. Shankar]]\n| producer       = [[Kalanithi Maran]]\n| writer         = S. Shankar\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Rajinikanth]]\n* [[Aishwarya Rai Bachchan]]\n* [[Danny Denzongpa]]\n}}\n| music          = [[A. R. Rahman]]\n| cinematography = [[R. Rathnavelu]]\n| editing        = [[Anthony (film editor)|Anthony]]\n| studio         = [[Sun Pictures]]\n| distributor    = Sun Pictures\n| released       = {{Film date|2010|10|1|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 166\u2013177 minutes{{refn|The [[British Board of Film Classification]] and [[Amazon.com]] gives the runtime as 166 minutes and 177 minutes respectively.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Enthiran-English-Subtitled-HD-Rajnikanth/dp/B00RA9G2V0 |title=Enthiran (English Subtitled) |publisher=[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122160952/http://www.amazon.com/Enthiran-English-Subtitled-HD-Rajnikanth/dp/B00RA9G2V0 |archive-date=22 January 2015 |access-date=22 January 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Tamil version runtime\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/enthiran-robot-1970-0 |title=ENTHIRAN (12A)&nbsp;\u2013 British Board of Film Classification |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122063906/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/enthiran-robot-1970-0 |archive-date=22 January 2015 |access-date=14 October 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref>|group=Note}}\n| country        = India<!-- do not link per MOS:OVERLINK -->\n| language       = Tamil\n| budget         = {{Estimation}} {{INR}}1.32{{mdash}}1.62&nbsp;billion{{refn|''[[The Economic Times]]'' claims the film's budget to be {{INR}}1.32&nbsp;million,<ref name=\"Q3\">{{Cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2011-01-28/news/28425591_1_interim-dividend-satellite-rights-enthiran |title=Sun TV Network Q3 Net up 48.40% at Rs 225.49 cr |date=28 January 2011 |work=[[The Economic Times]] |access-date=4 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204082505/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2011-01-28/news/28425591_1_interim-dividend-satellite-rights-enthiran |archive-date=4 February 2015 |publisher=Press Trust of India |url-status=live}}</ref> whereas Anirban Bhattacharya of [[CNN Travel]] and T. S. Sreenivasan Raghavan of ''[[Bangalore Mirror]]'' state that it is {{INR}}1.62&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"CNN Travel\">{{Cite web |url=http://travel.cnn.com/mumbai/play/rajinikanths-robot-end-all-robots-538335/ |title=Rajinikanth's 'Robot' to end all robots |last=Bhattacharya |first=Anirban |date=7 October 2010 |publisher=[[CNN Travel]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605125444/http://travel.cnn.com/mumbai/play/rajinikanths-robot-end-all-robots-538335/ |archive-date=5 June 2016 |access-date=5 June 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://bangaloremirror.indiatimes.com/bangalore/others/chitti-the-robot-delights-tax-officials/articleshow/21756582.cms |title=Chitti, the robot, delights tax officials |last=Raghavan |first=T. S. Sreenivasan |date=22 October 2010 |work=[[Bangalore Mirror]] |access-date=13 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180813085423/https://bangaloremirror.indiatimes.com/bangalore/others/chitti-the-robot-delights-tax-officials/articleshow/21756582.cms |archive-date=13 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>|name=budget|group=Note}}\n| gross          = <!-- do not add any amount here, since India is notorious for lack of reliable box office info. the supposed gross is listed under \"box office\". -->\n| Box office     = \u20b9250 Crores\n}}\n'''''Enthiran''''' ({{translation|Robot}}) is a 2010&nbsp;Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil]]-language [[science fiction action film]] written and directed by [[S. Shankar]].<ref name=\"AV Club\">{{Cite web |url=https://film.avclub.com/enthiran-1798224462 |title=Enthiran |last=Koski |first=Genevieve |date=3 March 2011 |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123151947/http://www.avclub.com/article/ienthirani-52653 |archive-date=23 January 2015 |access-date=1 August 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> It is the first instalment in the [[Enthiran (film series)|''Enthiran'' franchise]]. The film stars [[Rajinikanth]] and [[Aishwarya Rai Bachchan]] in lead roles; [[Danny Denzongpa]], [[Santhanam (actor)|Santhanam]] and [[Karunas]] play supporting roles. The [[Enthiran (soundtrack)|soundtrack album and background score]] were composed by [[A. R. Rahman]] while the dialogues, cinematography, editing and art direction were handled by [[Madhan Karky]], [[R. Rathnavelu]], [[Anthony (film editor)|Anthony]] and [[Sabu Cyril]] respectively.\n\nThe story revolves around the struggle of a scientist Vaseegaran (played by Rajinikanth) to control his creation, an [[Android (robot)|android]] named [[Chitti (character)|Chitti]] (also played by Rajinikanth), after Chitti's software is upgraded to give it the ability to comprehend and exhibit human emotions. The project backfires when Chitti falls in love with Vaseegaran's girlfriend, Sana (Rai), and is manipulated by Bohra (Denzongpa), a rival scientist, into becoming homicidal.\n\nAfter being stalled in the [[development hell|development]] phase for nearly a decade, the film's principal photography began in 2008 and lasted two years. The film marked the debut of [[Legacy Effects]] studio (which was responsible for the film's [[Facial prosthetic|prosthetic make-up]] and [[animatronics]]) in Indian cinema. ''Enthiran'' was released worldwide on 1 October 2010, along with its [[dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbed]] versions: ''Robot'' in [[Hindi]] and ''Robo'' in [[Telugu language|Telugu]]. Produced by [[Kalanithi Maran]], it was India's [[List of most expensive Indian films|most expensive film]] up to that point.\n\nThe film received generally positive reviews upon release. Critics were particularly appreciative of Rajinikanth's performance as Chitti, Rathnavelu's cinematography, Cyril's art direction and the visual effects by [[V. Srinivas Mohan]]. ''Enthiran'' emerged as the top-earning Indian film of 2010 and is among the [[List of highest-grossing Tamil films|highest-grossing]] [[Cinema of South India|South Indian film]]s of all time. It won two [[National Film Awards|Indian National Film Awards]], three [[Filmfare Awards South|Filmfare Awards]], seven [[Vijay Awards]] and two [[Screen Awards]]. ''Enthiran'' was followed up by its [[Standalone film#Standalone sequel|standalone sequel]], ''[[2.0 (film)|2.0]]'', which released in 2018.\n\n== Plot ==\nAfter a decade of research, the scientist Vaseegaran creates a sophisticated [[android (robot)|android robot]] with the help of his assistants, Siva and Ravi, to commission it into the [[Indian Army]]. He introduces the robot, named [[Chitti (character)|Chitti]], at a robotics conference in [[Chennai]]. Chitti helps Sana, Vaseegaran's [[Medical students|medical student]] girlfriend, cheat in her examination, then saves her from being assaulted by a group of thugs. Vaseegaran's mentor, Professor Bohra, is secretly engaged in a project to create similar android robots for a terrorist organisation, but has so far been unsuccessful.\n\nVaseegaran prepares Chitti for an evaluation by the Artificial Intelligence Research and Development (AIRD) Institute, which is headed by Bohra. During the evaluation, Chitti attempts to stab Vaseegaran at Bohra's command, which convinces the evaluation committee that the robot is a liability and cannot be used for military purposes. Vaseegaran's effort to prove Bohra wrong fails when he deploys Chitti to rescue people from a burning building. The robot saves most of them, including a girl named Selvi who was bathing at the time, but she is ashamed at being seen naked on camera and flees, only to be hit and killed by a truck. Vaseegaran asks for one month to modify Chitti's [[image schema|neural schema]] to enable it to understand human behaviour and emotions, to which Bohra agrees. While nearing the deadline, Chitti becomes angry with Vaseegaran, demonstrating to him that it can manifest emotions.\n\nChitti uses Sana's textbooks to successfully help Sana's sister Latha give birth to a child. Bohra congratulates Vaseegaran on the achievement and allows Chitti to pass the AIRD evaluation. Chitti develops romantic feelings for Sana after she congratulates Chitti by kissing it. When Vaseegaran and Sana realise this, Sana explains to Chitti that they are only friends. Saddened by Sana's rejection, yet still in love with her, Chitti deliberately fails an evaluation conducted by the Indian Army. Enraged, Vaseegaran chops Chitti into pieces, which are dumped by Siva and Ravi into a landfill site.\n\nBohra visits the site to retrieve Chitti, which has now reassembled itself, albeit in a damaged state. Bohra embeds a red chip inside Chitti while reconstructing it, converting it into version 2.0, which is more aggressive and unempathetic. It then gatecrashes Vaseegaran and Sana's wedding, kidnaps Sana, creates replicas of itself, and then kills Bohra. Using its robot army, Chitti occupies AIRD and causes mayhem in the city. After informing Sana that it has acquired the human ability to reproduce, Chitti wishes to marry her so that a machine and a human being can give birth to a preprogrammed child, but Sana refuses. It eventually finds Vaseegaran, who entered AIRD to stop it, and nearly kills him before the police appear. The ensuing battle between Chitti's robot army and the police personnel leads to a lot of property destruction and many casualties. Vaseegaran eventually captures Chitti using a magnetic wall and accesses its internal control panel, whereby he instructs all the other robots to self-destruct. He then removes Chitti's red chip, calming it.\n\nIn a court hearing, Vaseegaran is sentenced to death for the casualties and damages caused by the robot army, but Chitti explains that it was Bohra who caused its deviant behaviour and shows the court video footage of Bohra installing the red chip. The court releases Vaseegaran, while ordering that Chitti be dismantled. Left with no choice, Vaseegaran asks Chitti to dismantle itself. While saying goodbye, Chitti apologises to Vaseegaran and Sana, who forgive it, before dismantling itself.\n\nThe film's setting then shifts to 2030. Chitti is now a museum exhibit. A curious school student on excursion asks her guide why it was dismantled, to which Chitti responds, \"''Naan sinthikka arambichen''\" (''I started thinking'').\n\n== Cast ==\n{{quote box\n| quote = I thought that playing Chitti the robot would be very difficult. He is a machine. His movements should not be like a human being's. We had to draw a line. If I deviated even slightly, Shankar would point it out and say I was being too human. After four to five days of shooting, we found a rhythm.\n| source =\u2014 Rajinikanth, on his experience of playing Chitti.{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|page=227}}\n| align = right\n| width = 35%\n}}\n\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Rajinikanth]] as Vaseegaran and [[Chitti (character)|Chitti]]<ref name=\"OC\">{{Cite AV media |title=Enthiran |date=1 October 2010 |type=motion picture |language=ta |publisher=[[Sun Pictures]] |place=India |time=01:00 to 02:00 |time-caption=Opening credits from}}</ref>\n* [[Aishwarya Rai Bachchan]] as Sana<ref name=\"netflix\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.netflixmovies.com/enthiran-2010 |title=Enthiran |date=2010 |website=[[Netflix]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20171005082958/https://www.netflixmovies.com/enthiran-2010 |archive-date=5 October 2017 |access-date=8 October 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Danny Denzongpa]] as Bohra<ref name=\"netflix\" />\n* [[Santhanam (actor)|Santhanam]] as Siva<ref name=\"netflix\" />\n* [[Karunas]] as Ravi<ref name=\"netflix\" />\n* [[Cochin Haneefa]] as the traffic police officer<ref name=\"netflix\" />\n* [[Kalabhavan Mani]] as Pachaimuthu<ref name=\"netflix\" />\n* [[Delhi Kumar]] as Vaseegaran's father<ref name=\"netflix\" />\n* [[Raaghav]] as the neighbourhood bully<ref name=\"OC\" />\n* [[Devadarshini]] as Latha, Sana's sister<ref name=\"netflix\" />\n* [[Revathi Sankaran]] as Vaseegaran's mother<ref name=\"OC\" />\n* [[Sabu Cyril]] as Shah{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|page=231}}\n* Sugunthan as the police inspector<ref name=\"CC\">{{Cite AV media |title=Enthiran |date=1 October 2010 |type=motion picture |language=ta |publisher=[[Sun Pictures]] |place=India |time=2:55:05 |time-caption=Closing credits in}}</ref>\n* [[Shriya Sharma]] as the curious student<ref name=\"CC\" />\n* [[Chaams]] as one of the barbers working at [[The Park, Chennai|The Park Hotel]]<ref name=\"CC\" />\n* [[Devadas Kanakala]] as K. Bhajanlal, a customer at The Park Hotel<ref name=\"CC\" />\n{{colend}}\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Origin ===\nFollowing the completion of his first directorial venture in Hindi, ''[[Nayak (2001 Hindi film)|Nayak]]'' (2001), [[S. Shankar]] announced his next project, ''Robot'', which was to feature [[Kamal Haasan]] and [[Preity Zinta]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/others/news-interviews/Shankars-Endhiran-to-become-a-reality-soon/articleshow/6215072.cms? |title=Shankar's Endhiran to become a reality soon |date=26 July 2010 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=27 May 2012 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118101009/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/others/news-interviews/Shankars-Endhiran-to-become-a-reality-soon/articleshow/6215072.cms |archive-date=18 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"BZ\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/entertai/2002/jan/02south.htm |title=Boys Zone |date=2 January 2002 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118101218/http://www.rediff.com/entertai/2002/jan/02south.htm |archive-date=18 January 2015 |access-date=18 January 2015}}</ref> The film was to be produced by the now-defunct company [[Media Dreams]], a division of [[Pentamedia Graphics]].<ref name=\"BZ\" /><ref name=\"Govardan\">{{Cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2008-01-05/news/28413738_1_rajinikanth-lulla-owned-eros-multimedia |title=Rajinikanth replaces Shah Rukh Khan in India's costliest movie |last=Govardan |first=D. |date=5 January 2008 |work=The Economic Times |access-date=18 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130126124918/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2008-01-05/news/28413738_1_rajinikanth-lulla-owned-eros-multimedia |archive-date=26 January 2013}}</ref> The film was reported to be a futuristic [[techno-thriller]] set in Chennai in around 2200 or 3000&nbsp;[[Anno Domini|AD]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/mp/2004/08/16/stories/2004081600740200.htm |title=Man vs. machine |date=16 August 2004 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=18 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118100919/http://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/mp/2004/08/16/stories/2004081600740200.htm |archive-date=18 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/nirav-and-sabu-sign-up-for-robot-news-tamil-kkfuh8aidcdsi.html |title=Nirav and Sabu sign up for Robot! |date=9 January 2008 |website=[[Sify]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118162759/http://www.sify.com/movies/nirav-and-sabu-sign-up-for-robot-news-tamil-kkfuh8aidcdsi.html |archive-date=18 January 2015 |access-date=18 January 2015}}</ref> Despite the completion of a photoshoot featuring Haasan and Zinta,<ref name=\"RFR\" /> the project was shelved as a result of scheduling conflicts with Haasan.<ref name=\"Fate\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-newdelhi/script-decides-the-fate-of-the-movie/article982047.ece |title=Script decides the fate of the movie |last=Tankha |first=Madhur |date=27 December 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=18 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118101504/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-newdelhi/script-decides-the-fate-of-the-movie/article982047.ece |archive-date=18 January 2015}}</ref> Shankar consequently started work on ''[[Boys (2003 film)|Boys]]'' (2003).<ref name=\"BZ\" />\n\nAfter ''Boys'', Shankar began work on his next feature starring [[Vikram (actor)|Vikram]], which was initially reported by [[Rediff.com]] to be ''Robot'' revived,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2003/nov/24south.htm |title=Shankar now wants sci-fi with Vikram |date=24 November 2003 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118101527/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2003/nov/24south.htm |archive-date=18 January 2015 |access-date=18 January 2015}}</ref> but was later revealed as ''[[Anniyan]]'' (2005).<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/fr/2005/03/11/stories/2005031101810100.htm |title=Director's dream project |last=Pillai |first=Sreedhar |date=11 March 2005 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 April 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113151544/http://www.hindu.com/fr/2005/03/11/stories/2005031101810100.htm |archive-date=13 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/mp/2004/03/15/stories/2004031500800200.htm |title=Shankar's next |last=M.I.N |date=15 March 2004 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 April 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050529005859/http://www.hindu.com/mp/2004/03/15/stories/2004031500800200.htm |archive-date=29 May 2005}}</ref> One month post the release of his action film ''[[Sivaji: The Boss]]'' in June 2007, he approached [[Shah Rukh Khan]] for the lead in ''Robot''.<ref name=\"srkcasting\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/shah-rukh-to-star-in-shankars-robot/article1881733.ece |title=Shah Rukh to star in Shankar's 'Robot' |last=Kumar |first=S. R. Ashok |date=29 July 2007 |work=The Hindu |access-date=18 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118101927/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/shah-rukh-to-star-in-shankars-robot/article1881733.ece |archive-date=18 January 2015}}</ref> Shankar had cast [[Priyanka Chopra]] as the female lead opposite him.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/not-rajinikanth-and-aishwarya-rai-bachchan-shah-rukh-khan-and-priyanka-chopra-were-the-first-choice-for-robot-bollywood-news/322385|title=Not Rajinikanth and Aishwarya Rai Bachchan, Shah Rukh Khan and Priyanka Chopra were the first choice for Robot|last=Chauhan|first=Gaurang|website=[[Times Now]]|date=28 November 2018|access-date=30 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329165639/https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/not-rajinikanth-and-aishwarya-rai-bachchan-shah-rukh-khan-and-priyanka-chopra-were-the-first-choice-for-robot-bollywood-news/322385|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Khan was about to produce it under his own banner, [[Red Chillies Entertainment]], but in October the same year the project was officially aborted due to creative differences between him and Shankar.<ref name=\"srkcasting\"/><ref name=\"Superstar casting\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/jan/02robot.htm |title=Shankar signs on Rajnikanth for Robot |last=Vilakudy |first=Rajaneesh |date=2 January 2008 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118101954/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/jan/02robot.htm |archive-date=18 January 2015 |access-date=18 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe project was revived in January 2008 with [[Eros International]] and the [[London]]-based production company [[Ayngaran International]] willing to produce the film.<ref name=\"Govardan\" /> The state government of [[Tamil Nadu]] granted tax exemptions for films titled in [[Tamil language|Tamil]], resulting in the new production being renamed ''Enthiran''.<ref name=\"Fate\" /> While [[Sujatha Rangarajan]] was originally assigned to write the dialogue for the film, [[Madhan Karky]] took over after Rangarajan's death in February 2008.<ref name=\"RFR\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/article566585.ece |title=Ready for Robot? |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |date=12 August 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=18 September 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118103719/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/article566585.ece |archive-date=18 January 2015}}</ref> In December 2008, Eros International withdrew from funding the project after financial difficulties caused by the box-office failure of ''[[Drona (2008 film)|Drona]]'' (2008) and ''[[Yuvvraaj]]'' (2008),<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://archive.mid-day.com/news/2008/dec/301208-Rajinikanth-Aishwarya-Rai-Enthiran-Hollywood-HBO-simultaneous-release.htm |title=Hollywood dreams |last=Kumar |first=S. Suresh |date=30 December 2008 |work=[[Mid Day]] |access-date=18 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Vg1tedde?url=http://archive.mid-day.com/news/2008/dec/301208-Rajinikanth-Aishwarya-Rai-Enthiran-Hollywood-HBO-simultaneous-release.htm |archive-date=18 January 2015}}</ref> with the subsequent departure of Ayngaran International, which struggled with the [[financial crisis of 2007\u201308]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.asiantribune.com/node/14840 |title=Sri Lankan born producer edged out of Rs.150 crore Rajanikanth's mega film 'Endhiran' |last=Balakrishnan |first=Ravikumar |date=26 December 2008 |work=[[Asian Tribune]] |access-date=5 June 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605045455/http://www.asiantribune.com/node/14840 |archive-date=5 June 2016}}</ref> The film's production and release rights were sold to [[Sun Pictures]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/dec/18sun-pictures-to-produce-endhiran.htm |title=Sun Pictures to produce Rajni's Endhiran |date=18 December 2008 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118102809/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/dec/18sun-pictures-to-produce-endhiran.htm |archive-date=18 January 2015 |access-date=18 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Cast and crew ===\n[[File:Rajini and Aishwarya Rai.jpg|thumbnail|For their roles, Rajinikanth (''left'') and Rai (''right'') were paid {{INR}}450&nbsp;million and {{INR}}60&nbsp;million respectively.]]\nIn January 2008, [[Rajinikanth]] accepted the lead role in the film for a salary of {{INR}}450&nbsp;million ([[Indian rupee]]s).<ref name=\"Superstar casting\" /><ref name=\"R+R\">{{Cite news |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/robot+rajini=rs-300-cr/1/115629.html |title=Robot+Rajini=Rs. 300 cr |last=Subramanian |first=Lakshmi |date=9 October 2010 |work=[[India Today]] |access-date=22 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122111859/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/robot%2Brajini%3Drs-300-cr/1/115629.html |archive-date=22 January 2015 |last2=Bamzai |first2=Kaveree}}</ref>{{refn|The average exchange rate in 2008 was 49.82 [[Indian rupee]]s ({{INR}}) per 1 US dollar (US$).<ref name=\"ex2010\">{{Cite web |url=http://inwww.rediff.com/business/slide-show/slide-show-1-rupee-vs-dollar-in-the-last-2-decades/20120518.htm?print=true |title=Rupee vs dollar: From 1990 to 2012 |date=18 May 2012 |website=Rediff.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150321115240/http://inwww.rediff.com/business/slide-show/slide-show-1-rupee-vs-dollar-in-the-last-2-decades/20120518.htm?print=true |archive-date=21 March 2015 |access-date=21 March 2015}}</ref>|name=exchange2008|group=Note}} Shankar rewrote the original script to suit Rajinikanth's acting style.{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|page=227}} In an interview with the Tamil channel [[Sun TV (India)|Sun TV]], held shortly after the film's release in October 2010, Rajinikanth revealed that Shankar, following the release of his ''[[Indian (1996 film)|Indian]]'' in 1996, had approached and pitched three storylines for him to consider for his next venture. Rajinikanth was impressed with two of the scripts and agreed to star in the films, which became ''Sivaji'' and ''Enthiran''. The third script narrated by Shankar focused on an aspiring bodybuilder; it eventually became ''[[I (film)|I]]'' (2015).<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Super Star Rajini&nbsp;\u2013 Special Interview |date=October 2010 |last=Rajinikanth (actor) |type=interview |language=Tamil |publisher=Sun TV |place=Chennai}}</ref>\n\nAlthough [[Aishwarya Rai]] was Shankar's original choice for the female lead in 2001, she declined it owing to a busy schedule and was replaced by Zinta.<ref name=\"Touch\">{{Cite news |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/news-archive/web/the-human-touch-6/ |title=The HUMAN Touch |last=Sahgal |first=Geety |date=1 October 2010 |work=[[The Indian Express]] |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120151720/http://indianexpress.com/article/news-archive/web/the-human-touch-6/ |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref> When Shankar revived the project with Rajinikanth,<ref name=\"Superstar casting\" /> contenders for the part included [[Deepika Padukone]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/jan/10robot.htm |title=Who should Rajni romance in Robot: Deepika or Ash? |date=10 January 2008 |work=[[Rediff.com]] |access-date=18 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118164646/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/jan/10robot.htm |archive-date=18 January 2015 |agency=[[Press Trust of India]]}}</ref> [[Shriya Saran]] and Rai, who was ultimately selected and paid {{INR}}60&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/mar/17ash.htm |title=Ash is back in Rajni's Robot |last=Gupshup |first=Gullu |date=17 March 2008 |website=Rediff.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118170445/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/mar/17ash.htm |archive-date=18 January 2015 |access-date=18 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/apr/17msg.htm |title=Should Shriya star opposite Rajni in Robot? |date=17 April 2008 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090506070110/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/apr/17msg.htm |archive-date=6 May 2009 |access-date=18 January 2015}}</ref>{{refn|name=exchange2008|group=Note}} Rai's voice was dubbed by [[Savitha Reddy]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/savitha-reddy-to-dub-for-deepika-in-kochadaiyaan-113101000828_1.html |title=Savitha Reddy to dub for Deepika in 'Kochadaiyaan' |date=10 October 2013 |work=[[Business Standard]] |access-date=24 February 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225062543/http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/savitha-reddy-to-dub-for-deepika-in-kochadaiyaan-113101000828_1.html |archive-date=25 February 2015 |agency=[[Indo-Asian News Service|IANS]]}}</ref>{{refn|In an interview with Geety Sahgal of ''[[The Indian Express]]'', Shankar stated that Rai had her dialogues translated from Tamil to English and rehearsed it the night before each day of filming.<ref name=\"Touch\" />|group=Note}}\n\nSeveral actors were considered for the role of Professor Bohra, including [[Amitabh Bachchan]],<ref name=\"IT\">{{Cite news |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/rajinikanth-told-me-not-to-play-villain-in-enthiran-says-amitabh-bachchan/1/561739.html |title=Rajinikanth told me not to play villain in Enthiran, says Amitabh Bachchan |date=4 January 2016 |work=India Today |access-date=5 June 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605050104/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/rajinikanth-told-me-not-to-play-villain-in-enthiran-says-amitabh-bachchan/1/561739.html |archive-date=5 June 2016}}</ref> [[J. D. Chakravarthy]],<ref name=IT /> [[Sathyaraj]] and British actor [[Ben Kingsley]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/character-call/article2839950.ece |title=Character Call |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |date=28 January 2012 |work=The Hindu |access-date=18 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118171750/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/character-call/article2839950.ece |archive-date=18 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Manoj\" /> but it was [[Danny Denzongpa]] who eventually received it, making ''Enthiran'' his first film in Tamil.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Rajinis-unflappable-Danny/articleshow/6512564.cms |title=Rajini's unflappable: Danny |last=Dutt |first=Purba |date=8 September 2010 |work=The Times of India |access-date=18 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Vg6QiOB0?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Rajinis-unflappable-Danny/articleshow/6512564.cms |archive-date=18 January 2015}}</ref> Dubbing for Denzongpa was provided by Kadhir.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/over-to-the-voices/article2723614.ece |title=Over to the voices&nbsp;... |last=Rao |first=Subha J. |date=17 December 2011 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119031821/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/over-to-the-voices/article2723614.ece |archive-date=19 January 2015}}</ref> Comedians [[Santhanam (actor)|Santhanam]] and [[Karunas]] were cast to portray Vaseegaran's assistants Siva and Ravi respectively.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/101071/rajnikanths-endhiran-truly-entertaining-movie.html |title=Rajnikanth's 'Endhiran' truly entertaining movie |date=1 October 2010 |work=[[Deccan Herald]] |access-date=5 October 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005083136/http://www.deccanherald.com/content/101071/rajnikanths-endhiran-truly-entertaining-movie.html |archive-date=5 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe soundtrack album and background score were composed by A. R. Rahman.<ref name=\"Roll\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/endhiran-set-to-roll-out/article1424451.ece |title=Endhiran set to roll out |date=8 September 2008 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121024256/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/endhiran-set-to-roll-out/article1424451.ece |archive-date=21 January 2015}}</ref> [[Vairamuthu]], [[P. Vijay]] and Madhan Karky authored the lyrics for the songs.<ref name=\"Roll\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/money-and-careers/carry-on-karky/article1993594.ece |title=Carry On Karky |last=Reddy |first=T. Krithika |date=5 May 2011 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140325054559/http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/money-and-careers/carry-on-karky/article1993594.ece |archive-date=25 March 2014}}</ref> [[Manoj Bharathiraja]], son of filmmaker [[P. Bharathiraja]], was signed on to be an assistant director after he approached Shankar.<ref name=\"Manoj\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/interviews/article301242.ece |title=Manoj Bharatiraja and 'Endhiran' |last=Malini |first=Shankaran |date=14 September 2010 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=19 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119024947/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/interviews/article301242.ece |archive-date=19 January 2015}}</ref> Also working as assistant directors were [[Atlee Kumar]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/atlee-displays-his-chops/article5788431.ece |title=Atlee displays his chops |last=Chowdhary |first=Y. Sunita |date=15 March 2014 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119025905/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/atlee-displays-his-chops/article5788431.ece |archive-date=19 January 2015}}</ref> Shree and Karthik G. Krish.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-reviews/audio-beat-damaal-dumeel-hitting-the-high-notes/article5764172.ece |title=Audio Beat: Damaal Dumeel&nbsp;\u2013 Hitting the high notes |last=Kumar |first=S. R. Ashok |date=8 March 2014 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119030538/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-reviews/audio-beat-damaal-dumeel-hitting-the-high-notes/article5764172.ece |archive-date=19 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/reading-between-friendship/article5979081.ece |title=Reading between friendship |last=Ramanujam |first=Srinivasa |date=5 May 2014 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119030857/http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/reading-between-friendship/article5979081.ece |archive-date=19 January 2015}}</ref> [[Sabu Cyril]], in addition to being the film's art director, made a guest appearance as Shah, an interpreter between Bohra and the terrorist organisation.{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|page=231}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/all-in-a-sets-work/article2287617.ece |title=All in a set's work |last=Dundoo |first=Sangeetha Devi |date=23 July 2011 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119031637/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/all-in-a-sets-work/article2287617.ece |archive-date=19 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[R. Rathnavelu]] was hired as the cinematographer after [[Ravi K. Chandran]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/seeing-through-the-lens-he-creates-magic/article1295670.ece |title=Seeing through the lens, he creates magic |last=Srinivasan |first=Meera |date=13 July 2008 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119033950/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/seeing-through-the-lens-he-creates-magic/article1295670.ece |archive-date=19 January 2015}}</ref> [[Nirav Shah]] and [[Thiru]] were considered.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/light-camera-and-a-lens-to-top-it-all/article5604618.ece |title=Light, camera and a lens to top it all |last=Krishnamoorthy |first=Suresh |date=22 January 2014 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119034410/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/light-camera-and-a-lens-to-top-it-all/article5604618.ece |archive-date=19 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Shoote\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/robot-shoot-starts-news-tamil-kkftUPbiagdsi.html |title=''Robot'' shoot starts! |date=15 February 2008 |website=Sify |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422081847/http://sify.com/movies/tamil/fullstory.php?id=14605537 |archive-date=22 April 2008 |access-date=19 January 2015}}</ref> [[Anthony (film editor)|Anthony]] was the film's editor.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/robot-endhiran--behind-the-camera/131984-8-66.html |title='Robot': 'Endhiran'&nbsp;\u2013 Behind the camera |last=Joseph |first=Renju |date=30 September 2010 |website=[[CNN-News18]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Vgm6w0CK?url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/robot-endhiran--behind-the-camera/131984-8-66.html |archive-date=19 January 2015 |access-date=19 January 2015}}</ref> [[Yuen Woo-ping]], known for his work in [[The Matrix (franchise)|''The Matrix'' trilogy]] and the ''[[Kill Bill: Volume 1|Kill Bill]]'' films, was selected to be the stunt co-ordinator,<ref name=\"MYS\" /> while [[Legacy Effects]], a visual effects studio based in the United States, were in charge of the [[prosthetic make-up]] and animatronics in the film.<ref name=\"MYS\" /> [[Munich]]-based film technical company, [[Panther (company)|Panther]], were responsible for the [[crane shot]]s.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/the-sea-inside/article3657464.ece |title=The sea inside |date=19 July 2012 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120080408/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/the-sea-inside/article3657464.ece |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref>{{refn|In [[filmmaking]] and [[video production]], a crane shot is a shot taken by a [[video camera|camera]] on a [[Crane (machine)|crane]] or [[Jib (camera)|jib]].|group=Note}} The film's [[Subtitles|subtitle captioning]] was done by Rekha Haricharan.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://behindwoods.com/new-videos/videos-q1-09/director-interview/rekha.html |title=Rekhs Interview |last=Bhavanishankar |first=Jyothsna |date=28 September 2010 |website=Behindwoods |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412124101/http://behindwoods.com/new-videos/videos-q1-09/director-interview/rekha.html |archive-date=12 April 2015 |access-date=12 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Costume design ===\n[[Manish Malhotra]] and Mary E. Vogt were chosen to design the film's costumes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2009/apr/01slide3-best-of-manish-malhotra.htm |title=Manish Malhotra's fab filmi fashion&nbsp;\u2013 Aishwarya Rai Bachchan, Endhiran |date=1 April 2009 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119041810/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2009/apr/01slide3-best-of-manish-malhotra.htm |archive-date=19 January 2015 |access-date=19 January 2015}}</ref>{{refn|Vogt was also the costume designer for the ''[[Men in Black (film series)|Men in Black]]'' film series.<ref name=\"MYS\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article/Platinum-Mans-Dance/266773 |title=Platinum Man's Dance |last=Iyengar |first=Pushpa |date=30 September 2010 |website=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119042620/http://www.outlookindia.com/article/Platinum-Mans-Dance/266773 |archive-date=19 January 2015 |access-date=19 January 2015}}</ref>|group=Note}} Fifty-seven costumes were used for Rai, including a \"Mexican tribal\" look that she sported during the filming of the \"[[Kilimanjaro (song)|Kilimanjaro]]\" segment.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2009/may/20slide-show-1-ojas-talks-about-favourite-stars.htm#1 |title='Ash's tribal look in Enthiran is very glamorous' |last=Ramani |first=Nithya |date=21 May 2009 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120170121/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2009/may/20slide-show-1-ojas-talks-about-favourite-stars.htm |archive-date=20 January 2015 |access-date=20 January 2015}}</ref> According to make-up artist [[Banu (make-up artist)|Banu]], no prosthetics were used for Rajinikanth to avoid bothering him by withholding his time on set.<ref name=\"Banu\">{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Man-behind-Rajnis-looks/articleshow/6706929.cms |title=Man behind Rajni's looks |last=Pillai |first=Sreedhar |date=8 October 2010 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=29 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6VwRtka6p?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Man-behind-Rajnis-looks/articleshow/6706929.cms |archive-date=29 January 2015}}</ref> Additional make-up was by Vance Hartwell, an employee of Legacy Effects.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/whats-the-secret-behind-63-year-old-superstar-rajinikanths-youthful-looks/articleshow/45409978.cms |title=What's the secret behind 63-year-old superstar Rajinikanth's youthful looks? |last=Mathai |first=Kamini |date=8 December 2014 |work=The Economic Times |access-date=30 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20150130131858/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/whats-the-secret-behind-63-year-old-superstar-rajinikanths-youthful-looks/articleshow/45409978.cms |archive-date=30 January 2015 |last2=Nurullah |first2=Abdullah}}</ref>\n\nThe visual appearance of Chitti was based on the [[G.I. Joe]] [[action figure]]s. For Chitti's \"villain robot\" look, its hair was spiked and brown coloured lenses were used for its eyes, whereas for its \"good robot\" look, green coloured lenses were used.<ref name=\"Banu\" /> The wig used for Chitti's \"villain robot\" look had a silver streak in the middle, made out of [[Yak]] hair,<ref name=\"Banu Sify\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/banu-i-give-full-credit-to-rajini-sir-news-tamil-kkjrmldfhchsi.html |title=Banu&nbsp;\u2013 I give full credit to Rajini sir |date=9 October 2010 |website=Sify |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221074710/http://www.sify.com/movies/banu-i-give-full-credit-to-rajini-sir-news-tamil-kkjrmldfhchsi.html |archive-date=21 February 2015 |access-date=21 February 2015}}</ref> while its leather jacket was designed by Vogt.<ref name=\"Banu Sify\" /> To make Vaseegaran look mature, the team made Rajinikanth sport an [[Beard#Styles|Oakley beard]].{{refn|According to Banu, an Oakley beard is \"neither a French beard not a full beard\". It developed as a result of shaping Rajinikanth's already grown beard.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://behindwoods.com/new-videos/videos-q1-09/director-interview/make-up-artist-banu.html |title=Make&nbsp;\u2013 up artist Banu interview |last=Kingston |first=Daya |website=Behindwoods |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225062905/http://behindwoods.com/new-videos/videos-q1-09/director-interview/make-up-artist-banu.html |archive-date=25 February 2015 |access-date=24 February 2015}}</ref>|group=Note}} Suits made of copper were used for Chitti's costumes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/others/news-interviews/Rajinis-metallic-look/articleshow/4131575.cms |title=Rajini's metallic look! |date=16 February 2009 |work=The Times of India |access-date=29 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6VwSUJG9S?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/others/news-interviews/Rajinis-metallic-look/articleshow/4131575.cms |archive-date=29 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Principal photography ===\n{{multiple image\n<!-- Essential parameters -->\n| align     = right\n| direction = vertical\n| footer    = The residential section of the Incan city of Machu Picchu, which features in the song, \"Kilimanjaro\".\n| width     = 200px\n\n<!-- Image 1 -->\n| image1    = MachuPicchu Residential (pixinn.net).jpg\n| width1    = 100\n| alt1      = Photo of stone walls\n| caption1  =\n}}\nFor Sabu Cyril's sets, Shankar required approximately twice as much studio floor space as for his previous film. After rejecting [[Ramoji Film City]] for technical reasons, ''Enthiran''{{'s}} producer, [[Kalanithi Maran]], took six months to set up three air-conditioned studio floors on land in [[Perungudi]] owned by Sun TV Network.{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=226}} Filming began on 15 February 2008 at [[AVM Productions|AVM Studios]] in Chennai.<ref name=\"Shoote\" /> After the initial stages of filming, Shankar and Rathnavelu toured the world for three weeks, scouting for exotic filming locations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/entertainment/movies/tamil/boxoffice/fullstory.php?id=14694570 |title=Shankar goes on a global location hunt! |date=14 June 2008 |website=Sify |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080617110015/http://sify.com/movies/tamil/fullstory.php?id=14694570 |archive-date=17 June 2008 |access-date=19 January 2015}}</ref> They visited Austria, Germany, Peru, Brazil and Argentina, looking for a backdrop to shoot the \"Kilimanjaro\" and \"Kadhal Anukkal\" segments,<ref name=\"YHSH\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/your-hunt-stops-here/article804495.ece |title=Your hunt stops here |last=Kumar |first=S. R. Ashok |date=2 October 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120164057/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/your-hunt-stops-here/article804495.ece |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref> eventually deciding on Peru and Brazil.<ref name=\"WSJ\" /><ref name=\"EL\" /> \"Kilimanjaro\" was filmed at the ruins of the [[Inca Empire|Incan]] city of [[Machu Picchu]] in Peru, with some 100&nbsp;Brazilian extras.<ref name=\"YHSH\" /><ref name=\"WSJ\">{{Cite news |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2010/10/01/machu-picchu-welcomes-rajnikanth-and-india/ |title=Machu Picchu Welcomes Rajinikanth (and India) |last=Lahiri |first=Tripti |date=1 October 2010 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120104833/https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2010/10/01/machu-picchu-welcomes-rajnikanth-and-india/ |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref> It was choreographed by [[Raju Sundaram]] and supervised by Fernando Astete, director of the Machu Picchu archaeological park.<ref name=\"WSJ\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/why-bollywood-filmmakers-are-spending-generously-on-a-song-shoot/15239094 |title=Why Bollywood filmmakers are spending generously on a song shoot |last=Shetty |first=Shakti |date=19 April 2014 |work=Mid Day |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120105528/http://www.mid-day.com/articles/why-bollywood-filmmakers-are-spending-generously-on-a-song-shoot/15239094 |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref> \"Kadhal Anukkal\" was filmed in [[Len\u00e7\u00f3is Maranhenses National Park]] in northeastern Brazil.<ref name=\"EL\">{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/news-interviews/Kollywood-in-search-of-exotic-locations/articleshow/6809384.cms |title=Kollywood in search of exotic locations |last=Pillai |first=Sreedhar |date=26 October 2010 |work=The Times of India |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Vj4LuiS4?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/news-interviews/Kollywood-in-search-of-exotic-locations/articleshow/6809384.cms |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe filming for Chitti's introduction to the international robotics conference was completed in December 2008 at [[Sri Sivasubramaniya Nadar College of Engineering]] and [[Vellore Institute of Technology]], where more than 400&nbsp;students were used as extras.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/Aishwarya-Rajnikanth-in-Vellore-for-Endhiran/articleshow/3897654.cms |title=Aishwarya, Rajnikanth in Vellore for Endhiran |date=27 December 2008 |work=The Times of India |access-date=5 June 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605082449/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/Aishwarya-Rajnikanth-in-Vellore-for-Endhiran/articleshow/3897654.cms |archive-date=5 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/article427262.ece |title='Enthiran' highest budget Indian film! |date=2 June 2010 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120073105/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/article427262.ece |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref> Further footage was shot over five days at the [[Ennore Port]] on the [[Mitsui O.S.K. Lines]] car carrier, ''Neptune Ace''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/cresting-the-tech-wave/article3497160.ece |title=Cresting the tech wave |last=Padamanabhan |first=Geeta |date=6 June 2012 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120072000/http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/cresting-the-tech-wave/article3497160.ece |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref> An action sequence where Chitti saves Sana from thugs was filmed in [[Lonavla]], under the supervision of the action choreographer [[Peter Hein]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/endhiran-action-scenes-in-lonavala-news-tamil-kkfrgkfbfjesi.html |title=''Endhiran'' action scenes in Lonavala |date=29 December 2009 |website=Sify |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122163026/http://www.sify.com/movies/endhiran-action-scenes-in-lonavala-news-tamil-kkfrgkfbfjesi.html |archive-date=22 January 2015 |access-date=22 January 2015}}</ref> Scenes featuring Rajinikanth as Chitti were captured over five days at the [[Perungudi#Dump Yard|Perungudi Dump Yard]] in Chennai.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/now-garbage-dump-turns-shooting-spot/article761579.ece |title=Now garbage dump turns shooting spot |last=H. Ramakrishnan |first=Deepa |date=5 May 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120065159/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/endhiran-almost-complete-shankar/article76198.ece |archive-date=20 January 2015 |last2=Lakshmi |first2=K.}}</ref> Sabu Cyril told Uma Kannan of ''[[The New Indian Express]]'' that the sets for the climax sequence, which was filmed at [[Mayajaal]], consisted of a tar road and glass buildings which rose to {{convert|65|ft|m}}, and that [[Sandwich panel|aluminium composite panels]], reported to have cost {{INR}}50&nbsp;million, were also used to design the sets.<ref name=\"Sabu\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/interviews/article479419.ece |title=Sets, Sabu and 'Enthiran' |last=Kannan |first=Uma |date=29 September 2010 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120100715/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/interviews/article479419.ece |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/endhiran-shot-on-expensive-sets-news-tamil-kkfrK8bjcdjsi.html |title=Endhiran shot on expensive sets |date=2 July 2009 |website=Sify |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122162428/http://www.sify.com/movies/endhiran-shot-on-expensive-sets-news-tamil-kkfrK8bjcdjsi.html |archive-date=22 January 2015 |access-date=22 January 2015}}</ref>{{refn|The average exchange rate in 2010 was 45.09 Indian rupees ({{INR}}) per 1 US dollar (US$).<ref name=\"ex2010\" />|name=exchange2010|group=Note}}\n\nThe set for \"[[Arima Arima]]\", a sequence choreographed by [[Prabhu Deva]],<ref name=\"Dancing\" /> was designed and constructed by Cyril at Ramoji Film City.<ref name=\"Sabu\" /> Filming of the number took place over 22&nbsp;days in April 2009.<ref name=\"Dancing\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/dancing-in-100-ways-rajini-style/article317305.ece |title=Dancing in 100 ways, Rajini style |last=Srinivasan |first=Meera |date=28 April 2009 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120161226/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/dancing-in-100-ways-rajini-style/article317305.ece |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref> Junior artists were employed by Rathnavelu to wear masks of Rajinikanth.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/unveiled/article831081.ece |title=Unveiled! |last=Shivakumar |first=S. |date=15 October 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=21 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121043753/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/unveiled/article831081.ece |archive-date=21 January 2015}}</ref> For the sequence entitled \"Irumbile Oru Irudhaiyam\", choreographed by [[Remo D'Souza]] and featuring Rai and Rajinikanth as Chitti,<ref name=\"D\" /> three different sets were used: one of copper, one of gold and one in silver.<ref name=\"Sabu\" /> The musical number, which was filmed in AVM Studios for eight days, was the last portion of the film's principal photography.<ref name=\"D\" /> D'Souza incorporated the [[popping]] style of [[street dance]]s, but encountered difficulties in performing the dance movements in tandem with the robot, and with the restrictions created by the rigid costumes.<ref name=\"D\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/interviews/article488740.ece |title=Remo D'Souza and the 'Enthiran' dance |last=Malini |first=Shankaran |date=21 September 2010 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120155914/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/interviews/article488740.ece |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref> Principal photography ended on 7 July 2010.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/rajinikanth-aishwarya-and-shankar-at-the-enthiren-party-imagegallery-kollywood-khnkP2egjifsi.html |title=Rajinikanth, Aishwarya and Shankar at the Enthiren party |website=Sify |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609155103/http://www.sify.com/movies/rajinikanth-aishwarya-and-shankar-at-the-enthiren-party-imagegallery-kollywood-khnkP2egjifsi.html |archive-date=9 June 2016 |access-date=9 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Visual effects ===\nImpressed with the film's script, [[V. Srinivas Mohan]] became the visual effects supervisor in December 2007. He asked Shankar to increase the filming schedules by six months to include pre-production requirements.<ref name=\"SMBW\">{{Cite web |url=http://behindwoods.com/new-videos/videos-q1-09/director-interview/srinivas-mohan.html |title=Endhiran VFX Supervisor Srinivas Interview |last=Bhavanishankar |first=Jyothsna |date=22 October 2010 |website=Behindwoods |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121032143/http://behindwoods.com/new-videos/videos-q1-09/director-interview/srinivas-mohan.html |archive-date=21 January 2015 |access-date=21 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Clone\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/animatronics-maketh-the-clone/article860359.ece |title=Animatronics maketh the clone |last=Devi Dundoo |first=Sangeetha |date=31 October 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=21 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121041958/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/animatronics-maketh-the-clone/article860359.ece |archive-date=21 January 2015}}</ref> Both Mohan and Shankar visited several visual effects companies, including the New Zealand-based [[Weta Digital]] and the United States-based [[Industrial Light & Magic]], [[Cafe FX]] and [[Tippett Studio]] before partnering with Legacy Effects.<ref name=\"SMBW\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/science-meets-cinema/article567194.ece |title=Science meets cinema |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |date=13 August 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=21 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121030008/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/science-meets-cinema/article567194.ece |archive-date=21 January 2015}}</ref> The original Eros-Ayngaran visual effects budget was {{INR}}700&nbsp;million,{{refn|name=exchange2008|group=Note}} but after Sun Pictures took over production, it was significantly reduced to {{INR}}200&nbsp;million.{{refn|name=exchange2008|group=Note}} As a result, the visual effects team had to omit and alter some sequences, making Chitti wear sunglasses for most of the film to reduce the cost and difficulty of animating his eyes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/article1304321.ece |title=Why Enthiran Rajini wore coolers? |last=Venkadesan |first=S. |date=18 October 2012 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=21 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121034556/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/article1304321.ece |archive-date=21 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter a series of [[Previsualization|previsualisation]] tests, including a scene in which Chitti jumps on a train to save Sana, Mohan eventually decided to use the technique in 40&nbsp;out of the 60&nbsp;visual effects scenes featured in the film,<ref name=\"SMBW\" /> consisting of 2,000&nbsp;takes.<ref name=\"Behind\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/behind-the-robot/article859242.ece |title=Behind the Robot |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |date=30 October 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119040836/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/behind-the-robot/article859242.ece |archive-date=19 January 2015}}</ref> Further previsualisation supervision was conducted by P. C. Sanath of Firefly Creative Studios, a visual effects company based in [[Hyderabad]].<ref name=\"Clone\" /> [[Storyboard#Creation|3D storyboards]] were constructed using 3D&nbsp;animation programs for every scene in the film and were shot from different angles.<ref name=\"Clone\" /> In an interview with Malathi Rangarajan of ''[[The Hindu]]'', Mohan said all the pre-production work took one-and-a-half years to complete.<ref name=\"Behind\" />\n\nRathnavelu used the [[Arriflex 435#435 Xtreme|435 Xtreme]] camera and also wrote a 1,600-page manual, in which he listed all the possible angles from where he could film the characters Rajinikanth played.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://behindwoods.com/new-videos/videos-q1-09/director-interview/rathnavelu.html |title=Cameraman Rathanvelu Interview |last=Bhavanishankar |first=Jyothsna |date=22 October 2010 |website=Behindwoods |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120171704/http://behindwoods.com/new-videos/videos-q1-09/director-interview/rathnavelu.html |archive-date=20 January 2015 |access-date=20 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/interview-with-cinematographer-rathnavelu/article6646451.ece |title=Lingaa through Randy's lens |last=Reddy |first=T. Krithika |date=29 November 2014 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120080947/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/interview-with-cinematographer-rathnavelu/article6646451.ece |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref> Legacy Effects and the Hong Kong-based visual effects companies Kinomotive Studios and Menfond Electronics took responsibility for the film's [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] work.<ref name=\"Behind\" /> To create the robots with Rajinikanth's appearance, a complete scan of his face in 3D&nbsp;digital format in all possible lighting conditions was conducted using the Doom Light Stage,{{refn|The Doom Light Stage is based on an original research conducted by [[Paul Debevec]] at the [[Institute for Creative Technologies|ICT]] division of the [[University of California, Berkeley]]. The Light Stage systems efficiently capture how an actor's face appears when lit from every possible lighting direction. From this captured imagery, realistic virtual renditions of the actor are created in the illumination of any location or set, faithfully reproducing the colour, texture, shine, shading and translucency of the actor's skin.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.fxguide.com/quicktakes/light-stage-brings-the-robot-to-life-in-india/ |title=Light Stage brings The Robot to life in India |last=Seymour |first=Mike |date=23 October 2010 |website=[[Fxguide]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123145843/http://www.fxguide.com/quicktakes/light-stage-brings-the-robot-to-life-in-india/ |archive-date=23 January 2015 |access-date=23 January 2015}}</ref>|group=Note}} so that his face could be replicated on the [[mannequin]]s.<ref name=\"Clone\" /> The technique, according to Shankar, was previously used in ''[[The Curious Case of Benjamin Button (film)|The Curious Case of Benjamin Button]]'' (2008).<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/interviews/Enthiran-doesnt-have-a-regional-mosaic/articleshow/6644888.cms |title='Enthiran doesn't have a regional mosaic' |last=Ravi |first=Bhama Devi |date=29 September 2010 |work=The Times of India |access-date=26 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Vs1IJKK2?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/interviews/Enthiran-doesnt-have-a-regional-mosaic/articleshow/6644888.cms |archive-date=26 January 2015}}</ref> The robot Chitti featured in the film was a mannequin made by a Legacy Effects team of 100&nbsp;technicians in Los Angeles. For every robotic mannequin used, six puppeteers were employed to control the mannequin's movements.<ref name=\"Behind\" />\n\n== Themes and influences ==\n''Enthiran'' focuses on the battle between man and machine.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/magazine/enjoy-the-carnival-folks/article842791.ece |title=Enjoy the carnival folks |last=Srivathsan |first=A. |date=23 October 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=27 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150127041324/http://www.thehindu.com/features/magazine/enjoy-the-carnival-folks/article842791.ece |archive-date=27 January 2015}}</ref> Despite Shankar's claim that ''Enthiran'' was a purely original idea,<ref name=\"RFR\" /> it has been compared to [[Mary Shelley]]'s 1818&nbsp;novel ''[[Frankenstein]]'', owing to the similar personae of Chitti and [[Frankenstein's monster]], both of whom turn against their respective creators.<ref name=\"malini\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/reviews/article287453.ece |title=Enthiran |last=Mannath |first=Malini |date=4 October 2010 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123151201/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/reviews/article287453.ece |archive-date=23 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-11498630 |title=BBC News&nbsp;\u2013 India's most expensive film is another Rajinikanth hit |last=G. Tilak |first=Sudha |date=10 October 2010 |website=BBC News |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123151717/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-11498630 |archive-date=23 January 2015 |access-date=23 January 2015}}</ref> K. Moti Gokulsing and Wimal Dissanayake, in their book ''Routledge Handbook of Indian Cinemas'', noted the similarity between the two works, arguing that Chitti was \"manipulated by Bohra to become a Frankenstein-like figure\".<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QwGgF-rDucEC |title=Routledge Handbook of Indian Cinemas |last=Gokulsing |first=K. Moti |last2=Dissanayake |first2=Wimal |publisher=[[Routledge]] |year=2013 |isbn=978-0-415-67774-5 |pages=294 |ref=harv |access-date=27 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413223856/http://books.google.com/books?id=QwGgF-rDucEC |archive-date=13 April 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Writing for ''[[The A.V. Club]]'', Genevieve Koski observed, \"The plot of ''Enthiran'' is essentially ''Frankenstein'' via [[Isaac Asimov|[Isaac] Asimov]]'s [[Three Laws of Robotics]].\"<ref name=\"AV Club\" />\n\nDirector and film critic [[Sudhish Kamath]] called ''Enthiran'' \"a superhero film, a sci-fi adventure, a triangular love story with a hint of the [[Ramayana]]\", while remarking that ''Enthiran''{{'s}} similarities to ''[[The Terminator]]'' (1984) were \"more than obvious. Not just visually\u2014where we see the Superstar with one human eye and one scarred metallic eye but also intentionally spelt out when the bad robot announces that he has created Terminators.\"<ref name=\"man versus machine\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/superstar-wars-man-versus-machines/article836818.ece |title=Superstar Wars: Man versus Machines |last=Kamath |first=Sudhish |date=19 October 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=26 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150126074813/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/superstar-wars-man-versus-machines/article836818.ece |archive-date=26 January 2015}}</ref> Kamath compared two of the film's robots to [[C-3PO]] and [[R2-D2]], [[droid (Star Wars)|droids]] from the ''[[Star Wars]]'' film series, which was referenced in ''Enthiran'' when Vaseegaran refers to one of his creations as \"R2\".<ref name=\"man versus machine\" />\n\nAlthough Shankar initially claimed that ''Enthiran'' would be made for all audiences, including those lacking [[computer literacy]],<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L9kxJN4I1fk |title=Enthiran&nbsp;\u2013 The Robot Will Work in Villages Too: Shankar |date=24 September 2010 |last=Shankar, S. (director) |publisher=[[Rajshri Media]] |place=India |access-date=28 January 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150720013658/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L9kxJN4I1fk |archive-date=20 July 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> the film is influenced by and makes references to many scientific principles relating to the fields of engineering, computer science and robotics, including [[terabyte]]s and Asimov's laws of robotics.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/business-of-bollywood/the-experience-of-first-show-of-a-rajinikanth-film/articleshow/6668088.cms |title=The experience of first show of a Rajinikanth film |last=Balakrishnan |first=Ravi |date=2 October 2010 |work=The Economic Times |access-date=28 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Vuhy4vrt?url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/business-of-bollywood/the-experience-of-first-show-of-a-rajinikanth-film/articleshow/6668088.cms |archive-date=28 January 2015}}</ref> Visual references are made to the [[science book]]s ''[[A Briefer History of Time (Hawking and Mlodinow book)|A Briefer History of Time]]'' (2005) and ''[[Freakonomics]]'' (2005).<ref name=\"R+R\" /> In his book ''Visual Perception and Cultural Memory: Typecast and Typecast(e)ing in Malayalam Cinema'', Sujith Kumar Parayil notes the similarities between Kalabhavan Mani's role in the film to the one Mani played in the [[Malayalam]] film ''[[Sallapam]]'' (1996).<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Parayil |first=Sujith Kumar |year=2014 |title=Visual Perception and Cultural Memory: Typecast and Typecast(e)ing in Malayalam Cinema |url=http://synoptique.hybrid.concordia.ca/index.php/main/article/view/40/50 |url-status=live |format=PDF |journal=Synoptique |pages=75\u201376 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413071441/http://synoptique.hybrid.concordia.ca/index.php/main/article/view/40/50 |archive-date=13 April 2015 |access-date=13 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Music ==\n{{Main|Enthiran (soundtrack)}}\nFor ''Enthiran'''s soundtrack and score, A. R. Rahman made use of the [[Continuum Fingerboard]], an instrument he had experimented with previously in the song \"Rehna Tu\" from [[Rakeysh Omprakash Mehra]]'s [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] ''[[Delhi-6]]'' (2009).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mail-archive.com/arrahmanfans@yahoogroups.com/msg66979.html |title=Rahman uses novel concept for Endhiran |date=7 July 2009 |website=[[Radio City (Indian radio station)|PlanetRadiocity.com]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6i2BRom7m?url=https://www.mail-archive.com/arrahmanfans@yahoogroups.com/msg66979.html |archive-date=5 June 2016 |access-date=5 June 2016}}</ref> The film also marked the debut of Rahman's daughter Khatija as a playback singer.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Repository/getFiles.asp?Style=OliveXLib:LowLevelEntityToPrint_TOI&Type=text/html&Locale=english-skin-custom&Path=TOIBG/2010/08/01&ID=Ar04102 |title=Daughter croons for AR Rahman |date=1 August 2010 |work=The Times of India |access-date=16 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316051521/http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Repository/getFiles.asp?Style=OliveXLib%3ALowLevelEntityToPrint_TOI&Type=text%2Fhtml&Locale=english-skin-custom&Path=TOIBG%2F2010%2F08%2F01&ID=Ar04102 |archive-date=16 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe soundtrack album to ''Enthiran'' was released on 31 July 2010 at the [[Putrajaya International Convention Centre]] in [[Kuala Lumpur]], Malaysia.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/aishwarya-rajnikanth-launch-endhiran-music-615789 |title=Aishwarya, Rajnikanth launch Endhiran music |date=31 July 2010 |work=[[NDTV]] |access-date=24 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150124043033/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/aishwarya-rajnikanth-launch-endhiran-music-615789 |archive-date=24 January 2015 |agency=Press Trust of India}}</ref> The Tamil and Telugu versions were released by Think Music, while the Hindi version was released by Venus Music.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/venus-acquires-hindi-audio-rights-of-endhiran-615772 |title=Venus acquires Hindi audio rights of Endhiran |date=30 July 2010 |work=NDTV |access-date=30 July 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150124043413/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/venus-acquires-hindi-audio-rights-of-endhiran-615772 |archive-date=24 January 2015 |agency=IANS}}</ref> Think Music purchased the release rights of the Tamil and Telugu versions of the album for {{INR}}70&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2011-07-20/news/29795015_1_sony-music-shridhar-subramaniam-endhiran |title=Sony Music buys 146 catalogues of Think Music but loses on Rajinikanth starrer Endhiran's rights |last=Kandavel |first=Sangeetha |date=20 July 2011 |work=The Economic Times |access-date=24 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150124043155/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2011-07-20/news/29795015_1_sony-music-shridhar-subramaniam-endhiran |archive-date=24 January 2015}}</ref>{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}} The album of the film's Telugu version, ''Robo'', was released on 6 August 2010, while its Hindi version, ''Robot'', was released on 14 August 2010.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/ash-down-with-high-fever-gives-endhiran-music-launch-a-miss-615920 |title=Ash down with high fever, gives Endhiran music launch a miss |date=7 August 2010 |work=NDTV |access-date=24 January 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150124054557/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/ash-down-with-high-fever-gives-endhiran-music-launch-a-miss-615920 |archive-date=24 January 2015 |agency=Press Trust of India |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-robot-launch-in-mumbai/20100816.htm |title=When superstar Rajnikanth met superstar Big B |last=Padmanabhan |first=Krishnakumar |date=16 August 2010 |website=Rediff.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150124054705/http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-robot-launch-in-mumbai/20100816.htm |archive-date=24 January 2015 |access-date=24 January 2015}}</ref> After the second day of release, the album's Tamil version reached the number one position in the Top&nbsp;10 World Albums chart on [[iTunes]], making it the first Tamil album to do so.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/article200776.ece |title='Endhiran' tops iTunes chart |last=Narayanan |first=Sharadha |date=4 August 2010 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=24 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150124043426/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/article200776.ece |archive-date=24 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Fells\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/rajini-fells-all-records-with-sci-fi-entertainer-endhiran-110100200074_1.html |title=Rajini fells all records with sci-fi entertainer Endhiran |last=Narasimhan |first=T. E. |date=2 October 2010 |work=[[Business Standard]] |access-date=5 June 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605123527/http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/rajini-fells-all-records-with-sci-fi-entertainer-endhiran-110100200074_1.html |archive-date=5 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\n''Enthiran'' was released on 1 October 2010 in three languages\u2014in Tamil as ''Enthiran'', in Hindi as ''Robot'' and in Telugu as ''Robo''.<ref name=\"CNN Travel\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/enthiran-d-day-is-here-news-tamil-kkgu7Xchbedsi.html |title=''Enthiran''&nbsp;\u2013 D-Day is here! |date=1 October 2010 |website=Sify |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221064709/http://www.sify.com/movies/enthiran-d-day-is-here-news-tamil-kkgu7Xchbedsi.html |archive-date=21 February 2015 |access-date=21 February 2015}}</ref> The original version was in Tamil, while the Hindi and Telugu versions were dubbed.<ref name=\"CNN Travel\" /> The film was released in 2,250&nbsp;theatres worldwide, including 500&nbsp;theatres in Tamil Nadu,<ref name=\"HBLScreens\" /> 350&nbsp;theatres in [[Andhra Pradesh]],<ref name=\"HBLScreens\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/todays-paper/enthiran-curious-audience-optimistic-kollywood/article1005373.ece |title=Enthiran&nbsp;\u2013 curious audience, optimistic Kollywood |last=Ravikumar |first=R. |date=29 September 2010 |work=[[Business Line]] |access-date=21 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121084052/http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/todays-paper/enthiran-curious-audience-optimistic-kollywood/article1005373.ece |archive-date=21 January 2015}}</ref> 128&nbsp;theatres in [[Kerala]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/boxoffice.php?id=14957682&cid=2362 |title=''Enthiran'' creates record in Kerala |date=29 September 2010 |website=Sify |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121083015/http://www.sify.com/movies/boxoffice.php?id=14957682&cid=2362 |archive-date=21 January 2015 |access-date=21 January 2015}}</ref> 23&nbsp;theatres in [[Karnataka]], and 750&nbsp;theatres in North India.<ref name=\"Fells\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/enthiran-stalls-new-releases/article811969.ece |title=Enthiran crosses screening limit; Kannada producers irked |date=7 October 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=26 October 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121084058/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/article817325.ece |archive-date=21 January 2015}}</ref> With an estimated budget of {{INR}}1.32{{mdash}}1.62&nbsp;billion,<ref name=\"Q3\" />{{refn|name=budget|group=Note}}{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}} ''Enthiran'' was [[List of most expensive Indian films|India's most expensive film]] up to that point,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/endhiran-the-costliest-film-in-india/1/108599.html |title=Endhiran: The costliest film in India |date=11 August 2010 |work=India Today |access-date=11 August 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203012913/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/endhiran-the-costliest-film-in-india/1/108599.html |archive-date=3 February 2014 |agency=Press Trust of India}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/meet-indias-biggest-film-star-2096273.html |title=Meet India's biggest film star |last=Buncombe |first=Andrew |date=3 October 2010 |work=[[The Independent]] |access-date=3 October 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122065142/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/meet-indias-biggest-film-star-2096273.html |archive-date=22 January 2015}}</ref> surpassing the Hindi film ''[[Blue (2009 film)|Blue]]'' (2009), which was filmed on a budget of {{INR}}750&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-08-10/news/27627378_1_first-film-special-effects-yuen-woo-ping |title=At 150 crore, Rajinikant's Robot costliest ever movie |last=Iyer |first=Meena |date=10 August 2010 |work=The Economic Times |access-date=24 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20141214014845/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-08-10/news/27627378_1_first-film-special-effects-yuen-woo-ping |archive-date=14 December 2014}}</ref>{{refn|The average exchange rate in 2009 was 46.29 Indian rupees ({{INR}}) per 1 US dollar (US$).<ref name=\"ex2010\" />|group=Note}}\n\n''Enthiran'' became the first Tamil film to be released at the [[Colosseum kino]], a [[Norway|Norwegian]] theatre complex in [[Oslo]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/article289735.ece |title='Enthiran's bitter pill to Malayalam cinema |last=Raj K. |first=Rohith |date=10 October 2010 |website=The New Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208085811/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/article289735.ece |archive-date=8 February 2015 |access-date=8 February 2015}}</ref> and it was screened at the 21st&nbsp;[[Bath Film Festival]], held in the United Kingdom in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bathfilmfestival.org.uk/the-robot.html |title=The 21st Bath film festival |publisher=[[Bath Film Festival]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101101081726/http://bathfilmfestival.org.uk/the-robot.html |archive-date=1 November 2010 |access-date=24 November 2011}}</ref> Additionally, a version of the film, edited to a running length of two hours, was released in Japan in May 2012, and later screened at the 24th&nbsp;[[Tokyo International Film Festival]], where it won a special award under the section \"Winds of Asia\u2013Middle East\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://2011.tiff-jp.net/en/lineup/works.php?id=108 |title=Winds of Asia-Middle East&nbsp;\u2013 Film Panorama of Asia-Middle East: The Robot |publisher=[[Tokyo International Film Festival]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121090417/http://2011.tiff-jp.net/en/lineup/works.php?id=108 |archive-date=21 January 2015 |access-date=2 November 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"TIFF\">{{Cite web |url=http://2011.tiff-jp.net/en/tiff/awards.html |title=24th Tokyo International Film Festival&nbsp;\u2013 List of Winners |publisher=Tokyo International Film Festival |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121094438/http://2011.tiff-jp.net/en/tiff/awards.html |archive-date=21 January 2015 |access-date=21 January 2015}}</ref> By public demand, the original, unedited version was later released in that country.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/rajinikants-robot-becomes-a-hit-in-japan-photos-videos-351635 |title=Rajinikant's Robot Becomes a Hit in Japan [PHOTOS & VIDEOS] |last=Mehta |first=Ankita |date=13 June 2012 |website=[[International Business Times]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206154818/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/rajinikants-robot-becomes-a-hit-in-japan-photos-videos-351635 |archive-date=6 February 2015 |access-date=6 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Marketing and distribution ===\nThe first poster for ''Enthiran'' was released on 8 September 2008.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/enthiren-robot-first-look-news-tamil-kkfsWHedhfisi.html |title=Enthiren (Robot)&nbsp;\u2013 First Look! |date=8 September 2008 |publisher=Sify |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605085125/http://www.sify.com/movies/enthiren-robot-first-look-news-tamil-kkfsWHedhfisi.html |archive-date=5 June 2016 |access-date=5 June 2016}}</ref> The film's trailer was released on 11 September 2010, at the [[SPI Cinemas|Sathyam Cinemas]] theatre complex in Chennai.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/news-archive/web/endhiran-trailer-released/ |title=Endhiran trailer released |date=24 September 2010 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121100152/http://indianexpress.com/article/news-archive/web/endhiran-trailer-released/ |archive-date=21 January 2015 |access-date=21 January 2015}}</ref> To promote ''Enthiran'', [[AGS Entertainment]] organised a festival from 25 September 2010 until its release date, in which they screened popular films of Rajinikanth at the company's theatre in [[Villivakkam]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/one-for-the-fans/article791697.ece |title=One for the fans |date=24 September 2010 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=8 February 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208044841/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/one-for-the-fans/article791697.ece |archive-date=8 February 2015}}</ref> In Coimbatore, the [[India Post|Department of Posts]] printed 100,000&nbsp;post cards advertising the film.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/endhiran-advertisement-on-post-cards/article799913.ece |title=Endhiran advertisement on post cards |date=28 September 2010 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=8 February 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208044846/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/endhiran-advertisement-on-post-cards/article799913.ece |archive-date=8 February 2015}}</ref> Sun Pictures invested a total of {{INR}}500&nbsp;million on promotional activities.<ref name=\"R+R\" />{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}}\n\nAdvance bookings for the film began two weeks before the release date in the United States. In the [[Jackson Heights, Queens|Jackson Heights]] neighbourhood in New York, tickets were sold out within ten minutes of going on sale.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/news-archive/web/endhiran-makes-news-even-before-release/ |title=Endhiran makes news even before release |last=Nivas |first=Namita |date=1 October 2010 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121100802/http://indianexpress.com/article/news-archive/web/endhiran-makes-news-even-before-release/ |archive-date=21 January 2015 |access-date=21 January 2015}}</ref> In Kerala the distribution rights were sold for {{INR}}50&nbsp;million,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/article209164.ece |title=Malayalam rights of 'Endhiran' sets record |date=28 August 2010 |website=The New Indian Express |publisher=Sampurn Wire |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121080239/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/article209164.ece |archive-date=21 January 2015 |access-date=21 January 2015}}</ref>{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}} while in Karnataka they were sold for {{INR}}100&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bangaloremirror.com/index.aspx?Page=article&sectname=News%20-%20City&sectid=10&contentid=2010092520100925051125158c0163429 |title=Enthiran will singe you |last=Prasad |first=Shyam |date=25 September 2010 |website=Bangalore Mirror |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707213303/http://bangaloremirror.com/index.aspx?Page=article&sectname=News%20-%20City&sectid=10&contentid=2010092520100925051125158c0163429 |archive-date=7 July 2011 |access-date=24 December 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref>{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}} The distribution rights in Mumbai were sold to Shringar Films.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-10-04/news/27624325_1_box-office-anjaana-anjaani-occupancies |title=Robot, Anjaana Anjaani sweep box office |last=Sheikh |first=Aminah |date=4 October 2010 |website=The Economic Times |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130126024710/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-10-04/news/27624325_1_box-office-anjaana-anjaani-occupancies |archive-date=26 January 2013 |access-date=5 June 2016}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, ''Enthiran'' was released by Ayngaran International, while ''Robot'' was released by [[B4U (network)|B4U Network]].<ref name=\"Tamil version runtime\" /> DVD marketing in India was handled by [[Moser Baer]];<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.flipkart.com/endhiran/p/itmdgyahufaytfhh?pid=AVMDGY9Y6P2RHTKK&otracker=from-search&srno=t_1&query=endhiran&ref=18d2e162-a197-461c-9b97-f2efd7a691b1 |title=Endhiran (Movie, DVD) |publisher=[[Flipkart]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150130155109/http://www.flipkart.com/endhiran/p/itmdgyahufaytfhh?pid=AVMDGY9Y6P2RHTKK&otracker=from-search&srno=t_1&query=endhiran&ref=18d2e162-a197-461c-9b97-f2efd7a691b1 |archive-date=30 January 2015 |access-date=30 January 2015}}</ref> Ayngaran International released the two-DVD set of the film in early&nbsp;2011.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Endhiran-2-DVD-Special-Edition/dp/B004L2FCOW |title=Endhiran 2 DVD Special Edition |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808143758/http://www.amazon.com/Endhiran-2-DVD-Special-Edition/dp/B004L2FCOW |archive-date=8 August 2014 |access-date=30 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Plagiarism allegations ===\nThe novelist Aarur Thamizhnadan made a complaint with the [[Chennai Metropolitan Police]] against the filmmakers in November 2010, stating that the producers plagiarised his 1996&nbsp;novel ''Jugiba''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article/Chennai-Corner/267919 |title=Chennai Corner&nbsp;\u2013 So who wrote Endhiran? |last=Iyengar |first=Pushpa |date=11 November 2010 |website=Outlook |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122035951/http://www.outlookindia.com/article/Chennai-Corner/267919 |archive-date=22 January 2015 |access-date=22 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/kollywood/scribe-stakes-claim-enthiran-story-743 |title=Scribe stakes claim to Enthiran story |date=28 May 2011 |website=[[Deccan Chronicle]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110530010555/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/kollywood/scribe-stakes-claim-enthiran-story-743 |archive-date=30 May 2011 |access-date=15 December 2011}}</ref> Thamizhnadan demanded {{INR}}10&nbsp;million{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}} from the director and producers for damages and filed a case against Kalanithi Maran.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/plea-to-restrain-screening-of-enthiran/article877295.ece |title=Plea to restrain screening of 'Enthiran' |date=10 November 2010 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=22 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122054356/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/plea-to-restrain-screening-of-enthiran/article877295.ece |archive-date=22 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"EPMHC\">{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/HC-stay-on-case-against-Kalanithi/articleshow/8794646.cms |title=HC stay on case against Kalanithi |date=10 June 2011 |website=The Times of India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6X2XSIrYu?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/HC-stay-on-case-against-Kalanithi/articleshow/8794646.cms |archive-date=15 March 2015 |access-date=15 March 2015}}</ref> In June 2011, the [[Madras High Court]] dismissed the case after a petition filed by Maran denying the allegation was approved.<ref name=\"EPMHC\" />\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Box office ===\nThe daily newspaper ''[[Business Line]]'' reported that ''Enthiran'' grossed {{INR}}580&nbsp;million from all versions in the opening weekend,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/todays-paper/tp-marketing/bollywood-buoyant-as-q3-opens-on-positive-note/article1005838.ece |title=Bollywood buoyant as Q3 opens on positive note |last=Bhat |first=Varada |date=4 October 2010 |website=Business Line |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206082026/http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/todays-paper/tp-marketing/bollywood-buoyant-as-q3-opens-on-positive-note/article1005838.ece |archive-date=6 February 2015 |access-date=4 October 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref>{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}} and ''[[The Economic Times]]'' stated it netted {{INR}}1.17&nbsp;billion by the end of its opening week.<ref name=\"first week\">{{Cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-10-09/news/27593126_1_film-collection-endhiran |title=Rs 117 cr in just 7 days, 'Robot' Rajini smashes all records |last=Dubey |first=Bharati |date=9 October 2010 |work=The Economic Times |access-date=9 October 2010 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130126032109/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-10-09/news/27593126_1_film-collection-endhiran |archive-date=26 January 2013 |url-status=bot: unknown}}</ref>{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}} According to a February 2015 report by ''Hindustan Times'', the film has grossed \u20b92.56 billion worldwide in its lifetime.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/vikram-s-i-crosses-rs-200-crore-mark-eyeing-endhiran-record/story-yiOmxaPA0HSNn8v8s3T1mK.html |title=Vikram's I crosses Rs 200 crore mark, eyes Enthiran record |date=4 February 2015 |website=Hindustan Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919134414/http://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/vikram-s-i-crosses-rs-200-crore-mark-eyeing-endhiran-record/story-yiOmxaPA0HSNn8v8s3T1mK.html |archive-date=19 September 2016 |access-date=19 September 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Indo-Asian News Service]] stated in July 2015 that the film grossed \u20b92.90 billion from both its original and its dubbed versions.<ref name=\"2.90 billion\">{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/regional/ss-rajamoulis-baahubali-enters-rs-300-crore-club/ |title=SS Rajamouli's Baahubali enters RS 300 crore club |date=19 July 2015 |website=The Indian Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919134359/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/regional/ss-rajamoulis-baahubali-enters-rs-300-crore-club/ |archive-date=19 September 2016 |access-date=19 September 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}} ''Enthiran'' became the top-earning Indian film of 2010 ahead of ''[[My Name Is Khan]]'' and ''[[Dabangg]]'' and became the [[list of highest-grossing Tamil films|highest-grossing Tamil film of all time]] at that point.<ref name=\"worldwide gross\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=2171&nCat=box_office_news |title=Endhiran&nbsp;\u2013 The Robot Expected Lifetime Business |date=1 November 2010 |publisher=[[Box Office India]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104233643/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=2171&nCat=box_office_news |archive-date=4 November 2010 |access-date=6 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/i-mints-184-crore-12-days-worldwide-box-office-collections-621620 |title='I' Mints \u20b9184 Crore in 12 Days in Worldwide Box Office Collections |last=Upadhyaya |first=Prakash |date=27 January 2015 |website=International Business Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206083044/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/i-mints-184-crore-12-days-worldwide-box-office-collections-621620 |archive-date=6 February 2015 |access-date=6 February 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs of January 2018, ''Enthiran'' is the [[List of highest-grossing Tamil films|fourth-highest-grossing]] [[Cinema of South India|South Indian film]] of all time after ''[[Baahubali 2: The Conclusion]]'' (2017), ''[[Baahubali: The Beginning]]'' (2015),<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2017/05/baahubali-2-the-conclusion-record-box-office-india-imax-north-america-worldwide-prabhas-1202079770/ |title='Baahubali 2' Becomes All-Time No. 1 Indian Film At Worldwide Box Office |last=Tartaglione |first=Nancy |date=5 May 2017 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170505171227/http://deadline.com/2017/05/baahubali-2-the-conclusion-record-box-office-india-imax-north-america-worldwide-prabhas-1202079770/ |archive-date=5 May 2017 |access-date=5 May 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/baahubali-beats-endhirans-lifetime-box-office-record-639747 |title=2nd Saturday Box Office Collection: Baahubali Beats Endhiran's Lifetime Record in 9 Days |last=H. Hooli |first=Shekhar |date=19 July 2015 |website=International Business Times |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6aB2A1IPn?url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/baahubali-beats-endhirans-lifetime-box-office-record-639747 |archive-date=21 July 2015 |access-date=21 July 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> and ''[[Kabali (film)|Kabali]]'' (2016).<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/kabali-has-had-the-biggestever-opening-for-a-tamil-film/article8921554.ece |title='Magizhchi' at the box-office |last=Pillai |first=Sreedhar |date=30 July 2016 |work=The Hindu |access-date=31 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160731061021/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/kabali-has-had-the-biggestever-opening-for-a-tamil-film/article8921554.ece |archive-date=31 July 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Box Office India]] estimated that ''Enthiran'' netted {{INR}}1.95&nbsp;billion across India with the Tamil version netting {{INR}}1.20&nbsp;billion, the Telugu version netting {{INR}}530&nbsp;million and the Hindi version netting {{INR}}220&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2189 |title=Kabali Set To Be Biggest Tamil Grosser |date=27 July 2016 |publisher=Box Office India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727095155/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2189 |archive-date=27 July 2016 |access-date=27 July 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2187 |title=Kabali (Hindi) And Madaari Are Low On Monday |publisher=Box Office India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727095208/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2187 |archive-date=27 July 2016 |access-date=27 July 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}} The website estimated the overseas earnings of the film (including its dubbed versions) at approximately $12 million as of November 2010 with the Tamil version grossing $11 million and the remaining $1 million coming in from the Telugu and Hindi versions.<ref name=\"worldwide gross\" /> ''Enthiran'' collected {{INR}}1.05&nbsp;billion in Tamil Nadu alone,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/baahubali-2-bahubali-2-tamil-nadu-box-office-collection-ss-rajamoulis-film-inching-towards-rs-727904 |title=Baahubali 2 (Bahubali 2) Tamil Nadu box office collection: SS Rajamouli's film inching towards Rs. 125 crore-mark |last=Upadhyaya |first=Prakash |date=24 May 2017 |website=International Business Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525093647/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/baahubali-2-bahubali-2-tamil-nadu-box-office-collection-ss-rajamoulis-film-inching-towards-rs-727904 |archive-date=25 May 2017 |access-date=25 May 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}} a record it held for seven years before being surpassed by ''[[Baahubali 2: The Conclusion]]'' (2017), which grossed {{INR}}1.526&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/baahubali-2-bahubali-2-box-office-collection-ss-rajamoulis-film-mints-rs-1706-50-cr-140-days-742747 |title=Baahubali 2 (Bahubali 2) box office collection: SS Rajamouli's film mints Rs 1,706.50 cr in 140 days |last=Upadhyaya |first=Prakash |date=20 September 2017 |work=[[International Business Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023011833/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/baahubali-2-bahubali-2-box-office-collection-ss-rajamoulis-film-mints-rs-1706-50-cr-140-days-742747 |archive-date=23 October 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}}\n\nIn Japan, the film grossed $407,438, including $370,697 for the Hindi version and $36,741 for the Tamil version.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/trends/entertainment/japans-love-for-indian-films-continues-to-rise-3505491.html |title=Japan's love for Indian films continues to rise |date=9 February 2019 |work=[[Moneycontrol]] |access-date=9 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209095056/https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/trends/entertainment/japans-love-for-indian-films-continues-to-rise-3505491.html |archive-date=9 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Critical response ===\n==== India ====\n''Enthiran'' received positive reviews from critics in India, with praise particularly directed at Rathnavelu's cinematography, Cyril's art direction, Srinivas Mohan's visual effects and Rajinikanth's performance as Chitti.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/critics-give-a-thumbs-up-to-endhiran/story-o1InoBdTUUJ7tpF1Xtcl8K.html |title=Critics give a thumbs up to Endhiran |date=1 October 2010 |work=Hindustan Times |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150127100230/http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/critics-give-a-thumbs-up-to-endhiran/article1-606784.aspx |archive-date=27 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2010/10/01/review-round-up-endhiranrobot/ |title=Review Round-Up: 'Endhiran'/'Robot' |last=Agarwal |first=Vibhuti |date=1 October 2010 |work=The Wall Street Journal |access-date=29 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6VwPqteUr?url=http://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2010/10/01/review-round-up-endhiranrobot/ |archive-date=29 January 2015}}</ref> Aniruddha Guha of ''[[Daily News and Analysis]]'' gave the film a rating of four out of five stars and believed it had the \"best special effects ever seen in a Tamil film\" and that it was \"one of the most entertaining Tamil films\u2014across all languages\u2014ever made.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/review-review-robot-endhiran-is-an-indian-film-to-be-proud-of-1446033 |title=Robot (Endhiran) is an Indian film to be proud of |last=Guha |first=Aniruddha |date=1 October 2010 |work=[[Daily News and Analysis]] |access-date=1 October 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123151434/http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/review-review-robot-endhiran-is-an-indian-film-to-be-proud-of-1446033 |archive-date=23 January 2015}}</ref> Both [[Nikhat Kazmi]] of ''The Times of India'' and Kaveree Bamzai of ''[[India Today]]'' rated the film four out of five stars. Kazmi called it \"the perfect getaway film\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/movie-reviews/hindi/Robot/movie-review/6658514.cms |title=Robot Review |last=Kazmi |first=Nikhat |date=30 September 2010 |work=The Times of India |access-date=1 October 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6W5oOH49J?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-review/Robot/movie-review/6658514.cms |archive-date=4 February 2015 |author-link=Nikhat Kazmi}}</ref> Bamzai praised Rajinikanth's acting in the film and said, \"Rajni tells us why robot sapiens are superior to [[homo sapiens]]\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/film-review-endhiran/1/114755.html |title=Film review: Endhiran |last=Bamzai |first=Kaveree |date=1 October 2010 |work=India Today |access-date=9 July 2011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204095812/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/film-review-endhiran/1/114755.html |archive-date=4 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nBoth [[Anupama Chopra]] of [[NDTV]] and Pavithra Srinivasan of Rediff.com gave ''Enthiran'' a rating of three-and-a-half stars out of five. Chopra criticised the film's portions in the second half, describing them as \"needlessly stretched and cacophonous\",<ref name=\"Chopra\">{{Cite web |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/movie-reviews/review-robot-551 |title=Review: Robot |last=Chopra |first=Anupama |authorlink=Anupama Chopra |date=1 October 2010 |website=NDTV |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204151648/http://movies.ndtv.com/movie-reviews/review-robot-551 |archive-date=4 February 2015 |access-date=1 October 2010}}</ref> but concluded her review by saying, \"''Robot'' rides on Rajinikanth's shoulders and he never stoops under the burden. Aided by snazzy clothes, make-up and special effects, he makes Chitti endearing.\"<ref name=\"Chopra\" /> Srinivasan, however, said that Shankar \"strikes the balance between science fiction and masala quotient.\"<ref name=\"PRrediff\" /> She concluded that, \"Whichever way you look at it, {{sic|''Endhiran''|nolink=y}} is one of those rare films that give you just enough material to pull you in, and enjoy yourself.\"<ref name=\"PRrediff\">{{Cite web |url=http://movies.rediff.com/review/2010/oct/01/south-tamil-review-endhiran.htm |title=Shankar, Rajinikanth make Endhiran work |last=Srinivasan |first=Pavithra |date=1 October 2010 |website=Rediff.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204094855/http://movies.rediff.com/review/2010/oct/01/south-tamil-review-endhiran.htm |archive-date=4 February 2015 |access-date=9 July 2011}}</ref> [[Rajeev Masand]] of [[CNN-News18]] gave a rating of three out of five stars and said, \"In the end, it's the fantastic special effects and an inspired performance from {{sic|Rajnikant|nolink=y}} that keeps the film fresh.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/masand-robot-is-an-adventure-waiting-for-you/132161-47-84.html |title='Robot' is an adventure waiting for you |last=Masand |first=Rajeev |authorlink=Rajeev Masand |date=8 October 2010 |website=CNN-News18 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6W5po6YQx?url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/masand-robot-is-an-adventure-waiting-for-you/132161-47-84.html |archive-date=4 February 2015 |access-date=6 November 2011}}</ref> [[Mayank Shekhar]], writing for ''Hindustan Times'', rated it three stars and said, \"Leave aside jokes running on the Internet. This film, just a few feet too long, is fine entertainment by itself.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/movie-reviews/mayank-shekhar-s-review-robot/story-QvlgAwwSQRpAbqpE5utmRO.html |title=Mayank Shekhar's Review: Robot |last=Shekhar |first=Mayank |date=4 October 2010 |work=Hindustan Times |access-date=22 September 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922090833/http://www.hindustantimes.com/movie-reviews/mayank-shekhar-s-review-robot/story-QvlgAwwSQRpAbqpE5utmRO.html |archive-date=22 September 2017 |author-link=Mayank Shekhar}}</ref>\n\nMalini Mannath of ''The New Indian Express'' noted ''Enthiran'' for having \"An engaging script, brilliant special effects, and a debonair hero who still carries his charisma effortlessly.\"<ref name=\"malini\" /> Karthik Subramanian of ''The Hindu'' observed that actors \"tend to get lost in special effects movies.\" He believed it was not the case in ''Enthiran'': \"Rajinikanth and [Aishwarya Rai] carry the movie on their shoulders, and considering the fact that much of the acting must have been in front of green screens, one has to say that nothing looks artificial right through.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/unabashed-entertainer/article807284.ece |title=Unabashed entertainer |last=Subramanian |first=Karthik |date=1 October 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=1 August 2011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204094450/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/unabashed-entertainer/article807284.ece |archive-date=4 February 2015}}</ref> In contrast, Gautaman Bhaskaran of ''Hindustan Times'' rated it two out of five stars, writing that \"Shankar's work slips into a loud, overdramatic and exaggerated mess\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/gautaman-bhaskaran-s-review-endhiran/story-ENP80sXGeoKJxuITEAdiyN.html |title=Gautaman Bhaskaran's Review: Endhiran |last=Bhaskaran |first=Gautaman |date=1 October 2010 |work=Hindustan Times |access-date=26 October 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204100758/http://www.hindustantimes.com/regional/gautaman-bhaskaran-s-review-endhiran/article1-606907.aspx |archive-date=4 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== Overseas ====\n''Enthiran'' has received a rating of 67%&nbsp;on the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], based on twelve reviews, with an average rating of 5.62/10.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/endhiran/ |title=Endhiran (2010) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |access-date=30 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160719052215/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/endhiran/ |archive-date=19 July 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lisa Tsering from ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' said, \"Rajinikanth is such a badass that [[Chuck Norris]] is [[Chuck Norris facts|afraid of him]].\"<ref name=\"LSHR\" /> She praised the filming locations, especially the \"Kilimanjaro\" song sequence, but criticised the length of the film's climax portions.<ref name=\"LSHR\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/robot-film-review-30163 |title=Robot&nbsp;\u2013 Film Review |last=Tsering |first=Lisa |date=14 October 2010 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=1 August 2011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205164503/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/robot-film-review-30163 |archive-date=5 February 2015}}</ref> Genevieve Koski from ''The A. V. Club'' believed that ''Enthiran'' was \"pretty good\" and concluded that \"if you prefer elaborate costumes and dance music mixed in with your killer-robot action, expect to enjoy up to an hour of ''Enthiran''.\"<ref name=\"AV Club\" /> Marc Savlov of ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]'' called ''Enthiran'' \"the best apocalyptic sci-fi-romcom-melodrama-dance-off date movie of the year.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/calendar/film/2011-02-25/endhiran-the-robot/ |title=Endhiran (Robot) |last=Savlov |first=Marc |date=25 February 2011 |work=[[The Austin Chronicle]] |access-date=6 February 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206072711/http://www.austinchronicle.com/calendar/film/2011-02-25/endhiran-the-robot/ |archive-date=6 February 2015}}</ref> Roger Moore, writing for the ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]'', gave a mixed review, evaluating it as a \"melodramatic kitschy Indian musical about a robot built for national defense but who discovers his human side.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blogs.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment_movies_blog/2010/10/movie-review-endhiran.html |title=Movie Review: Endhiran |last=Moore |first=Roger |date=7 October 2010 |website=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101013034935/http://blogs.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment_movies_blog/2010/10/movie-review-endhiran.html |archive-date=13 October 2010 |access-date=21 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the film's screening at the [[Mumbai International Film Festival]], American film director [[Oliver Stone]] praised ''Enthiran''{{'s}} originality.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SaabAwAAQBAJ |title=Grand Brand Rajini |last=Balasubramanianram |first=P. C. |last2=Ramakrishnan |first2=N. |publisher=Rupa Publications |year=2012 |isbn=978-81-291-2059-5 |pages=79 |ref=harv}}</ref> Conversely, [[Joe Leydon]] of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' believed that Shankar \"riffs on everything\" from ''Frankenstein'' to ''The Terminator'', but suggested that the film was an \"overwhelming mash-up of American-style, f/x-driven sci-fi spectacle and a Bollywood musical.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2010/film/reviews/endhiran-the-robot-1117943809/ |title=Review: 'Endhiran&nbsp;\u2013 The Robot' |last=Leydon |first=Joe |authorlink=Joe Leydon |date=8 October 2010 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131223083911/http://variety.com/2010/film/reviews/endhiran-the-robot-1117943809 |archive-date=23 December 2013 |access-date=20 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{{Main|List of accolades received by Enthiran}}\nAt the [[58th National Film Awards]], ''Enthiran'' won for [[National Film Award for Best Special Effects|Best Special Effects]] and [[National Film Award for Best Production Design|Best Production Design]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://dff.nic.in/awards.asp |title=58th National Film Awards for 2010 announced |website=Directorate of Film Festivals |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131230233408/http://dff.nic.in/awards.asp |archive-date=30 December 2013 |access-date=19 May 2011}}</ref> It won in three categories at the [[58th Filmfare Awards South]] for [[Filmfare Award for Best Cinematographer&nbsp;\u2013 South|Best Cinematographer]], [[Filmfare Award for Best Art Director&nbsp;\u2013 South|Best Art Director]] and Best Costume Design.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ndtv.com/photos/entertainment/58th-south-filmfare-awards-winners-10839/slide/21 |title=58th Idea Filmfare Awards South winners |website=[[NDTV]] |pages=21, 22, 23 27, 28, 30 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122121638/http://www.ndtv.com/photos/entertainment/58th-south-filmfare-awards-winners-10839/slide/21 |archive-date=22 January 2015 |access-date=27 May 2012}}</ref> At the [[5th Vijay Awards]], it was nominated in fourteen categories and won in seven, including [[Vijay Award for Best Villain|Best Villain]] and [[Vijay Award for Favourite Hero|Favourite Hero]] for Rajinikanth, [[Vijay Award for Favourite Film|Favourite Film]] and [[Vijay Award for Favourite Director|Favourite Director]].<ref name=\"Vijay\">{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cl0sMfvSm_M |title=Vijay Awards 07/15/11 |date=6 June 2012 |publisher=[[YouTube]] |place=[[Chennai]] |access-date=11 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921063254/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cl0sMfvSm_M |archive-date=21 September 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> At the [[Screen Awards|17th Screen Awards]], the film won awards under the [[Screen Award for Best Special Effects|Best Special Effects]] and Spectacular Cutting Edge Technology categories.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/features/type/view/id/1748/ |title=Winners of 17th Annual Star Screen Awards 2011 |date=6 January 2011 |website=[[Bollywood Hungama]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150126105906/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/features/type/view/id/1748/ |archive-date=26 January 2015 |access-date=7 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nIn a personal appreciation letter to Shankar following the film's release, the director [[K. Balachander]] described Shankar as India's [[James Cameron]], ''Enthiran'' as India's ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]'' (2009) and Sun Pictures as India's [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]].<ref name=\"letter\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/oct-10-03/k-balachander-endhiran-shankar-15-10-10.html |title=\"Kamalhaasan sent me flowers\"&nbsp;\u2013 Shankar |date=15 October 2010 |website=Behindwoods |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204155915/http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/oct-10-03/k-balachander-endhiran-shankar-15-10-10.html |archive-date=4 February 2015 |access-date=19 May 2011}}</ref> ''Enthiran'' was the only Tamil film featured on the [[IMDb|Internet Movie Database]] (IMDb) list of the 50&nbsp;best films of 2010.<ref name=\"Facts\">{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/Rajinikanth-Lesser-known-facts/photostory/34830196.cms |title=Rajinikanth: Lesser known facts&nbsp;\u2013 Page 7 |website=The Times of India |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6W5sfb5uy?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/Rajinikanth-Lesser-known-facts/photostory/34830196.cms |archive-date=4 February 2015 |access-date=4 February 2015}}</ref> The film was also included as a case study in a postgraduate elective course of the [[Indian Institute of Management Ahmedabad]], \"Contemporary Film Industry: A Business Perspective\".<ref name=\"Facts\" />\n\nScenes from ''Enthiran'', particularly one known as the \"Black Sheep\" scene,{{refn|The \"Black Sheep\" scene refers to a scene where Chitti finds Dr. Vaseegaran disguised as him amidst the robot army.<ref name=\"Behind\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/magazine/article289615.ece |title=Why you should watch Endhiran |last=Gunasekaran |first=Ranjitha |date=10 October 2010 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=6 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206165657/http://www.newindianexpress.com/magazine/article289615.ece |archive-date=6 February 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>|group=Note}} have been parodied in subsequent films, including ''[[Mankatha]]'' (2011),<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Mankatha |date=2011 |last=[[Venkat Prabhu|Prabhu, Venkat]] (director) |publisher=[[Cloud Nine Movies]] |place=India |time=45:12 |medium=motion picture}}</ref><ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Mankatha |date=2011 |last=[[Venkat Prabhu|Prabhu, Venkat]] (director) |publisher=[[Cloud Nine Movies]] |place=India |time=2:17:26 |medium=motion picture}}</ref> ''[[Osthe]]'' (2011),<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Osthe |date=2011 |last=[[Dharani (director)|Dharani]] (director) |publisher=Balaji Real Media |place=India |time=2:01:16 |medium=motion picture}}</ref> ''[[Singam II]]'' (2013),<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Singam II |date=2013 |last=[[Hari (director)|Hari]] (director) |publisher=Prince Pictures |place=India |time=14:25 |medium=motion picture}}</ref>  ''[[Ya Ya (film)|Ya Ya]]'' (2013),<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Ya Ya|date=2013 |last=I. Rajasekaran (director) |publisher=M10 Productions |place=India |time=53:13 |medium=motion picture}}</ref>  as well as in the Telugu films ''[[Dookudu]]'' (2011) and ''[[Nuvva Nena]]'' (2011).<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Dookudu |date=2011 |last=[[Srinu Vaitla|Vaitla, Srinu]] (director) |publisher=[[14 Reels Entertainment]] |place=India |time=1:43:02 |medium=motion picture}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/old-wine-same-old-bottle/article3007871.ece |title=Old wine, same old bottle |last=Dundoo |first=Sangeetha Devi |date=18 March 2012 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122041218/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/old-wine-same-old-bottle/article3007871.ece |archive-date=22 January 2015}}</ref>{{refn|The satellite rights of ''Mankatha'', ''Osthe'' and ''Singam II'' were purchased by Sun TV.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/k-family-unites-to-release-mankatha-news-tamil-lizkKhjibjesi.html |title=K&nbsp;\u2013 Family unites to release ''Mankatha'' |date=26 August 2011 |publisher=Sify |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150314135235/http://www.sify.com/movies/k-family-unites-to-release-mankatha-news-tamil-lizkKhjibjesi.html |archive-date=14 March 2015 |access-date=14 March 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/osthi-all-clear-for-dec-8-release-imagegallery-kollywood-lmfpb5aabfisi.html |title=''Osthi'', all clear for Dec 8 release |website=Sify |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150314135338/http://www.sify.com/movies/osthi-all-clear-for-dec-8-release-imagegallery-kollywood-lmfpb5aabfisi.html |archive-date=14 March 2015 |access-date=14 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/Sun-TV-Grabs-Rights-for-Anjaan/2014/05/01/article2198491.ece |title=Sun TV Grabs Rights for Anjaan |date=1 May 2014 |website=The New Indian Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605113455/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/Sun-TV-Grabs-Rights-for-Anjaan/2014/05/01/article2198491.ece |archive-date=5 June 2016 |access-date=5 June 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>|group=Note}} In the film, Chitti often introduces himself by stating the [[clock rate]] of his [[central processing unit]], which is 1&nbsp;terahertz (10<sup>12</sup> [[hertz]]), and his [[random-access memory]] limit, which is 1&nbsp;zettabyte (10<sup>21</sup> [[byte]]s). This introduction dialogue, which is spoken by Chitti as \"Hi, I'm Chitti, speed 1&nbsp;terahertz, memory 1&nbsp;zettabyte\" became popular.<ref name=\"Clone\" /><ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l2RPAk2Tipw |title=Chitti meets G.One sequence&nbsp;\u2013 RA.One |date=5 January 2012 |last=Kareena Kapoor, Rajinikanth, Shah Rukh Khan |publisher=[[Eros International|Eros Now]] |place=India |access-date=25 February 2015 |medium=Motion picture |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150914034010/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l2RPAk2Tipw |archive-date=14 September 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Rajinikanth featured in a cameo role as Chitti in the science-fiction film ''[[Ra.One]]'' (2011).<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/rajnikanth-plays-chitti-the-robot-in-srks-ra-one/article2511736.ece |title=Rajnikanth plays Chitti&nbsp;\u2013 the robot in SRK's \"Ra. One\" |date=4 October 2011 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122041225/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/rajnikanth-plays-chitti-the-robot-in-srks-ra-one/article2511736.ece |archive-date=22 January 2015 |agency=Press Trust of India}}</ref>\n\nOn Rajinikanth's 64th birthday, an agency named Minimal Kollywood Posters designed posters of Rajinikanth's films, in which the [[Despicable Me (franchise)#Minions|Minion]] characters from the ''[[Despicable Me (franchise)|Despicable Me]]'' franchise are dressed as Rajinikanth.<ref name=\"Minions\" /> The digital art was hand drawn on a digital pad by Gautham Raj.<ref name=\"Minions\" /> One of the posters depicted a mutated Minion, reminiscent of Chitti's \"villain robot\" look in ''Enthiran''.<ref name=\"Minions\">{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/Superstar-Rajinikanth-as-Minions/photostory/45519505.cms |title=Superstar Rajinikanth as Minions&nbsp;\u2013 Enthiran (2010) |last=Prasad |first=Shiva |date=15 December 2014 |website=The Times of India |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6XC9ugLHl?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/Superstar-Rajinikanth-as-Minions/photostory/45519505.cms |archive-date=21 March 2015 |access-date=21 March 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2015, Kamath, in his review of the science fiction film ''[[Chappie (film)|Chappie]]'', compared its eponymous lead character to Chitti in terms of learning human emotions.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-reviews/chappie-chittis-hollywood-cousin/article6993688.ece |title=Chappie: Chitti's Hollywood cousin |last=Kamath |first=Sudhish |date=14 March 2015 |work=The Hindu |access-date=30 March 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150330064030/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-reviews/chappie-chittis-hollywood-cousin/article6993688.ece |archive-date=30 March 2015}}</ref> [[Russo brothers|Joe Russo]], who co-directed ''[[Avengers: Infinity War]]'' (2018), said the sequence in ''Enthiran'' where numerous clones of Chitti come together to form a giant snake inspired a similar scene in ''Infinity War''{{'}}s predecessor ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron|Age of Ultron]]'' (2015) where the titular antagonist, [[Ultron]] and his clones come together to form a gigantic version of himself, but that the scene was cut from the final version of the film to accommodate its runtime.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://scroll.in/reel/918568/what-to-expect-as-the-countdown-to-avengers-endgame-begins-the-cost-of-being-a-hero |title=What to expect as the countdown to 'Avengers: Endgame' begins: 'The cost of being a hero' |last=Raman |first=Sruthi Ganapathy |date=1 April 2019 |work=[[Scroll.in]] |access-date=2 April 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402140056/https://scroll.in/reel/918568/what-to-expect-as-the-countdown-to-avengers-endgame-begins-the-cost-of-being-a-hero |archive-date=2 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/hollywood/avengers-endgame-director-joe-russo-confirms-marvel-is-talking-to-priyanka-chopra-about-future-project/story-Ty0qzYYZeLzZgQ8xWFchCM.html |title=Avengers: Endgame director Joe Russo confirms he is 'talking to Priyanka Chopra' about future project |last=Naahar |first=Rohan |date=1 April 2019 |work=Hindustan Times |access-date=2 April 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402135840/https://www.hindustantimes.com/hollywood/avengers-endgame-director-joe-russo-confirms-marvel-is-talking-to-priyanka-chopra-about-future-project/story-Ty0qzYYZeLzZgQ8xWFchCM.html |archive-date=2 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Standalone sequel ==\n{{Main|2.0 (film)}}\nIn September 2015, writer [[B. Jeyamohan]] announced that the pre-production stage of a standalone sequel to ''Enthiran'' was \"going on in full swing\" and that principal photography would commence once Rajinikanth finished filming for ''Kabali'', by the end of that year.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Enthiran-sequel-to-start-filming-by-the-end-of-this-year/articleshow/48773748.cms |title=Enthiran sequel to start filming by the end of this year |last=Sidhardhan |first=Sanjith |date=3 September 2015 |work=The Times of India |access-date=9 September 2015 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6bPO73muw?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Enthiran-sequel-to-start-filming-by-the-end-of-this-year/articleshow/48773748.cms |archive-date=9 September 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Nirav Shah]] would be the cinematographer and A. R. Rahman would return as music director, while Muthuraj would handle the art direction. The sequel would be shot in 3D, unlike its predecessor which was shot in 2D and converted to 3D in post-production.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/rajinikanths-endhiran-2-be-shot-3d-649656 |title=Rajinikanth's 'Endhiran 2' to be shot in 3D |last=Upadhyaya |first=Prakash |date=8 October 2015 |website=International Business Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151012070359/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/rajinikanths-endhiran-2-be-shot-3d-649656 |archive-date=12 October 2015 |access-date=12 October 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> Titled ''2.0'', the film entered production in December 2015 and was released on 29 November 2018. Rajinikanth reprised his role as Vaseegaran and Chitti with the additional cast played by [[Akshay Kumar]] and [[Amy Jackson]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/rajinikanths-vaseegaran-look-enthiran-2-endhiran-revealed-photos-659843 |title=Rajinikanth's Vaseegaran look in 2.0 (Enthiran 2, Endhiran) revealed [PHOTOS] |last=Upadhyaya |first=Prakash |date=17 December 2015 |website=International Business Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151218131706/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/rajinikanths-vaseegaran-look-enthiran-2-endhiran-revealed-photos-659843 |archive-date=18 December 2015 |access-date=18 December 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movie-reviews/2-0/movie-review/66858163.cms |title=2.0 Movie Review |last=Suganth |first=M. |date=29 November 2018 |work=The Times of India |access-date=29 November 2018 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181129130545/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movie-reviews/2-0/movie-review/66858163.cms |archive-date=29 November 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |title=Rajinikanth: The Definitive Biography |title-link=Rajinikanth: The Definitive Biography |last=Ramachandran |first=Naman |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |year=2014 |isbn=978-81-8475-796-5 |edition=2nd |location=New Delhi |ref=harv |author-link=Naman Ramachandran |orig-year=2012}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|1305797|Enthiran}}\n* [https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?id=_fENDHIRAN01 ''Enthiran''] at [[Box Office Mojo]]\n\n{{Portal bar|Film|India}}\n{{Enthiran franchise}}\n{{National Film Award Best Special Effects}}\n{{S. Shankar}}\n\n[[Category:2010 films]]\n[[Category:2010s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:2010s science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:Android (robot) films]]\n[[Category:Films about artificial intelligence]]\n[[Category:Enthiran| ]]\n[[Category:Films directed by S. Shankar]]\n[[Category:Films involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n[[Category:Films scored by A. R. Rahman]]\n[[Category:Films set in Chennai]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 2030s]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Himachal Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Peru]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Special Effects National Film Award]]\n[[Category:Films whose production designer won the Best Production Design National Film Award]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:Robot films]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2010 Tamil film directed by Shankar}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Enthiran\n| image          = Enthiran poster.jpg\n| alt            = Theatrical release poster of the film Enthiran.\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[S. Shankar]]\n| producer       = [[Kalanithi Maran]]\n| writer         = S. Shankar\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Rajinikanth]]\n* [[Aishwarya Rai Bachchan]]\n* [[Danny Denzongpa]]\n}}\n| music          = [[A. R. Rahman]]\n| cinematography = [[R. Rathnavelu]]\n| editing        = [[Anthony (film editor)|Anthony]]\n| studio         = [[Sun Pictures]]\n| distributor    = Sun Pictures\n| released       = {{Film date|2010|10|1|df=y}}\n| runtime        = 166\u2013177 minutes{{refn|The [[British Board of Film Classification]] and [[Amazon.com]] gives the runtime as 166 minutes and 177 minutes respectively.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Enthiran-English-Subtitled-HD-Rajnikanth/dp/B00RA9G2V0 |title=Enthiran (English Subtitled) |publisher=[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122160952/http://www.amazon.com/Enthiran-English-Subtitled-HD-Rajnikanth/dp/B00RA9G2V0 |archive-date=22 January 2015 |access-date=22 January 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Tamil version runtime\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/enthiran-robot-1970-0 |title=ENTHIRAN (12A)&nbsp;\u2013 British Board of Film Classification |publisher=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122063906/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/enthiran-robot-1970-0 |archive-date=22 January 2015 |access-date=14 October 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref>|group=Note}}\n| country        = India<!-- do not link per MOS:OVERLINK -->\n| language       = Tamil\n| budget         = {{Estimation}} {{INR}}1.32{{mdash}}1.62&nbsp;billion{{refn|''[[The Economic Times]]'' claims the film's budget to be {{INR}}1.32&nbsp;million,<ref name=\"Q3\">{{Cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2011-01-28/news/28425591_1_interim-dividend-satellite-rights-enthiran |title=Sun TV Network Q3 Net up 48.40% at Rs 225.49 cr |date=28 January 2011 |work=[[The Economic Times]] |access-date=4 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204082505/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2011-01-28/news/28425591_1_interim-dividend-satellite-rights-enthiran |archive-date=4 February 2015 |publisher=Press Trust of India |url-status=live}}</ref> whereas Anirban Bhattacharya of [[CNN Travel]] and T. S. Sreenivasan Raghavan of ''[[Bangalore Mirror]]'' state that it is {{INR}}1.62&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"CNN Travel\">{{Cite web |url=http://travel.cnn.com/mumbai/play/rajinikanths-robot-end-all-robots-538335/ |title=Rajinikanth's 'Robot' to end all robots |last=Bhattacharya |first=Anirban |date=7 October 2010 |publisher=[[CNN Travel]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605125444/http://travel.cnn.com/mumbai/play/rajinikanths-robot-end-all-robots-538335/ |archive-date=5 June 2016 |access-date=5 June 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://bangaloremirror.indiatimes.com/bangalore/others/chitti-the-robot-delights-tax-officials/articleshow/21756582.cms |title=Chitti, the robot, delights tax officials |last=Raghavan |first=T. S. Sreenivasan |date=22 October 2010 |work=[[Bangalore Mirror]] |access-date=13 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180813085423/https://bangaloremirror.indiatimes.com/bangalore/others/chitti-the-robot-delights-tax-officials/articleshow/21756582.cms |archive-date=13 August 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>|name=budget|group=Note}}\n| gross = <!-- do not add any amount here, since India is notorious for lack of reliable box office info. the supposed gross is listed under \"box office\". -->\n}}\n'''''Enthiran''''' ({{translation|Robot}}) is a 2010&nbsp;Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil]]-language [[science fiction action film]] written and directed by [[S. Shankar]].<ref name=\"AV Club\">{{Cite web |url=https://film.avclub.com/enthiran-1798224462 |title=Enthiran |last=Koski |first=Genevieve |date=3 March 2011 |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123151947/http://www.avclub.com/article/ienthirani-52653 |archive-date=23 January 2015 |access-date=1 August 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> It is the first instalment in the [[Enthiran (film series)|''Enthiran'' franchise]]. The film stars [[Rajinikanth]] and [[Aishwarya Rai Bachchan]] in lead roles; [[Danny Denzongpa]], [[Santhanam (actor)|Santhanam]] and [[Karunas]] play supporting roles. The [[Enthiran (soundtrack)|soundtrack album and background score]] were composed by [[A. R. Rahman]] while the dialogues, cinematography, editing and art direction were handled by [[Madhan Karky]], [[R. Rathnavelu]], [[Anthony (film editor)|Anthony]] and [[Sabu Cyril]] respectively.\n\nThe story revolves around the struggle of a scientist Vaseegaran (played by Rajinikanth) to control his creation, an [[Android (robot)|android]] named [[Chitti (character)|Chitti]] (also played by Rajinikanth), after Chitti's software is upgraded to give it the ability to comprehend and exhibit human emotions. The project backfires when Chitti falls in love with Vaseegaran's girlfriend, Sana (Rai), and is manipulated by Bohra (Denzongpa), a rival scientist, into becoming homicidal.\n\nAfter being stalled in the [[development hell|development]] phase for nearly a decade, the film's principal photography began in 2008 and lasted two years. The film marked the debut of [[Legacy Effects]] studio (which was responsible for the film's [[Facial prosthetic|prosthetic make-up]] and [[animatronics]]) in Indian cinema. ''Enthiran'' was released worldwide on 1 October 2010, along with its [[dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbed]] versions: ''Robot'' in [[Hindi]] and ''Robo'' in [[Telugu language|Telugu]]. Produced by [[Kalanithi Maran]], it was India's [[List of most expensive Indian films|most expensive film]] up to that point.\n\nThe film received generally positive reviews upon release. Critics were particularly appreciative of Rajinikanth's performance as Chitti, Rathnavelu's cinematography, Cyril's art direction and the visual effects by [[V. Srinivas Mohan]]. ''Enthiran'' emerged as the top-earning Indian film of 2010 and is among the [[List of highest-grossing Tamil films|highest-grossing]] [[Cinema of South India|South Indian film]]s of all time. It won two [[National Film Awards|Indian National Film Awards]], three [[Filmfare Awards South|Filmfare Awards]], seven [[Vijay Awards]] and two [[Screen Awards]]. ''Enthiran'' was followed up by its [[Standalone film#Standalone sequel|standalone sequel]], ''[[2.0 (film)|2.0]]'', which released in 2018.\n\n== Plot ==\nAfter a decade of research, the scientist Vaseegaran creates a sophisticated [[android (robot)|android robot]] with the help of his assistants, Siva and Ravi, to commission it into the [[Indian Army]]. He introduces the robot, named [[Chitti (character)|Chitti]], at a robotics conference in [[Chennai]]. Chitti helps Sana, Vaseegaran's [[Medical students|medical student]] girlfriend, cheat in her examination, then saves her from being assaulted by a group of thugs. Vaseegaran's mentor, Professor Bohra, is secretly engaged in a project to create similar android robots for a terrorist organisation, but has so far been unsuccessful.\n\nVaseegaran prepares Chitti for an evaluation by the Artificial Intelligence Research and Development (AIRD) Institute, which is headed by Bohra. During the evaluation, Chitti attempts to stab Vaseegaran at Bohra's command, which convinces the evaluation committee that the robot is a liability and cannot be used for military purposes. Vaseegaran's effort to prove Bohra wrong fails when he deploys Chitti to rescue people from a burning building. The robot saves most of them, including a girl named Selvi who was bathing at the time, but she is ashamed at being seen naked on camera and flees, only to be hit and killed by a truck. Vaseegaran asks for one month to modify Chitti's [[image schema|neural schema]] to enable it to understand human behaviour and emotions, to which Bohra agrees. While nearing the deadline, Chitti becomes angry with Vaseegaran, demonstrating to him that it can manifest emotions.\n\nChitti uses Sana's textbooks to successfully help Sana's sister Latha give birth to a child. Bohra congratulates Vaseegaran on the achievement and allows Chitti to pass the AIRD evaluation. Chitti develops romantic feelings for Sana after she congratulates Chitti by kissing it. When Vaseegaran and Sana realise this, Sana explains to Chitti that they are only friends. Saddened by Sana's rejection, yet still in love with her, Chitti deliberately fails an evaluation conducted by the Indian Army. Enraged, Vaseegaran chops Chitti into pieces, which are dumped by Siva and Ravi into a landfill site.\n\nBohra visits the site to retrieve Chitti, which has now reassembled itself, albeit in a damaged state. Bohra embeds a red chip inside Chitti while reconstructing it, converting it into version 2.0, which is more aggressive and unempathetic. It then gatecrashes Vaseegaran and Sana's wedding, kidnaps Sana, creates replicas of itself, and then kills Bohra. Using its robot army, Chitti occupies AIRD and causes mayhem in the city. After informing Sana that it has acquired the human ability to reproduce, Chitti wishes to marry her so that a machine and a human being can give birth to a preprogrammed child, but Sana refuses. It eventually finds Vaseegaran, who entered AIRD to stop it, and nearly kills him before the police appear. The ensuing battle between Chitti's robot army and the police personnel leads to a lot of property destruction and many casualties. Vaseegaran eventually captures Chitti using a magnetic wall and accesses its internal control panel, whereby he instructs all the other robots to self-destruct. He then removes Chitti's red chip, calming it.\n\nIn a court hearing, Vaseegaran is sentenced to death for the casualties and damages caused by the robot army, but Chitti explains that it was Bohra who caused its deviant behaviour and shows the court video footage of Bohra installing the red chip. The court releases Vaseegaran, while ordering that Chitti be dismantled. Left with no choice, Vaseegaran asks Chitti to dismantle itself. While saying goodbye, Chitti apologises to Vaseegaran and Sana, who forgive it, before dismantling itself.\n\nThe film's setting then shifts to 2030. Chitti is now a museum exhibit. A curious school student on excursion asks her guide why it was dismantled, to which Chitti responds, \"''Naan sinthikka arambichen''\" (''I started thinking'').\n\n== Cast ==\n{{quote box\n| quote = I thought that playing Chitti the robot would be very difficult. He is a machine. His movements should not be like a human being's. We had to draw a line. If I deviated even slightly, Shankar would point it out and say I was being too human. After four to five days of shooting, we found a rhythm.\n| source =\u2014 Rajinikanth, on his experience of playing Chitti.{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|page=227}}\n| align = right\n| width = 35%\n}}\n\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Rajinikanth]] as Vaseegaran and [[Chitti (character)|Chitti]]<ref name=\"OC\">{{Cite AV media |title=Enthiran |date=1 October 2010 |type=motion picture |language=ta |publisher=[[Sun Pictures]] |place=India |time=01:00 to 02:00 |time-caption=Opening credits from}}</ref>\n* [[Aishwarya Rai Bachchan]] as Sana<ref name=\"netflix\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.netflixmovies.com/enthiran-2010 |title=Enthiran |date=2010 |website=[[Netflix]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20171005082958/https://www.netflixmovies.com/enthiran-2010 |archive-date=5 October 2017 |access-date=8 October 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Danny Denzongpa]] as Bohra<ref name=\"netflix\" />\n* [[Santhanam (actor)|Santhanam]] as Siva<ref name=\"netflix\" />\n* [[Karunas]] as Ravi<ref name=\"netflix\" />\n* [[Cochin Haneefa]] as the traffic police officer<ref name=\"netflix\" />\n* [[Kalabhavan Mani]] as Pachaimuthu<ref name=\"netflix\" />\n* [[Delhi Kumar]] as Vaseegaran's father<ref name=\"netflix\" />\n* [[Raaghav]] as the neighbourhood bully<ref name=\"OC\" />\n* [[Devadarshini]] as Latha, Sana's sister<ref name=\"netflix\" />\n* [[Revathi Sankaran]] as Vaseegaran's mother<ref name=\"OC\" />\n* [[Sabu Cyril]] as Shah{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|page=231}}\n* Sugunthan as the police inspector<ref name=\"CC\">{{Cite AV media |title=Enthiran |date=1 October 2010 |type=motion picture |language=ta |publisher=[[Sun Pictures]] |place=India |time=2:55:05 |time-caption=Closing credits in}}</ref>\n* [[Shriya Sharma]] as the curious student<ref name=\"CC\" />\n* [[Chaams]] as one of the barbers working at [[The Park, Chennai|The Park Hotel]]<ref name=\"CC\" />\n* [[Devadas Kanakala]] as K. Bhajanlal, a customer at The Park Hotel<ref name=\"CC\" />\n{{colend}}\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Origin ===\nFollowing the completion of his first directorial venture in Hindi, ''[[Nayak (2001 Hindi film)|Nayak]]'' (2001), [[S. Shankar]] announced his next project, ''Robot'', which was to feature [[Kamal Haasan]] and [[Preity Zinta]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/others/news-interviews/Shankars-Endhiran-to-become-a-reality-soon/articleshow/6215072.cms? |title=Shankar's Endhiran to become a reality soon |date=26 July 2010 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=27 May 2012 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118101009/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/others/news-interviews/Shankars-Endhiran-to-become-a-reality-soon/articleshow/6215072.cms |archive-date=18 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"BZ\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/entertai/2002/jan/02south.htm |title=Boys Zone |date=2 January 2002 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118101218/http://www.rediff.com/entertai/2002/jan/02south.htm |archive-date=18 January 2015 |access-date=18 January 2015}}</ref> The film was to be produced by the now-defunct company [[Media Dreams]], a division of [[Pentamedia Graphics]].<ref name=\"BZ\" /><ref name=\"Govardan\">{{Cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2008-01-05/news/28413738_1_rajinikanth-lulla-owned-eros-multimedia |title=Rajinikanth replaces Shah Rukh Khan in India's costliest movie |last=Govardan |first=D. |date=5 January 2008 |work=The Economic Times |access-date=18 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130126124918/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2008-01-05/news/28413738_1_rajinikanth-lulla-owned-eros-multimedia |archive-date=26 January 2013}}</ref> The film was reported to be a futuristic [[techno-thriller]] set in Chennai in around 2200 or 3000&nbsp;[[Anno Domini|AD]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/mp/2004/08/16/stories/2004081600740200.htm |title=Man vs. machine |date=16 August 2004 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=18 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118100919/http://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/mp/2004/08/16/stories/2004081600740200.htm |archive-date=18 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/nirav-and-sabu-sign-up-for-robot-news-tamil-kkfuh8aidcdsi.html |title=Nirav and Sabu sign up for Robot! |date=9 January 2008 |website=[[Sify]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118162759/http://www.sify.com/movies/nirav-and-sabu-sign-up-for-robot-news-tamil-kkfuh8aidcdsi.html |archive-date=18 January 2015 |access-date=18 January 2015}}</ref> Despite the completion of a photoshoot featuring Haasan and Zinta,<ref name=\"RFR\" /> the project was shelved as a result of scheduling conflicts with Haasan.<ref name=\"Fate\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-newdelhi/script-decides-the-fate-of-the-movie/article982047.ece |title=Script decides the fate of the movie |last=Tankha |first=Madhur |date=27 December 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=18 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118101504/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-newdelhi/script-decides-the-fate-of-the-movie/article982047.ece |archive-date=18 January 2015}}</ref> Shankar consequently started work on ''[[Boys (2003 film)|Boys]]'' (2003).<ref name=\"BZ\" />\n\nAfter ''Boys'', Shankar began work on his next feature starring [[Vikram (actor)|Vikram]], which was initially reported by [[Rediff.com]] to be ''Robot'' revived,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2003/nov/24south.htm |title=Shankar now wants sci-fi with Vikram |date=24 November 2003 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118101527/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2003/nov/24south.htm |archive-date=18 January 2015 |access-date=18 January 2015}}</ref> but was later revealed as ''[[Anniyan]]'' (2005).<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/fr/2005/03/11/stories/2005031101810100.htm |title=Director's dream project |last=Pillai |first=Sreedhar |date=11 March 2005 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 April 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113151544/http://www.hindu.com/fr/2005/03/11/stories/2005031101810100.htm |archive-date=13 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/mp/2004/03/15/stories/2004031500800200.htm |title=Shankar's next |last=M.I.N |date=15 March 2004 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 April 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050529005859/http://www.hindu.com/mp/2004/03/15/stories/2004031500800200.htm |archive-date=29 May 2005}}</ref> One month post the release of his action film ''[[Sivaji: The Boss]]'' in June 2007, he approached [[Shah Rukh Khan]] for the lead in ''Robot''.<ref name=\"srkcasting\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/shah-rukh-to-star-in-shankars-robot/article1881733.ece |title=Shah Rukh to star in Shankar's 'Robot' |last=Kumar |first=S. R. Ashok |date=29 July 2007 |work=The Hindu |access-date=18 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118101927/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/shah-rukh-to-star-in-shankars-robot/article1881733.ece |archive-date=18 January 2015}}</ref> Shankar had cast [[Priyanka Chopra]] as the female lead opposite him.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/not-rajinikanth-and-aishwarya-rai-bachchan-shah-rukh-khan-and-priyanka-chopra-were-the-first-choice-for-robot-bollywood-news/322385|title=Not Rajinikanth and Aishwarya Rai Bachchan, Shah Rukh Khan and Priyanka Chopra were the first choice for Robot|last=Chauhan|first=Gaurang|website=[[Times Now]]|date=28 November 2018|access-date=30 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329165639/https://www.timesnownews.com/entertainment/news/bollywood-news/article/not-rajinikanth-and-aishwarya-rai-bachchan-shah-rukh-khan-and-priyanka-chopra-were-the-first-choice-for-robot-bollywood-news/322385|archive-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Khan was about to produce it under his own banner, [[Red Chillies Entertainment]], but in October the same year the project was officially aborted due to creative differences between him and Shankar.<ref name=\"srkcasting\"/><ref name=\"Superstar casting\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/jan/02robot.htm |title=Shankar signs on Rajnikanth for Robot |last=Vilakudy |first=Rajaneesh |date=2 January 2008 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118101954/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/jan/02robot.htm |archive-date=18 January 2015 |access-date=18 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe project was revived in January 2008 with [[Eros International]] and the [[London]]-based production company [[Ayngaran International]] willing to produce the film.<ref name=\"Govardan\" /> The state government of [[Tamil Nadu]] granted tax exemptions for films titled in [[Tamil language|Tamil]], resulting in the new production being renamed ''Enthiran''.<ref name=\"Fate\" /> While [[Sujatha Rangarajan]] was originally assigned to write the dialogue for the film, [[Madhan Karky]] took over after Rangarajan's death in February 2008.<ref name=\"RFR\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/article566585.ece |title=Ready for Robot? |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |date=12 August 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=18 September 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118103719/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/article566585.ece |archive-date=18 January 2015}}</ref> In December 2008, Eros International withdrew from funding the project after financial difficulties caused by the box-office failure of ''[[Drona (2008 film)|Drona]]'' (2008) and ''[[Yuvvraaj]]'' (2008),<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://archive.mid-day.com/news/2008/dec/301208-Rajinikanth-Aishwarya-Rai-Enthiran-Hollywood-HBO-simultaneous-release.htm |title=Hollywood dreams |last=Kumar |first=S. Suresh |date=30 December 2008 |work=[[Mid Day]] |access-date=18 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Vg1tedde?url=http://archive.mid-day.com/news/2008/dec/301208-Rajinikanth-Aishwarya-Rai-Enthiran-Hollywood-HBO-simultaneous-release.htm |archive-date=18 January 2015}}</ref> with the subsequent departure of Ayngaran International, which struggled with the [[financial crisis of 2007\u201308]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.asiantribune.com/node/14840 |title=Sri Lankan born producer edged out of Rs.150 crore Rajanikanth's mega film 'Endhiran' |last=Balakrishnan |first=Ravikumar |date=26 December 2008 |work=[[Asian Tribune]] |access-date=5 June 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605045455/http://www.asiantribune.com/node/14840 |archive-date=5 June 2016}}</ref> The film's production and release rights were sold to [[Sun Pictures]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/dec/18sun-pictures-to-produce-endhiran.htm |title=Sun Pictures to produce Rajni's Endhiran |date=18 December 2008 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118102809/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/dec/18sun-pictures-to-produce-endhiran.htm |archive-date=18 January 2015 |access-date=18 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Cast and crew ===\n[[File:Rajini and Aishwarya Rai.jpg|thumbnail|For their roles, Rajinikanth (''left'') and Rai (''right'') were paid {{INR}}450&nbsp;million and {{INR}}60&nbsp;million respectively.]]\nIn January 2008, [[Rajinikanth]] accepted the lead role in the film for a salary of {{INR}}450&nbsp;million ([[Indian rupee]]s).<ref name=\"Superstar casting\" /><ref name=\"R+R\">{{Cite news |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/robot+rajini=rs-300-cr/1/115629.html |title=Robot+Rajini=Rs. 300 cr |last=Subramanian |first=Lakshmi |date=9 October 2010 |work=[[India Today]] |access-date=22 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122111859/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/robot%2Brajini%3Drs-300-cr/1/115629.html |archive-date=22 January 2015 |last2=Bamzai |first2=Kaveree}}</ref>{{refn|The average exchange rate in 2008 was 49.82 [[Indian rupee]]s ({{INR}}) per 1 US dollar (US$).<ref name=\"ex2010\">{{Cite web |url=http://inwww.rediff.com/business/slide-show/slide-show-1-rupee-vs-dollar-in-the-last-2-decades/20120518.htm?print=true |title=Rupee vs dollar: From 1990 to 2012 |date=18 May 2012 |website=Rediff.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150321115240/http://inwww.rediff.com/business/slide-show/slide-show-1-rupee-vs-dollar-in-the-last-2-decades/20120518.htm?print=true |archive-date=21 March 2015 |access-date=21 March 2015}}</ref>|name=exchange2008|group=Note}} Shankar rewrote the original script to suit Rajinikanth's acting style.{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|page=227}} In an interview with the Tamil channel [[Sun TV (India)|Sun TV]], held shortly after the film's release in October 2010, Rajinikanth revealed that Shankar, following the release of his ''[[Indian (1996 film)|Indian]]'' in 1996, had approached and pitched three storylines for him to consider for his next venture. Rajinikanth was impressed with two of the scripts and agreed to star in the films, which became ''Sivaji'' and ''Enthiran''. The third script narrated by Shankar focused on an aspiring bodybuilder; it eventually became ''[[I (film)|I]]'' (2015).<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Super Star Rajini&nbsp;\u2013 Special Interview |date=October 2010 |last=Rajinikanth (actor) |type=interview |language=Tamil |publisher=Sun TV |place=Chennai}}</ref>\n\nAlthough [[Aishwarya Rai]] was Shankar's original choice for the female lead in 2001, she declined it owing to a busy schedule and was replaced by Zinta.<ref name=\"Touch\">{{Cite news |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/news-archive/web/the-human-touch-6/ |title=The HUMAN Touch |last=Sahgal |first=Geety |date=1 October 2010 |work=[[The Indian Express]] |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120151720/http://indianexpress.com/article/news-archive/web/the-human-touch-6/ |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref> When Shankar revived the project with Rajinikanth,<ref name=\"Superstar casting\" /> contenders for the part included [[Deepika Padukone]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/jan/10robot.htm |title=Who should Rajni romance in Robot: Deepika or Ash? |date=10 January 2008 |work=[[Rediff.com]] |access-date=18 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118164646/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/jan/10robot.htm |archive-date=18 January 2015 |agency=[[Press Trust of India]]}}</ref> [[Shriya Saran]] and Rai, who was ultimately selected and paid {{INR}}60&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/mar/17ash.htm |title=Ash is back in Rajni's Robot |last=Gupshup |first=Gullu |date=17 March 2008 |website=Rediff.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118170445/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/mar/17ash.htm |archive-date=18 January 2015 |access-date=18 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/apr/17msg.htm |title=Should Shriya star opposite Rajni in Robot? |date=17 April 2008 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090506070110/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2008/apr/17msg.htm |archive-date=6 May 2009 |access-date=18 January 2015}}</ref>{{refn|name=exchange2008|group=Note}} Rai's voice was dubbed by [[Savitha Reddy]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/savitha-reddy-to-dub-for-deepika-in-kochadaiyaan-113101000828_1.html |title=Savitha Reddy to dub for Deepika in 'Kochadaiyaan' |date=10 October 2013 |work=[[Business Standard]] |access-date=24 February 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225062543/http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/savitha-reddy-to-dub-for-deepika-in-kochadaiyaan-113101000828_1.html |archive-date=25 February 2015 |agency=[[Indo-Asian News Service|IANS]]}}</ref>{{refn|In an interview with Geety Sahgal of ''[[The Indian Express]]'', Shankar stated that Rai had her dialogues translated from Tamil to English and rehearsed it the night before each day of filming.<ref name=\"Touch\" />|group=Note}}\n\nSeveral actors were considered for the role of Professor Bohra, including [[Amitabh Bachchan]],<ref name=\"IT\">{{Cite news |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/rajinikanth-told-me-not-to-play-villain-in-enthiran-says-amitabh-bachchan/1/561739.html |title=Rajinikanth told me not to play villain in Enthiran, says Amitabh Bachchan |date=4 January 2016 |work=India Today |access-date=5 June 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605050104/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/rajinikanth-told-me-not-to-play-villain-in-enthiran-says-amitabh-bachchan/1/561739.html |archive-date=5 June 2016}}</ref> [[J. D. Chakravarthy]],<ref name=IT /> [[Sathyaraj]] and British actor [[Ben Kingsley]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/character-call/article2839950.ece |title=Character Call |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |date=28 January 2012 |work=The Hindu |access-date=18 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118171750/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/character-call/article2839950.ece |archive-date=18 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Manoj\" /> but it was [[Danny Denzongpa]] who eventually received it, making ''Enthiran'' his first film in Tamil.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Rajinis-unflappable-Danny/articleshow/6512564.cms |title=Rajini's unflappable: Danny |last=Dutt |first=Purba |date=8 September 2010 |work=The Times of India |access-date=18 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Vg6QiOB0?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Rajinis-unflappable-Danny/articleshow/6512564.cms |archive-date=18 January 2015}}</ref> Dubbing for Denzongpa was provided by Kadhir.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/over-to-the-voices/article2723614.ece |title=Over to the voices&nbsp;... |last=Rao |first=Subha J. |date=17 December 2011 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119031821/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/over-to-the-voices/article2723614.ece |archive-date=19 January 2015}}</ref> Comedians [[Santhanam (actor)|Santhanam]] and [[Karunas]] were cast to portray Vaseegaran's assistants Siva and Ravi respectively.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/101071/rajnikanths-endhiran-truly-entertaining-movie.html |title=Rajnikanth's 'Endhiran' truly entertaining movie |date=1 October 2010 |work=[[Deccan Herald]] |access-date=5 October 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005083136/http://www.deccanherald.com/content/101071/rajnikanths-endhiran-truly-entertaining-movie.html |archive-date=5 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe soundtrack album and background score were composed by A. R. Rahman.<ref name=\"Roll\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/endhiran-set-to-roll-out/article1424451.ece |title=Endhiran set to roll out |date=8 September 2008 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121024256/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/endhiran-set-to-roll-out/article1424451.ece |archive-date=21 January 2015}}</ref> [[Vairamuthu]], [[P. Vijay]] and Madhan Karky authored the lyrics for the songs.<ref name=\"Roll\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/money-and-careers/carry-on-karky/article1993594.ece |title=Carry On Karky |last=Reddy |first=T. Krithika |date=5 May 2011 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140325054559/http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/money-and-careers/carry-on-karky/article1993594.ece |archive-date=25 March 2014}}</ref> [[Manoj Bharathiraja]], son of filmmaker [[P. Bharathiraja]], was signed on to be an assistant director after he approached Shankar.<ref name=\"Manoj\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/interviews/article301242.ece |title=Manoj Bharatiraja and 'Endhiran' |last=Malini |first=Shankaran |date=14 September 2010 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=19 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119024947/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/interviews/article301242.ece |archive-date=19 January 2015}}</ref> Also working as assistant directors were [[Atlee Kumar]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/atlee-displays-his-chops/article5788431.ece |title=Atlee displays his chops |last=Chowdhary |first=Y. Sunita |date=15 March 2014 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119025905/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/atlee-displays-his-chops/article5788431.ece |archive-date=19 January 2015}}</ref> Shree and Karthik G. Krish.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-reviews/audio-beat-damaal-dumeel-hitting-the-high-notes/article5764172.ece |title=Audio Beat: Damaal Dumeel&nbsp;\u2013 Hitting the high notes |last=Kumar |first=S. R. Ashok |date=8 March 2014 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119030538/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-reviews/audio-beat-damaal-dumeel-hitting-the-high-notes/article5764172.ece |archive-date=19 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/reading-between-friendship/article5979081.ece |title=Reading between friendship |last=Ramanujam |first=Srinivasa |date=5 May 2014 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119030857/http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/reading-between-friendship/article5979081.ece |archive-date=19 January 2015}}</ref> [[Sabu Cyril]], in addition to being the film's art director, made a guest appearance as Shah, an interpreter between Bohra and the terrorist organisation.{{Sfn|Ramachandran|2014|page=231}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/all-in-a-sets-work/article2287617.ece |title=All in a set's work |last=Dundoo |first=Sangeetha Devi |date=23 July 2011 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119031637/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/all-in-a-sets-work/article2287617.ece |archive-date=19 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[R. Rathnavelu]] was hired as the cinematographer after [[Ravi K. Chandran]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/seeing-through-the-lens-he-creates-magic/article1295670.ece |title=Seeing through the lens, he creates magic |last=Srinivasan |first=Meera |date=13 July 2008 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119033950/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/seeing-through-the-lens-he-creates-magic/article1295670.ece |archive-date=19 January 2015}}</ref> [[Nirav Shah]] and [[Thiru]] were considered.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/light-camera-and-a-lens-to-top-it-all/article5604618.ece |title=Light, camera and a lens to top it all |last=Krishnamoorthy |first=Suresh |date=22 January 2014 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119034410/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/light-camera-and-a-lens-to-top-it-all/article5604618.ece |archive-date=19 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Shoote\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/robot-shoot-starts-news-tamil-kkftUPbiagdsi.html |title=''Robot'' shoot starts! |date=15 February 2008 |website=Sify |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422081847/http://sify.com/movies/tamil/fullstory.php?id=14605537 |archive-date=22 April 2008 |access-date=19 January 2015}}</ref> [[Anthony (film editor)|Anthony]] was the film's editor.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/robot-endhiran--behind-the-camera/131984-8-66.html |title='Robot': 'Endhiran'&nbsp;\u2013 Behind the camera |last=Joseph |first=Renju |date=30 September 2010 |website=[[CNN-News18]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Vgm6w0CK?url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/robot-endhiran--behind-the-camera/131984-8-66.html |archive-date=19 January 2015 |access-date=19 January 2015}}</ref> [[Yuen Woo-ping]], known for his work in [[The Matrix (franchise)|''The Matrix'' trilogy]] and the ''[[Kill Bill: Volume 1|Kill Bill]]'' films, was selected to be the stunt co-ordinator,<ref name=\"MYS\" /> while [[Legacy Effects]], a visual effects studio based in the United States, were in charge of the [[prosthetic make-up]] and animatronics in the film.<ref name=\"MYS\" /> [[Munich]]-based film technical company, [[Panther (company)|Panther]], were responsible for the [[crane shot]]s.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/the-sea-inside/article3657464.ece |title=The sea inside |date=19 July 2012 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120080408/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/the-sea-inside/article3657464.ece |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref>{{refn|In [[filmmaking]] and [[video production]], a crane shot is a shot taken by a [[video camera|camera]] on a [[Crane (machine)|crane]] or [[Jib (camera)|jib]].|group=Note}} The film's [[Subtitles|subtitle captioning]] was done by Rekha Haricharan.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://behindwoods.com/new-videos/videos-q1-09/director-interview/rekha.html |title=Rekhs Interview |last=Bhavanishankar |first=Jyothsna |date=28 September 2010 |website=Behindwoods |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150412124101/http://behindwoods.com/new-videos/videos-q1-09/director-interview/rekha.html |archive-date=12 April 2015 |access-date=12 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Costume design ===\n[[Manish Malhotra]] and Mary E. Vogt were chosen to design the film's costumes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2009/apr/01slide3-best-of-manish-malhotra.htm |title=Manish Malhotra's fab filmi fashion&nbsp;\u2013 Aishwarya Rai Bachchan, Endhiran |date=1 April 2009 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119041810/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2009/apr/01slide3-best-of-manish-malhotra.htm |archive-date=19 January 2015 |access-date=19 January 2015}}</ref>{{refn|Vogt was also the costume designer for the ''[[Men in Black (film series)|Men in Black]]'' film series.<ref name=\"MYS\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article/Platinum-Mans-Dance/266773 |title=Platinum Man's Dance |last=Iyengar |first=Pushpa |date=30 September 2010 |website=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119042620/http://www.outlookindia.com/article/Platinum-Mans-Dance/266773 |archive-date=19 January 2015 |access-date=19 January 2015}}</ref>|group=Note}} Fifty-seven costumes were used for Rai, including a \"Mexican tribal\" look that she sported during the filming of the \"[[Kilimanjaro (song)|Kilimanjaro]]\" segment.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2009/may/20slide-show-1-ojas-talks-about-favourite-stars.htm#1 |title='Ash's tribal look in Enthiran is very glamorous' |last=Ramani |first=Nithya |date=21 May 2009 |website=[[Rediff.com]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120170121/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2009/may/20slide-show-1-ojas-talks-about-favourite-stars.htm |archive-date=20 January 2015 |access-date=20 January 2015}}</ref> According to make-up artist [[Banu (make-up artist)|Banu]], no prosthetics were used for Rajinikanth to avoid bothering him by withholding his time on set.<ref name=\"Banu\">{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Man-behind-Rajnis-looks/articleshow/6706929.cms |title=Man behind Rajni's looks |last=Pillai |first=Sreedhar |date=8 October 2010 |work=[[The Times of India]] |access-date=29 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6VwRtka6p?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Man-behind-Rajnis-looks/articleshow/6706929.cms |archive-date=29 January 2015}}</ref> Additional make-up was by Vance Hartwell, an employee of Legacy Effects.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/whats-the-secret-behind-63-year-old-superstar-rajinikanths-youthful-looks/articleshow/45409978.cms |title=What's the secret behind 63-year-old superstar Rajinikanth's youthful looks? |last=Mathai |first=Kamini |date=8 December 2014 |work=The Economic Times |access-date=30 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20150130131858/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/whats-the-secret-behind-63-year-old-superstar-rajinikanths-youthful-looks/articleshow/45409978.cms |archive-date=30 January 2015 |last2=Nurullah |first2=Abdullah}}</ref>\n\nThe visual appearance of Chitti was based on the [[G.I. Joe]] [[action figure]]s. For Chitti's \"villain robot\" look, its hair was spiked and brown coloured lenses were used for its eyes, whereas for its \"good robot\" look, green coloured lenses were used.<ref name=\"Banu\" /> The wig used for Chitti's \"villain robot\" look had a silver streak in the middle, made out of [[Yak]] hair,<ref name=\"Banu Sify\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/banu-i-give-full-credit-to-rajini-sir-news-tamil-kkjrmldfhchsi.html |title=Banu&nbsp;\u2013 I give full credit to Rajini sir |date=9 October 2010 |website=Sify |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221074710/http://www.sify.com/movies/banu-i-give-full-credit-to-rajini-sir-news-tamil-kkjrmldfhchsi.html |archive-date=21 February 2015 |access-date=21 February 2015}}</ref> while its leather jacket was designed by Vogt.<ref name=\"Banu Sify\" /> To make Vaseegaran look mature, the team made Rajinikanth sport an [[Beard#Styles|Oakley beard]].{{refn|According to Banu, an Oakley beard is \"neither a French beard not a full beard\". It developed as a result of shaping Rajinikanth's already grown beard.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://behindwoods.com/new-videos/videos-q1-09/director-interview/make-up-artist-banu.html |title=Make&nbsp;\u2013 up artist Banu interview |last=Kingston |first=Daya |website=Behindwoods |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225062905/http://behindwoods.com/new-videos/videos-q1-09/director-interview/make-up-artist-banu.html |archive-date=25 February 2015 |access-date=24 February 2015}}</ref>|group=Note}} Suits made of copper were used for Chitti's costumes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/others/news-interviews/Rajinis-metallic-look/articleshow/4131575.cms |title=Rajini's metallic look! |date=16 February 2009 |work=The Times of India |access-date=29 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6VwSUJG9S?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/others/news-interviews/Rajinis-metallic-look/articleshow/4131575.cms |archive-date=29 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Principal photography ===\n{{multiple image\n<!-- Essential parameters -->\n| align     = right\n| direction = vertical\n| footer    = The residential section of the Incan city of Machu Picchu, which features in the song, \"Kilimanjaro\".\n| width     = 200px\n\n<!-- Image 1 -->\n| image1    = MachuPicchu Residential (pixinn.net).jpg\n| width1    = 100\n| alt1      = Photo of stone walls\n| caption1  =\n}}\nFor Sabu Cyril's sets, Shankar required approximately twice as much studio floor space as for his previous film. After rejecting [[Ramoji Film City]] for technical reasons, ''Enthiran''{{'s}} producer, [[Kalanithi Maran]], took six months to set up three air-conditioned studio floors on land in [[Perungudi]] owned by Sun TV Network.{{sfn|Ramachandran|2014|p=226}} Filming began on 15 February 2008 at [[AVM Productions|AVM Studios]] in Chennai.<ref name=\"Shoote\" /> After the initial stages of filming, Shankar and Rathnavelu toured the world for three weeks, scouting for exotic filming locations.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/entertainment/movies/tamil/boxoffice/fullstory.php?id=14694570 |title=Shankar goes on a global location hunt! |date=14 June 2008 |website=Sify |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080617110015/http://sify.com/movies/tamil/fullstory.php?id=14694570 |archive-date=17 June 2008 |access-date=19 January 2015}}</ref> They visited Austria, Germany, Peru, Brazil and Argentina, looking for a backdrop to shoot the \"Kilimanjaro\" and \"Kadhal Anukkal\" segments,<ref name=\"YHSH\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/your-hunt-stops-here/article804495.ece |title=Your hunt stops here |last=Kumar |first=S. R. Ashok |date=2 October 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120164057/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/your-hunt-stops-here/article804495.ece |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref> eventually deciding on Peru and Brazil.<ref name=\"WSJ\" /><ref name=\"EL\" /> \"Kilimanjaro\" was filmed at the ruins of the [[Inca Empire|Incan]] city of [[Machu Picchu]] in Peru, with some 100&nbsp;Brazilian extras.<ref name=\"YHSH\" /><ref name=\"WSJ\">{{Cite news |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2010/10/01/machu-picchu-welcomes-rajnikanth-and-india/ |title=Machu Picchu Welcomes Rajinikanth (and India) |last=Lahiri |first=Tripti |date=1 October 2010 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120104833/https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2010/10/01/machu-picchu-welcomes-rajnikanth-and-india/ |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref> It was choreographed by [[Raju Sundaram]] and supervised by Fernando Astete, director of the Machu Picchu archaeological park.<ref name=\"WSJ\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/why-bollywood-filmmakers-are-spending-generously-on-a-song-shoot/15239094 |title=Why Bollywood filmmakers are spending generously on a song shoot |last=Shetty |first=Shakti |date=19 April 2014 |work=Mid Day |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120105528/http://www.mid-day.com/articles/why-bollywood-filmmakers-are-spending-generously-on-a-song-shoot/15239094 |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref> \"Kadhal Anukkal\" was filmed in [[Len\u00e7\u00f3is Maranhenses National Park]] in northeastern Brazil.<ref name=\"EL\">{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/news-interviews/Kollywood-in-search-of-exotic-locations/articleshow/6809384.cms |title=Kollywood in search of exotic locations |last=Pillai |first=Sreedhar |date=26 October 2010 |work=The Times of India |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Vj4LuiS4?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/news-interviews/Kollywood-in-search-of-exotic-locations/articleshow/6809384.cms |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe filming for Chitti's introduction to the international robotics conference was completed in December 2008 at [[Sri Sivasubramaniya Nadar College of Engineering]] and [[Vellore Institute of Technology]], where more than 400&nbsp;students were used as extras.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/Aishwarya-Rajnikanth-in-Vellore-for-Endhiran/articleshow/3897654.cms |title=Aishwarya, Rajnikanth in Vellore for Endhiran |date=27 December 2008 |work=The Times of India |access-date=5 June 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605082449/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/Aishwarya-Rajnikanth-in-Vellore-for-Endhiran/articleshow/3897654.cms |archive-date=5 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/article427262.ece |title='Enthiran' highest budget Indian film! |date=2 June 2010 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120073105/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/article427262.ece |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref> Further footage was shot over five days at the [[Ennore Port]] on the [[Mitsui O.S.K. Lines]] car carrier, ''Neptune Ace''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/cresting-the-tech-wave/article3497160.ece |title=Cresting the tech wave |last=Padamanabhan |first=Geeta |date=6 June 2012 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120072000/http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/cresting-the-tech-wave/article3497160.ece |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref> An action sequence where Chitti saves Sana from thugs was filmed in [[Lonavla]], under the supervision of the action choreographer [[Peter Hein]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/endhiran-action-scenes-in-lonavala-news-tamil-kkfrgkfbfjesi.html |title=''Endhiran'' action scenes in Lonavala |date=29 December 2009 |website=Sify |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122163026/http://www.sify.com/movies/endhiran-action-scenes-in-lonavala-news-tamil-kkfrgkfbfjesi.html |archive-date=22 January 2015 |access-date=22 January 2015}}</ref> Scenes featuring Rajinikanth as Chitti were captured over five days at the [[Perungudi#Dump Yard|Perungudi Dump Yard]] in Chennai.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/now-garbage-dump-turns-shooting-spot/article761579.ece |title=Now garbage dump turns shooting spot |last=H. Ramakrishnan |first=Deepa |date=5 May 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120065159/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/endhiran-almost-complete-shankar/article76198.ece |archive-date=20 January 2015 |last2=Lakshmi |first2=K.}}</ref> Sabu Cyril told Uma Kannan of ''[[The New Indian Express]]'' that the sets for the climax sequence, which was filmed at [[Mayajaal]], consisted of a tar road and glass buildings which rose to {{convert|65|ft|m}}, and that [[Sandwich panel|aluminium composite panels]], reported to have cost {{INR}}50&nbsp;million, were also used to design the sets.<ref name=\"Sabu\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/interviews/article479419.ece |title=Sets, Sabu and 'Enthiran' |last=Kannan |first=Uma |date=29 September 2010 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120100715/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/interviews/article479419.ece |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/endhiran-shot-on-expensive-sets-news-tamil-kkfrK8bjcdjsi.html |title=Endhiran shot on expensive sets |date=2 July 2009 |website=Sify |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122162428/http://www.sify.com/movies/endhiran-shot-on-expensive-sets-news-tamil-kkfrK8bjcdjsi.html |archive-date=22 January 2015 |access-date=22 January 2015}}</ref>{{refn|The average exchange rate in 2010 was 45.09 Indian rupees ({{INR}}) per 1 US dollar (US$).<ref name=\"ex2010\" />|name=exchange2010|group=Note}}\n\nThe set for \"[[Arima Arima]]\", a sequence choreographed by [[Prabhu Deva]],<ref name=\"Dancing\" /> was designed and constructed by Cyril at Ramoji Film City.<ref name=\"Sabu\" /> Filming of the number took place over 22&nbsp;days in April 2009.<ref name=\"Dancing\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/dancing-in-100-ways-rajini-style/article317305.ece |title=Dancing in 100 ways, Rajini style |last=Srinivasan |first=Meera |date=28 April 2009 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120161226/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/dancing-in-100-ways-rajini-style/article317305.ece |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref> Junior artists were employed by Rathnavelu to wear masks of Rajinikanth.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/unveiled/article831081.ece |title=Unveiled! |last=Shivakumar |first=S. |date=15 October 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=21 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121043753/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/unveiled/article831081.ece |archive-date=21 January 2015}}</ref> For the sequence entitled \"Irumbile Oru Irudhaiyam\", choreographed by [[Remo D'Souza]] and featuring Rai and Rajinikanth as Chitti,<ref name=\"D\" /> three different sets were used: one of copper, one of gold and one in silver.<ref name=\"Sabu\" /> The musical number, which was filmed in AVM Studios for eight days, was the last portion of the film's principal photography.<ref name=\"D\" /> D'Souza incorporated the [[popping]] style of [[street dance]]s, but encountered difficulties in performing the dance movements in tandem with the robot, and with the restrictions created by the rigid costumes.<ref name=\"D\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/interviews/article488740.ece |title=Remo D'Souza and the 'Enthiran' dance |last=Malini |first=Shankaran |date=21 September 2010 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120155914/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/interviews/article488740.ece |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref> Principal photography ended on 7 July 2010.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/rajinikanth-aishwarya-and-shankar-at-the-enthiren-party-imagegallery-kollywood-khnkP2egjifsi.html |title=Rajinikanth, Aishwarya and Shankar at the Enthiren party |website=Sify |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609155103/http://www.sify.com/movies/rajinikanth-aishwarya-and-shankar-at-the-enthiren-party-imagegallery-kollywood-khnkP2egjifsi.html |archive-date=9 June 2016 |access-date=9 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Visual effects ===\nImpressed with the film's script, [[V. Srinivas Mohan]] became the visual effects supervisor in December 2007. He asked Shankar to increase the filming schedules by six months to include pre-production requirements.<ref name=\"SMBW\">{{Cite web |url=http://behindwoods.com/new-videos/videos-q1-09/director-interview/srinivas-mohan.html |title=Endhiran VFX Supervisor Srinivas Interview |last=Bhavanishankar |first=Jyothsna |date=22 October 2010 |website=Behindwoods |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121032143/http://behindwoods.com/new-videos/videos-q1-09/director-interview/srinivas-mohan.html |archive-date=21 January 2015 |access-date=21 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Clone\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/animatronics-maketh-the-clone/article860359.ece |title=Animatronics maketh the clone |last=Devi Dundoo |first=Sangeetha |date=31 October 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=21 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121041958/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/animatronics-maketh-the-clone/article860359.ece |archive-date=21 January 2015}}</ref> Both Mohan and Shankar visited several visual effects companies, including the New Zealand-based [[Weta Digital]] and the United States-based [[Industrial Light & Magic]], [[Cafe FX]] and [[Tippett Studio]] before partnering with Legacy Effects.<ref name=\"SMBW\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/science-meets-cinema/article567194.ece |title=Science meets cinema |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |date=13 August 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=21 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121030008/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/science-meets-cinema/article567194.ece |archive-date=21 January 2015}}</ref> The original Eros-Ayngaran visual effects budget was {{INR}}700&nbsp;million,{{refn|name=exchange2008|group=Note}} but after Sun Pictures took over production, it was significantly reduced to {{INR}}200&nbsp;million.{{refn|name=exchange2008|group=Note}} As a result, the visual effects team had to omit and alter some sequences, making Chitti wear sunglasses for most of the film to reduce the cost and difficulty of animating his eyes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/article1304321.ece |title=Why Enthiran Rajini wore coolers? |last=Venkadesan |first=S. |date=18 October 2012 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=21 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121034556/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/article1304321.ece |archive-date=21 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter a series of [[Previsualization|previsualisation]] tests, including a scene in which Chitti jumps on a train to save Sana, Mohan eventually decided to use the technique in 40&nbsp;out of the 60&nbsp;visual effects scenes featured in the film,<ref name=\"SMBW\" /> consisting of 2,000&nbsp;takes.<ref name=\"Behind\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/behind-the-robot/article859242.ece |title=Behind the Robot |last=Rangarajan |first=Malathi |date=30 October 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119040836/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/behind-the-robot/article859242.ece |archive-date=19 January 2015}}</ref> Further previsualisation supervision was conducted by P. C. Sanath of Firefly Creative Studios, a visual effects company based in [[Hyderabad]].<ref name=\"Clone\" /> [[Storyboard#Creation|3D storyboards]] were constructed using 3D&nbsp;animation programs for every scene in the film and were shot from different angles.<ref name=\"Clone\" /> In an interview with Malathi Rangarajan of ''[[The Hindu]]'', Mohan said all the pre-production work took one-and-a-half years to complete.<ref name=\"Behind\" />\n\nRathnavelu used the [[Arriflex 435#435 Xtreme|435 Xtreme]] camera and also wrote a 1,600-page manual, in which he listed all the possible angles from where he could film the characters Rajinikanth played.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://behindwoods.com/new-videos/videos-q1-09/director-interview/rathnavelu.html |title=Cameraman Rathanvelu Interview |last=Bhavanishankar |first=Jyothsna |date=22 October 2010 |website=Behindwoods |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120171704/http://behindwoods.com/new-videos/videos-q1-09/director-interview/rathnavelu.html |archive-date=20 January 2015 |access-date=20 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/interview-with-cinematographer-rathnavelu/article6646451.ece |title=Lingaa through Randy's lens |last=Reddy |first=T. Krithika |date=29 November 2014 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120080947/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/interview-with-cinematographer-rathnavelu/article6646451.ece |archive-date=20 January 2015}}</ref> Legacy Effects and the Hong Kong-based visual effects companies Kinomotive Studios and Menfond Electronics took responsibility for the film's [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] work.<ref name=\"Behind\" /> To create the robots with Rajinikanth's appearance, a complete scan of his face in 3D&nbsp;digital format in all possible lighting conditions was conducted using the Doom Light Stage,{{refn|The Doom Light Stage is based on an original research conducted by [[Paul Debevec]] at the [[Institute for Creative Technologies|ICT]] division of the [[University of California, Berkeley]]. The Light Stage systems efficiently capture how an actor's face appears when lit from every possible lighting direction. From this captured imagery, realistic virtual renditions of the actor are created in the illumination of any location or set, faithfully reproducing the colour, texture, shine, shading and translucency of the actor's skin.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.fxguide.com/quicktakes/light-stage-brings-the-robot-to-life-in-india/ |title=Light Stage brings The Robot to life in India |last=Seymour |first=Mike |date=23 October 2010 |website=[[Fxguide]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123145843/http://www.fxguide.com/quicktakes/light-stage-brings-the-robot-to-life-in-india/ |archive-date=23 January 2015 |access-date=23 January 2015}}</ref>|group=Note}} so that his face could be replicated on the [[mannequin]]s.<ref name=\"Clone\" /> The technique, according to Shankar, was previously used in ''[[The Curious Case of Benjamin Button (film)|The Curious Case of Benjamin Button]]'' (2008).<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/interviews/Enthiran-doesnt-have-a-regional-mosaic/articleshow/6644888.cms |title='Enthiran doesn't have a regional mosaic' |last=Ravi |first=Bhama Devi |date=29 September 2010 |work=The Times of India |access-date=26 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Vs1IJKK2?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/interviews/Enthiran-doesnt-have-a-regional-mosaic/articleshow/6644888.cms |archive-date=26 January 2015}}</ref> The robot Chitti featured in the film was a mannequin made by a Legacy Effects team of 100&nbsp;technicians in Los Angeles. For every robotic mannequin used, six puppeteers were employed to control the mannequin's movements.<ref name=\"Behind\" />\n\n== Themes and influences ==\n''Enthiran'' focuses on the battle between man and machine.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/magazine/enjoy-the-carnival-folks/article842791.ece |title=Enjoy the carnival folks |last=Srivathsan |first=A. |date=23 October 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=27 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150127041324/http://www.thehindu.com/features/magazine/enjoy-the-carnival-folks/article842791.ece |archive-date=27 January 2015}}</ref> Despite Shankar's claim that ''Enthiran'' was a purely original idea,<ref name=\"RFR\" /> it has been compared to [[Mary Shelley]]'s 1818&nbsp;novel ''[[Frankenstein]]'', owing to the similar personae of Chitti and [[Frankenstein's monster]], both of whom turn against their respective creators.<ref name=\"malini\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/reviews/article287453.ece |title=Enthiran |last=Mannath |first=Malini |date=4 October 2010 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123151201/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/reviews/article287453.ece |archive-date=23 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-11498630 |title=BBC News&nbsp;\u2013 India's most expensive film is another Rajinikanth hit |last=G. Tilak |first=Sudha |date=10 October 2010 |website=BBC News |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123151717/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-11498630 |archive-date=23 January 2015 |access-date=23 January 2015}}</ref> K. Moti Gokulsing and Wimal Dissanayake, in their book ''Routledge Handbook of Indian Cinemas'', noted the similarity between the two works, arguing that Chitti was \"manipulated by Bohra to become a Frankenstein-like figure\".<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QwGgF-rDucEC |title=Routledge Handbook of Indian Cinemas |last=Gokulsing |first=K. Moti |last2=Dissanayake |first2=Wimal |publisher=[[Routledge]] |year=2013 |isbn=978-0-415-67774-5 |pages=294 |ref=harv |access-date=27 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413223856/http://books.google.com/books?id=QwGgF-rDucEC |archive-date=13 April 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Writing for ''[[The A.V. Club]]'', Genevieve Koski observed, \"The plot of ''Enthiran'' is essentially ''Frankenstein'' via [[Isaac Asimov|[Isaac] Asimov]]'s [[Three Laws of Robotics]].\"<ref name=\"AV Club\" />\n\nDirector and film critic [[Sudhish Kamath]] called ''Enthiran'' \"a superhero film, a sci-fi adventure, a triangular love story with a hint of the [[Ramayana]]\", while remarking that ''Enthiran''{{'s}} similarities to ''[[The Terminator]]'' (1984) were \"more than obvious. Not just visually\u2014where we see the Superstar with one human eye and one scarred metallic eye but also intentionally spelt out when the bad robot announces that he has created Terminators.\"<ref name=\"man versus machine\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/superstar-wars-man-versus-machines/article836818.ece |title=Superstar Wars: Man versus Machines |last=Kamath |first=Sudhish |date=19 October 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=26 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150126074813/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/superstar-wars-man-versus-machines/article836818.ece |archive-date=26 January 2015}}</ref> Kamath compared two of the film's robots to [[C-3PO]] and [[R2-D2]], [[droid (Star Wars)|droids]] from the ''[[Star Wars]]'' film series, which was referenced in ''Enthiran'' when Vaseegaran refers to one of his creations as \"R2\".<ref name=\"man versus machine\" />\n\nAlthough Shankar initially claimed that ''Enthiran'' would be made for all audiences, including those lacking [[computer literacy]],<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L9kxJN4I1fk |title=Enthiran&nbsp;\u2013 The Robot Will Work in Villages Too: Shankar |date=24 September 2010 |last=Shankar, S. (director) |publisher=[[Rajshri Media]] |place=India |access-date=28 January 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150720013658/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L9kxJN4I1fk |archive-date=20 July 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> the film is influenced by and makes references to many scientific principles relating to the fields of engineering, computer science and robotics, including [[terabyte]]s and Asimov's laws of robotics.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/business-of-bollywood/the-experience-of-first-show-of-a-rajinikanth-film/articleshow/6668088.cms |title=The experience of first show of a Rajinikanth film |last=Balakrishnan |first=Ravi |date=2 October 2010 |work=The Economic Times |access-date=28 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Vuhy4vrt?url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/business-of-bollywood/the-experience-of-first-show-of-a-rajinikanth-film/articleshow/6668088.cms |archive-date=28 January 2015}}</ref> Visual references are made to the [[science book]]s ''[[A Briefer History of Time (Hawking and Mlodinow book)|A Briefer History of Time]]'' (2005) and ''[[Freakonomics]]'' (2005).<ref name=\"R+R\" /> In his book ''Visual Perception and Cultural Memory: Typecast and Typecast(e)ing in Malayalam Cinema'', Sujith Kumar Parayil notes the similarities between Kalabhavan Mani's role in the film to the one Mani played in the [[Malayalam]] film ''[[Sallapam]]'' (1996).<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Parayil |first=Sujith Kumar |year=2014 |title=Visual Perception and Cultural Memory: Typecast and Typecast(e)ing in Malayalam Cinema |url=http://synoptique.hybrid.concordia.ca/index.php/main/article/view/40/50 |url-status=live |format=PDF |journal=Synoptique |pages=75\u201376 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413071441/http://synoptique.hybrid.concordia.ca/index.php/main/article/view/40/50 |archive-date=13 April 2015 |access-date=13 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Music ==\n{{Main|Enthiran (soundtrack)}}\nFor ''Enthiran'''s soundtrack and score, A. R. Rahman made use of the [[Continuum Fingerboard]], an instrument he had experimented with previously in the song \"Rehna Tu\" from [[Rakeysh Omprakash Mehra]]'s [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]] ''[[Delhi-6]]'' (2009).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mail-archive.com/arrahmanfans@yahoogroups.com/msg66979.html |title=Rahman uses novel concept for Endhiran |date=7 July 2009 |website=[[Radio City (Indian radio station)|PlanetRadiocity.com]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6i2BRom7m?url=https://www.mail-archive.com/arrahmanfans@yahoogroups.com/msg66979.html |archive-date=5 June 2016 |access-date=5 June 2016}}</ref> The film also marked the debut of Rahman's daughter Khatija as a playback singer.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Repository/getFiles.asp?Style=OliveXLib:LowLevelEntityToPrint_TOI&Type=text/html&Locale=english-skin-custom&Path=TOIBG/2010/08/01&ID=Ar04102 |title=Daughter croons for AR Rahman |date=1 August 2010 |work=The Times of India |access-date=16 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316051521/http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Repository/getFiles.asp?Style=OliveXLib%3ALowLevelEntityToPrint_TOI&Type=text%2Fhtml&Locale=english-skin-custom&Path=TOIBG%2F2010%2F08%2F01&ID=Ar04102 |archive-date=16 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe soundtrack album to ''Enthiran'' was released on 31 July 2010 at the [[Putrajaya International Convention Centre]] in [[Kuala Lumpur]], Malaysia.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/aishwarya-rajnikanth-launch-endhiran-music-615789 |title=Aishwarya, Rajnikanth launch Endhiran music |date=31 July 2010 |work=[[NDTV]] |access-date=24 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150124043033/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/aishwarya-rajnikanth-launch-endhiran-music-615789 |archive-date=24 January 2015 |agency=Press Trust of India}}</ref> The Tamil and Telugu versions were released by Think Music, while the Hindi version was released by Venus Music.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/venus-acquires-hindi-audio-rights-of-endhiran-615772 |title=Venus acquires Hindi audio rights of Endhiran |date=30 July 2010 |work=NDTV |access-date=30 July 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150124043413/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/venus-acquires-hindi-audio-rights-of-endhiran-615772 |archive-date=24 January 2015 |agency=IANS}}</ref> Think Music purchased the release rights of the Tamil and Telugu versions of the album for {{INR}}70&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2011-07-20/news/29795015_1_sony-music-shridhar-subramaniam-endhiran |title=Sony Music buys 146 catalogues of Think Music but loses on Rajinikanth starrer Endhiran's rights |last=Kandavel |first=Sangeetha |date=20 July 2011 |work=The Economic Times |access-date=24 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150124043155/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2011-07-20/news/29795015_1_sony-music-shridhar-subramaniam-endhiran |archive-date=24 January 2015}}</ref>{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}} The album of the film's Telugu version, ''Robo'', was released on 6 August 2010, while its Hindi version, ''Robot'', was released on 14 August 2010.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/ash-down-with-high-fever-gives-endhiran-music-launch-a-miss-615920 |title=Ash down with high fever, gives Endhiran music launch a miss |date=7 August 2010 |work=NDTV |access-date=24 January 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150124054557/http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/ash-down-with-high-fever-gives-endhiran-music-launch-a-miss-615920 |archive-date=24 January 2015 |agency=Press Trust of India |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-robot-launch-in-mumbai/20100816.htm |title=When superstar Rajnikanth met superstar Big B |last=Padmanabhan |first=Krishnakumar |date=16 August 2010 |website=Rediff.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150124054705/http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-robot-launch-in-mumbai/20100816.htm |archive-date=24 January 2015 |access-date=24 January 2015}}</ref> After the second day of release, the album's Tamil version reached the number one position in the Top&nbsp;10 World Albums chart on [[iTunes]], making it the first Tamil album to do so.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/article200776.ece |title='Endhiran' tops iTunes chart |last=Narayanan |first=Sharadha |date=4 August 2010 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=24 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150124043426/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/article200776.ece |archive-date=24 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Fells\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/rajini-fells-all-records-with-sci-fi-entertainer-endhiran-110100200074_1.html |title=Rajini fells all records with sci-fi entertainer Endhiran |last=Narasimhan |first=T. E. |date=2 October 2010 |work=[[Business Standard]] |access-date=5 June 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605123527/http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/rajini-fells-all-records-with-sci-fi-entertainer-endhiran-110100200074_1.html |archive-date=5 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\n''Enthiran'' was released on 1 October 2010 in three languages\u2014in Tamil as ''Enthiran'', in Hindi as ''Robot'' and in Telugu as ''Robo''.<ref name=\"CNN Travel\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/enthiran-d-day-is-here-news-tamil-kkgu7Xchbedsi.html |title=''Enthiran''&nbsp;\u2013 D-Day is here! |date=1 October 2010 |website=Sify |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221064709/http://www.sify.com/movies/enthiran-d-day-is-here-news-tamil-kkgu7Xchbedsi.html |archive-date=21 February 2015 |access-date=21 February 2015}}</ref> The original version was in Tamil, while the Hindi and Telugu versions were dubbed.<ref name=\"CNN Travel\" /> The film was released in 2,250&nbsp;theatres worldwide, including 500&nbsp;theatres in Tamil Nadu,<ref name=\"HBLScreens\" /> 350&nbsp;theatres in [[Andhra Pradesh]],<ref name=\"HBLScreens\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/todays-paper/enthiran-curious-audience-optimistic-kollywood/article1005373.ece |title=Enthiran&nbsp;\u2013 curious audience, optimistic Kollywood |last=Ravikumar |first=R. |date=29 September 2010 |work=[[Business Line]] |access-date=21 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121084052/http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/todays-paper/enthiran-curious-audience-optimistic-kollywood/article1005373.ece |archive-date=21 January 2015}}</ref> 128&nbsp;theatres in [[Kerala]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/boxoffice.php?id=14957682&cid=2362 |title=''Enthiran'' creates record in Kerala |date=29 September 2010 |website=Sify |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121083015/http://www.sify.com/movies/boxoffice.php?id=14957682&cid=2362 |archive-date=21 January 2015 |access-date=21 January 2015}}</ref> 23&nbsp;theatres in [[Karnataka]], and 750&nbsp;theatres in North India.<ref name=\"Fells\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/enthiran-stalls-new-releases/article811969.ece |title=Enthiran crosses screening limit; Kannada producers irked |date=7 October 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=26 October 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121084058/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/article817325.ece |archive-date=21 January 2015}}</ref> With an estimated budget of {{INR}}1.32{{mdash}}1.62&nbsp;billion,<ref name=\"Q3\" />{{refn|name=budget|group=Note}}{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}} ''Enthiran'' was [[List of most expensive Indian films|India's most expensive film]] up to that point,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/endhiran-the-costliest-film-in-india/1/108599.html |title=Endhiran: The costliest film in India |date=11 August 2010 |work=India Today |access-date=11 August 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203012913/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/endhiran-the-costliest-film-in-india/1/108599.html |archive-date=3 February 2014 |agency=Press Trust of India}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/meet-indias-biggest-film-star-2096273.html |title=Meet India's biggest film star |last=Buncombe |first=Andrew |date=3 October 2010 |work=[[The Independent]] |access-date=3 October 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122065142/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/meet-indias-biggest-film-star-2096273.html |archive-date=22 January 2015}}</ref> surpassing the Hindi film ''[[Blue (2009 film)|Blue]]'' (2009), which was filmed on a budget of {{INR}}750&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-08-10/news/27627378_1_first-film-special-effects-yuen-woo-ping |title=At 150 crore, Rajinikant's Robot costliest ever movie |last=Iyer |first=Meena |date=10 August 2010 |work=The Economic Times |access-date=24 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20141214014845/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-08-10/news/27627378_1_first-film-special-effects-yuen-woo-ping |archive-date=14 December 2014}}</ref>{{refn|The average exchange rate in 2009 was 46.29 Indian rupees ({{INR}}) per 1 US dollar (US$).<ref name=\"ex2010\" />|group=Note}}\n\n''Enthiran'' became the first Tamil film to be released at the [[Colosseum kino]], a [[Norway|Norwegian]] theatre complex in [[Oslo]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/article289735.ece |title='Enthiran's bitter pill to Malayalam cinema |last=Raj K. |first=Rohith |date=10 October 2010 |website=The New Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208085811/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/article289735.ece |archive-date=8 February 2015 |access-date=8 February 2015}}</ref> and it was screened at the 21st&nbsp;[[Bath Film Festival]], held in the United Kingdom in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bathfilmfestival.org.uk/the-robot.html |title=The 21st Bath film festival |publisher=[[Bath Film Festival]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101101081726/http://bathfilmfestival.org.uk/the-robot.html |archive-date=1 November 2010 |access-date=24 November 2011}}</ref> Additionally, a version of the film, edited to a running length of two hours, was released in Japan in May 2012, and later screened at the 24th&nbsp;[[Tokyo International Film Festival]], where it won a special award under the section \"Winds of Asia\u2013Middle East\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://2011.tiff-jp.net/en/lineup/works.php?id=108 |title=Winds of Asia-Middle East&nbsp;\u2013 Film Panorama of Asia-Middle East: The Robot |publisher=[[Tokyo International Film Festival]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121090417/http://2011.tiff-jp.net/en/lineup/works.php?id=108 |archive-date=21 January 2015 |access-date=2 November 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"TIFF\">{{Cite web |url=http://2011.tiff-jp.net/en/tiff/awards.html |title=24th Tokyo International Film Festival&nbsp;\u2013 List of Winners |publisher=Tokyo International Film Festival |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121094438/http://2011.tiff-jp.net/en/tiff/awards.html |archive-date=21 January 2015 |access-date=21 January 2015}}</ref> By public demand, the original, unedited version was later released in that country.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/rajinikants-robot-becomes-a-hit-in-japan-photos-videos-351635 |title=Rajinikant's Robot Becomes a Hit in Japan [PHOTOS & VIDEOS] |last=Mehta |first=Ankita |date=13 June 2012 |website=[[International Business Times]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206154818/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/rajinikants-robot-becomes-a-hit-in-japan-photos-videos-351635 |archive-date=6 February 2015 |access-date=6 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Marketing and distribution ===\nThe first poster for ''Enthiran'' was released on 8 September 2008.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/enthiren-robot-first-look-news-tamil-kkfsWHedhfisi.html |title=Enthiren (Robot)&nbsp;\u2013 First Look! |date=8 September 2008 |publisher=Sify |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605085125/http://www.sify.com/movies/enthiren-robot-first-look-news-tamil-kkfsWHedhfisi.html |archive-date=5 June 2016 |access-date=5 June 2016}}</ref> The film's trailer was released on 11 September 2010, at the [[SPI Cinemas|Sathyam Cinemas]] theatre complex in Chennai.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/news-archive/web/endhiran-trailer-released/ |title=Endhiran trailer released |date=24 September 2010 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121100152/http://indianexpress.com/article/news-archive/web/endhiran-trailer-released/ |archive-date=21 January 2015 |access-date=21 January 2015}}</ref> To promote ''Enthiran'', [[AGS Entertainment]] organised a festival from 25 September 2010 until its release date, in which they screened popular films of Rajinikanth at the company's theatre in [[Villivakkam]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/one-for-the-fans/article791697.ece |title=One for the fans |date=24 September 2010 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=8 February 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208044841/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/one-for-the-fans/article791697.ece |archive-date=8 February 2015}}</ref> In Coimbatore, the [[India Post|Department of Posts]] printed 100,000&nbsp;post cards advertising the film.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/endhiran-advertisement-on-post-cards/article799913.ece |title=Endhiran advertisement on post cards |date=28 September 2010 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=8 February 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208044846/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/endhiran-advertisement-on-post-cards/article799913.ece |archive-date=8 February 2015}}</ref> Sun Pictures invested a total of {{INR}}500&nbsp;million on promotional activities.<ref name=\"R+R\" />{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}}\n\nAdvance bookings for the film began two weeks before the release date in the United States. In the [[Jackson Heights, Queens|Jackson Heights]] neighbourhood in New York, tickets were sold out within ten minutes of going on sale.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/news-archive/web/endhiran-makes-news-even-before-release/ |title=Endhiran makes news even before release |last=Nivas |first=Namita |date=1 October 2010 |website=The Indian Express |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121100802/http://indianexpress.com/article/news-archive/web/endhiran-makes-news-even-before-release/ |archive-date=21 January 2015 |access-date=21 January 2015}}</ref> In Kerala the distribution rights were sold for {{INR}}50&nbsp;million,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/article209164.ece |title=Malayalam rights of 'Endhiran' sets record |date=28 August 2010 |website=The New Indian Express |publisher=Sampurn Wire |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121080239/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/article209164.ece |archive-date=21 January 2015 |access-date=21 January 2015}}</ref>{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}} while in Karnataka they were sold for {{INR}}100&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bangaloremirror.com/index.aspx?Page=article&sectname=News%20-%20City&sectid=10&contentid=2010092520100925051125158c0163429 |title=Enthiran will singe you |last=Prasad |first=Shyam |date=25 September 2010 |website=Bangalore Mirror |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707213303/http://bangaloremirror.com/index.aspx?Page=article&sectname=News%20-%20City&sectid=10&contentid=2010092520100925051125158c0163429 |archive-date=7 July 2011 |access-date=24 December 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref>{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}} The distribution rights in Mumbai were sold to Shringar Films.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-10-04/news/27624325_1_box-office-anjaana-anjaani-occupancies |title=Robot, Anjaana Anjaani sweep box office |last=Sheikh |first=Aminah |date=4 October 2010 |website=The Economic Times |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130126024710/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-10-04/news/27624325_1_box-office-anjaana-anjaani-occupancies |archive-date=26 January 2013 |access-date=5 June 2016}}</ref> In the United Kingdom, ''Enthiran'' was released by Ayngaran International, while ''Robot'' was released by [[B4U (network)|B4U Network]].<ref name=\"Tamil version runtime\" /> DVD marketing in India was handled by [[Moser Baer]];<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.flipkart.com/endhiran/p/itmdgyahufaytfhh?pid=AVMDGY9Y6P2RHTKK&otracker=from-search&srno=t_1&query=endhiran&ref=18d2e162-a197-461c-9b97-f2efd7a691b1 |title=Endhiran (Movie, DVD) |publisher=[[Flipkart]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150130155109/http://www.flipkart.com/endhiran/p/itmdgyahufaytfhh?pid=AVMDGY9Y6P2RHTKK&otracker=from-search&srno=t_1&query=endhiran&ref=18d2e162-a197-461c-9b97-f2efd7a691b1 |archive-date=30 January 2015 |access-date=30 January 2015}}</ref> Ayngaran International released the two-DVD set of the film in early&nbsp;2011.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Endhiran-2-DVD-Special-Edition/dp/B004L2FCOW |title=Endhiran 2 DVD Special Edition |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808143758/http://www.amazon.com/Endhiran-2-DVD-Special-Edition/dp/B004L2FCOW |archive-date=8 August 2014 |access-date=30 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Plagiarism allegations ===\nThe novelist Aarur Thamizhnadan made a complaint with the [[Chennai Metropolitan Police]] against the filmmakers in November 2010, stating that the producers plagiarised his 1996&nbsp;novel ''Jugiba''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article/Chennai-Corner/267919 |title=Chennai Corner&nbsp;\u2013 So who wrote Endhiran? |last=Iyengar |first=Pushpa |date=11 November 2010 |website=Outlook |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122035951/http://www.outlookindia.com/article/Chennai-Corner/267919 |archive-date=22 January 2015 |access-date=22 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/kollywood/scribe-stakes-claim-enthiran-story-743 |title=Scribe stakes claim to Enthiran story |date=28 May 2011 |website=[[Deccan Chronicle]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110530010555/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/kollywood/scribe-stakes-claim-enthiran-story-743 |archive-date=30 May 2011 |access-date=15 December 2011}}</ref> Thamizhnadan demanded {{INR}}10&nbsp;million{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}} from the director and producers for damages and filed a case against Kalanithi Maran.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/plea-to-restrain-screening-of-enthiran/article877295.ece |title=Plea to restrain screening of 'Enthiran' |date=10 November 2010 |work=[[The Hindu]] |access-date=22 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122054356/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/plea-to-restrain-screening-of-enthiran/article877295.ece |archive-date=22 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"EPMHC\">{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/HC-stay-on-case-against-Kalanithi/articleshow/8794646.cms |title=HC stay on case against Kalanithi |date=10 June 2011 |website=The Times of India |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6X2XSIrYu?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/HC-stay-on-case-against-Kalanithi/articleshow/8794646.cms |archive-date=15 March 2015 |access-date=15 March 2015}}</ref> In June 2011, the [[Madras High Court]] dismissed the case after a petition filed by Maran denying the allegation was approved.<ref name=\"EPMHC\" />\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Box office ===\nThe daily newspaper ''[[Business Line]]'' reported that ''Enthiran'' grossed {{INR}}580&nbsp;million from all versions in the opening weekend,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/todays-paper/tp-marketing/bollywood-buoyant-as-q3-opens-on-positive-note/article1005838.ece |title=Bollywood buoyant as Q3 opens on positive note |last=Bhat |first=Varada |date=4 October 2010 |website=Business Line |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206082026/http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/todays-paper/tp-marketing/bollywood-buoyant-as-q3-opens-on-positive-note/article1005838.ece |archive-date=6 February 2015 |access-date=4 October 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref>{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}} and ''[[The Economic Times]]'' stated it netted {{INR}}1.17&nbsp;billion by the end of its opening week.<ref name=\"first week\">{{Cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-10-09/news/27593126_1_film-collection-endhiran |title=Rs 117 cr in just 7 days, 'Robot' Rajini smashes all records |last=Dubey |first=Bharati |date=9 October 2010 |work=The Economic Times |access-date=9 October 2010 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130126032109/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2010-10-09/news/27593126_1_film-collection-endhiran |archive-date=26 January 2013 |url-status=bot: unknown}}</ref>{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}} According to a February 2015 report by ''Hindustan Times'', the film has grossed \u20b92.56 billion worldwide in its lifetime.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/vikram-s-i-crosses-rs-200-crore-mark-eyeing-endhiran-record/story-yiOmxaPA0HSNn8v8s3T1mK.html |title=Vikram's I crosses Rs 200 crore mark, eyes Enthiran record |date=4 February 2015 |website=Hindustan Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919134414/http://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/vikram-s-i-crosses-rs-200-crore-mark-eyeing-endhiran-record/story-yiOmxaPA0HSNn8v8s3T1mK.html |archive-date=19 September 2016 |access-date=19 September 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Indo-Asian News Service]] stated in July 2015 that the film grossed \u20b92.90 billion from both its original and its dubbed versions.<ref name=\"2.90 billion\">{{Cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/regional/ss-rajamoulis-baahubali-enters-rs-300-crore-club/ |title=SS Rajamouli's Baahubali enters RS 300 crore club |date=19 July 2015 |website=The Indian Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919134359/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/regional/ss-rajamoulis-baahubali-enters-rs-300-crore-club/ |archive-date=19 September 2016 |access-date=19 September 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}} ''Enthiran'' became the top-earning Indian film of 2010 ahead of ''[[My Name Is Khan]]'' and ''[[Dabangg]]'' and became the [[list of highest-grossing Tamil films|highest-grossing Tamil film of all time]] at that point.<ref name=\"worldwide gross\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=2171&nCat=box_office_news |title=Endhiran&nbsp;\u2013 The Robot Expected Lifetime Business |date=1 November 2010 |publisher=[[Box Office India]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104233643/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/boxnewsdetail.php?page=shownews&articleid=2171&nCat=box_office_news |archive-date=4 November 2010 |access-date=6 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/i-mints-184-crore-12-days-worldwide-box-office-collections-621620 |title='I' Mints \u20b9184 Crore in 12 Days in Worldwide Box Office Collections |last=Upadhyaya |first=Prakash |date=27 January 2015 |website=International Business Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206083044/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/i-mints-184-crore-12-days-worldwide-box-office-collections-621620 |archive-date=6 February 2015 |access-date=6 February 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs of January 2018, ''Enthiran'' is the [[List of highest-grossing Tamil films|fourth-highest-grossing]] [[Cinema of South India|South Indian film]] of all time after ''[[Baahubali 2: The Conclusion]]'' (2017), ''[[Baahubali: The Beginning]]'' (2015),<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2017/05/baahubali-2-the-conclusion-record-box-office-india-imax-north-america-worldwide-prabhas-1202079770/ |title='Baahubali 2' Becomes All-Time No. 1 Indian Film At Worldwide Box Office |last=Tartaglione |first=Nancy |date=5 May 2017 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170505171227/http://deadline.com/2017/05/baahubali-2-the-conclusion-record-box-office-india-imax-north-america-worldwide-prabhas-1202079770/ |archive-date=5 May 2017 |access-date=5 May 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/baahubali-beats-endhirans-lifetime-box-office-record-639747 |title=2nd Saturday Box Office Collection: Baahubali Beats Endhiran's Lifetime Record in 9 Days |last=H. Hooli |first=Shekhar |date=19 July 2015 |website=International Business Times |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6aB2A1IPn?url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/baahubali-beats-endhirans-lifetime-box-office-record-639747 |archive-date=21 July 2015 |access-date=21 July 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> and ''[[Kabali (film)|Kabali]]'' (2016).<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/kabali-has-had-the-biggestever-opening-for-a-tamil-film/article8921554.ece |title='Magizhchi' at the box-office |last=Pillai |first=Sreedhar |date=30 July 2016 |work=The Hindu |access-date=31 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160731061021/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/kabali-has-had-the-biggestever-opening-for-a-tamil-film/article8921554.ece |archive-date=31 July 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Box Office India]] estimated that ''Enthiran'' netted {{INR}}1.95&nbsp;billion across India with the Tamil version netting {{INR}}1.20&nbsp;billion, the Telugu version netting {{INR}}530&nbsp;million and the Hindi version netting {{INR}}220&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2189 |title=Kabali Set To Be Biggest Tamil Grosser |date=27 July 2016 |publisher=Box Office India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727095155/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2189 |archive-date=27 July 2016 |access-date=27 July 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2187 |title=Kabali (Hindi) And Madaari Are Low On Monday |publisher=Box Office India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727095208/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/report-details.php?articleid=2187 |archive-date=27 July 2016 |access-date=27 July 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}} The website estimated the overseas earnings of the film (including its dubbed versions) at approximately $12 million as of November 2010 with the Tamil version grossing $11 million and the remaining $1 million coming in from the Telugu and Hindi versions.<ref name=\"worldwide gross\" /> ''Enthiran'' collected {{INR}}1.05&nbsp;billion in Tamil Nadu alone,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/baahubali-2-bahubali-2-tamil-nadu-box-office-collection-ss-rajamoulis-film-inching-towards-rs-727904 |title=Baahubali 2 (Bahubali 2) Tamil Nadu box office collection: SS Rajamouli's film inching towards Rs. 125 crore-mark |last=Upadhyaya |first=Prakash |date=24 May 2017 |website=International Business Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525093647/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/baahubali-2-bahubali-2-tamil-nadu-box-office-collection-ss-rajamoulis-film-inching-towards-rs-727904 |archive-date=25 May 2017 |access-date=25 May 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}} a record it held for seven years before being surpassed by ''[[Baahubali 2: The Conclusion]]'' (2017), which grossed {{INR}}1.526&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/baahubali-2-bahubali-2-box-office-collection-ss-rajamoulis-film-mints-rs-1706-50-cr-140-days-742747 |title=Baahubali 2 (Bahubali 2) box office collection: SS Rajamouli's film mints Rs 1,706.50 cr in 140 days |last=Upadhyaya |first=Prakash |date=20 September 2017 |work=[[International Business Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023011833/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/baahubali-2-bahubali-2-box-office-collection-ss-rajamoulis-film-mints-rs-1706-50-cr-140-days-742747 |archive-date=23 October 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>{{refn|name=exchange2010|group=Note}}\n\nIn Japan, the film grossed $407,438, including $370,697 for the Hindi version and $36,741 for the Tamil version.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/trends/entertainment/japans-love-for-indian-films-continues-to-rise-3505491.html |title=Japan's love for Indian films continues to rise |date=9 February 2019 |work=[[Moneycontrol]] |access-date=9 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209095056/https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/trends/entertainment/japans-love-for-indian-films-continues-to-rise-3505491.html |archive-date=9 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Critical response ===\n==== India ====\n''Enthiran'' received positive reviews from critics in India, with praise particularly directed at Rathnavelu's cinematography, Cyril's art direction, Srinivas Mohan's visual effects and Rajinikanth's performance as Chitti.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/critics-give-a-thumbs-up-to-endhiran/story-o1InoBdTUUJ7tpF1Xtcl8K.html |title=Critics give a thumbs up to Endhiran |date=1 October 2010 |work=Hindustan Times |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150127100230/http://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/critics-give-a-thumbs-up-to-endhiran/article1-606784.aspx |archive-date=27 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2010/10/01/review-round-up-endhiranrobot/ |title=Review Round-Up: 'Endhiran'/'Robot' |last=Agarwal |first=Vibhuti |date=1 October 2010 |work=The Wall Street Journal |access-date=29 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6VwPqteUr?url=http://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2010/10/01/review-round-up-endhiranrobot/ |archive-date=29 January 2015}}</ref> Aniruddha Guha of ''[[Daily News and Analysis]]'' gave the film a rating of four out of five stars and believed it had the \"best special effects ever seen in a Tamil film\" and that it was \"one of the most entertaining Tamil films\u2014across all languages\u2014ever made.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/review-review-robot-endhiran-is-an-indian-film-to-be-proud-of-1446033 |title=Robot (Endhiran) is an Indian film to be proud of |last=Guha |first=Aniruddha |date=1 October 2010 |work=[[Daily News and Analysis]] |access-date=1 October 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123151434/http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/review-review-robot-endhiran-is-an-indian-film-to-be-proud-of-1446033 |archive-date=23 January 2015}}</ref> Both [[Nikhat Kazmi]] of ''The Times of India'' and Kaveree Bamzai of ''[[India Today]]'' rated the film four out of five stars. Kazmi called it \"the perfect getaway film\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/movie-reviews/hindi/Robot/movie-review/6658514.cms |title=Robot Review |last=Kazmi |first=Nikhat |date=30 September 2010 |work=The Times of India |access-date=1 October 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6W5oOH49J?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-review/Robot/movie-review/6658514.cms |archive-date=4 February 2015 |author-link=Nikhat Kazmi}}</ref> Bamzai praised Rajinikanth's acting in the film and said, \"Rajni tells us why robot sapiens are superior to [[homo sapiens]]\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/film-review-endhiran/1/114755.html |title=Film review: Endhiran |last=Bamzai |first=Kaveree |date=1 October 2010 |work=India Today |access-date=9 July 2011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204095812/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/film-review-endhiran/1/114755.html |archive-date=4 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nBoth [[Anupama Chopra]] of [[NDTV]] and Pavithra Srinivasan of Rediff.com gave ''Enthiran'' a rating of three-and-a-half stars out of five. Chopra criticised the film's portions in the second half, describing them as \"needlessly stretched and cacophonous\",<ref name=\"Chopra\">{{Cite web |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/movie-reviews/review-robot-551 |title=Review: Robot |last=Chopra |first=Anupama |authorlink=Anupama Chopra |date=1 October 2010 |website=NDTV |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204151648/http://movies.ndtv.com/movie-reviews/review-robot-551 |archive-date=4 February 2015 |access-date=1 October 2010}}</ref> but concluded her review by saying, \"''Robot'' rides on Rajinikanth's shoulders and he never stoops under the burden. Aided by snazzy clothes, make-up and special effects, he makes Chitti endearing.\"<ref name=\"Chopra\" /> Srinivasan, however, said that Shankar \"strikes the balance between science fiction and masala quotient.\"<ref name=\"PRrediff\" /> She concluded that, \"Whichever way you look at it, {{sic|''Endhiran''|nolink=y}} is one of those rare films that give you just enough material to pull you in, and enjoy yourself.\"<ref name=\"PRrediff\">{{Cite web |url=http://movies.rediff.com/review/2010/oct/01/south-tamil-review-endhiran.htm |title=Shankar, Rajinikanth make Endhiran work |last=Srinivasan |first=Pavithra |date=1 October 2010 |website=Rediff.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204094855/http://movies.rediff.com/review/2010/oct/01/south-tamil-review-endhiran.htm |archive-date=4 February 2015 |access-date=9 July 2011}}</ref> [[Rajeev Masand]] of [[CNN-News18]] gave a rating of three out of five stars and said, \"In the end, it's the fantastic special effects and an inspired performance from {{sic|Rajnikant|nolink=y}} that keeps the film fresh.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/masand-robot-is-an-adventure-waiting-for-you/132161-47-84.html |title='Robot' is an adventure waiting for you |last=Masand |first=Rajeev |authorlink=Rajeev Masand |date=8 October 2010 |website=CNN-News18 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6W5po6YQx?url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/masand-robot-is-an-adventure-waiting-for-you/132161-47-84.html |archive-date=4 February 2015 |access-date=6 November 2011}}</ref> [[Mayank Shekhar]], writing for ''Hindustan Times'', rated it three stars and said, \"Leave aside jokes running on the Internet. This film, just a few feet too long, is fine entertainment by itself.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/movie-reviews/mayank-shekhar-s-review-robot/story-QvlgAwwSQRpAbqpE5utmRO.html |title=Mayank Shekhar's Review: Robot |last=Shekhar |first=Mayank |date=4 October 2010 |work=Hindustan Times |access-date=22 September 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922090833/http://www.hindustantimes.com/movie-reviews/mayank-shekhar-s-review-robot/story-QvlgAwwSQRpAbqpE5utmRO.html |archive-date=22 September 2017 |author-link=Mayank Shekhar}}</ref>\n\nMalini Mannath of ''The New Indian Express'' noted ''Enthiran'' for having \"An engaging script, brilliant special effects, and a debonair hero who still carries his charisma effortlessly.\"<ref name=\"malini\" /> Karthik Subramanian of ''The Hindu'' observed that actors \"tend to get lost in special effects movies.\" He believed it was not the case in ''Enthiran'': \"Rajinikanth and [Aishwarya Rai] carry the movie on their shoulders, and considering the fact that much of the acting must have been in front of green screens, one has to say that nothing looks artificial right through.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/unabashed-entertainer/article807284.ece |title=Unabashed entertainer |last=Subramanian |first=Karthik |date=1 October 2010 |work=The Hindu |access-date=1 August 2011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204094450/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/unabashed-entertainer/article807284.ece |archive-date=4 February 2015}}</ref> In contrast, Gautaman Bhaskaran of ''Hindustan Times'' rated it two out of five stars, writing that \"Shankar's work slips into a loud, overdramatic and exaggerated mess\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/gautaman-bhaskaran-s-review-endhiran/story-ENP80sXGeoKJxuITEAdiyN.html |title=Gautaman Bhaskaran's Review: Endhiran |last=Bhaskaran |first=Gautaman |date=1 October 2010 |work=Hindustan Times |access-date=26 October 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204100758/http://www.hindustantimes.com/regional/gautaman-bhaskaran-s-review-endhiran/article1-606907.aspx |archive-date=4 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== Overseas ====\n''Enthiran'' has received a rating of 67%&nbsp;on the [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], based on twelve reviews, with an average rating of 5.62/10.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/endhiran/ |title=Endhiran (2010) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |access-date=30 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160719052215/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/endhiran/ |archive-date=19 July 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lisa Tsering from ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' said, \"Rajinikanth is such a badass that [[Chuck Norris]] is [[Chuck Norris facts|afraid of him]].\"<ref name=\"LSHR\" /> She praised the filming locations, especially the \"Kilimanjaro\" song sequence, but criticised the length of the film's climax portions.<ref name=\"LSHR\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/robot-film-review-30163 |title=Robot&nbsp;\u2013 Film Review |last=Tsering |first=Lisa |date=14 October 2010 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=1 August 2011 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205164503/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/robot-film-review-30163 |archive-date=5 February 2015}}</ref> Genevieve Koski from ''The A. V. Club'' believed that ''Enthiran'' was \"pretty good\" and concluded that \"if you prefer elaborate costumes and dance music mixed in with your killer-robot action, expect to enjoy up to an hour of ''Enthiran''.\"<ref name=\"AV Club\" /> Marc Savlov of ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]'' called ''Enthiran'' \"the best apocalyptic sci-fi-romcom-melodrama-dance-off date movie of the year.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/calendar/film/2011-02-25/endhiran-the-robot/ |title=Endhiran (Robot) |last=Savlov |first=Marc |date=25 February 2011 |work=[[The Austin Chronicle]] |access-date=6 February 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206072711/http://www.austinchronicle.com/calendar/film/2011-02-25/endhiran-the-robot/ |archive-date=6 February 2015}}</ref> Roger Moore, writing for the ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]'', gave a mixed review, evaluating it as a \"melodramatic kitschy Indian musical about a robot built for national defense but who discovers his human side.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blogs.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment_movies_blog/2010/10/movie-review-endhiran.html |title=Movie Review: Endhiran |last=Moore |first=Roger |date=7 October 2010 |website=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101013034935/http://blogs.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment_movies_blog/2010/10/movie-review-endhiran.html |archive-date=13 October 2010 |access-date=21 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the film's screening at the [[Mumbai International Film Festival]], American film director [[Oliver Stone]] praised ''Enthiran''{{'s}} originality.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SaabAwAAQBAJ |title=Grand Brand Rajini |last=Balasubramanianram |first=P. C. |last2=Ramakrishnan |first2=N. |publisher=Rupa Publications |year=2012 |isbn=978-81-291-2059-5 |pages=79 |ref=harv}}</ref> Conversely, [[Joe Leydon]] of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' believed that Shankar \"riffs on everything\" from ''Frankenstein'' to ''The Terminator'', but suggested that the film was an \"overwhelming mash-up of American-style, f/x-driven sci-fi spectacle and a Bollywood musical.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2010/film/reviews/endhiran-the-robot-1117943809/ |title=Review: 'Endhiran&nbsp;\u2013 The Robot' |last=Leydon |first=Joe |authorlink=Joe Leydon |date=8 October 2010 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131223083911/http://variety.com/2010/film/reviews/endhiran-the-robot-1117943809 |archive-date=23 December 2013 |access-date=20 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{{Main|List of accolades received by Enthiran}}\nAt the [[58th National Film Awards]], ''Enthiran'' won for [[National Film Award for Best Special Effects|Best Special Effects]] and [[National Film Award for Best Production Design|Best Production Design]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://dff.nic.in/awards.asp |title=58th National Film Awards for 2010 announced |website=Directorate of Film Festivals |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131230233408/http://dff.nic.in/awards.asp |archive-date=30 December 2013 |access-date=19 May 2011}}</ref> It won in three categories at the [[58th Filmfare Awards South]] for [[Filmfare Award for Best Cinematographer&nbsp;\u2013 South|Best Cinematographer]], [[Filmfare Award for Best Art Director&nbsp;\u2013 South|Best Art Director]] and Best Costume Design.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ndtv.com/photos/entertainment/58th-south-filmfare-awards-winners-10839/slide/21 |title=58th Idea Filmfare Awards South winners |website=[[NDTV]] |pages=21, 22, 23 27, 28, 30 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122121638/http://www.ndtv.com/photos/entertainment/58th-south-filmfare-awards-winners-10839/slide/21 |archive-date=22 January 2015 |access-date=27 May 2012}}</ref> At the [[5th Vijay Awards]], it was nominated in fourteen categories and won in seven, including [[Vijay Award for Best Villain|Best Villain]] and [[Vijay Award for Favourite Hero|Favourite Hero]] for Rajinikanth, [[Vijay Award for Favourite Film|Favourite Film]] and [[Vijay Award for Favourite Director|Favourite Director]].<ref name=\"Vijay\">{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cl0sMfvSm_M |title=Vijay Awards 07/15/11 |date=6 June 2012 |publisher=[[YouTube]] |place=[[Chennai]] |access-date=11 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921063254/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cl0sMfvSm_M |archive-date=21 September 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> At the [[Screen Awards|17th Screen Awards]], the film won awards under the [[Screen Award for Best Special Effects|Best Special Effects]] and Spectacular Cutting Edge Technology categories.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/features/type/view/id/1748/ |title=Winners of 17th Annual Star Screen Awards 2011 |date=6 January 2011 |website=[[Bollywood Hungama]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150126105906/http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movies/features/type/view/id/1748/ |archive-date=26 January 2015 |access-date=7 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nIn a personal appreciation letter to Shankar following the film's release, the director [[K. Balachander]] described Shankar as India's [[James Cameron]], ''Enthiran'' as India's ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]'' (2009) and Sun Pictures as India's [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]].<ref name=\"letter\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/oct-10-03/k-balachander-endhiran-shankar-15-10-10.html |title=\"Kamalhaasan sent me flowers\"&nbsp;\u2013 Shankar |date=15 October 2010 |website=Behindwoods |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204155915/http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/oct-10-03/k-balachander-endhiran-shankar-15-10-10.html |archive-date=4 February 2015 |access-date=19 May 2011}}</ref> ''Enthiran'' was the only Tamil film featured on the [[IMDb|Internet Movie Database]] (IMDb) list of the 50&nbsp;best films of 2010.<ref name=\"Facts\">{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/Rajinikanth-Lesser-known-facts/photostory/34830196.cms |title=Rajinikanth: Lesser known facts&nbsp;\u2013 Page 7 |website=The Times of India |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6W5sfb5uy?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/Rajinikanth-Lesser-known-facts/photostory/34830196.cms |archive-date=4 February 2015 |access-date=4 February 2015}}</ref> The film was also included as a case study in a postgraduate elective course of the [[Indian Institute of Management Ahmedabad]], \"Contemporary Film Industry: A Business Perspective\".<ref name=\"Facts\" />\n\nScenes from ''Enthiran'', particularly one known as the \"Black Sheep\" scene,{{refn|The \"Black Sheep\" scene refers to a scene where Chitti finds Dr. Vaseegaran disguised as him amidst the robot army.<ref name=\"Behind\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/magazine/article289615.ece |title=Why you should watch Endhiran |last=Gunasekaran |first=Ranjitha |date=10 October 2010 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=6 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206165657/http://www.newindianexpress.com/magazine/article289615.ece |archive-date=6 February 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>|group=Note}} have been parodied in subsequent films, including ''[[Mankatha]]'' (2011),<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Mankatha |date=2011 |last=[[Venkat Prabhu|Prabhu, Venkat]] (director) |publisher=[[Cloud Nine Movies]] |place=India |time=45:12 |medium=motion picture}}</ref><ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Mankatha |date=2011 |last=[[Venkat Prabhu|Prabhu, Venkat]] (director) |publisher=[[Cloud Nine Movies]] |place=India |time=2:17:26 |medium=motion picture}}</ref> ''[[Osthe]]'' (2011),<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Osthe |date=2011 |last=[[Dharani (director)|Dharani]] (director) |publisher=Balaji Real Media |place=India |time=2:01:16 |medium=motion picture}}</ref> ''[[Singam II]]'' (2013),<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Singam II |date=2013 |last=[[Hari (director)|Hari]] (director) |publisher=Prince Pictures |place=India |time=14:25 |medium=motion picture}}</ref>  ''[[Ya Ya (film)|Ya Ya]]'' (2013),<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Ya Ya|date=2013 |last=I. Rajasekaran (director) |publisher=M10 Productions |place=India |time=53:13 |medium=motion picture}}</ref>  as well as in the Telugu films ''[[Dookudu]]'' (2011) and ''[[Nuvva Nena]]'' (2011).<ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Dookudu |date=2011 |last=[[Srinu Vaitla|Vaitla, Srinu]] (director) |publisher=[[14 Reels Entertainment]] |place=India |time=1:43:02 |medium=motion picture}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/old-wine-same-old-bottle/article3007871.ece |title=Old wine, same old bottle |last=Dundoo |first=Sangeetha Devi |date=18 March 2012 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122041218/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/old-wine-same-old-bottle/article3007871.ece |archive-date=22 January 2015}}</ref>{{refn|The satellite rights of ''Mankatha'', ''Osthe'' and ''Singam II'' were purchased by Sun TV.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/k-family-unites-to-release-mankatha-news-tamil-lizkKhjibjesi.html |title=K&nbsp;\u2013 Family unites to release ''Mankatha'' |date=26 August 2011 |publisher=Sify |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150314135235/http://www.sify.com/movies/k-family-unites-to-release-mankatha-news-tamil-lizkKhjibjesi.html |archive-date=14 March 2015 |access-date=14 March 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/osthi-all-clear-for-dec-8-release-imagegallery-kollywood-lmfpb5aabfisi.html |title=''Osthi'', all clear for Dec 8 release |website=Sify |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150314135338/http://www.sify.com/movies/osthi-all-clear-for-dec-8-release-imagegallery-kollywood-lmfpb5aabfisi.html |archive-date=14 March 2015 |access-date=14 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/Sun-TV-Grabs-Rights-for-Anjaan/2014/05/01/article2198491.ece |title=Sun TV Grabs Rights for Anjaan |date=1 May 2014 |website=The New Indian Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605113455/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/Sun-TV-Grabs-Rights-for-Anjaan/2014/05/01/article2198491.ece |archive-date=5 June 2016 |access-date=5 June 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref>|group=Note}} In the film, Chitti often introduces himself by stating the [[clock rate]] of his [[central processing unit]], which is 1&nbsp;terahertz (10<sup>12</sup> [[hertz]]), and his [[random-access memory]] limit, which is 1&nbsp;zettabyte (10<sup>21</sup> [[byte]]s). This introduction dialogue, which is spoken by Chitti as \"Hi, I'm Chitti, speed 1&nbsp;terahertz, memory 1&nbsp;zettabyte\" became popular.<ref name=\"Clone\" /><ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l2RPAk2Tipw |title=Chitti meets G.One sequence&nbsp;\u2013 RA.One |date=5 January 2012 |last=Kareena Kapoor, Rajinikanth, Shah Rukh Khan |publisher=[[Eros International|Eros Now]] |place=India |access-date=25 February 2015 |medium=Motion picture |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150914034010/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l2RPAk2Tipw |archive-date=14 September 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Rajinikanth featured in a cameo role as Chitti in the science-fiction film ''[[Ra.One]]'' (2011).<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/rajnikanth-plays-chitti-the-robot-in-srks-ra-one/article2511736.ece |title=Rajnikanth plays Chitti&nbsp;\u2013 the robot in SRK's \"Ra. One\" |date=4 October 2011 |work=The Hindu |access-date=20 January 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122041225/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/rajnikanth-plays-chitti-the-robot-in-srks-ra-one/article2511736.ece |archive-date=22 January 2015 |agency=Press Trust of India}}</ref>\n\nOn Rajinikanth's 64th birthday, an agency named Minimal Kollywood Posters designed posters of Rajinikanth's films, in which the [[Despicable Me (franchise)#Minions|Minion]] characters from the ''[[Despicable Me (franchise)|Despicable Me]]'' franchise are dressed as Rajinikanth.<ref name=\"Minions\" /> The digital art was hand drawn on a digital pad by Gautham Raj.<ref name=\"Minions\" /> One of the posters depicted a mutated Minion, reminiscent of Chitti's \"villain robot\" look in ''Enthiran''.<ref name=\"Minions\">{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/Superstar-Rajinikanth-as-Minions/photostory/45519505.cms |title=Superstar Rajinikanth as Minions&nbsp;\u2013 Enthiran (2010) |last=Prasad |first=Shiva |date=15 December 2014 |website=The Times of India |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6XC9ugLHl?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/Superstar-Rajinikanth-as-Minions/photostory/45519505.cms |archive-date=21 March 2015 |access-date=21 March 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2015, Kamath, in his review of the science fiction film ''[[Chappie (film)|Chappie]]'', compared its eponymous lead character to Chitti in terms of learning human emotions.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-reviews/chappie-chittis-hollywood-cousin/article6993688.ece |title=Chappie: Chitti's Hollywood cousin |last=Kamath |first=Sudhish |date=14 March 2015 |work=The Hindu |access-date=30 March 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150330064030/http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-reviews/chappie-chittis-hollywood-cousin/article6993688.ece |archive-date=30 March 2015}}</ref> [[Russo brothers|Joe Russo]], who co-directed ''[[Avengers: Infinity War]]'' (2018), said the sequence in ''Enthiran'' where numerous clones of Chitti come together to form a giant snake inspired a similar scene in ''Infinity War''{{'}}s predecessor ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron|Age of Ultron]]'' (2015) where the titular antagonist, [[Ultron]] and his clones come together to form a gigantic version of himself, but that the scene was cut from the final version of the film to accommodate its runtime.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://scroll.in/reel/918568/what-to-expect-as-the-countdown-to-avengers-endgame-begins-the-cost-of-being-a-hero |title=What to expect as the countdown to 'Avengers: Endgame' begins: 'The cost of being a hero' |last=Raman |first=Sruthi Ganapathy |date=1 April 2019 |work=[[Scroll.in]] |access-date=2 April 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402140056/https://scroll.in/reel/918568/what-to-expect-as-the-countdown-to-avengers-endgame-begins-the-cost-of-being-a-hero |archive-date=2 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/hollywood/avengers-endgame-director-joe-russo-confirms-marvel-is-talking-to-priyanka-chopra-about-future-project/story-Ty0qzYYZeLzZgQ8xWFchCM.html |title=Avengers: Endgame director Joe Russo confirms he is 'talking to Priyanka Chopra' about future project |last=Naahar |first=Rohan |date=1 April 2019 |work=Hindustan Times |access-date=2 April 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402135840/https://www.hindustantimes.com/hollywood/avengers-endgame-director-joe-russo-confirms-marvel-is-talking-to-priyanka-chopra-about-future-project/story-Ty0qzYYZeLzZgQ8xWFchCM.html |archive-date=2 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Standalone sequel ==\n{{Main|2.0 (film)}}\nIn September 2015, writer [[B. Jeyamohan]] announced that the pre-production stage of a standalone sequel to ''Enthiran'' was \"going on in full swing\" and that principal photography would commence once Rajinikanth finished filming for ''Kabali'', by the end of that year.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Enthiran-sequel-to-start-filming-by-the-end-of-this-year/articleshow/48773748.cms |title=Enthiran sequel to start filming by the end of this year |last=Sidhardhan |first=Sanjith |date=3 September 2015 |work=The Times of India |access-date=9 September 2015 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6bPO73muw?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Enthiran-sequel-to-start-filming-by-the-end-of-this-year/articleshow/48773748.cms |archive-date=9 September 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Nirav Shah]] would be the cinematographer and A. R. Rahman would return as music director, while Muthuraj would handle the art direction. The sequel would be shot in 3D, unlike its predecessor which was shot in 2D and converted to 3D in post-production.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/rajinikanths-endhiran-2-be-shot-3d-649656 |title=Rajinikanth's 'Endhiran 2' to be shot in 3D |last=Upadhyaya |first=Prakash |date=8 October 2015 |website=International Business Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151012070359/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/rajinikanths-endhiran-2-be-shot-3d-649656 |archive-date=12 October 2015 |access-date=12 October 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> Titled ''2.0'', the film entered production in December 2015 and was released on 29 November 2018. Rajinikanth reprised his role as Vaseegaran and Chitti with the additional cast played by [[Akshay Kumar]] and [[Amy Jackson]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/rajinikanths-vaseegaran-look-enthiran-2-endhiran-revealed-photos-659843 |title=Rajinikanth's Vaseegaran look in 2.0 (Enthiran 2, Endhiran) revealed [PHOTOS] |last=Upadhyaya |first=Prakash |date=17 December 2015 |website=International Business Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151218131706/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/rajinikanths-vaseegaran-look-enthiran-2-endhiran-revealed-photos-659843 |archive-date=18 December 2015 |access-date=18 December 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movie-reviews/2-0/movie-review/66858163.cms |title=2.0 Movie Review |last=Suganth |first=M. |date=29 November 2018 |work=The Times of India |access-date=29 November 2018 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20181129130545/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movie-reviews/2-0/movie-review/66858163.cms |archive-date=29 November 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |title=Rajinikanth: The Definitive Biography |title-link=Rajinikanth: The Definitive Biography |last=Ramachandran |first=Naman |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |year=2014 |isbn=978-81-8475-796-5 |edition=2nd |location=New Delhi |ref=harv |author-link=Naman Ramachandran |orig-year=2012}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|1305797|Enthiran}}\n* [https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?id=_fENDHIRAN01 ''Enthiran''] at [[Box Office Mojo]]\n\n{{Portal bar|Film|India}}\n{{Enthiran franchise}}\n{{National Film Award Best Special Effects}}\n{{S. Shankar}}\n\n[[Category:2010 films]]\n[[Category:2010s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:2010s science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:Android (robot) films]]\n[[Category:Films about artificial intelligence]]\n[[Category:Enthiran| ]]\n[[Category:Films directed by S. Shankar]]\n[[Category:Films involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n[[Category:Films scored by A. R. Rahman]]\n[[Category:Films set in Chennai]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 2030s]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Himachal Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Peru]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Special Effects National Film Award]]\n[[Category:Films whose production designer won the Best Production Design National Film Award]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:Robot films]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n", "name_user": "Arun2984", "label": "safe", "comment": "I create a information about the box office collection of this flim", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enthiran"}
{"title_page": "Ramakant Yadav (politician)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2009}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Ramakant Yadav\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1957|7|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Azamgarh]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[India]]\n| residence = [[Azamgarh]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| constituency = [[Azamgarh (Lok Sabha constituency)|Azamgarh]]\n| office = \n| term =\n| predecessor =\n| successor =\n| party = [[Indian National Congress ]]\n| religion = hindu\n| spouse = Ranjana Yadav\n| children = 2 sons and 1 daughter\n| website = \n| footnotes = \n| date = 17 September |\n| year =2000 | \n| source =  http://india.gov.in/govt/loksabhampdetail.php?mpcode=531 \n}}\n\n'''Ramakant Yadav'''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://archive.india.gov.in/govt/loksabhampbiodata.php?mpcode=531|title=Ramakant Yadav|last=|first=|date=|work=Indian Government Archive|access-date=}}</ref> (born 1 July 1957) is an [[List of political parties in India|Indian politician]] for the [[Azamgarh (Lok Sabha constituency)]] in [[Uttar Pradesh]].\n\nRamakant Yadav had switched from the [[Samajwadi Party]] to the [[Bahujan Samaj Party]] in 2004 parliament elections,<ref name=\"elect\">{{cite web|title=Azamgarh(Uttar Pradesh) Lok Sabha Election Results 2014 with Sitting MP and Party Name|url=http://www.elections.in/uttar-pradesh/parliamentary-constituencies/azamgarh.html|website=www.elections.in|publisher=elections.in|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"OIH\">{{cite news|title=\u092f\u0942\u092a\u0940 \u0935\u093f\u0927\u093e\u0928\u0938\u092d\u093e \u091a\u0941\u0928\u093e\u0935 2017: \u0906\u0916\u093f\u0930 \u0930\u092e\u093e\u0915\u093e\u0902\u0924 \u092f\u093e\u0926\u0935 \u0928\u0947 \u0930\u093e\u091c\u0928\u093e\u0925 \u0938\u093f\u0902\u0939 \u0938\u0947 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u094b\u0902 \u0932\u093f\u092f\u093e \u092a\u0902\u0917\u093e?|url=http://hindi.oneindia.com/news/features/rajnath-singh-are-anti-backward-former-azamgarh-mp-ramakant-yadav-why-380310.html|accessdate=19 March 2017|work=hindi.oneindia.com|agency=One India Hindi|publisher=One India Hindi|language=hi}}</ref> before finally joining the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] in 2008.<ref name=\"Patrika1\">{{cite news|title=Ex MP Ramakant yadav will stop Mulayam Singh Yadav in UP Election 2017|url=http://www.patrika.com/news/azamgarh/difficult-way-for-mulayam-singh-yadav-in-azamgarh-1300378/|accessdate=19 March 2017|work=www.patrika.com|agency=Patrika|publisher=Patrik|date=2016-05-18|language=en}}</ref> [[Samajwadi Party]] supremo [[Mulayam Singh Yadav]] fought [[Member of parliament]] election against Ramakant Yadav and was able to win with very low margin. It was challenging and surprising for all political analyzers. This was because of his great bond with people as he has the image of \"backward saviour\" .\n \nHe has a brother named Umakant Yadav, FORMER BSP MP. One of his sons  Arun Kumar Yadav is presently the BJP MLA from Phoolpur Pawai in district Azamgarh U.P.In 2019 he contested from Bhadohi loksabha seat on the Congress ticket but faced humiliating defeat. He got only 25000 votes.\n\n== Positions held ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|1985-95\n|Member, Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly (four terms)\n|-\n|1996\n|Elected to 11th Lok Sabha\n|-\n|1999\n|Re-elected to 13th Lok Sabha (2nd term)\n|-\n|1999-2004\n|Member, Committee on Commerce\n|-\n|2000-2004\n|Member, Consultative Committee, Ministry of Railways\n|-\n|2004\n|Re-elected to 14th Lok Sabha (3rd term)\n|-\n|2004-2008\n|Member, Committee on Food, Consumer Affairs & Public Distribution\n|-\n|2008\n|Ceased to be a member w.e.f. 28.1.2008\n|-\n|2009\n|Re-elected to 15th Lok Sabha (4th term)\n|-\n|31 Aug. 2009\n|Member, Committee on Food, Consumer Affairs and Public Distribution\n|-\n| 5 Oct 2019 \n| Join Samajwadi Party..\n\n|}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://india.gov.in/govt/loksabhampdetail.php?mpcode=531 Official biographical sketch in Parliament of India website]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yadav, Ramakant}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:People from Azamgarh]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:11th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:14th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:15th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:13th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:National Democratic Alliance candidates in the 2014 Indian general election]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Bahujan Samaj Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Samajwadi Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2009}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Ramakant Yadav\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1957|7|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Azamgarh]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[India]]\n| residence = [[Azamgarh]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| constituency = [[Azamgarh (Lok Sabha constituency)|Azamgarh]]\n| office = \n| term =\n| predecessor =\n| successor =\n| party = [[Indian National Congress ]]\n| religion = hindu\n| spouse = Ranjana Yadav\n| children = 2 sons and 1 daughter\n| website = \n| footnotes = \n| date = 17 September |\n| year =2000 | \n| source =  http://india.gov.in/govt/loksabhampdetail.php?mpcode=531 \n}}\n\n'''Ramakant Yadav'''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://archive.india.gov.in/govt/loksabhampbiodata.php?mpcode=531|title=Ramakant Yadav|last=|first=|date=|work=Indian Government Archive|access-date=}}</ref> (born 1 July 1957) is an [[List of political parties in India|Indian politician]] for the [[Azamgarh (Lok Sabha constituency)]] in [[Uttar Pradesh]].\n\nRamakant Yadav had switched from the [[Samajwadi Party]] to the [[Bahujan Samaj Party]] in 2004 parliament elections,<ref name=\"elect\">{{cite web|title=Azamgarh(Uttar Pradesh) Lok Sabha Election Results 2014 with Sitting MP and Party Name|url=http://www.elections.in/uttar-pradesh/parliamentary-constituencies/azamgarh.html|website=www.elections.in|publisher=elections.in|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"OIH\">{{cite news|title=\u092f\u0942\u092a\u0940 \u0935\u093f\u0927\u093e\u0928\u0938\u092d\u093e \u091a\u0941\u0928\u093e\u0935 2017: \u0906\u0916\u093f\u0930 \u0930\u092e\u093e\u0915\u093e\u0902\u0924 \u092f\u093e\u0926\u0935 \u0928\u0947 \u0930\u093e\u091c\u0928\u093e\u0925 \u0938\u093f\u0902\u0939 \u0938\u0947 \u0915\u094d\u092f\u094b\u0902 \u0932\u093f\u092f\u093e \u092a\u0902\u0917\u093e?|url=http://hindi.oneindia.com/news/features/rajnath-singh-are-anti-backward-former-azamgarh-mp-ramakant-yadav-why-380310.html|accessdate=19 March 2017|work=hindi.oneindia.com|agency=One India Hindi|publisher=One India Hindi|language=hi}}</ref> before finally joining the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] in 2008.<ref name=\"Patrika1\">{{cite news|title=Ex MP Ramakant yadav will stop Mulayam Singh Yadav in UP Election 2017|url=http://www.patrika.com/news/azamgarh/difficult-way-for-mulayam-singh-yadav-in-azamgarh-1300378/|accessdate=19 March 2017|work=www.patrika.com|agency=Patrika|publisher=Patrik|date=2016-05-18|language=en}}</ref> [[Samajwadi Party]] supremo [[Mulayam Singh Yadav]] fought [[Member of parliament]] election against Ramakant Yadav and was able to win with very low margin. It was challenging and surprising for all political analyzers. This was because of his great bond with people as he has the image of \"backward saviour\" .\n \nHe has a brother named Umakant Yadav, FORMER BSP MP. One of his sons  Arun Kumar Yadav is presently the BJP MLA from Phoolpur Pawai in district Azamgarh U.P.In 2019 he contested from Bhadohi loksabha seat on the Congress ticket but faced humiliating defeat. He got only 25000 votes.\n\n== Positions held ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|1985-95\n|Member, Uttar Pradesh Legislative Assembly (four terms)\n|-\n|1996\n|Elected to 11th Lok Sabha\n|-\n|1999\n|Re-elected to 13th Lok Sabha (2nd term)\n|-\n|1999-2004\n|Member, Committee on Commerce\n|-\n|2000-2004\n|Member, Consultative Committee, Ministry of Railways\n|-\n|2004\n|Re-elected to 14th Lok Sabha (3rd term)\n|-\n|2004-2008\n|Member, Committee on Food, Consumer Affairs & Public Distribution\n|-\n|2008\n|Ceased to be a member w.e.f. 28.1.2008\n|-\n|2009\n|Re-elected to 15th Lok Sabha (4th term)\n|-\n|31 Aug. 2009\n|Member, Committee on Food, Consumer Affairs and Public Distribution\n|-\n| 5 Oct 2019 \n| Join Samajwadi Party..\n\n|}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://india.gov.in/govt/loksabhampdetail.php?mpcode=531 Official biographical sketch in Parliament of India website]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yadav, Ramakant}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:People from Azamgarh]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:11th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:14th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:15th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:13th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:National Democratic Alliance candidates in the 2014 Indian general election]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Uttar Pradesh]]\n", "name_user": "Jaywardhan009", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ramakant_Yadav_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "Post-traumatic amnesia", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = <!--{{PAGENAME}} by default-->\n| synonym         = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| pronounce       = \n| specialty       = psychiatry, neurology, neuropsychology\n| symptoms        =\n| complications   =\n| onset           =\n| duration        =\n| types           = \n| causes          =\n| risks           =\n| diagnosis       =\n| differential    =\n| prevention      =\n| treatment       =\n| medication      =\n| prognosis       =\n| frequency       =\n| deaths          =\n}}\n'''Post-traumatic amnesia''' ('''PTA''') is a state of [[mental confusion|confusion]] that occurs immediately following a [[traumatic brain injury]] (TBI) in which the injured person is [[Orientation (mental)|disoriented]] and unable to remember events that occur after the [[physical injury|injury]].<ref name=LeeLK07>\n{{cite journal |author=Lee LK |title=Controversies in the sequelae of pediatric mild traumatic brain injury |journal=Pediatric Emergency Care |volume=23 |issue=8 |pages=580\u201383; quiz 584\u201386 |year=2007 |pmid=17726422 |doi=10.1097/PEC.0b013e31813444ea\n}}\n</ref>  The person may be unable to state their name, where they are, and what time it is.<ref name=LeeLK07/>  When continuous memory returns, PTA is considered to have resolved.<ref name=Petchprapai07>\n{{cite journal |vauthors=Petchprapai N, Winkelman C |title=Mild Traumatic Brain Injury: Determinants and Subsequent Quality of Life. A Review of the Literature |journal=Journal of Neuroscience Nursing |volume=39 |issue=5 |pages=260\u2013272 |year=2007 |pmid=17966292 |doi=10.1097/01376517-200710000-00002\n}}\n</ref>  While PTA lasts, new events cannot be stored in the memory.<ref name=vanderNaalt>\n{{cite journal |author=van der Naalt J |title=Prediction of outcome in mild to moderate head injury: A review |journal=Journal of Clinical and Experimental Neuropsychology |volume=23 |issue=6 |pages=837\u2013851 |year=2001 |pmid=11910548 |doi=10.1076/jcen.23.6.837.1018 \n}}\n</ref> About a third of patients with [[mild head injury]] are reported to have \"islands of memory\", in which the patient can recall only some events.<ref name=vanderNaalt/> During PTA, the patient's consciousness is \"clouded\".<ref name=Silver05>\n{{cite book|vauthors=Trzepacz PT, Kennedy RE |chapter=Delerium and Posttraumatic Amnesia |veditors=Silver JM, McAllister TW, Yudofsky SC |year=2005 | title=Textbook Of Traumatic Brain Injury |publisher=American Psychiatric Pub., Inc |isbn=978-1-58562-105-7 |pages=175\u2013176\n|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3CuM6MviwMAC&pg=PR13&dq=%22Silver%22+%22Textbook+Of+Traumatic+Brain+Injury%22+ |accessdate=2008-03-06\n}}\n</ref>  Because PTA involves confusion in addition to the memory loss typical of amnesia, the term ''\"post-traumatic confusional state\"'' has been proposed as an alternative.<ref name=Silver05/>\n\nThere are two types of [[amnesia]]:  [[retrograde amnesia]] (loss of memories that were formed shortly before the injury) and [[anterograde amnesia]] (problems with creating new memories after the injury has taken place).<ref name=Shaw02>\n{{cite journal |author=Shaw NA |title=The Neurophysiology of Concussion |journal=Progress in Neurobiology |volume=67 |issue=4 |pages=281\u2013344 |year=2002 |pmid=12207973 |doi=10.1016/S0301-0082(02)00018-7\n}}\n</ref> Both retrograde and anterograde forms may be referred to as PTA,<ref name=cantu01>\n{{cite journal|author=Cantu RC |year=2001 |pmc=155413 |title=Posttraumatic Retrograde and Anterograde Amnesia: Pathophysiology and Implications in Grading and Safe Return to Play |journal=Journal of Athletic Training |volume=36 |issue=3 |pages=244\u2013248 |pmid=12937491 \n}}\n</ref> or the term may be used to refer only to anterograde amnesia.<ref name=sivak>\n{{cite journal |vauthors=Siv\u00e1k \u0160, Kur\u010da E, Jan\u010dovi\u010d D, Petri\u0161\u010d\u00e1k \u0160, Ku\u010dera P |year=2005 |url=http://www.clsjep.cz/odkazy/clc0507_445.pdf |title=An Outline of the Current Concepts of Mild Brain Injury with Emphasis on the Adult Population |journal=\u010casopis L\u00e9ka\u0159\u016f \u010cesk\u00fdch |volume=144 |issue=7 |pages=445\u2013450 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080227161612/http://www.clsjep.cz/odkazy/clc0507_445.pdf |archivedate=2008-02-27 }}\n</ref>\n\nA common example in sports concussion is the quarterback who was able to conduct the complicated mental tasks of leading a [[football team]] after a concussion, but has no recollection the next day of the part of the game that took place after the injury.   Retrograde amnesia sufferers may partially regain memory later, but memories are not regained with anterograde amnesia because they were not [[Encoding (memory)|encoded]] properly.<ref name=Rees03/>\n\nThe term \"post-traumatic amnesia\" was first used in 1940 in a paper by Symonds to refer to the period between the injury and the return of full, continuous memory, including any time during which the patient was unconscious.<ref>Symonds CP. Concussion and contusion of the brain and their\nsequelae. In: Brock S, ed. Injuries of the Skull, Brain and Spinal Cord:\nNeuro-Psychiatric, Surgical, andMedico-Legal Aspects. London, UK:\nBailliere, Tindall and Cox; 1940:69\u2013111.</ref>\n\n==Symptoms==\n[[File:Headscratcher.png|thumb|A common symptom of PTA is confusion.]]\n\nThe most prominent symptom of post-traumatic amnesia (PTA) is a loss of [[memory]] of the present time.<ref name = Headway/> As a result, patients are often unaware of their condition and may behave as if they are going about their regular lives. This can cause complications if patients are confined to a hospital and may lead to agitation, distress and [[anxiety]].<ref name = Headway/> Many patients report feeling as though they were being \"held prisoner\" and being prevented from carrying on with their daily lives.<ref name = Headway/> Other symptoms include agitation, [[confusion]], [[disorientation]], and restlessness.<ref name = Metting >{{cite journal |author1=Metting Z. |author2=Rodiger L. A. |author3=de Jong B. M. |author4=Stewart R. E. |author5=Kremer B. P. |author6=Naalt J. V. | year = 2010 | title = Acute cerebral perfusion CT abnormalities associated with posttraumatic amnesia in mild head injury | url = | journal = Journal of Neurotrauma | volume = 27 | issue = 12| pages = 2183\u20132189 | doi = 10.1089/neu.2010.1395 |pmid=20939700 }}</ref>\n\nPatients also often display behavioral disturbances. Patients may shout, swear and behave in a disinhibited fashion.<ref name = Headway/> There have been cases in which patients who do not recognize anyone will ask for family members or acquaintances that they have not seen in years.<ref name = Headway/> Some patients exhibit childlike behavior.<ref name = Headway/> Other patients show uncharacteristically quiet, friendly and loving behavior. Although this behavior may seem less threatening because of its lack of aggressiveness, it may be equally worrisome.<ref name = Headway/>\n\nPTA patients are often unaware of their surroundings and will ask questions repeatedly.<ref name = Headway/> Patients may also have a tendency to wander off, which can be a major concern in those who have suffered additional injuries at the time of trauma, such as injured limbs, as it may lead to the worsening of these secondary injuries.<ref name = Headway/>\n\n===Attention===\n\n[[Attention]] is a cognitive resource that contributes to many mental functions. The ability to engage attention requires a certain level of conscious awareness, arousal and concentration, all mechanisms that are generally impaired by traumatic brain injury.<ref name=Tittle>{{cite journal | author = Tittle A., Burgess G. H. | year = 2011 | title = Relative contribution of attention and memory toward disorientation or post-traumatic amnesia in an acute brain injury sample | url = | journal = Brain Injury | volume = 25 | issue = 10| pages = 933\u2013942 | doi=10.3109/02699052.2011.597042| pmid = 21749193 }}</ref>  The involvement of attention in such a vast array of cognitive processes has led to the suggestion that attentional deficit may act as an underlying factor in the range of cognitive deficits observed in patients experiencing post-traumatic amnesia (PTA).\n\nAttention has been regarded as an important factor in the healthy functioning of encoding, verbal comprehension and new learning.<ref name=Tittle/> Automatic attention processes (such as counting forwards) are recovered before simple memory skills (such as a recognition test of verbal material) in individuals with mild to moderate brain injury.<ref name=Tittle/> This implies that the recovery of attentional ability precedes the progression of memory recovery after injury, helping to pave the way to regain ability for new learning. In terms of more severe brain injuries, this automatic attention task performance recovers before disorientation completely resolves.<ref name=Tittle/>\n\nOne of the weaknesses of the method most often used in assessing PTA, the Galveston Orientation and Amnesia Test (GOAT), is that it does not include any assessment of attention, which could help give a better indication of potential for recovery. By omitting attention, the test is omitting some crucial aspects of a person's cognitive capabilities.\n\nIn addition, assessing attention during the period of PTA may help determine whether the patient is still in a state of PTA or if they are suffering from a more permanent form of memory deficit.<ref name=Tittle/> In patients with mild TBI, the damage consists primarily of [[diffuse axonal injury]] (widespread damage to white matter) without any focal damage (damage to specific areas). Sometimes, injury of the [[brainstem]] was also observed. In these cases, there is likely the presence of an attentional deficit without a true amnesiac state. In more severely brain-damaged individuals, the damage to the [[temporal lobes]] and the [[frontal lobes]] serves as good indication that amnesia will result.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Stuss D. T. |author2=Binns M. A. |author3=Carruth F. G. |author4=Levine B. |author5=Brandys C. E. |author6=Moulton R. J. |author7=Snow W. G. |author8=Schwartz M. L. | year = 1999 | title = The Acute period of recovery from traumatic brain injury: Posttraumatic amnesia or posttraumatic confusional state? | url = | journal = Journal of Neurosurgery | volume = 90 | issue = 4| pages = 635\u2013643 | doi=10.3171/jns.1999.90.4.0635|pmid=10193606 }}</ref> Patients suffering from more chronic forms of memory impairment showed poor performance when tested with PTA scales, making differentiation between the two types of memory impairment very difficult. PTA patients exhibit poor simple [[reaction time]], reduced information processing speed and reduced verbal fluency, which are all attentional deficits that could be used to distinguish these patients from those suffering from more severe and permanent memory problems.<ref name=Tittle/>\n\n===Communication skills===\nThe effects of PTA on communication skills were studied using the Revised Edinburgh Functional Communication Profile (REFCP), which measures both linguistic elements (related to speech) and [[pragmatics|pragmatic]] elements (related to body language and other non-verbal communication skills).<ref name = Deal>{{cite journal | author = Deal R. A., Hough M. S., Walker M., Rastatter M., Hudson S., King K. A. | year = 2010 | title = Post-Traumatic Amnesia Duration after Traumatic Brain Injury: Relationship to Outcome of Pragmatic Skills during Chronic Phases of Recovery | url = | journal = Journal of Medical Speech-Language Pathology | volume = 18 | issue = 1| pages = 35\u201347 }}</ref> PTA has effects on memory, [[perception]] and attention, which are all important for communication. Patients showed mild deficits in verbal communication skills, and moderate to severe deficits in nonverbal communication skills such as maintaining eye contact, initiating greetings, and responding appropriately.<ref name = Deal/> Also, a negative correlation was found between the duration of a patient's episode of PTA and his REFCP score; the longer the PTA episode, the more severe the deficit in non-linguistic pragmatic skills. However, the small sample size of this study (only 10 males) means that the results must be interpreted with caution, as they may not generalize to larger samples or to the population at large.\n\n==Pathophysiology==\n[[Pathophysiology]] is the study of the changes to an individual's normal physical, biological, and mental functions as a result of disease, injury, or other damage. Currently, the [[pathophysiological]] mechanisms which produce post-traumatic amnesia are not completely known. The most common research strategy to clarify these mechanisms is the  examination of the impaired functional capabilities of people with post-traumatic amnesia (PTA) after a traumatic brain injury.<ref name = Ahmed>{{cite journal |author1=Ahmed S. |author2=Bierley R. |author3=Sheikh J. I. |author4=Date E. S. | year = 2000 | title = Post-traumatic amnesia after closed head injury: A review of the literature and some suggestions for further research | url = | journal = Brain Injury | volume = 14 | issue = 9| pages = 765\u2013780 | doi = 10.1080/026990500421886 }}</ref>\n\n===Neurological mechanisms===\n[[File:Hippocampus.gif|thumb|left|Hippocampus (animation)]]\nResearch on the effect of emotional trauma on memory retention and amnesic symptoms has shown that exposure to prolonged levels of extreme stress has a direct effect on the [[hippocampus]]. Elevated [[stress (psychological)|stress]] levels can lead to an increase in the production of [[enkephalins]] and [[corticosteroids]], which can produce abnormal neural activity and disrupt [[long-term potentiation]] (a neural mechanism associated with learning) in the hippocampus.<ref name = Joseph/> Individuals who have been subjected to repeated sexual abuse during childhood or who have experienced combat show significant impairment and atrophy of the hippocampal region of the brain.<ref name = Joseph>{{cite journal | author = Joseph R | year = 1998 | title = Traumatic amnesia, repression, and hippocampus injury due to emotional stress, corticosteroids and enkephalins | url = | journal = Child Psychiatry and Human Development | volume = 29 | issue = 2| pages = 169\u2013185 | doi = 10.1023/A:1025092117657 }}</ref>  The [[amygdala]], an area of the brain involved in emotional regulation, may be involved in producing remembrance for some aspects of the trauma.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Roozendaal B. |author2=Mcewen B. S. |author3=Chattarji S. | year = 2009 | title = Stress, memory and the amygdala | url = | journal = Nature Reviews Neuroscience | volume = 10 | issue = 6| pages = 423\u2013433 | doi=10.1038/nrn2651 | pmid=19469026}}</ref> Even though the trace of a memory for trauma may be lost from the hippocampus, it may remain partially encoded in the form of an emotional memory in the amygdala where it can be subsequently recalled in the form of a [[flashback (psychology)|flashback]] or partially [[recovered memory]].\n\n===Diaschisis===\n[[Diaschisis]] refers to the sudden dysfunction of portions of the brain due to lesions in distant but connected [[neurons]]. Diaschisis is implicated as playing an important role in PTA, more particularly in the [[declarative memory]] impairments observed in patients experiencing an episode of PTA. The loss of function observed after traumatic brain injuries, as well as the resulting loss of consciousness, was thought to be mediated by the 'neural shock' associated with diaschisis.<ref name = Feeney>{{cite journal | author = Feeney D. M., Baron J. C. | year = 1986 | title = Diaschisis | url = | journal = Stroke | volume = 17 | issue = 5| pages = 817\u2013830 | doi=10.1161/01.str.17.5.817}}</ref>\n\nDiaschisis was originally believed to be a result of disruption to neural tissue, but more recent evidence implicates increased activity levels of [[choline acetyltransferase]], the enzyme responsible for the production of [[acetylcholine]], as a major cause. Based on these findings, diaschisis could be helped through the use of drugs that would reduce cholinergic (acetylcholine) activity, and reduce the levels of acetylcholine in the brain.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Riese W | year = 1958 | title = The Principle of diaschisis: Its History, its nature, and its general significance | url = | journal = International Record of Medicine | volume = 171 | issue = | pages = 73\u201381 }}</ref> This idea is supported by the fact that there is an increase in acetylcholine concentrations in the brain after head injury. Animal studies have shown that concussive injuries in rats lead to changes in the [[central nervous system]]'s cholinergic system. This increase in acetylcholine levels has also been tied to behavioral suppression and unconsciousness, both symptoms of PTA. In long-term recovery, acetylcholine levels associated with diaschisis may continue to play a role in maintaining memory deficits.<ref name = Ahmed/>\n\n===Brain-imaging studies===\n[[Brain imaging]] techniques are useful for examining the changes in the brain that occur as a result of damage. Metting et al. (2001) used [[CT scans]] to examine the pathophyiological damage in patients currently experiencing an episode of PTA, patients with resolved PTA, and a [[control group]] that had not experienced PTA. Bloodflow to the [[occipital lobe]], the [[caudate nucleus]], and the [[grey matter]] of the frontal lobe was significantly reduced in patients who were scanned during the episode of PTA. No differences were seen between patients with resolved PTA and the control group.<ref name = Metting /> This encouraging finding points to the positive long term prognosis of PTA; most patients return to normal levels of functioning.<ref name = Metting /> The frontal lobes are associated with [[explicit memory]] [[memory retrieval|retrieval]], and deficits on explicit memory tasks are often found with patients experiencing PTA.\n\nWorking memory deficits are a common symptom in patients with PTA.  The duration of an episode of PTA was correlated with reduced bloodflow to the right [[Cerebral hemisphere|hemisphere]], a finding which was consistent with [[functional MRI]] studies that link [[working memory]] with right frontal activity.<ref name = Metting />  The [[prefrontal cortex]], which plays an important role in explicit memory retrieval, was also found to have decreased neural activation in patients scanned during the episode of PTA.<ref name = Metting /> Researchers noted that the damage was related to [[vascularization]] and neural functionality, but not to structural injury, suggesting that the resolution of PTA is dependent on functional changes.<ref name = Metting />\n\nMemory and new learning involve the [[cerebral cortex]], the subcortical projections, the [[hippocampus]], the [[diencephalon]] and the [[thalamus]], areas that often suffer damage as a result of TBI. Frontal lobe lesions may also play a role in PTA, as damage to these areas is associated with changes in behavior, including irritability, aggressiveness, disinhibition, and a loss of judgment.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Cantu R. C. | year = 2001 | title = Posttraumatic retrograde and anterograde amnesia: Pathophysiology and implications in grading and safe return to play | url = | journal = Journal of Athletic Training | volume = 36 | issue = 3| pages = 244\u2013248 | pmid = 12937491 | pmc = 155413 }}</ref> Damage to this area may account for the uncharacteristic behavior often exhibited in PTA patients.\n\n====Accelerated forgetting====\nResearchers have also found that individuals experiencing PTA show accelerated forgetting. This contrasts with the normal forgetting observed by patients with normal amnesia related to brain damage. The [[temporal lobes]] are often the most vulnerable to the diffuse (widely distributed) and focal (more specifically localized) effects of TBI and it is possible that temporal lobe lesions may account for the accelerated forgetting observed in patients with PTA. These predictions were supported by the finding that most of the patients who showed rapid forgetting also had lesions to the temporal lobe.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Levin H. S. |author2=High W. M. |author3=Eisenberg H. M. | year = 1988 | title = Learning and forgetting during posttraumatic amnesia in head injured patients | url = | journal = Journal of Neurology, Neurosurgery, and Psychiatry | volume = 51 | issue = 1| pages = 14\u201320 | doi=10.1136/jnnp.51.1.14|pmid=3351514 |pmc=1032708}}</ref> Bilateral damage to the temporal lobes also causes severe anterograde amnesia, making it likely that lesions to this area would be involved in PTA. Patients exhibit a temporal gradient with memory loss, meaning that older memories are preserved at the expense of newer memories. Temporal lobe damage has been linked to a temporal gradient of this sort, because older memories are less dependent on the hippocampus and thus are less influenced by its damage.<ref name = Ahmed />\n\nThere is a significant link between individuals currently suffering from PTA and their performance on the [[Wechsler Adult Intelligence Scale]] (WAIS). The scores of those currently experiencing an episode of PTA were compared to individuals who had previously suffered a traumatic brain injury resulting in PTA. Those still suffering from PTA performed significantly worse on both the performance and the verbal subscales of the WAIS.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Mandleberg I. A. | year = 1975 | title = Cognitive recovery after severe head injury: Wechsler Adult Intelligence Scale during post-traumatic amnesia | url = | journal = Journal of Neurology, Neurosurgery, and Psychiatry | volume = 38 | issue = 11| pages = 1127\u20131132 | doi=10.1136/jnnp.38.11.1127| pmid = 1206424 | pmc = 492168}}</ref> Also, people in early stages of PTA have substantial impairment to anterograde memory function. For example, in the [[case report]] of a patient referred to as \"JL\", Demery et al. noted that his memory impairments were so severe following his injury that he had forgotten that he had attended a [[Major League Baseball]] game less than 30 minutes after returning to the center where he was being treated.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Demery J. A. |author2=Hanlon R. E. |author3=Bauer R. M. | year = 2001 | title = Profound amnesia and confabulation following traumatic brain injury | url = | journal = Neurocase | volume = 7 | issue = 4| pages = 295\u2013302 | doi = 10.1093/neucas/7.4.295 |pmid=11557825 }}</ref>\n\nThe majority of neuropsychological studies available have suggested that the medial temporal lobes are the most important system in the pathophysiology of PTA. However, there is little research done on this topic, and as new research is done, more information should come forth concerning  functionality in these areas in PTA patients. One MRI study showed that a long duration of PTA was correlated with damage in the hemispheric and central areas, regardless of whether the duration of the coma  was relatively short. In patients who had a longer coma duration, deeper lesions in the central area were observed without extensive damage to the hemispheric area.<ref name = Ahmed />\n\n==Diagnosis==\n===Measure of traumatic brain injury severity===\n\n{| border=\"0\" align=\"right\"\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"right\" style = \"margin-left:15px; text-align:center;\"\n|+ ''' Levels of TBI severity'''<ref name=RaoLyketsos>\n{{cite journal |vauthors=Rao V, Lyketsos C |title=Neuropsychiatric Sequelae of Traumatic Brain Injury |journal=Psychosomatics |volume=41 |issue=2 |pages=95\u2013103 |year=2000 |pmid=10749946 |doi=10.1176/appi.psy.41.2.95 \n}}\n</ref>\n! &nbsp; !! GCS !! PTA !! LOC\n|-\n!Mild\n|align=\"center\" width=25%| 13\u201315 ||width=25%| < 1<br> hour || width=\"25%\" | < 30<br> minutes\n|-\n!Moderate\n| 9\u201312 || 30 minutes\u2013<br>24 hours || 1\u201324<br> hours\n|-\n! Severe\n| 3\u20138 || > 1 day || > 24 <br>hours\n|}\n|-\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style = \"float:right; margin-left:15px; text-align:left\"\n|+ '''TBI severity using PTA alone'''<ref name=Howieson04/>\n! Severity !! PTA \n|-\n! Very mild\n| < 5 minutes\n|-\n! Mild\n| 5\u201360 minutes\n|-\n! Moderate\n| 1\u201324 hours\n|-\n! Severe\n| 1\u20137 days\n|-\n! Very severe\n| 1\u20134 weeks\n|-\n! Extremely severe\n| > 4 weeks\n|}\n|}\nPTA has been proposed to be the best measure of head trauma severity,<ref name=Rees03>\n{{cite journal |author=Rees PM |title=Contemporary Issues in Mild Traumatic Brain Injury |journal=Archives of Physical Medicine and Rehabilitation |volume=84 |issue=12 |pages=1885\u20131894 |year=2003 |pmid=14669199 |doi=10.1016/j.apmr.2003.03.001 \n}}\n</ref> but it may not be a reliable indicator of outcome.<ref name=vanderNaalt/>\nHowever, PTA duration may be linked to the likelihood that psychiatric and behavioral problems will occur as consequences of TBI.<ref name=Silver05/>\n\nClassification systems for determining the severity of TBI may use duration of PTA alone or with other factors such as [[Glasgow Coma Scale]] (GCS) score and duration of [[loss of consciousness]] (LOC) to divide TBI into categories of mild, moderate, and severe.  One common system using all three factors and one using PTA alone are shown in the tables at right. Duration of PTA usually correlates well with GCS and usually lasts about four times longer than unconsciousness.<ref name=Howieson04>{{cite book |vauthors=Hannay HJ, Howieson DB, Loring DW, Fischer JS, Lezak MD |veditors=Lezak MD, Howieson DB, Loring DW |chapter=Neuropathology for neuropsychologists|title=Neuropsychological Assessment |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford [Oxfordshire] |year=2004 |pages=160 |isbn=978-0-19-511121-7 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nPTA is considered a hallmark of [[concussion]],<ref name=Rees03/> and is used as a measure of predicting its severity, for example in [[concussion grading scales]]. It may be more reliable for determining severity of concussion than GCS because the latter may not be sensitive enough; concussion sufferers often quickly regain a GCS score of 15.<ref name=vanderNaalt/>\n\nLonger periods of amnesia or loss of consciousness immediately after the injury may indicate longer recovery times from residual symptoms from concussion.<ref name=Masferrer>\n{{cite web|url=http://www.sadlersports.com/blog/concussion-rating-scale/|title=Concussion Grading Scale|date=2009-10-05|work=Sadler Sports & Recreation Insurance|author=Sadler, John M.}}</ref>\nIncreased duration of PTA is associated with a heightened risk for [[Complications of traumatic brain injury|TBI complications]] such as [[post-traumatic epilepsy]].<ref name=eepilepsy>\n{{cite web | url=http://www.e-epilepsy.org.uk/pages/articles/show_article.cfm?id=35 |title=Adult Onset Epilepsies |author=Chadwick D| publisher=E-epilepsy - Library of articles, National Society for Epilepsy |year=2005\n}} \n</ref>\n\n===Assessment===\nDuration of PTA may be difficult to gauge accurately; it may be overestimated (for example, if the patient is asleep or under the influence of drugs or alcohol for part of the time) or underestimated (for example, if some memories come back before continuous memory is regained).<ref name=vanderNaalt/>  The [https://web.archive.org/web/20121104060956/http://www.utmb.edu/psychology/Adultrehab/GOAT.htm Galveston Orientation and Amnesia Test] (GOAT) exists to determine how oriented a patient is and how much material they are able to recall.<ref name=Silver0563>\n{{cite book|vauthors=Silver JM, McAllister TW, Yudofsky SC |year=2005| title=Textbook Of Traumatic Brain Injury |publisher=American Psychiatric Pub., Inc |isbn=978-1-58562-105-7 |page=63\n}}\n</ref>\nThe GOAT is the most widely used standardized scale for the prospective assessment of PTA in the United States and Canada. The test is made up of 10 items that assess orientation and recollection of the events before and after the injury. It can be used to assess the duration of PTA; this particular GOAT assessment has been found to strongly predict functional outcome as measured by the [[Glasgow Outcome Scale]], return to productivity, psychosocial function and distress.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Baird A. |author2=Papadopoulou K. |author3=Greenwood R. |author4=Cipolotti L. | year = 2005 | title = Memory function after resolution of post-traumatic amnesia | url = | journal = Brain Injury | volume = 9 | issue = 10| pages = 811\u2013817 |doi=10.1080/02699050500149213 }}</ref>\n\nAn alternative to the GOAT is the [[Westmead Post-Traumatic Amnesia Scale]] (WPTAS)<ref name=\"Shores1986\">{{cite journal |author1=Shores E. A. |author2=Marosszeky J. E. |author3=Sandanam J. |author4=Batchelor J. | year = 1986 | title = Preliminary validation of a clinical scale for measuring the duration of post-traumatic amnesia | url = | journal = The Medical Journal of Australia | volume = 144 | issue = | pages = 569\u2013572 }}</ref><ref name=\"mqpta\">{{cite web | url=http://www.psy.mq.edu.au/pta | title=The PTA Protocol}}</ref> which examines not only orientation to person, place and time, but also crucially the ability to consistently remember new information from one day to the next. It consists of twelve questions (seven orientation questions, and five memory items) and is administered once daily, each and every day, until the patient scores a perfect score of 12/12 on three ''consecutive'' days. It is suitable for patients with moderate to severe traumatic brain injury. The WPTAS is the most common post-traumatic amnesia scale used in Australia and New Zealand.<ref name=\"Seeman2014\">{{cite journal | author = Seeman R | year = 2014 | title = Prediction of outcomes following severe traumatic brain injury | url = | journal = Critical Reviews in Physical and Rehabilitation Medicine | volume = 26 | issue = 1\u20132| pages = 13\u201325 | doi=10.1615/critrevphysrehabilmed.2014010603}}</ref> An abbreviated version has been developed to assess patients with mild traumatic brain injury, the [http://www.psy.mq.edu.au/gcs Abbreviated Westmead PTA Scale] (AWPTAS).<ref name=\"Meares2011\">{{cite journal |author1=Meares S. |author2=Shores E. A. |author3=Taylor A. J. |author4=Lammel A. |author5=Batchelor J. | year = 2011 | title = Validation of the Abbreviated Westmead Post-traumatic Amnesia Scale: A brief measure to identify acute cognitive impairment in mild traumatic brain injury | url = | journal = Brain Injury | volume = 25 | issue = 12| pages = 1198\u20131205 | doi=10.3109/02699052.2011.608213|pmid=21902551 }}</ref>\n\n===Testing===\nBefore the development of the current tests for the assessment of post-traumatic amnesia (PTA), a retrospective method was used to determine the patient's condition, consisting of one or more interviews with the patient after the episode of PTA was judged to be over. The retrospective method, however, fails to account for the apparent lucidity of patients who are still experiencing substantial disorientation, or the finding that the recovery from post-traumatic amnesia is often characterized by the presence of \"islands of memory\" (short periods of clarity).<ref name = Ahmed/> A failure to take these facts into consideration may have biased retrospective methods towards underestimating the length and severity of an episode of PTA.<ref name = Ahmed/> Also, the retrospective method relies on [[retrospective memory]], one's memory for past events, which is not very reliable in healthy individuals, and even less so in patients who have recently experienced a traumatic brain injury (TBI). Patients may also unconsciously or consciously bias their answers because they want to appear more healthy or more ill than they truly were, or because of poor insight.<ref name = Ahmed/> The retrospective method is also flawed because there is no standard measurement procedure.<ref name = Ahmed/> Although the retrospective method may provide useful subjective data, it is not a useful tool for measurement or categorization.\n\n====GOAT====\nThe Galveston Orientation and Amnesia Test (GOAT) is the most frequently used test for assessing PTA in the United States and Canada. The test consists of 10 items that involve the recall of events that occurred right before and after the injury, as well as questions about [[disorientation]]. Scores of 75 or more on this scale (out of a total possible score of 100) correspond to the termination  of the PTA episode. The GOAT typically classifies orientation into three categories: orientation to the person, orientation to the place, and orientation to the time. The idea behind these questions is that each of these classifications places a large demand on the patient's memory and learning abilities.<ref name = Ahmed/>\n\n====WPTAS and AWPTAS====\nThe [[Westmead Post-Traumatic Amnesia Scale]] (WPTAS)<ref name=\"Shores1986\"/><ref name=\"mqpta\"/> is commonly used in Australia and New Zealand.<ref name=\"Seeman2014\"/> It questions twelve questions that examine orientation to person, place and time, in addition to the ability to consistently remember new information from one day to the next. The scale is administered once each day, until the patient scores 12/12 on three consecutive days. The WPTAS is suitable for patients with moderate-to-severe traumatic brain injury. An abbreviated version of the WPTAS, the [http://www.psy.mq.edu.au/gcs Abbreviated Westmead PTA Scale] (AWPTAS) assesses patients with mild traumatic brain injury.<ref name=\"Meares2011\"/>\n\n=====Drawbacks=====\nAlthough the GOAT has proved useful in acute care, recent research has called attention to some of its drawbacks. The GOAT's assessment of orientation may put too much of a focus on memory as the main mechanism behind orientation. The range of cognitive and behavioral symptoms associated with PTA seems to indicate that the patient's disorientation is more than just a memory deficit. Consequently, it may be beneficial to incorporate tests of other cognitive functions, such as attention, which relate to both memory and orientation.<ref name=Tittle/>\n\nAnother recent study compared the success of the GOAT and the Orientation Log (O-Log) in predicting rehabilitation outcomes, and found that, while the O-Log and the GOAT perform similarly as measures of PTA severity and duration, the O-Log provides a more accurate picture of rehabilitation.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Frey K. L. |author2=Rojas D. C. |author3=Anderson C. A. |author4=Arciniegas D.B. | year = 2007 | title = Comparison of the O-Log and GOAT as measures of post-traumatic amnesia | url = | journal = Brain Injury | volume = 21 | issue = 5| pages = 513\u2013520 | doi=10.1080/02699050701311026|pmid=17522991 }}</ref>\n\nWhile the GOAT is a useful tool, these results suggest that using alternative methods of assessing PTA may increase the amount of information available to physicians and may help in predicting rehabilitative success. The international cognitive (INCOG) expert panel has recommended the use of a validated PTA scale such as the GOAT or WPTAS for assessing PTA duration in patients with moderate-to-severe traumatic brain injury on a daily basis.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Ponsford J. |author2=Janzen S. |author3=McIntyre A. |author4=Bayley M. |author5=Velikonja D. |author6=Tate R. | year = 2014 | title = INCOG Recommendations for Management of cognition Following Traumatic Brain Injury, Part I: Posttraumatic Amnesia/Delirium | url = | journal = J Head Trauma Rehabil | volume = 29 | issue = 4| pages = 307\u2013320 | doi=10.1097/htr.0000000000000074|pmid=24984094 }}</ref>\n\n===Severity===\nThe severity of post-traumatic amnesia (PTA) is directly related to its duration, although a longer duration does not necessarily indicate more severe symptoms.<ref name = Ahmed/> The duration of PTA in brain-injured patients is a useful predictor of the expected long-term effects of the injury,<ref name = \"K\u00f6nigs\">{{cite journal | pmid = 22791900 | doi=10.1136/jnnp-2012-302635 | volume=83 | issue=11 | title=Post-traumatic amnesia predicts intelligence impairment following traumatic brain injury: a meta-analysis |vauthors=K\u00f6nigs M, de Kieviet JF, Oosterlaan J | journal=J Neurol Neurosurg Psychiatry | pages=1048\u201355| year=2012 }}</ref> along with  the duration of [[loss of consciousness]](LOC), and scores on the [[Glasgow Coma Scale]] (GCS), which measures degrees of consciousness, with higher scores indicating higher levels of functioning. A score of three indicates complete unconsciousness, and a score of 15 indicates normal functioning.<ref name = Ahmed/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"right\" style=\"margin-left:15px; text-align:center;\"\n|+ ''' Levels of TBI severity'''<ref>{{cite journal | author = Rao V., Lyketsos C. | year = 2000 | title = Neuropsychiatric Sequelae of Traumatic Brain Injury | url = | journal = Psychosomatics | volume = 41 | issue = 2| pages = 95\u2013103 | doi = 10.1176/appi.psy.41.2.95 | pmid=10749946}}</ref>\n! &nbsp; !! GCS score !! duration of PTA !! duration of LOC\n|-\n!Mild\n|align=\"center\" width=25%| 13\u201315 || width=\"25%\" | < 1<br> hour ||width=25%| < 30<br> minutes\n|-\n!Moderate\n| 9\u201312 || 30 minutes \u2013 <br>24 hours || 1\u20132\n24<br> hours\n|-\n! Severe\n| 3\u20138 || > 1 day || > 24 <br>hours\n|}\nIn patients experiencing PTA for the duration of:\n\nUp to one hour \u2013 the injury is very mild in severity and full recovery is expected. The patient may experience a few minor post-concussive symptoms (e.g. headaches, dizziness).\n\n1\u201324 hours \u2013 the injury is moderate in severity and full recovery is expected. The patient may experience some minor post-concussive symptoms (e.g. headaches, dizziness).\n\n1\u20137 days \u2013 the injury is severe, and recovery may take weeks to months. The patient may be able to return to work, but may be less capable than before the injury.\n\n1\u20132 weeks \u2013 the injury is very severe, and recovery is likely to take many months. The patient is likely to experience long-lasting cognitive effects such as decreased verbal and nonverbal intelligence as well as decreased performance on visual tests. Patients should, however, still be able to return to work.\n\n2\u201312 weeks \u2013 the injury is very severe, and recovery is likely to take a year or more. The patient is likely to exhibit permanent deficits in memory and cognitive function, and the patient is unlikely to be able to return to work.\n\n12+ weeks \u2013 injury is very severe and accompanied by significant disabilities that will require long-term [[rehabilitation (neuropsychology)|rehabilitation]] and management. The patient is unlikely to be able to return to work.<ref name = Headway>Headway UK. (2008). ''Post-Traumatic Amnesia - Fact Sheet'' [Fact Sheet]. Retrieved from http://www.headway.org.uk/sitePages.asp?step=4&contentID=1334&navID=115.</ref>\n\nNote: return to work is meant to indicate a return to a reasonable level of functionality, both in professional and personal arenas.<ref name = Headway/>\n\nThe long-term [[prognosis]] of PTA is generally positive. Many patients do recover a great deal of cognitive function, although they may not return to their pre-injury state.<ref name = Headway/>\n\n==Treatment==\n[[File:Arginine vasopressin3d.png|thumb|A Vasopressin molecule]]\n\n===Vasopressin===\n\n====Animal research====\nEarly research pointed to [[vasopressin]] as a potential treatment for improving the memory of patients living with post-traumatic amnesia (PTA). [[Lysine]] vasopressin, a modified form of the vasopressin molecule, had positive effects on memory when administered by injection to patients with amnesia resulting from traumatic brain injury and [[Korsakoff's syndrome]].<ref>Oliveros, J. C., Jandali, M. K., Timsit-Berthier, M. et al. (1978). Vasopressin in amnesia. ''Lancet, 42.''</ref> Subsequent animal studies with rats found similar results, particularly in aversion and avoidance learning tasks. Rats lacking adequate vasopressin, either due to genetic defect or [[hypophysectomy]] (surgical removal of the pituitary gland), exhibited significant improvements in memory and learning functions when [[exogenous]] vasopressin was administered.<ref name = Eames>{{cite journal | author = Eames P., Wood R. L. | year = 1999 | title = Lysine vasopressin in post-traumatic memory disorders: an uncontrolled pilot study | url = | journal = Brain Injury | volume = 13 | issue = 4| pages = 255\u2013260 | doi=10.1080/026990599121629}}</ref> Particularly encouraging was the finding that a short treatment period produced long-lasting improvements, in both humans and rats.<ref name = Eames/> However, the animal models of PTA are highly limited, as the dimension of self-awareness and orientation is almost impossible to model adequately. PTA in animals, especially rats, is often observed post-trauma (commonly post-surgery), but it is often only measured in terms of impaired learning or unusual behavior.<ref name = Eames/>\n\n====Human studies====\nOne subsequent human study found no effects of vasopressin on memory.<ref>Jenkins, J. S., Mather, H. M., Coughlan, A. K., & Jenkins, D. G. (1981). Desmopressin and desglycinamide vasopressin in post-traumatic amnesia. ''Lancet, 39.''</ref> The nonsignificant results were attributed to the study's many potential flaws, particularly its small sample size, the inability of vasopressin to penetrate the [[blood brain barrier]] when administered as a nasal spray, inadequate dosing and differences in severity of head injury between the samples. However, Eames et al. (1999) found statistically significant improvements on several tests of memory with the use of a vasopressin nasal spray, with no reported ill effects.<ref name = Eames/> Although the degree of improvement was mild, and it could be attributed to numerous other factors of the rehabilitative program, the lack of any ill effects suggests that vasopressin is, at the least, a possible enhancement for a treatment regimen.<ref name = Eames/>\n\n===Norepinephrine agonists===\n[[Diaschisis]], as mentioned earlier, has been linked to the mechanism of PTA. The noradrenergic systems may play a role in diaschisis. [[Norepinephrine]], also known as noradrenalin, is a [[catecholamine]] [[neurotransmitter]].  Administering a norepinephrine receptor [[agonist]] (a substance that initiates a cell response when it binds with a receptor) to patients promoted the recovery of memory and many other cognitive functions after a traumatic brain injury.<ref name = Feeney/> Conversely,  the administration of norpinephrine [[antagonist]]s slowed recovery, and could lead to the reinstatement of deficits when administered after recovery. Noradrenergic antagonists were not prescribed for the purposes of slowing the recovery of memory. Rather, these findings are based on the effects of other commonly prescribed drugs that happen to block noradrenergic receptors. The [[alpha-1 adrenergic receptor]] is specifically implicated.<ref name = Feeney/> Although it has not yet been thoroughly investigated, there is potential for [[stimulants]], which promote catecholamine release, to be an effective treatment in the early stages of recovery from brain trauma, and these positive effects could reduce the symptoms of PTA.<ref name=\"pmid8959228\">{{cite journal |vauthors = Feeney DM |title=From laboratory to clinic: noradrenergic enhancement of physical therapy for stroke or trauma patients |journal=Adv Neurol |volume=73 |issue= |pages=383\u201394 |year=1997 |pmid=8959228 }}</ref>\n\n==Research==\n\n===The North Star Project ===\nThe North Star Project was developed by researchers at [[McGill University]]. Researchers developed a \"reality orientation\", which involved discussing general facts (e.g. date, time, names of family members, etc.) with amnesic patients twice a day in an attempt to lessen their confusion during the early stages of their recovery. Younger patients often had  shorter amnesic episodes than older patients, especially those in the North Star group. Although more improvements were noted in the North Star group than in the control group, researchers did not find a statistically significant effect of their intervention.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=De Guise E. |author2=Leblanc J. |author3=Feyz M. |author4=Thomas H. |author5=Gosselin N. | year = 2005 | title = Effect of an integrated reality orientation programme in acute care on post-traumatic amnesia in patients with traumatic brain injury | url = | journal = Brain Injury | volume = 19 | issue = 4| pages = 263\u2013269 | doi=10.1080/02699050400004971}}</ref>\n\n====Findings====\nA comprehensive analysis of literature based on the effects of early rehabilitation of traumatic brain injury concluded that there is no strong evidence linking any one particular practice of post-injury care to a reduced severity in symptoms. However,  even in the absence of a concrete correlation between a specific rehabilitation program and improved outcomes, the evidence and research available can provide many good suggestions for how to proceed with treatment. All rehabilitation strategies reviewed had positive effects on recovery, but none more so than the others.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Langhorn L. |author2=Sorensen J. C. |author3=Pedersen P. U. | year = 2010 | title = A critical review of the literature on early rehabilitation of patients with post-traumatic amnesia in acute care | url = | journal = Journal of Clinical Nursing | volume = 19 | issue = 21\u201322| pages = 2959\u20132969 | doi = 10.1111/j.1365-2702.2010.03330.x |pmid=21040002 }}</ref>\n\nThe most accurate measure of determining the length of amnesia is still the a behavioural measure, the duration of the episode of post-traumatic amnesia, rather than a neuroimaging technique or an electrophysiological or biochemical technique.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Greenwood R | year = 1997 | title = Value or recording duration of post-traumatic amnesia | url = | journal = The Lancet | volume = 349 | issue = 9058| pages = 1041\u20132 | doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(05)62288-x| pmid = 9107239 }}</ref>  The length of amnesia is also one of the most accurate predictors for determining later cognitive problems, even more so than the duration of either the coma or the period of loss of consciousness.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Ellenberg J. H. |author2=Levin H. S. |author3=Saydjari C. | year = 1996 | title = Post-traumatic amnesia as a predictor of outcome after severe closed head injury | url = | journal = Archives of Neurology | volume = 53 | issue = 8| pages = 782\u2013791 | doi=10.1001/archneur.1996.00550080104018}}</ref> The duration of amnesia after TBI, therefore, can be very useful in the planning the length and intensity of rehabilitation programs for persons afflicted with PTA.\n\n==History==\n\n===C.P. Symonds===\n\nAlthough Franklin described PTA, it was the British physician C. P. Symonds who first discussed the specific amnesiac symptoms that often follow a [[cerebral contusion]], which is a specific kind of traumatic brain injury. Symonds observed that the patient remains \"stuperose, restless and irritable\"<ref name = Symonds>{{cite journal | author = Symonds C. P. | year = 1928 | title = The differential diagnosis and treatment of cerebral states consequent upon head injuries | url = | journal = The British Medical Journal | volume = 2 | issue = 3540| pages = 829\u2013832 | doi=10.1136/bmj.2.3540.829| pmc = 2456401 | pmid=20774242}}</ref> after recovering consciousness. He also identified a recovery period of days to weeks for this post-concussive state.<ref name = Symonds/> Presumably, shorter durations of PTA, which are now included in the definition, were not thought to be serious enough for documentation. Most importantly, he identified the amnesia that the patient experiences during this period of recovery, and recommended the use of \"formal tests for memory and retention\" to assess recovery.<ref name = Symonds/>\n\n===In WWI soldiers===\n\n[[File:Shellshock2.jpg|thumb|left|Image from WWI, taken in an Australian dressing station near Ypres in 1917. The wounded soldier in the lower left of the photo has a dazed stare, a frequent symptom of \"shell shock\".]]\n\nAlthough there was a general lack of knowledge about its mechanisms, a review of patients seen during WWI combat reveals the symptoms of post-traumatic amnesia (PTA) in many soldiers. The term [[shell shock]] was used to refer to the acute psychological state that accompanied exposure to exploding shells, and more generally, exposure to combat conditions.<ref name = Hart>{{cite journal |author1=van der Hart O. |author2=Brown P. |author3=Graafland M. | year = 1999 | title = Trauma-induced dissociative amnesia in World War I combat soldiers | url = | journal = Australian and New Zealand Journal of Psychiatry | volume = 33 | issue = 1| pages = 37\u201346 | doi = 10.1046/j.1440-1614.1999.00508.x |pmid=10197884 }}</ref> There are a number of documented cases of shell shock victims. These soldiers commonly displayed dizziness, varying degrees of consciousness, a loss of non-traumatic personal information, and a lack of normal [[self-awareness]] lasting anywhere from hours to days. Many of the symptoms of shell shock are highly similar to those of PTA.<ref name=Hart/> The following excerpt from a case report illustrates the loss of personal information observed in one patient:\n{{cquote|A soldier was assessed three days after having been admitted into a field ambulance. He was unable to give his name, regiment, or number, and he could not be identified. He could remember being found on the outskirts of a village, but his military history and all events in his past including his childhood were a complete blank.<ref>Myers, 6, quoted in Hart, O. v. d., Brown, P., & Graafland, M. (1999). Trauma-induced dissociative amnesia in World War I combat soldiers. ''Australian and New Zealand Journal of Psychiatry'', 33 (1), 37-46. {{DOI|10.1046/j.1440-1614.1999.00508.x}}</ref>}}\n\nResearchers found that physicians had documented reports of combatants where \"[b]oth central and peripheral details of the traumatic experience were lost.\"<ref name=Hart /> Patients displayed gaps in memory recollection for the period following the trauma, sometimes up to the time of hospitalization, which could be weeks later.\n\nAn initial assessment supported the role of concussions in causing these symptoms. Concussions could account for the [[anterograde amnesia]] and [[retrograde amnesia]] observed in patients, as well as the periods of fluctuating consciousness or delirium that sometimes followed. However, many soldiers who showed these amnesiac effects did not suffer injuries that would have led to concussions.<ref name=Hart/> As a result, there was controversy over the possible causes of PTA in these non-concussed soldiers, with a separation between proponents of [[Freudian]] [[Psychological repression|repression]] and those supporting a [[dissociative]] view of the condition. This dissociative view was ultimately supported, and accounted for the [[fugue state]] seen in soldiers who were thought to have dissociated from normal consciousness.<ref name=Hart/>\n\n==Other psychological disorders ==\n\nResearchers have investigated the relationship between posttraumatic amnesia (PTA) resulting from traumatic brain injury (TBI) and the development of symptoms of [[posttraumatic stress disorder]] (PTSD) and [[acute stress disorder]] (ASD). 282 outpatients, who were an average of 53 days post-TBI in their recovery, were divided into four groups: PTA episode lasting less than one hour; PTA episode lasting between one hour and 24 hours; PTA episode lasting between 24 hours and one week; and PTA episode lasting for longer than one week. The patients' personal details were used as variables classified for age, gender, marital status, time elapsed between injury and assessment, and type of injury (motor vehicle accident, pedestrian, assault and other). Patients were given two [[self-report inventories]]: the Impact of Event Scale (IES) and the General Health Questionnaire (GHQ). The IES measures  symptoms of PTSD and contains questions regarding the intrusiveness of the traumatic event (ex. nightmares) and avoidant behaviours related to the traumatic event (ex. avoiding a certain location).<ref name =Feinstein/>  The GHQ was used as an indicator of overall psychological health.<ref name =Feinstein>{{cite journal | author = Feinstein A., Hershkop S., Ouchterlony D., Jardine A., McCullagh S. | year = 2002 | title = Posttraumatic amnesia and recall of a traumatic event following traumatic brain injury | url = | journal = Journal of Neuropsychiatry and Clinical Neurosciences | volume = 14 | issue = 1| pages = 25\u201330 | doi = 10.1176/appi.neuropsych.14.1.25 | pmid = 195251885 }}</ref> The majority of subjects were in Group 1 (PTA episode lasting less than one hour), injured in motor vehicle accidents, and male.\n\nThere were no statistical differences found with regards to age, gender, marital status and type of injury. There was an increase in the severity of all indicators of brain damage for the longest durations of PTA; specifically, the GCS scores for this group decreased and the number of patients with an abnormal CT scan increased.<ref name = Feinstein/> There were significant differences in IES scores when comparing the group with the least serious episode of PTA, lasting less than an hour, to all other groups, with the duration of the episode of PTA lasting longer than an hour. The group with an episode of PTA lasting less than an hour had higher IES scores and more intrusive and avoidant symptoms.<ref name = Feinstein/> The fact that GHQ scores were constant throughout all groups, although there were differences in IES scores, suggests that the two scores measure different phenomena.<ref name = Feinstein/>\n\n==Aging==\n[[File:Elderly Woman, B&W image by Chalmers Butterfield.jpg|thumb|left|An elderly woman]]\nGrey and white matter are both found in the many areas of the brain, as well as throughout the central nervous system. [[Grey matter]] is more involved in nerve function, and [[white matter]] is more involved in nerve maintenance,  as well as the regulation of unconscious functions. However, both are important for memory and learning. The volume of grey and white matter in the brains of aging individuals has been correlated with working memory and retention of cognitive function.<ref name = Schonberger/> Researchers hypothesized that the lesions of both grey and white matter would be larger in older individuals and in those with more severe traumatic brain injuries, and longer episodes of PTA, and the volume of grey and white matter would be smaller in those injured at an older age. A group of 98 participants, predominantly male, were examined using fMRI. The results supported these hypotheses, leading researchers to suggest that the impact of traumatic brain injury gets more severe as age progresses.<ref name = Schonberger>{{cite journal | author = Sch\u00f6nberger M., Ponsford J., Reutens D., Beare R., O'Sullivan R. | year = 2009 | title = The Relationship between age, injury, severity, and MRI findings after traumatic brain injury | url = | journal = Journal of Neurotrauma | volume = 26 | issue = 2| pages = 2157\u20132167 | doi = 10.1089/neu.2009.0939 }}</ref>\n\nAlthough grey and white matter volume was reduced throughout the brain, researchers noted that the grey matter of the [[neocortical]] brain regions was particularly affected.<ref name = Schonberger/> This is consistent with the fact that older individuals who had experienced PTA showed greater cognitive impairments than a control group of individuals of the same age who had not experienced PTA. The duration of the episode of PTA was related to the size of the grey matter lesion; longer episodes of PTA correlated with larger grey matter lesions. Advanced age also correlated with reduced [[glial]] activity. With less grey matter, the patient is less able to retrieve memories effectively, as neuron function is impaired.<ref name = Schonberger />\n\n==Controversies==\nOn the topic of trauma and memory, [[Richard McNally]] (2005) wrote that memories are not videotapes of our experiences, meaning that they are not unchangeable records.<ref name = Mcnally>{{cite journal | author = McNally R | year = 2005 | title = Debunking Myths about Trauma and Memory | url = | journal = Canadian Journal of Psychiatry | volume = 50 | issue = 13| pages = 817\u2013822 | doi = 10.1177/070674370505001302 | pmid = 16483114 }}</ref> The mechanism that retrieves a memory involves activation of several areas of the brain. Similarly, the mechanism that encodes a memory requires the use of different parts of the brain. Any fault in the encoding-retrieval system will degrade memory, and there are many potential faults, such as distortion by emotion, or focusing on the peripheral details at the expense of central details.<ref name = Mcnally/> An example of the latter is the well-known phenomenon where a person being robbed at gunpoint is so distracted by the gun that they don't have time to encode the robber's face.<ref name = Mcnally/>\n\nMisconstruing retrieval failure as traumatic amnesia is not the same phenomenon as post-traumatic amnesia, which describes amnesia for the current elapsing time post-trauma, not amnesia for trauma from the past. Typically, \"[[repressed memory]]\" is the term used to explain this sort of traumatic amnesia; the experience was so horrific that the adult cannot process what occurred years before.<ref name = Mcnally/> The topic of repressed memory is controversial within psychology; many clinicians argue for its importance, while researchers remain skeptical of its existence. A more viable explanation for this forgetting is [[childhood amnesia]], a phenomenon describing the fact that most children do not have recall of events in their lives before the age of three, partially due to the lack of development of cognitive elements such as language.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{memory}}\n\n[[Category:Amnesia]]\n[[Category:Medical signs]]\n[[Category:Neurotrauma]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = <!--{{PAGENAME}} by default-->\n| synonym         = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| pronounce       = \n| specialty       = psychiatry, neurology, neuropsychology\n| symptoms        =\n| complications   =\n| onset           =\n| duration        =\n| types           = \n| causes          =\n| risks           =\n| diagnosis       =\n| differential    =\n| prevention      =\n| treatment       =\n| medication      =\n| prognosis       =\n| frequency       =\n| deaths          =\n}}\n'''Post-traumatic amnesia''' ('''PTA''') is a state of [[mental confusion|confusion]] that occurs immediately following a [[traumatic brain injury]] (TBI) in which the injured person is [[Orientation (mental)|disoriented]] and unable to remember events that occur after the [[physical injury|injury]].<ref name=LeeLK07>\n{{cite journal |author=Lee LK |title=Controversies in the sequelae of pediatric mild traumatic brain injury |journal=Pediatric Emergency Care |volume=23 |issue=8 |pages=580\u201383; quiz 584\u201386 |year=2007 |pmid=17726422 |doi=10.1097/PEC.0b013e31813444ea\n}}\n</ref>  The person may be unable to state their name, where they are, and what time it is.<ref name=LeeLK07/>  When continuous memory returns, PTA is considered to have resolved.<ref name=Petchprapai07>\n{{cite journal |vauthors=Petchprapai N, Winkelman C |title=Mild Traumatic Brain Injury: Determinants and Subsequent Quality of Life. A Review of the Literature |journal=Journal of Neuroscience Nursing |volume=39 |issue=5 |pages=260\u2013272 |year=2007 |pmid=17966292 |doi=10.1097/01376517-200710000-00002\n}}\n</ref>  While PTA lasts, new events cannot be stored in the memory.<ref name=vanderNaalt>\n{{cite journal |author=van der Naalt J |title=Prediction of outcome in mild to moderate head injury: A review |journal=Journal of Clinical and Experimental Neuropsychology |volume=23 |issue=6 |pages=837\u2013851 |year=2001 |pmid=11910548 |doi=10.1076/jcen.23.6.837.1018 \n}}\n</ref> About a third of patients with [[mild head injury]] are reported to have \"islands of memory\", in which the patient can recall only some events.<ref name=vanderNaalt/> During PTA, the patient's consciousness is \"clouded\".<ref name=Silver05>\n{{cite book|vauthors=Trzepacz PT, Kennedy RE |chapter=Delerium and Posttraumatic Amnesia |veditors=Silver JM, McAllister TW, Yudofsky SC |year=2005 | title=Textbook Of Traumatic Brain Injury |publisher=American Psychiatric Pub., Inc |isbn=978-1-58562-105-7 |pages=175\u2013176\n|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3CuM6MviwMAC&pg=PR13&dq=%22Silver%22+%22Textbook+Of+Traumatic+Brain+Injury%22+ |accessdate=2008-03-06\n}}\n</ref>  Because PTA involves confusion in addition to the memory loss typical of amnesia, the term ''\"post-traumatic confusional state\"'' has been proposed as an alternative.<ref name=Silver05/>\n\nThere are two types of [[amnesia]]:  [[retrograde amnesia]] (loss of memories that were formed shortly before the injury) and [[anterograde amnesia]] (problems with creating new memories after the injury has taken place).<ref name=Shaw02>\n{{cite journal |author=Shaw NA |title=The Neurophysiology of Concussion |journal=Progress in Neurobiology |volume=67 |issue=4 |pages=281\u2013344 |year=2002 |pmid=12207973 |doi=10.1016/S0301-0082(02)00018-7\n}}\n</ref> Both retrograde and anterograde forms may be referred to as PTA,<ref name=cantu01>\n{{cite journal|author=Cantu RC |year=2001 |pmc=155413 |title=Posttraumatic Retrograde and Anterograde Amnesia: Pathophysiology and Implications in Grading and Safe Return to Play |journal=Journal of Athletic Training |volume=36 |issue=3 |pages=244\u2013248 |pmid=12937491 \n}}\n</ref> or the term may be used to refer only to anterograde amnesia.<ref name=sivak>\n{{cite journal |vauthors=Siv\u00e1k \u0160, Kur\u010da E, Jan\u010dovi\u010d D, Petri\u0161\u010d\u00e1k \u0160, Ku\u010dera P |year=2005 |url=http://www.clsjep.cz/odkazy/clc0507_445.pdf |title=An Outline of the Current Concepts of Mild Brain Injury with Emphasis on the Adult Population |journal=\u010casopis L\u00e9ka\u0159\u016f \u010cesk\u00fdch |volume=144 |issue=7 |pages=445\u2013450 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080227161612/http://www.clsjep.cz/odkazy/clc0507_445.pdf |archivedate=2008-02-27 }}\n</ref>\n\nA common example in sports concussion is the quarterback who was able to conduct the complicated mental tasks of leading a [[football team]] after a concussion, but has no recollection the next day of the part of the game that took place after the injury.   Retrograde amnesia sufferers may partially regain memory later, but memories are not regained with anterograde amnesia because they were not [[Encoding (memory)|encoded]] properly.<ref name=Rees03/>\n\nThe term \"post-traumatic amnesia\" was first used in 1940 in a paper by Symonds to refer to the period between the injury and the return of full, continuous memory, including any time during which the patient was unconscious.<ref>Symonds CP. Concussion and contusion of the brain and their\nsequelae. In: Brock S, ed. Injuries of the Skull, Brain and Spinal Cord:\nNeuro-Psychiatric, Surgical, andMedico-Legal Aspects. London, UK:\nBailliere, Tindall and Cox; 1940:69\u2013111.</ref>\n\n==Symptoms==\n[[File:Headscratcher.png|thumb|A common symptom of PTA is confusion.]]\n\nThe most prominent symptom of post-traumatic amnesia (PTA) is a loss of [[memory]] of the present time.<ref name = Headway/> As a result, patients are often unaware of their condition and may behave as if they are going about their regular lives. This can cause complications if patients are confined to a hospital and may lead to agitation, distress and [[anxiety]].<ref name = Headway/> Many patients report feeling as though they were being \"held prisoner\" and being prevented from carrying on with their daily lives.<ref name = Headway/> Other symptoms include agitation, [[confusion]], [[disorientation]], and restlessness.<ref name = Metting >{{cite journal |author1=Metting Z. |author2=Rodiger L. A. |author3=de Jong B. M. |author4=Stewart R. E. |author5=Kremer B. P. |author6=Naalt J. V. | year = 2010 | title = Acute cerebral perfusion CT abnormalities associated with posttraumatic amnesia in mild head injury | url = | journal = Journal of Neurotrauma | volume = 27 | issue = 12| pages = 2183\u20132189 | doi = 10.1089/neu.2010.1395 |pmid=20939700 }}</ref>\n\nPatients also often display behavioral disturbances. Patients may shout, swear and behave in a disinhibited fashion.<ref name = Headway/> There have been cases in which patients who do not recognize anyone will ask for family members or acquaintances that they have not seen in years.<ref name = Headway/> Some patients exhibit childlike behavior.<ref name = Headway/> Other patients show uncharacteristically quiet, friendly and loving behavior. Although this behavior may seem less threatening because of its lack of aggressiveness, it may be equally worrisome.<ref name = Headway/>\n\nPTA patients are often unaware of their surroundings and will ask questions repeatedly.<ref name = Headway/> Patients may also have a tendency to wander off, which can be a major concern in those who have suffered additional injuries at the time of trauma, such as injured limbs, as it may lead to the worsening of these secondary injuries.<ref name = Headway/>\n\n===Attention===\n\n[[Attention]] is a cognitive resource that contributes to many mental functions. The ability to engage attention requires a certain level of conscious awareness, arousal and concentration, all mechanisms that are generally impaired by traumatic brain injury.<ref name=Tittle>{{cite journal | author = Tittle A., Burgess G. H. | year = 2011 | title = Relative contribution of attention and memory toward disorientation or post-traumatic amnesia in an acute brain injury sample | url = | journal = Brain Injury | volume = 25 | issue = 10| pages = 933\u2013942 | doi=10.3109/02699052.2011.597042| pmid = 21749193 }}</ref>  The involvement of attention in such a vast array of cognitive processes has led to the suggestion that attentional deficit may act as an underlying factor in the range of cognitive deficits observed in patients experiencing post-traumatic amnesia (PTA).\n\nAttention has been regarded as an important factor in the healthy functioning of encoding, verbal comprehension and new learning.<ref name=Tittle/> Automatic attention processes (such as counting forwards) are recovered before simple memory skills (such as a recognition test of verbal material) in individuals with mild to moderate brain injury.<ref name=Tittle/> This implies that the recovery of attentional ability precedes the progression of memory recovery after injury, helping to pave the way to regain ability for new learning. In terms of more severe brain injuries, this automatic attention task performance recovers before disorientation completely resolves.<ref name=Tittle/>\n\nOne of the weaknesses of the method most often used in assessing PTA, the Galveston Orientation and Amnesia Test (GOAT), is that it does not include any assessment of attention, which could help give a better indication of potential for recovery. By omitting attention, the test is omitting some crucial aspects of a person's cognitive capabilities.\n\nIn addition, assessing attention during the period of PTA may help determine whether the patient is still in a state of PTA or if they are suffering from a more permanent form of memory deficit.<ref name=Tittle/> In patients with mild TBI, the damage consists primarily of [[diffuse axonal injury]] (widespread damage to white matter) without any focal damage (damage to specific areas). Sometimes, injury of the [[brainstem]] was also observed. In these cases, there is likely the presence of an attentional deficit without a true amnesiac state. In more severely brain-damaged individuals, the damage to the [[temporal lobes]] and the [[frontal lobes]] serves as good indication that amnesia will result.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Stuss D. T. |author2=Binns M. A. |author3=Carruth F. G. |author4=Levine B. |author5=Brandys C. E. |author6=Moulton R. J. |author7=Snow W. G. |author8=Schwartz M. L. | year = 1999 | title = The Acute period of recovery from traumatic brain injury: Posttraumatic amnesia or posttraumatic confusional state? | url = | journal = Journal of Neurosurgery | volume = 90 | issue = 4| pages = 635\u2013643 | doi=10.3171/jns.1999.90.4.0635|pmid=10193606 }}</ref> Patients suffering from more chronic forms of memory impairment showed poor performance when tested with PTA scales, making differentiation between the two types of memory impairment very difficult. PTA patients exhibit poor simple [[reaction time]], reduced information processing speed and reduced verbal fluency, which are all attentional deficits that could be used to distinguish these patients from those suffering from more severe and permanent memory problems.<ref name=Tittle/>\n\n===Communication skills===\nThe effects of PTA on communication skills were studied using the Revised Edinburgh Functional Communication Profile (REFCP), which measures both linguistic elements (related to speech) and [[pragmatics|pragmatic]] elements (related to body language and other non-verbal communication skills).<ref name = Deal>Deal, R. A., Hough, M. S., Walker, M., Rastatter, M., Hudson, S., & King, K. A. (2010). Post-Traumatic Amnesia Duration after Traumatic Brain Injury: Relationship to Outcome of Pragmatic Skills during Chronic Phases of Recovery. ''Journal of Medical Speech-Language Pathology, 18''(1), 35-47. doi: Immediate Online Access gi_0199-12788828</ref> PTA has effects on memory, [[perception]] and attention, which are all important for communication. Patients showed mild deficits in verbal communication skills, and moderate to severe deficits in nonverbal communication skills such as maintaining eye contact, initiating greetings, and responding appropriately.<ref name = Deal/> Also, a negative correlation was found between the duration of a patient's episode of PTA and his REFCP score; the longer the PTA episode, the more severe the deficit in non-linguistic pragmatic skills. However, the small sample size of this study (only 10 males) means that the results must be interpreted with caution, as they may not generalize to larger samples or to the population at large.\n==Pathophysiology==\n[[Pathophysiology]] is the study of the changes to an individual's normal physical, biological, and mental functions as a result of disease, injury, or other damage. Currently, the [[pathophysiological]] mechanisms which produce post-traumatic amnesia are not completely known. The most common research strategy to clarify these mechanisms is the  examination of the impaired functional capabilities of people with post-traumatic amnesia (PTA) after a traumatic brain injury.<ref name = Ahmed>{{cite journal |author1=Ahmed S. |author2=Bierley R. |author3=Sheikh J. I. |author4=Date E. S. | year = 2000 | title = Post-traumatic amnesia after closed head injury: A review of the literature and some suggestions for further research | url = | journal = Brain Injury | volume = 14 | issue = 9| pages = 765\u2013780 | doi = 10.1080/026990500421886 }}</ref>\n\n===Neurological mechanisms===\n[[File:Hippocampus.gif|thumb|left|Hippocampus (animation)]]\nResearch on the effect of emotional trauma on memory retention and amnesic symptoms has shown that exposure to prolonged levels of extreme stress has a direct effect on the [[hippocampus]]. Elevated [[stress (psychological)|stress]] levels can lead to an increase in the production of [[enkephalins]] and [[corticosteroids]], which can produce abnormal neural activity and disrupt [[long-term potentiation]] (a neural mechanism associated with learning) in the hippocampus.<ref name = Joseph/> Individuals who have been subjected to repeated sexual abuse during childhood or who have experienced combat show significant impairment and atrophy of the hippocampal region of the brain.<ref name = Joseph>{{cite journal | author = Joseph R | year = 1998 | title = Traumatic amnesia, repression, and hippocampus injury due to emotional stress, corticosteroids and enkephalins | url = | journal = Child Psychiatry and Human Development | volume = 29 | issue = 2| pages = 169\u2013185 | doi = 10.1023/A:1025092117657 }}</ref>  The [[amygdala]], an area of the brain involved in emotional regulation, may be involved in producing remembrance for some aspects of the trauma.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Roozendaal B. |author2=Mcewen B. S. |author3=Chattarji S. | year = 2009 | title = Stress, memory and the amygdala | url = | journal = Nature Reviews Neuroscience | volume = 10 | issue = 6| pages = 423\u2013433 | doi=10.1038/nrn2651 | pmid=19469026}}</ref> Even though the trace of a memory for trauma may be lost from the hippocampus, it may remain partially encoded in the form of an emotional memory in the amygdala where it can be subsequently recalled in the form of a [[flashback (psychology)|flashback]] or partially [[recovered memory]].\n\n===Diaschisis===\n[[Diaschisis]] refers to the sudden dysfunction of portions of the brain due to lesions in distant but connected [[neurons]]. Diaschisis is implicated as playing an important role in PTA, more particularly in the [[declarative memory]] impairments observed in patients experiencing an episode of PTA. The loss of function observed after traumatic brain injuries, as well as the resulting loss of consciousness, was thought to be mediated by the 'neural shock' associated with diaschisis.<ref name = Feeney>{{cite journal | author = Feeney D. M., Baron J. C. | year = 1986 | title = Diaschisis | url = | journal = Stroke | volume = 17 | issue = 5| pages = 817\u2013830 | doi=10.1161/01.str.17.5.817}}</ref>\n\nDiaschisis was originally believed to be a result of disruption to neural tissue, but more recent evidence implicates increased activity levels of [[choline acetyltransferase]], the enzyme responsible for the production of [[acetylcholine]], as a major cause. Based on these findings, diaschisis could be helped through the use of drugs that would reduce cholinergic (acetylcholine) activity, and reduce the levels of acetylcholine in the brain.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Riese W | year = 1958 | title = The Principle of diaschisis: Its History, its nature, and its general significance | url = | journal = International Record of Medicine | volume = 171 | issue = | pages = 73\u201381 }}</ref> This idea is supported by the fact that there is an increase in acetylcholine concentrations in the brain after head injury. Animal studies have shown that concussive injuries in rats lead to changes in the [[central nervous system]]'s cholinergic system. This increase in acetylcholine levels has also been tied to behavioral suppression and unconsciousness, both symptoms of PTA. In long-term recovery, acetylcholine levels associated with diaschisis may continue to play a role in maintaining memory deficits.<ref name = Ahmed/>\n\n===Brain-imaging studies===\n[[Brain imaging]] techniques are useful for examining the changes in the brain that occur as a result of damage. Metting et al. (2001) used [[CT scans]] to examine the pathophyiological damage in patients currently experiencing an episode of PTA, patients with resolved PTA, and a [[control group]] that had not experienced PTA. Bloodflow to the [[occipital lobe]], the [[caudate nucleus]], and the [[grey matter]] of the frontal lobe was significantly reduced in patients who were scanned during the episode of PTA. No differences were seen between patients with resolved PTA and the control group.<ref name = Metting /> This encouraging finding points to the positive long term prognosis of PTA; most patients return to normal levels of functioning.<ref name = Metting /> The frontal lobes are associated with [[explicit memory]] [[memory retrieval|retrieval]], and deficits on explicit memory tasks are often found with patients experiencing PTA.\n\nWorking memory deficits are a common symptom in patients with PTA.  The duration of an episode of PTA was correlated with reduced bloodflow to the right [[Cerebral hemisphere|hemisphere]], a finding which was consistent with [[functional MRI]] studies that link [[working memory]] with right frontal activity.<ref name = Metting />  The [[prefrontal cortex]], which plays an important role in explicit memory retrieval, was also found to have decreased neural activation in patients scanned during the episode of PTA.<ref name = Metting /> Researchers noted that the damage was related to [[vascularization]] and neural functionality, but not to structural injury, suggesting that the resolution of PTA is dependent on functional changes.<ref name = Metting />\n\nMemory and new learning involve the [[cerebral cortex]], the subcortical projections, the [[hippocampus]], the [[diencephalon]] and the [[thalamus]], areas that often suffer damage as a result of TBI. Frontal lobe lesions may also play a role in PTA, as damage to these areas is associated with changes in behavior, including irritability, aggressiveness, disinhibition, and a loss of judgment.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Cantu R. C. | year = 2001 | title = Posttraumatic retrograde and anterograde amnesia: Pathophysiology and implications in grading and safe return to play | url = | journal = Journal of Athletic Training | volume = 36 | issue = 3| pages = 244\u2013248 | pmid = 12937491 | pmc = 155413 }}</ref> Damage to this area may account for the uncharacteristic behavior often exhibited in PTA patients.\n\n====Accelerated forgetting====\nResearchers have also found that individuals experiencing PTA show accelerated forgetting. This contrasts with the normal forgetting observed by patients with normal amnesia related to brain damage. The [[temporal lobes]] are often the most vulnerable to the diffuse (widely distributed) and focal (more specifically localized) effects of TBI and it is possible that temporal lobe lesions may account for the accelerated forgetting observed in patients with PTA. These predictions were supported by the finding that most of the patients who showed rapid forgetting also had lesions to the temporal lobe.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Levin H. S. |author2=High W. M. |author3=Eisenberg H. M. | year = 1988 | title = Learning and forgetting during posttraumatic amnesia in head injured patients | url = | journal = Journal of Neurology, Neurosurgery, and Psychiatry | volume = 51 | issue = 1| pages = 14\u201320 | doi=10.1136/jnnp.51.1.14|pmid=3351514 |pmc=1032708}}</ref> Bilateral damage to the temporal lobes also causes severe anterograde amnesia, making it likely that lesions to this area would be involved in PTA. Patients exhibit a temporal gradient with memory loss, meaning that older memories are preserved at the expense of newer memories. Temporal lobe damage has been linked to a temporal gradient of this sort, because older memories are less dependent on the hippocampus and thus are less influenced by its damage.<ref name = Ahmed />\n\nThere is a significant link between individuals currently suffering from PTA and their performance on the [[Wechsler Adult Intelligence Scale]] (WAIS). The scores of those currently experiencing an episode of PTA were compared to individuals who had previously suffered a traumatic brain injury resulting in PTA. Those still suffering from PTA performed significantly worse on both the performance and the verbal subscales of the WAIS.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Mandleberg I. A. | year = 1975 | title = Cognitive recovery after severe head injury: Wechsler Adult Intelligence Scale during post-traumatic amnesia | url = | journal = Journal of Neurology, Neurosurgery, and Psychiatry | volume = 38 | issue = 11| pages = 1127\u20131132 | doi=10.1136/jnnp.38.11.1127| pmid = 1206424 | pmc = 492168}}</ref> Also, people in early stages of PTA have substantial impairment to anterograde memory function. For example, in the [[case report]] of a patient referred to as \"JL\", Demery et al. noted that his memory impairments were so severe following his injury that he had forgotten that he had attended a [[Major League Baseball]] game less than 30 minutes after returning to the center where he was being treated.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Demery J. A. |author2=Hanlon R. E. |author3=Bauer R. M. | year = 2001 | title = Profound amnesia and confabulation following traumatic brain injury | url = | journal = Neurocase | volume = 7 | issue = 4| pages = 295\u2013302 | doi = 10.1093/neucas/7.4.295 |pmid=11557825 }}</ref>\n\nThe majority of neuropsychological studies available have suggested that the medial temporal lobes are the most important system in the pathophysiology of PTA. However, there is little research done on this topic, and as new research is done, more information should come forth concerning  functionality in these areas in PTA patients. One MRI study showed that a long duration of PTA was correlated with damage in the hemispheric and central areas, regardless of whether the duration of the coma  was relatively short. In patients who had a longer coma duration, deeper lesions in the central area were observed without extensive damage to the hemispheric area.<ref name = Ahmed />\n\n==Diagnosis==\n===Measure of traumatic brain injury severity===\n\n{| border=\"0\" align=\"right\"\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"right\" style = \"margin-left:15px; text-align:center;\"\n|+ ''' Levels of TBI severity'''<ref name=RaoLyketsos>\n{{cite journal |vauthors=Rao V, Lyketsos C |title=Neuropsychiatric Sequelae of Traumatic Brain Injury |journal=Psychosomatics |volume=41 |issue=2 |pages=95\u2013103 |year=2000 |pmid=10749946 |doi=10.1176/appi.psy.41.2.95 \n}}\n</ref>\n! &nbsp; !! GCS !! PTA !! LOC\n|-\n!Mild\n|align=\"center\" width=25%| 13\u201315 ||width=25%| < 1<br> hour || width=\"25%\" | < 30<br> minutes\n|-\n!Moderate\n| 9\u201312 || 30 minutes\u2013<br>24 hours || 1\u201324<br> hours\n|-\n! Severe\n| 3\u20138 || > 1 day || > 24 <br>hours\n|}\n|-\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style = \"float:right; margin-left:15px; text-align:left\"\n|+ '''TBI severity using PTA alone'''<ref name=Howieson04/>\n! Severity !! PTA \n|-\n! Very mild\n| < 5 minutes\n|-\n! Mild\n| 5\u201360 minutes\n|-\n! Moderate\n| 1\u201324 hours\n|-\n! Severe\n| 1\u20137 days\n|-\n! Very severe\n| 1\u20134 weeks\n|-\n! Extremely severe\n| > 4 weeks\n|}\n|}\nPTA has been proposed to be the best measure of head trauma severity,<ref name=Rees03>\n{{cite journal |author=Rees PM |title=Contemporary Issues in Mild Traumatic Brain Injury |journal=Archives of Physical Medicine and Rehabilitation |volume=84 |issue=12 |pages=1885\u20131894 |year=2003 |pmid=14669199 |doi=10.1016/j.apmr.2003.03.001 \n}}\n</ref> but it may not be a reliable indicator of outcome.<ref name=vanderNaalt/>\nHowever, PTA duration may be linked to the likelihood that psychiatric and behavioral problems will occur as consequences of TBI.<ref name=Silver05/>\n\nClassification systems for determining the severity of TBI may use duration of PTA alone or with other factors such as [[Glasgow Coma Scale]] (GCS) score and duration of [[loss of consciousness]] (LOC) to divide TBI into categories of mild, moderate, and severe.  One common system using all three factors and one using PTA alone are shown in the tables at right. Duration of PTA usually correlates well with GCS and usually lasts about four times longer than unconsciousness.<ref name=Howieson04>{{cite book |vauthors=Hannay HJ, Howieson DB, Loring DW, Fischer JS, Lezak MD |veditors=Lezak MD, Howieson DB, Loring DW |chapter=Neuropathology for neuropsychologists|title=Neuropsychological Assessment |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford [Oxfordshire] |year=2004 |pages=160 |isbn=978-0-19-511121-7 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nPTA is considered a hallmark of [[concussion]],<ref name=Rees03/> and is used as a measure of predicting its severity, for example in [[concussion grading scales]]. It may be more reliable for determining severity of concussion than GCS because the latter may not be sensitive enough; concussion sufferers often quickly regain a GCS score of 15.<ref name=vanderNaalt/>\n\nLonger periods of amnesia or loss of consciousness immediately after the injury may indicate longer recovery times from residual symptoms from concussion.<ref name=Masferrer>\n{{cite web|url=http://www.sadlersports.com/blog/concussion-rating-scale/|title=Concussion Grading Scale|date=2009-10-05|work=Sadler Sports & Recreation Insurance|author=Sadler, John M.}}</ref>\nIncreased duration of PTA is associated with a heightened risk for [[Complications of traumatic brain injury|TBI complications]] such as [[post-traumatic epilepsy]].<ref name=eepilepsy>\n{{cite web | url=http://www.e-epilepsy.org.uk/pages/articles/show_article.cfm?id=35 |title=Adult Onset Epilepsies |author=Chadwick D| publisher=E-epilepsy - Library of articles, National Society for Epilepsy |year=2005\n}} \n</ref>\n\n===Assessment===\nDuration of PTA may be difficult to gauge accurately; it may be overestimated (for example, if the patient is asleep or under the influence of drugs or alcohol for part of the time) or underestimated (for example, if some memories come back before continuous memory is regained).<ref name=vanderNaalt/>  The [https://web.archive.org/web/20121104060956/http://www.utmb.edu/psychology/Adultrehab/GOAT.htm Galveston Orientation and Amnesia Test] (GOAT) exists to determine how oriented a patient is and how much material they are able to recall.<ref name=Silver0563>\n{{cite book|vauthors=Silver JM, McAllister TW, Yudofsky SC |year=2005| title=Textbook Of Traumatic Brain Injury |publisher=American Psychiatric Pub., Inc |isbn=978-1-58562-105-7 |page=63\n}}\n</ref>\nThe GOAT is the most widely used standardized scale for the prospective assessment of PTA in the United States and Canada. The test is made up of 10 items that assess orientation and recollection of the events before and after the injury. It can be used to assess the duration of PTA; this particular GOAT assessment has been found to strongly predict functional outcome as measured by the [[Glasgow Outcome Scale]], return to productivity, psychosocial function and distress.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Baird A. |author2=Papadopoulou K. |author3=Greenwood R. |author4=Cipolotti L. | year = 2005 | title = Memory function after resolution of post-traumatic amnesia | url = | journal = Brain Injury | volume = 9 | issue = 10| pages = 811\u2013817 |doi=10.1080/02699050500149213 }}</ref>\n\nAn alternative to the GOAT is the [[Westmead Post-Traumatic Amnesia Scale]] (WPTAS)<ref name=\"Shores1986\">{{cite journal |author1=Shores E. A. |author2=Marosszeky J. E. |author3=Sandanam J. |author4=Batchelor J. | year = 1986 | title = Preliminary validation of a clinical scale for measuring the duration of post-traumatic amnesia | url = | journal = The Medical Journal of Australia | volume = 144 | issue = | pages = 569\u2013572 }}</ref><ref name=\"mqpta\">{{cite web | url=http://www.psy.mq.edu.au/pta | title=The PTA Protocol}}</ref> which examines not only orientation to person, place and time, but also crucially the ability to consistently remember new information from one day to the next. It consists of twelve questions (seven orientation questions, and five memory items) and is administered once daily, each and every day, until the patient scores a perfect score of 12/12 on three ''consecutive'' days. It is suitable for patients with moderate to severe traumatic brain injury. The WPTAS is the most common post-traumatic amnesia scale used in Australia and New Zealand.<ref name=\"Seeman2014\">{{cite journal | author = Seeman R | year = 2014 | title = Prediction of outcomes following severe traumatic brain injury | url = | journal = Critical Reviews in Physical and Rehabilitation Medicine | volume = 26 | issue = 1\u20132| pages = 13\u201325 | doi=10.1615/critrevphysrehabilmed.2014010603}}</ref> An abbreviated version has been developed to assess patients with mild traumatic brain injury, the [http://www.psy.mq.edu.au/gcs Abbreviated Westmead PTA Scale] (AWPTAS).<ref name=\"Meares2011\">{{cite journal |author1=Meares S. |author2=Shores E. A. |author3=Taylor A. J. |author4=Lammel A. |author5=Batchelor J. | year = 2011 | title = Validation of the Abbreviated Westmead Post-traumatic Amnesia Scale: A brief measure to identify acute cognitive impairment in mild traumatic brain injury | url = | journal = Brain Injury | volume = 25 | issue = 12| pages = 1198\u20131205 | doi=10.3109/02699052.2011.608213|pmid=21902551 }}</ref>\n\n===Testing===\nBefore the development of the current tests for the assessment of post-traumatic amnesia (PTA), a retrospective method was used to determine the patient's condition, consisting of one or more interviews with the patient after the episode of PTA was judged to be over. The retrospective method, however, fails to account for the apparent lucidity of patients who are still experiencing substantial disorientation, or the finding that the recovery from post-traumatic amnesia is often characterized by the presence of \"islands of memory\" (short periods of clarity).<ref name = Ahmed/> A failure to take these facts into consideration may have biased retrospective methods towards underestimating the length and severity of an episode of PTA.<ref name = Ahmed/> Also, the retrospective method relies on [[retrospective memory]], one's memory for past events, which is not very reliable in healthy individuals, and even less so in patients who have recently experienced a traumatic brain injury (TBI). Patients may also unconsciously or consciously bias their answers because they want to appear more healthy or more ill than they truly were, or because of poor insight.<ref name = Ahmed/> The retrospective method is also flawed because there is no standard measurement procedure.<ref name = Ahmed/> Although the retrospective method may provide useful subjective data, it is not a useful tool for measurement or categorization.\n\n====GOAT====\nThe Galveston Orientation and Amnesia Test (GOAT) is the most frequently used test for assessing PTA in the United States and Canada. The test consists of 10 items that involve the recall of events that occurred right before and after the injury, as well as questions about [[disorientation]]. Scores of 75 or more on this scale (out of a total possible score of 100) correspond to the termination  of the PTA episode. The GOAT typically classifies orientation into three categories: orientation to the person, orientation to the place, and orientation to the time. The idea behind these questions is that each of these classifications places a large demand on the patient's memory and learning abilities.<ref name = Ahmed/>\n\n====WPTAS and AWPTAS====\nThe [[Westmead Post-Traumatic Amnesia Scale]] (WPTAS)<ref name=\"Shores1986\"/><ref name=\"mqpta\"/> is commonly used in Australia and New Zealand.<ref name=\"Seeman2014\"/> It questions twelve questions that examine orientation to person, place and time, in addition to the ability to consistently remember new information from one day to the next. The scale is administered once each day, until the patient scores 12/12 on three consecutive days. The WPTAS is suitable for patients with moderate-to-severe traumatic brain injury. An abbreviated version of the WPTAS, the [http://www.psy.mq.edu.au/gcs Abbreviated Westmead PTA Scale] (AWPTAS) assesses patients with mild traumatic brain injury.<ref name=\"Meares2011\"/>\n\n=====Drawbacks=====\nAlthough the GOAT has proved useful in acute care, recent research has called attention to some of its drawbacks. The GOAT's assessment of orientation may put too much of a focus on memory as the main mechanism behind orientation. The range of cognitive and behavioral symptoms associated with PTA seems to indicate that the patient's disorientation is more than just a memory deficit. Consequently, it may be beneficial to incorporate tests of other cognitive functions, such as attention, which relate to both memory and orientation.<ref name=Tittle/>\n\nAnother recent study compared the success of the GOAT and the Orientation Log (O-Log) in predicting rehabilitation outcomes, and found that, while the O-Log and the GOAT perform similarly as measures of PTA severity and duration, the O-Log provides a more accurate picture of rehabilitation.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Frey K. L. |author2=Rojas D. C. |author3=Anderson C. A. |author4=Arciniegas D.B. | year = 2007 | title = Comparison of the O-Log and GOAT as measures of post-traumatic amnesia | url = | journal = Brain Injury | volume = 21 | issue = 5| pages = 513\u2013520 | doi=10.1080/02699050701311026|pmid=17522991 }}</ref>\n\nWhile the GOAT is a useful tool, these results suggest that using alternative methods of assessing PTA may increase the amount of information available to physicians and may help in predicting rehabilitative success. The international cognitive (INCOG) expert panel has recommended the use of a validated PTA scale such as the GOAT or WPTAS for assessing PTA duration in patients with moderate-to-severe traumatic brain injury on a daily basis.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Ponsford J. |author2=Janzen S. |author3=McIntyre A. |author4=Bayley M. |author5=Velikonja D. |author6=Tate R. | year = 2014 | title = INCOG Recommendations for Management of cognition Following Traumatic Brain Injury, Part I: Posttraumatic Amnesia/Delirium | url = | journal = J Head Trauma Rehabil | volume = 29 | issue = 4| pages = 307\u2013320 | doi=10.1097/htr.0000000000000074|pmid=24984094 }}</ref>\n\n===Severity===\nThe severity of post-traumatic amnesia (PTA) is directly related to its duration, although a longer duration does not necessarily indicate more severe symptoms.<ref name = Ahmed/> The duration of PTA in brain-injured patients is a useful predictor of the expected long-term effects of the injury,<ref name = \"K\u00f6nigs\">{{cite journal | pmid = 22791900 | doi=10.1136/jnnp-2012-302635 | volume=83 | issue=11 | title=Post-traumatic amnesia predicts intelligence impairment following traumatic brain injury: a meta-analysis |vauthors=K\u00f6nigs M, de Kieviet JF, Oosterlaan J | journal=J Neurol Neurosurg Psychiatry | pages=1048\u201355| year=2012 }}</ref> along with  the duration of [[loss of consciousness]](LOC), and scores on the [[Glasgow Coma Scale]] (GCS), which measures degrees of consciousness, with higher scores indicating higher levels of functioning. A score of three indicates complete unconsciousness, and a score of 15 indicates normal functioning.<ref name = Ahmed/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"right\" style=\"margin-left:15px; text-align:center;\"\n|+ ''' Levels of TBI severity'''<ref>{{cite journal | author = Rao V., Lyketsos C. | year = 2000 | title = Neuropsychiatric Sequelae of Traumatic Brain Injury | url = | journal = Psychosomatics | volume = 41 | issue = 2| pages = 95\u2013103 | doi = 10.1176/appi.psy.41.2.95 | pmid=10749946}}</ref>\n! &nbsp; !! GCS score !! duration of PTA !! duration of LOC\n|-\n!Mild\n|align=\"center\" width=25%| 13\u201315 || width=\"25%\" | < 1<br> hour ||width=25%| < 30<br> minutes\n|-\n!Moderate\n| 9\u201312 || 30 minutes \u2013 <br>24 hours || 1\u20132\n24<br> hours\n|-\n! Severe\n| 3\u20138 || > 1 day || > 24 <br>hours\n|}\nIn patients experiencing PTA for the duration of:\n\nUp to one hour \u2013 the injury is very mild in severity and full recovery is expected. The patient may experience a few minor post-concussive symptoms (e.g. headaches, dizziness).\n\n1\u201324 hours \u2013 the injury is moderate in severity and full recovery is expected. The patient may experience some minor post-concussive symptoms (e.g. headaches, dizziness).\n\n1\u20137 days \u2013 the injury is severe, and recovery may take weeks to months. The patient may be able to return to work, but may be less capable than before the injury.\n\n1\u20132 weeks \u2013 the injury is very severe, and recovery is likely to take many months. The patient is likely to experience long-lasting cognitive effects such as decreased verbal and nonverbal intelligence as well as decreased performance on visual tests. Patients should, however, still be able to return to work.\n\n2\u201312 weeks \u2013 the injury is very severe, and recovery is likely to take a year or more. The patient is likely to exhibit permanent deficits in memory and cognitive function, and the patient is unlikely to be able to return to work.\n\n12+ weeks \u2013 injury is very severe and accompanied by significant disabilities that will require long-term [[rehabilitation (neuropsychology)|rehabilitation]] and management. The patient is unlikely to be able to return to work.<ref name = Headway>Headway UK. (2008). ''Post-Traumatic Amnesia - Fact Sheet'' [Fact Sheet]. Retrieved from http://www.headway.org.uk/sitePages.asp?step=4&contentID=1334&navID=115.</ref>\n\nNote: return to work is meant to indicate a return to a reasonable level of functionality, both in professional and personal arenas.<ref name = Headway/>\n\nThe long-term [[prognosis]] of PTA is generally positive. Many patients do recover a great deal of cognitive function, although they may not return to their pre-injury state.<ref name = Headway/>\n\n==Treatment==\n[[File:Arginine vasopressin3d.png|thumb|A Vasopressin molecule]]\n\n===Vasopressin===\n\n====Animal research====\nEarly research pointed to [[vasopressin]] as a potential treatment for improving the memory of patients living with post-traumatic amnesia (PTA). [[Lysine]] vasopressin, a modified form of the vasopressin molecule, had positive effects on memory when administered by injection to patients with amnesia resulting from traumatic brain injury and [[Korsakoff's syndrome]].<ref>Oliveros, J. C., Jandali, M. K., Timsit-Berthier, M. et al. (1978). Vasopressin in amnesia. ''Lancet, 42.''</ref> Subsequent animal studies with rats found similar results, particularly in aversion and avoidance learning tasks. Rats lacking adequate vasopressin, either due to genetic defect or [[hypophysectomy]] (surgical removal of the pituitary gland), exhibited significant improvements in memory and learning functions when [[exogenous]] vasopressin was administered.<ref name = Eames>{{cite journal | author = Eames P., Wood R. L. | year = 1999 | title = Lysine vasopressin in post-traumatic memory disorders: an uncontrolled pilot study | url = | journal = Brain Injury | volume = 13 | issue = 4| pages = 255\u2013260 | doi=10.1080/026990599121629}}</ref> Particularly encouraging was the finding that a short treatment period produced long-lasting improvements, in both humans and rats.<ref name = Eames/> However, the animal models of PTA are highly limited, as the dimension of self-awareness and orientation is almost impossible to model adequately. PTA in animals, especially rats, is often observed post-trauma (commonly post-surgery), but it is often only measured in terms of impaired learning or unusual behavior.<ref name = Eames/>\n\n====Human studies====\nOne subsequent human study found no effects of vasopressin on memory.<ref>Jenkins, J. S., Mather, H. M., Coughlan, A. K., & Jenkins, D. G. (1981). Desmopressin and desglycinamide vasopressin in post-traumatic amnesia. ''Lancet, 39.''</ref> The nonsignificant results were attributed to the study's many potential flaws, particularly its small sample size, the inability of vasopressin to penetrate the [[blood brain barrier]] when administered as a nasal spray, inadequate dosing and differences in severity of head injury between the samples. However, Eames et al. (1999) found statistically significant improvements on several tests of memory with the use of a vasopressin nasal spray, with no reported ill effects.<ref name = Eames/> Although the degree of improvement was mild, and it could be attributed to numerous other factors of the rehabilitative program, the lack of any ill effects suggests that vasopressin is, at the least, a possible enhancement for a treatment regimen.<ref name = Eames/>\n\n===Norepinephrine agonists===\n[[Diaschisis]], as mentioned earlier, has been linked to the mechanism of PTA. The noradrenergic systems may play a role in diaschisis. [[Norepinephrine]], also known as noradrenalin, is a [[catecholamine]] [[neurotransmitter]].  Administering a norepinephrine receptor [[agonist]] (a substance that initiates a cell response when it binds with a receptor) to patients promoted the recovery of memory and many other cognitive functions after a traumatic brain injury.<ref name = Feeney/> Conversely,  the administration of norpinephrine [[antagonist]]s slowed recovery, and could lead to the reinstatement of deficits when administered after recovery. Noradrenergic antagonists were not prescribed for the purposes of slowing the recovery of memory. Rather, these findings are based on the effects of other commonly prescribed drugs that happen to block noradrenergic receptors. The [[alpha-1 adrenergic receptor]] is specifically implicated.<ref name = Feeney/> Although it has not yet been thoroughly investigated, there is potential for [[stimulants]], which promote catecholamine release, to be an effective treatment in the early stages of recovery from brain trauma, and these positive effects could reduce the symptoms of PTA.<ref name=\"pmid8959228\">{{cite journal |vauthors = Feeney DM |title=From laboratory to clinic: noradrenergic enhancement of physical therapy for stroke or trauma patients |journal=Adv Neurol |volume=73 |issue= |pages=383\u201394 |year=1997 |pmid=8959228 }}</ref>\n==Research==\n\n===The North Star Project ===\nThe North Star Project was developed by researchers at [[McGill University]]. Researchers developed a \"reality orientation\", which involved discussing general facts (e.g. date, time, names of family members, etc.) with amnesic patients twice a day in an attempt to lessen their confusion during the early stages of their recovery. Younger patients often had  shorter amnesic episodes than older patients, especially those in the North Star group. Although more improvements were noted in the North Star group than in the control group, researchers did not find a statistically significant effect of their intervention.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=De Guise E. |author2=Leblanc J. |author3=Feyz M. |author4=Thomas H. |author5=Gosselin N. | year = 2005 | title = Effect of an integrated reality orientation programme in acute care on post-traumatic amnesia in patients with traumatic brain injury | url = | journal = Brain Injury | volume = 19 | issue = 4| pages = 263\u2013269 | doi=10.1080/02699050400004971}}</ref>\n\n====Findings====\nA comprehensive analysis of literature based on the effects of early rehabilitation of traumatic brain injury concluded that there is no strong evidence linking any one particular practice of post-injury care to a reduced severity in symptoms. However,  even in the absence of a concrete correlation between a specific rehabilitation program and improved outcomes, the evidence and research available can provide many good suggestions for how to proceed with treatment. All rehabilitation strategies reviewed had positive effects on recovery, but none more so than the others.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Langhorn L. |author2=Sorensen J. C. |author3=Pedersen P. U. | year = 2010 | title = A critical review of the literature on early rehabilitation of patients with post-traumatic amnesia in acute care | url = | journal = Journal of Clinical Nursing | volume = 19 | issue = 21\u201322| pages = 2959\u20132969 | doi = 10.1111/j.1365-2702.2010.03330.x |pmid=21040002 }}</ref>\n\nThe most accurate measure of determining the length of amnesia is still the a behavioural measure, the duration of the episode of post-traumatic amnesia, rather than a neuroimaging technique or an electrophysiological or biochemical technique.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Greenwood R | year = 1997 | title = Value or recording duration of post-traumatic amnesia | url = | journal = The Lancet | volume = 349 | issue = 9058| pages = 1041\u20132 | doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(05)62288-x| pmid = 9107239 }}</ref>  The length of amnesia is also one of the most accurate predictors for determining later cognitive problems, even more so than the duration of either the coma or the period of loss of consciousness.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Ellenberg J. H. |author2=Levin H. S. |author3=Saydjari C. | year = 1996 | title = Post-traumatic amnesia as a predictor of outcome after severe closed head injury | url = | journal = Archives of Neurology | volume = 53 | issue = 8| pages = 782\u2013791 | doi=10.1001/archneur.1996.00550080104018}}</ref> The duration of amnesia after TBI, therefore, can be very useful in the planning the length and intensity of rehabilitation programs for persons afflicted with PTA.\n\n==History==\n\n===C.P. Symonds===\n\nAlthough Franklin described PTA, it was the British physician C. P. Symonds who first discussed the specific amnesiac symptoms that often follow a [[cerebral contusion]], which is a specific kind of traumatic brain injury. Symonds observed that the patient remains \"stuperose, restless and irritable\"<ref name = Symonds>{{cite journal | author = Symonds C. P. | year = 1928 | title = The differential diagnosis and treatment of cerebral states consequent upon head injuries | url = | journal = The British Medical Journal | volume = 2 | issue = 3540| pages = 829\u2013832 | doi=10.1136/bmj.2.3540.829| pmc = 2456401 | pmid=20774242}}</ref> after recovering consciousness. He also identified a recovery period of days to weeks for this post-concussive state.<ref name = Symonds/> Presumably, shorter durations of PTA, which are now included in the definition, were not thought to be serious enough for documentation. Most importantly, he identified the amnesia that the patient experiences during this period of recovery, and recommended the use of \"formal tests for memory and retention\" to assess recovery.<ref name = Symonds/>\n\n===In WWI soldiers===\n\n[[File:Shellshock2.jpg|thumb|left|Image from WWI, taken in an Australian dressing station near Ypres in 1917. The wounded soldier in the lower left of the photo has a dazed stare, a frequent symptom of \"shell shock\".]]\n\nAlthough there was a general lack of knowledge about its mechanisms, a review of patients seen during WWI combat reveals the symptoms of post-traumatic amnesia (PTA) in many soldiers. The term [[shell shock]] was used to refer to the acute psychological state that accompanied exposure to exploding shells, and more generally, exposure to combat conditions.<ref name = Hart>{{cite journal |author1=van der Hart O. |author2=Brown P. |author3=Graafland M. | year = 1999 | title = Trauma-induced dissociative amnesia in World War I combat soldiers | url = | journal = Australian and New Zealand Journal of Psychiatry | volume = 33 | issue = 1| pages = 37\u201346 | doi = 10.1046/j.1440-1614.1999.00508.x |pmid=10197884 }}</ref> There are a number of documented cases of shell shock victims. These soldiers commonly displayed dizziness, varying degrees of consciousness, a loss of non-traumatic personal information, and a lack of normal [[self-awareness]] lasting anywhere from hours to days. Many of the symptoms of shell shock are highly similar to those of PTA.<ref name=Hart/> The following excerpt from a case report illustrates the loss of personal information observed in one patient:\n{{cquote|A soldier was assessed three days after having been admitted into a field ambulance. He was unable to give his name, regiment, or number, and he could not be identified. He could remember being found on the outskirts of a village, but his military history and all events in his past including his childhood were a complete blank.<ref>Myers, 6, quoted in Hart, O. v. d., Brown, P., & Graafland, M. (1999). Trauma-induced dissociative amnesia in World War I combat soldiers. ''Australian and New Zealand Journal of Psychiatry, 33''(1), 37-46. doi:10.1046/j.1440-1614.1999.00508.x.</ref>}}\n\nResearchers found that physicians had documented reports of combatants where \"[b]oth central and peripheral details of the traumatic experience were lost.\"<ref name=Hart /> Patients displayed gaps in memory recollection for the period following the trauma, sometimes up to the time of hospitalization, which could be weeks later.\n\nAn initial assessment supported the role of concussions in causing these symptoms. Concussions could account for the [[anterograde amnesia]] and [[retrograde amnesia]] observed in patients, as well as the periods of fluctuating consciousness or delirium that sometimes followed. However, many soldiers who showed these amnesiac effects did not suffer injuries that would have led to concussions.<ref name=Hart/> As a result, there was controversy over the possible causes of PTA in these non-concussed soldiers, with a separation between proponents of [[Freudian]] [[Psychological repression|repression]] and those supporting a [[dissociative]] view of the condition. This dissociative view was ultimately supported, and accounted for the [[fugue state]] seen in soldiers who were thought to have dissociated from normal consciousness.<ref name=Hart/>\n\n==Other psychological disorders ==\n\nResearchers have investigated the relationship between posttraumatic amnesia (PTA) resulting from traumatic brain injury (TBI) and the development of symptoms of [[posttraumatic stress disorder]] (PTSD) and [[acute stress disorder]] (ASD). 282 outpatients, who were an average of 53 days post-TBI in their recovery, were divided into four groups: PTA episode lasting less than one hour; PTA episode lasting between one hour and 24 hours; PTA episode lasting between 24 hours and one week; and PTA episode lasting for longer than one week. The patients' personal details were used as variables classified for age, gender, marital status, time elapsed between injury and assessment, and type of injury (motor vehicle accident, pedestrian, assault and other). Patients were given two [[self-report inventories]]: the Impact of Event Scale (IES) and the General Health Questionnaire (GHQ). The IES measures  symptoms of PTSD and contains questions regarding the intrusiveness of the traumatic event (ex. nightmares) and avoidant behaviours related to the traumatic event (ex. avoiding a certain location).<ref name =Feinstein/>  The GHQ was used as an indicator of overall psychological health.<ref name =Feinstein>Feinstein, A., Hershkop, S., Ouchterlony, D., Jardine, A., & McCullagh, S. (2002). Posttraumatic amnesia and recall of a traumatic event following traumatic brain injury. ''Journal of Neuropsychiatry and Clinical Neurosciences, 14''(1), 25-30.  doi: {{PMID|10}}.1176/appi.neuropsych.14.1.25 195251885.</ref> The majority of subjects were in Group 1 (PTA episode lasting less than one hour), injured in motor vehicle accidents, and male.\n\nThere were no statistical differences found with regards to age, gender, marital status and type of injury. There was an increase in the severity of all indicators of brain damage for the longest durations of PTA; specifically, the GCS scores for this group decreased and the number of patients with an abnormal CT scan increased.<ref name = Feinstein/> There were significant differences in IES scores when comparing the group with the least serious episode of PTA, lasting less than an hour, to all other groups, with the duration of the episode of PTA lasting longer than an hour. The group with an episode of PTA lasting less than an hour had higher IES scores and more intrusive and avoidant symptoms.<ref name = Feinstein/> The fact that GHQ scores were constant throughout all groups, although there were differences in IES scores, suggests that the two scores measure different phenomena.<ref name = Feinstein/>\n\n==Aging==\n[[File:Elderly Woman, B&W image by Chalmers Butterfield.jpg|thumb|left|An elderly woman]]\nGrey and white matter are both found in the many areas of the brain, as well as throughout the central nervous system. [[Grey matter]] is more involved in nerve function, and [[white matter]] is more involved in nerve maintenance,  as well as the regulation of unconscious functions. However, both are important for memory and learning. The volume of grey and white matter in the brains of aging individuals has been correlated with working memory and retention of cognitive function.<ref name = Schonberger/> Researchers hypothesized that the lesions of both grey and white matter would be larger in older individuals and in those with more severe traumatic brain injuries, and longer episodes of PTA, and the volume of grey and white matter would be smaller in those injured at an older age. A group of 98 participants, predominantly male, were examined using fMRI. The results supported these hypotheses, leading researchers to suggest that the impact of traumatic brain injury gets more severe as age progresses.<ref name = Schonberger>Sch\u00f6nberger, M., Ponsford, J., Reutens, D., Beare, R., & O'Sullivan, R. (2009). The Relationship between age, injury, severity, and MRI findings after traumatic brain injury. ''Journal of Neurotrauma, 26''(2), 2157-2167. doi: 10. 1089/neu.2009.0939.</ref>\n\nAlthough grey and white matter volume was reduced throughout the brain, researchers noted that the grey matter of the [[neocortical]] brain regions was particularly affected.<ref name = Schonberger/> This is consistent with the fact that older individuals who had experienced PTA showed greater cognitive impairments than a control group of individuals of the same age who had not experienced PTA. The duration of the episode of PTA was related to the size of the grey matter lesion; longer episodes of PTA correlated with larger grey matter lesions. Advanced age also correlated with reduced [[glial]] activity. With less grey matter, the patient is less able to retrieve memories effectively, as neuron function is impaired.<ref name = Schonberger />\n\n==Controversies==\nOn the topic of trauma and memory, [[Richard McNally]] (2005) wrote that memories are not videotapes of our experiences, meaning that they are not unchangeable records.<ref name = Mcnally>{{cite journal | author = McNally R | year = 2005 | title = Debunking Myths about Trauma and Memory | url = | journal = Canadian Journal of Psychiatry | volume = 50 | issue = 13| pages = 817\u2013822 | doi = 10.1177/070674370505001302 | pmid = 16483114 }}</ref> The mechanism that retrieves a memory involves activation of several areas of the brain. Similarly, the mechanism that encodes a memory requires the use of different parts of the brain. Any fault in the encoding-retrieval system will degrade memory, and there are many potential faults, such as distortion by emotion, or focusing on the peripheral details at the expense of central details.<ref name = Mcnally/> An example of the latter is the well-known phenomenon where a person being robbed at gunpoint is so distracted by the gun that they don't have time to encode the robber's face.<ref name = Mcnally/>\n\nMisconstruing retrieval failure as traumatic amnesia is not the same phenomenon as post-traumatic amnesia, which describes amnesia for the current elapsing time post-trauma, not amnesia for trauma from the past. Typically, \"[[repressed memory]]\" is the term used to explain this sort of traumatic amnesia; the experience was so horrific that the adult cannot process what occurred years before.<ref name = Mcnally/> The topic of repressed memory is controversial within psychology; many clinicians argue for its importance, while researchers remain skeptical of its existence. A more viable explanation for this forgetting is [[childhood amnesia]], a phenomenon describing the fact that most children do not have recall of events in their lives before the age of three, partially due to the lack of development of cognitive elements such as language.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{memory}}\n\n[[Category:Amnesia]]\n[[Category:Medical signs]]\n[[Category:Neurotrauma]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Post-traumatic_amnesia"}
